<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5824 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      01-03 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Servie clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ As the final minutes of Saturday's NFC ild-card game
were winding down, an irate Deion Sanders challenged his Dallas
teammates: ``How are you going to feel in the morning?''
</P>
<P>
   This hangover should rival even the worst one from New Year's
Day.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having three Super Bowl rings and having beaten the
Arizona Cardinals 16 of 17 times entering the game, the Cowboys
were vastly overmatched, losing 20-7 and getting eliminated from
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, by the Cardinals. The team that hadn't won a playoff game
since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are supposed to be big-time players and play in big-time
games, then we have to perform in big-time games,'' said Sanders,
who returned to play after missing five starts because of a
sprained toe. ``I think a lot of people were thinking about the
next game. To lose like this was crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys weren't supposed to lose to Arizona. After all, they
already had beaten the Cardinals twice this season, scoring 73
points in the two games. And the Cardinals hadn't been in the
playoffs in a non-strike year since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   They were supposed to be awed by Texas Stadium and the Cowboys'
aura.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about the past, only the future,'' Cardinals
coach Vince Tobin said. ``It doesn't matter who was the president
the last time the Cardinals won in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals blanketed the Dallas receivers, resulting in a
22-of-49 passing day for Troy Aikman, who threw three interceptions
and was sacked four times. They limited the Cowboys to 96 yards
rushing and generally frustrated coach Chan Gailey's offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we stunk up the stadium,'' said Cowboys running
back Emmitt Smith, who carried 16 times for 74 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had six possessions begin at their 37-yard line or
better, but they didn't score until there were only 3 minutes, 33
seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the weapons,'' Smith said. ``I guess we just don't
have the bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   What they were shooting were blanks. Cowboys kicker Richie
Cunningham kicked a 36-yard field-goal attempt wide in the first
quarter. The Cowboys were stuffed on fourth-and-one at the Arizona
seven in the second. They had a third-quarter possession that
included two fumbles and two sacks on three consecutive plays. They
allowed Jamir Miller to come up the middle to pound Aikman for a
loss of 10 yards on fourth-and-one in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And those were only a few plays that will stand out when they
watch the film in the offseason. There were dropped balls that
became too numerous to count as early as the first half. There were
penalties that eliminated short-yardage situations. And there were
miscommunications that resulted in missed blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you throw the football down the field and it hits
receivers in the chest, I can see how it would get frustrating,''
Smith said. ``We were all getting frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't get better. They went into the locker room at halftime
trailing by 10 but could get nothing going in the third quarter.
The Cowboys ran a total of 17 plays on the first five possessions
of the second half, punting three times, throwing one interception
and turning the ball over on downs once. In those five drives, they
moved the ball a net 29 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that we would play well after the first half,''
Gailey said of his halftime locker-room talk. ``I truly believed
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Pro Bowler Aeneas Williams effectively took Cowboys
receiver Michael Irvin out of the game. Irvin finished with four
catches for 32 yards, the longest an 11-yarder. Williams also
intercepted two passes.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the Jake Plummer show that some might have expected.
Plummer, who threw for 314 yards in the second half the last time
the teams met, threw for 213 yards and two touchdowns. But it
wasn't the passing yardage or any big plays that stood out.
Instead, the second-year player simply showed poise and
consistency. He completed 19 of 36 passes with two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals also mixed in a ground game, adding 133 yards, 95
by Adrian Murrell. Murrell had the longest run ever against Dallas
in the postseason, going straight up the middle for a 74-yarder at
the start of the third quarter. On the next play, Plummer threw a
three-yard pass to fullback Larry Centers in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never run the ball well against Dallas,'' Tobin said.
``That first big run in the second half really helped our game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys put their only points on the board after Sanders
returned a punt to the Arizona 25. Three passes later, Aikman
connected with Billy Davis for a six-yard touchdown. The Cowboys
were trailing 20-0 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew what the hell was going on today,'' Cowboys
offensive lineman Nate Newton said. ``Every football player knows
there are three seasons. We failed in the third one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
