<HEADER>
A5839 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-DUCKS-BOS &LR;      01-03 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-DUCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SHOW PLUCK, STOP DUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns didn't have to put the fear of God into his team
about the dangerous combination of Paul Kariya, Teemu Selanne, and
Steve Rucchin.
</P>
<P>
   All the Bruins had to do was take a look at the summary in
Saturday's paper showing the trio's five goals and seven assists
against the best goalie in hockey _ Buffalo's Dominik Hasek _ in
Friday afternoon's 7-2 Anaheim victory.
</P>
<P>
   After a momentary gulp, the Bruins came up with a plan _ send
speeding wingers P.J. Axelsson and Peter Ferraro out on a makeshift
checking line with big center Joe Thornton. The result was a 2-1
win at the FleetCenter Saturday night, with Anaheim's only goal
coming on a power play late in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a tough trip where we were giving up a lot of goals,''
said goaltender Byron Dafoe, who had 29 saves after serving as a
backup the last two games. ``Tonight we focused on defense. It was
definitely a test, and we came through.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to playing strong defense, Thornton scored the first
Boston goal on a power play at 8:15 of the second period to give
Boston a 1-0 lead. As tough a time as the Bruins have had scoring
goals recently, it was the defensive side that contributed to their
recent 1-3 road trip. Saturday night the Bruins played with more
discipline against an electrifying combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take your eyes off them because once you do, they're
right behind you and they have a couple steps on you, and once they
have a couple of steps on you, there's no turning back, they're
gone,'' said Ferraro of the Ducks' top line. ``I'm definitely tired
from chasing those guys around.''
</P>
<P>
   For Thornton, who has bounced around from line to line, it was a
fresh challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe did a good job especially down low,'' said Burns. ``You
don't try to win the faceoffs in your own end, you just try to tie
them up. He did that basically every time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm usually against the third or fourth lines,'' said
Thornton. ``Tonight was a kind of different role I played. It was
exciting. It's big, him showing confidence in me. When he does
that, and I'm out in the last minute, my confidence definitely
(builds).''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's goal, scored on a rebound of Ray Bourque's shot,
ended three dubious streaks for Boston. It broke the Bruins'
scoreless skein against the Ducks at 149 minutes 2 seconds. It also
was the first man-advantage goal the Bruins scored against Anaheim
in 31 tries. Their last was Jan. 11, 1996 in Boston. It also ended
a shutout streak for Guy Hebert, who held the Bruins scoreless for
159 minutes 51 seconds before Thornton's score.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks thought they had tied the game at 11:42 when a
backhander from the slot by Selanne hit the post, hit Dafoe and
then went behind the goalie. Selanne raised his arms in celebration
but video replay officials ruled the puck hadn't completely crossed
the goal line before it was snagged by Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   That reprieve proved to be short-lived however as the Ducks did
tie it on the power play with 44.2 seconds left in the period.
Kariya dished a pass from the right point to defenseman Fredrik
Olausson. Olausson relayed it to Selanne in the left circle.
Selanne one-timed a blistering shot that Dafoe never had a chance
on.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for Heinze's goal at 10:28 of the third.
Heinze, shortly after coming off the bench, scored his 10th of the
year just 29 seconds after the Bruins killed off a penalty to
Bourque. Center Jason Allison dished a pass to Heinze, who skated
through the left circle and down into the crease, beating Hebert.
The Ducks protested, thinking Heinze jumped on the ice too early
but the goal stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Heinzey,'' said Burns. ``We can't hide the fact that
if we don't get any goals from him and if the top line isn't going,
who's going to score? He's a guy who's going to be a a 25-goal
scorer every year and he has to give it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a minute after the Heinze goal, the Bruins thought
they had bought themselves some breathing room. Sergei Samsonov
fired a forehand shot on Hebert that the goalie stopped. The puck
went off defenseman Kevin Haller's stick and then back to Samsonov,
who fired in a forehander from the crease. It was ruled no goal
because Samsonov was in the crease before the puck. It turned out
the Bruins didn't need it. They managed to fend off Kariya and
company the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the bread and butter of their lineup,'' said Burns of
Kariya and Selanne. ``If you can shut them down, you have a chance
to win. If you don't, it's difficult. We knew coming off what
happened in Dallas (a 6-1 loss) that we couldn't go out and give
out those same opportunities. This was more of a match for us than
Dallas was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
