<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5841 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYAN-HALL-HNS &LR;      01-03 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-HALL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Despite rumors to the contrary, Nolan Ryan did not invent the
strikeout. He only perfected it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Appropriately, Ryan on Sept. 11, 1966, struck out the first
major-leaguer he ever faced _ Atlanta Braves pitcher Pat Jarvis _
in his debut with the New York Mets. By the time his two-inning
appearance was complete, Ryan had retired two future Hall of
Famers, getting Eddie Mathews on a strikeout and Henry Aaron on a
foulout to first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from Class A ball into the big leagues and playing
against the Braves it was pretty overwhelming,'' said Ryan, a lanky
19-year-old from Alvin at the time of his debut. ``A lot of guys on
that team were people that it wasn't that many years before I had
baseball cards of.''
</P>
<P>
   From that point, a 27-year path to the Hall of Fame was filled
with more names than the phone directories for some Texas towns.
Cesar Geronimo was Ryan's 3,000th strikeout victim, Danny Heep his
4,000th and Rickey Henderson his 5,000th. In all, Ryan racked up
5,714 K's, a record seemingly safe for eternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say you're nobody until you've struck out against Nolan
Ryan,'' said third baseman Travis Fryman, a 21-year-old Detroit
rookie at the time, before a game toward the end of Ryan's career.
</P>
<P>
   Fryman batted twice against Ryan in the game, bouncing out to
third and flying to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't strike out,'' Fryman said afterward. ``I guess I'm
still nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the ``Ryan Express'' retired in 1993 _ at age 46 _
he had amassed 324 victories and a record seven no-hitters while
pitching for the Mets, Angels, Astros and Rangers. Come Tuesday,
Ryan figures to be among the newest electees to baseball's Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   With Ryan considered a lock, Kansas City third baseman George
Brett is also a favorite to be inducted in his first year of
eligibility. Robin Yount, Carlton Fisk and Dale Murphy are other
first-ballot hopefuls, with Tony Perez, Jim Rice, Tommy John, Gary
Carter and Bruce Sutter among the top holdovers yet to be elected.
To gain Hall enshrinement, candidates must be named on 75 percent
of the ballots turned in by 10-year members of the Baseball
Writers' Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for any professional athlete, if they are fortunate
enough to (go into the Hall of Fame), it pretty much wraps up their
career, sums up their career,'' said Ryan, who pitched for the
Astros from 1980-88 and continues to live in Alvin, where he is
involved in ranching.
</P>
<P>
   Did Ryan ever imagine having such a career? Hardly. Early on, he
developed a reputation as a hard thrower who terrorized opposing
hitters with his lack of control. His talent was so raw, he was
passed over until the eighth round of the 1965 free-agent draft,
when the Mets picked him at the behest of scout Red Murff.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I signed (with the Mets), I had no idea whether I had the
talent or the ability to make the big leagues,'' Ryan said. ``Then,
I made it my goal to qualify for the pension. I felt that (playing
four years) was hopefully a realistic goal.''
</P>
<P>
   He almost qualified six times over, lasting an extra 23 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But Ryan's first victory did not come until April 14, 1968, in
the Astrodome. Paired against the Astros' Larry Dierker, he allowed
three hits, walked two and struck out eight in 6 innings of a 4-2
Mets victory before leaving the game with a blister on his middle
finger.
</P>
<P>
   The next season, Ryan went 6-3 to help the Miracle Mets to the
World Series championship. At the time, he earned $18,000. In 1980,
the Astros would make him the first pro athlete to play for $1
million in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Ryan's best seasons came while with California. In 1972,
he went 19-16 with a 2.28 ERA, leading the American League in
strikeouts (329) and shutouts (nine). The following year, he
finished 21-16 with a 2.87 ERA, breaking Sandy Koufax's
single-season record with 383 strikeouts and tossing two no-hitters
in a two-month span. In 1974, he won a career-high 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ryan's four no-hitters in eight seasons with the Angels,
California general manager Buzzie Bavasi labeled him a ``.500
pitcher'' and decided to let him become a free agent at the end of
the 1979 season.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan got his wish of playing closer to home when he signed with
the Astros in 1980. While in Houston, he pitched his fifth
no-hitter and twice led the National League in ERA while helping
the Astros to division titles in 1980 and '86.
</P>
<P>
   During the end of his playing days with the Astros, team doctors
suggested Ryan undergo surgery for a tear in his right elbow.
Realizing time might be running out, he took a chance and continued
to play seven more years.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point in time, I felt it was too late in my career,
and rehabilitation time was over a year. I didn't feel that was
realistic,'' Ryan said. ``It just finally healed on its own where I
could continue to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Ryan and the Astros soured at the end
of the 1988 season when the club asked him to take a cut in base
salary (he was making about $1.4 million at the time). On Dec. 7,
1988, Ryan signed a free-agent contract with the Rangers for $1.8
million and proceeded to baffle opposing batters for five more
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, who threw no-hitters in three decades, won 69 games and
pitched two of those no-hitters after turning 40 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember walking out of that room thinking, `My God, we've
just signed Nolan Ryan,''' former Rangers general manager Tom
Grieve recalls.
</P>
<P>
   It was as a Ranger that Ryan achieved some of his most memorable
moments, among them his 5,000th strikeout, sixth and seventh
no-hitters, and 300th win.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's career ended when a torn ligament in his right elbow
forced him to leave a game two weeks before the end of the 1993
season. With him, he took 53 records _ owned or shared _ and no
regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at my career is I was very fortunate, and I was
happy with it,'' said Ryan, the first professional athlete to have
his number retired by three teams (Rangers, Astros and Angels). ``I
don't think you have regrets. I would have liked to gotten into
more postseason play, but a lot of times you don't have control of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all his achievements, Ryan is proudest of his durability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really reflect (on my career), but I think I pretty
much get the most satisfaction out of being able to pitch as long
as I did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While many believe he will wear a Rangers cap on his Cooperstown
plaque, Ryan said Saturday he will wait to make a final decision.
Five Hall of Famers spent time with the Astros. None, however,
wears an Astros cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came to Houston as a free agent, I really thought and
anticipated that they would be the last team I'd play for,'' said
Ryan, who initially signed a three-year deal with the Astros with
an option for a fourth. ``I never anticipated that I was going to
stay in Houston for nine years.''
</P>
<P>
   And even then, he seemed only to be getting started.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
