<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRIVERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CLEAN AIR ADVOCATES, PRACTICALITY OFTEN OUTWEIGHS PRINCIPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finding folks who drive alternatively fueled cars is tough, even
among the clean-air crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, the American Lung Association of Arizona, even
the director of the state's Energy Office, don't have an alt-fuel
car among them.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Lung Association. It's in the forefront of the Valley's
push to clean up air pollution and often has sued to force change.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the group has nary an alternatively fueled vehicle in its
small fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the idea hasn't crossed their minds, said Dave
Feuerherd, program manager for the Lung Association. Negotiations
faltered over plans to add an electric vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they get a CNG (compressed natural gas) van, and if we
can afford it, we'll go for it,'' Feuerherd said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will you find members of the Sierra Club tooling around in
such cars.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Smith, the club's Southwest staff director, couldn't think
of anyone who drives an alt-fuel car.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Ormond, who as director of the state's Energy Office
oversees the state's alternative-fuel policies, is thinking about
converting a vehicle to run on both gasoline and CNG.
</P>
<P>
   It will make even more sense when a fueling station opens near
her Tempe home, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull does not use alternative fuels, although she has
signed legislation promoting their use.
</P>
<P>
   Her predecessor, Fife Symington, tried to drum up support for
the movement by having his state-owned car converted to run on both
gasoline and CNG. But that lasted for only the one-year duration of
his car's lease.
</P>
<P>
   There's one policymaker who walks, or drives, the talk.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Jeff Groscost, the sponsor of most of Arizona's
alternative-fuel legislation, drives a 1994 Dodge Intrepid that
runs on gas and CNG.
</P>
<P>
   He reels off the benefits like the best of pitchmen _ everything
from reduced auto emissions to less reliance on foreign oil. But
there's one perk he's especially fond of: unrestricted use of the
carpool lane, even if he's driving alone.
</P>
<P>
   The Mesa Republican estimates he saves up to 1{ hours on his
commute between the East Valley and the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the formerly late Jeff Groscost is now the on-time
Jeff Groscost,'' he boasts.
</P>
<P>
   There were 6,589 alternative-fuel vehicles in Arizona in 1998,
according to state statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Half of those were in government fleets, which by state mandate
must convert to alternative fuels.
</P>
<P>
   By far, the most prevalent fuel type was compressed natural gas,
used by half of the alt-fuel fleet. Liquefied natural gas is the
next most popular, and electric vehicles were a distant third. &QL; 
 &UR; Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at 444-8963, or at
maryjo.pitzl &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 0030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5849 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     01-03 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
IRVING _ All along, you sort of suspected these Dallas Cowboys
weren't much good. The 10-6 record was surely a ruse, given that
fully 80 percent of their W's were inherently tainted, having come
at the expense of their four NFC Least rivals.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But, OK, Dallas had looked pretty stout in whupping modestly
resurgent Washington last weekend and, praise the Lord, Deion
Sanders, he of the most famous toe since Lou Groza's, was back.
Besides, Arizona's abject lack of playoff pedigree seemed too much
for our feathered friends from the Arizona desert to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   The Bidwill family's bumbling, bird-brained franchise had not
tasted triumph in a playoff game since 1947, the year Al Capone
died, Chuck Yeager broke the sound barrier and Jackie Robinson
integrated baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention Harry Truman's becoming the first president to
address the American public via TV? Indeed, that happened in '47,
too.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, that was a long, long time ago. Owner Bill
Bidwill, now portly and gray, was a 16-year-old water boy for the
NFL champion Cardinals, who called Chicago's Comiskey Park home.
</P>
<P>
   On the weight of tradition and recent results alone, the Cowboys
wore the look of prohibitive favorites Saturday. When Sanders, in a
well-orchestrated, typically Deionesque move, jogged out late to a
worshipful roar from the Texas Stadium faithful, you half-expected
a raft of white flags to pop up on the Arizona bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad Deion played,'' observed Larry Centers, one of
Arizona's longest-suffering Cardinals. ``That way, they didn't have
any excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the game began, it was the Cowboys who took on the look of
postseason rubes, a bumbling bunch of turnips tumbling
helter-skelter off the proverbial truck. Ultimately, the only
surprising development would be the Cowboys' actually scoring a
late-fourth-quarter touchdown, thus averting the additional umbrage
of being shut out by a team that hadn't prevailed in a
second-season knockout game in more than half a century.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Bidwill conceded, ``was our biggest win in 51 years.
Oh, boy. I'm numb.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny. So was Jerry Jones. Except I think he was having a
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Hadn't Dallas beaten Arizona 16 out of 17 times? And nine in a
row in Texas? Hadn't Emmitt Smith run for almost 250 yards in the
two regular-season meetings? Hadn't Troy Aikman thrown for some 464
yards, completing just under 65 percent of his passes? Hadn't the
Cowboys scored 73 points at the expense of the Cardinals'
crimson-faced defenders?
</P>
<P>
   All true. But all utterly, completely and totally meaningless
data. Ditto Dallas' five Super Bowl championships and NFL records
for playoff seasons and playoff victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who the president was the last time the
Cardinals won in the playoffs,'' Arizona coach Vince Tobin
protested afterward.
</P>
<P>
   No, what mattered was the Cardinals had the Plummer, and Dallas
had the leaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're living in the present,'' Jake Plummer said. ``The past
is the past. We can't do anything about it. The past is over.''
</P>
<P>
   They call young Jake ``the Snake,'' and they should, considering
how slithery and coldblooded he is for his age. He almost
quarterbacked Arizona State to a national championship a couple
years ago, and now here he is in his second NFL season beating the
Cowboys in January and behaving, as Centers said, ``like a six- or
seven-year veteran.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Sanders, who tends to be a tad self-absorbed, paid homage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Jake Plummer fan,'' Deion acknowledged. ``A lot of times
we forced him to make plays, and he did. He played a wonderful
game. He's going to be a premier player in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Going to be? He already is. Granted, he suffered a couple dumb
picks, but he also passed for a pair of touchdowns _ the first on
the most beautifully executed shovel pass you will ever see _ and
overshadowed the great 'Boy Troy at almost every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman was dreadful, no two ways about it. He made bad reads and
worse throws. Perhaps Arizona's inspired defensive effort was the
reason, or maybe a few early dropped balls broke his spirit, but he
never found any rhythm. He couldn't sustain a drive.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't keep the football out of Aeneas Williams' hands,
either. And when Williams wasn't intercepting Ache-man's passes _
he stole two of them _ Dallas was either punting, blowing a gimmie
36-yard field goal or failing to convert a fourth-and-one at the
Arizona seven.
</P>
<P>
   There, when it was still a 7-0 game and Arizona's upset bid was
barely pipe-dream stuff, the Cowboys couldn't get a yard even with
the ball in Emmitt Smith's esteemed hands. Mark Maddox met Emmitt
head-on and drove him backward. It was the last moment the Cowboys
sniffed the end zone with the outcome in the least bit of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' Dallas coach Chan Gailey said later, ``this is
not how I thought I would be standing before you today. It's a sore
loss for our team, not how we wanted to end the season.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, nonetheless, a more realistic end than a trip to the
Super Bowl would have been. The Cowboys weren't a super team by any
stretch. They were only the best of a bodaciously bad lot, and the
fraud they were perpetrating was certain to be exposed once
everyone began playing for keeps.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill, for one, gleaned no special pleasure from the fact his
impossibly quixotic quest reached fruition at the expense of such a
revered franchise as Dallas, this decade's lone three-time
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been very happy today,'' he mused, ``to beat
anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
