<HEADER>
A5850 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-GEORGETOWN-     01-03 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-GEORGETOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN SHOWS HOYAS WHO'S NO. 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  STORRS, Conn. _ One of the University of Connecticut players
had to stress to coach Jim Calhoun after Saturday night's game that
the Huskies were still undefeated after they wiped out Georgetown,
87-64.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that UConn, ranked first in the country throughout the
first five weeks of the season, led by 22 at halftime and got a bit
bored in the second half. The Huskies allowed Georgetown to get as
close as 13 points (57-44) on a 3-pointer by the Hoyas' Anthony
Perry with just 13 minutes remaining, and that didn't please
Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in front of 10,027 at Gampel Pavilion, UConn got its
lead back to 20 points again, 67-47, with nine minutes left when
sophomore forward Edmund Saunders canned a layup. But Georgetown,
with two freshman in the backcourt, was only outscored by 1 in the
second half, 44-43.
</P>
<P>
   UConn (11-0, 3-0) had four players in double figures. Khalid
El-Amin pumped in 22 points, while Kevin Freeman and Richard
Hamilton had 16 and 15, respectively. Georgetown (7-5, 0-3) had
three players in double figures, and was led by Anthony Perry's 24,
a career high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like we were playing the scoreboard, as opposed to
playing the game,'' said Calhoun, who is now third in the Big East
in wins with 140, one better than former St. John's coach Lou
Carnesecca. Thompson leads with 231, while Syracuse's Jim Boeheim
has 227. ``Give Georgetown credit in the second half, though,''
said Calhoun. ``It got the ball low, and it went after the glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun didn't like that his team shot 53.3 percent (16 of 30)
in the first half and was a mere 34.4 percent (11 of 32) in the
second. The reverse was true of Georgetown, which shot 22.2 percent
(8 of 36) in the first half, 45.9 percent (17 of 37) in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``No excuses, though, as one kid said to me in the locker room,
we didn't lose, and we won by 23 points,'' Calhoun said. ``We were
inconsistent. Maybe it was the fact that we've been practicing
eight straight days. So we have (Sunday) off. We just didn't
maintain our pressure against a young team. We're pleased, though,
that we're in a decent position.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown, which had 10 turnovers the first half (18 for the
game), trailed 7-0 after the first 2 1/2 minutes. Ricky Moore cut
to the basket for a layup and hit a free throw for a 3-point play.
Then Moore made a foul shot, Freeman put back a rebound, and
El-Amin hit a jumper. It was 14-2 with 15:47 left when UConn's
Souleymane Wane made a layup. The Huskies kept it up, scoring 10 of
the next 12 points in building a 22-4 lead on a 3-pointer by
El-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the game we were very tense, sometimes (that happens)
when some of the younger kids come out on the road for the first
time,'' Thompson said. ``Then you relax, you get acclimated to some
of the things you need to get acclimated to, but you can't play a
team as good as Connecticut and get it all back. This has been a
tough year for us, but we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point Thompson, trademark white towel flung over his
shoulder, kidded with El-Amin. ``I kept telling him that he was a
passer, so go back to passing the ball around rather than shooting
it,'' he kidded. ``But he didn't force things. He took shots that
were open.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then when we got it to 13 points, we started to make young
mistakes again.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun wants his team to play just as it does in practice _
never letting up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I want to play in games,'' he said. ``We didn't
play to our advantage during those last 20 minutes. We have to make
sure that we stay focused, stay sharp. We did what we needed to do
during the first half, that's when we made the extra pass. But
we've got to stay focused.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 0037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5858 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-HNS &LR;      01-03 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Although generally outplayed by the Miami Dolphins, the
Buffalo Bills almost pulled out a come-from-behind victory Saturday
afternoon _ a Doug Flutie special.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills believed it was taken away from them _ by Miami's
overzealous defenders, who stripped them of the football four
times, and by an overzealous official who denied them a touchdown
when he was bumped by receiver Andre Reed.
</P>
<P>
   In a season in which referees have come under every scrutiny
short of a congressional investigation, Saturday's AFC wild-card
playoff game brought the din of protest to a new level.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins won 24-17 at Pro Player Stadium, but the Bills
might have forced an overtime if field judge Steve Zimmer hadn't
penalized Reed for unsportsmanlike conduct and ejected him for the
bump.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills were on the Miami 10 yard-line, trailing 24-14 with
two minutes left, when Reed caught a pass close to the goal line.
The Bills thought he had crossed it, but the officials ruled not
quite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still say Andre was in the end zone,'' Flutie said. ``I
think Andre was just getting up and he happened to bump an
official. It wasn't anything intentional. At playoff time, you
don't take a touchdown away from a team for something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said, ``I didn't even know he (Zimmer) was there. I heard
somebody running up behind me, but I thought it was a player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills were pushed back to the Dolphins' 15-yard line, and
after two incompletions they had to settle for a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Andre out, we had to move people around and put them in
positions they hadn't been playing,'' Flutie said. ``Kevin Williams
had to move into Andre's position, and we had to put a tight end,
Jay Riemersma, at wide receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Bills fought valiantly. They recovered an onside kick
and drove to the Miami five-yard line, where they had a first down
with 17 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie tried to tie the score with a slant to Williams, but he
was covered. Before the 5-10 quarterback could throw the ball away,
defensive end Trace Armstrong hit Flutie and knocked it loose.
Miami's other end, Shane Burton, recovered the fumble, and the game
was over.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in the game that Flutie was blindsided
into a costly fumble. ``In both situations,'' he said, ``I didn't
see him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins said Buffalo's fumbles were not entirely
accidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stripping the ball is the first thing we practice every day,''
coach Jimmy Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The tone was set on the first play from scrimmage. Buffalo's
Eric Moulds (nine receptions for 240 yards) beat Terrell Buckley
for a 65-yard reception. But he lost the ball when Buckley grabbed
him from behind, and Brock Marion recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran a post, and he caught the ball out in front,''
Buckley said, ``so I pushed him and held onto him. Our attitude is
they're going to make some catches on us, but we're taught to
finish the play, get a good lick on them and try to strip the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley said the Buffalo receivers ``were not getting the ball
into their body quickly, and that's why we had some of the
takeaways.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins capitalized on the first takeaway, with quarterback
Dan Marino leading them 57 yards to a 31-yard field goal by Olindo
Mare.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills were trailing 17-14 in the fourth quarter when nickel
back Jerry Wilson stripped the ball from Reed's hands, and Buckley
recovered. Marino then took his team 50 yards, mixing in four runs
with five passes, the last one an 11-yard touchdown to Lamar
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Down 24-14 with 3:42 remaining, Flutie was far from through.
With a five-receiver formation, he picked apart the skilled Miami
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went exclusively to the spread package, they couldn't
defend it,'' Flutie said. For the day, he was 21-of-36 for 360
yards with one interception. Marino was 23-of-34 for 235 yards with
an interception.
</P>
<P>
   But on this day, the Dolphins had the better running game. They
outrushed Buffalo 117-77, and Miami dominated in time of
possession, 37:32 to 22:28.
</P>
<P>
   Marino is the all-time touchdown king, but the Dolphins are 1-7
in postseason games in which he has thrown more than 35 passes.
They are 6-1 when he has thrown fewer than 35 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the same intentions that Denver had last year, a wild
card winning the Super Bowl,'' Miami cornerback Sam Madison said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Jacksonville Jaguars beat New England in their playoff
game today, the Dolphins next Saturday will play the Broncos, whom
they beat 31-21 last month.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Bills, they can do nothing but lament the footballs
that were taken away and the bump-and-get-run play that proved so
fateful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 0053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
