<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESENDING FOR ALL NEEDING 
COACH, QUARTERBACK ARE NOT ONLY RESIDENTS IN DOGHOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Through the Texas twilight, cold and bleak, a
voice shaking with frustration and rage echoed in the upper reaches
of fast-emptying Texas Stadium late yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dog! Dog! Dog!''
</P>
<P>
   This time it wasn't Troy Aikman, screaming at his offensive
line.
</P>
<P>
   The fan, clearly in abject agony, ran out of breath before
counting all 47 of them, but there was no misinterpreting his
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   With all due apologies to man's best friend, we came yesterday
expecting a first-round NFL playoff game and caught the American
Kennel Club Follies instead.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there a blue ribbon for the Cowboys as Best of Show.
They did, however, capture consolation prize as Biggest Dog of the
day and for showing they can still roll over and play dead.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals 20, Cowboys 7 not only means an early exit from the
playoffs for Dallas, it also opens up the team, its coaches and its
players to a hard, intensive review.
</P>
<P>
   Insert gleeful hand-rubbing and chop-licking here.
</P>
<P>
   It's all well and good to feel warm and fuzzy about rebounding
from 6-10 a year ago to 10-6 and an NFC East championship, even if
the division did reek with ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   To be embarrassed as they were yesterday, however, was a
disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won 10 games this season and I doubt there were many in
this room who thought we could do that,'' Aikman said defensively
in the interview room afterward. ``For anyone other than those in
our locker room to imply that we've had a bad year would be wrong.
``We're'' disappointed. No one else in this room should be.''
</P>
<P>
   What nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   We shouldn't be disappointed because the Cowboys couldn't beat a
mediocre team that hadn't won a postseason game in more than half a
century? We shouldn't be disappointed that the Cowboys looked more
canine than primetime in their biggest game of the year?
</P>
<P>
   Aikman was almost as far off the mark with that line of bilge
water as he was with most of his passes. On a day when the Cowboys
needed the guy with three Super Bowl rings to step up and take
charge of his team, he wasn't even the best quarterback on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   It took Deion Sanders, of all people, to face facts and put the
proper spin on what happened yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're supposed to be big-time players, we're supposed to
perform in big-time games,'' said Sanders, who took an injection in
his injured left big toe before the game that allowed him to play
for the first time in six weeks. ``We're all accountable; all of
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``People on this team have been holding their tongues but I'm
very angry. We all need to look at ourselves, me included, and how
we played today.''
</P>
<P>
   What they see won't be pretty, especially offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not show up to play,'' Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't intend it that way, but that's an indictment of
Gailey, who was grim with disappointment at how his first season as
a head coach concluded. It is his responsibility to gauge his
team's emotional level and provide the motivational spark it needs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Cowboys continued to remain unfocused and make the
same mistakes that plagued them through most of December.
</P>
<P>
   ``A ball gets tipped, we drop a pass, we fumble a snap, we get a
penalty. ... we just can't win playing that way,'' Gailey said.
``The mistakes kept us from developing any rhythm or consistency
offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the head coach who must be held accountable for that lack
of focus.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the quarterback? Aikman will go down in NFL history
as one of its most efficient passers ever. He's on his way to the
Hall of Fame. But where's the passion when this team needs it?
Where's the leadership and the fire, the willpower and
determination, that not only made Staubach and Montana Hall of
Famers, but legends as well?
</P>
<P>
   ``They \Rthe Cardinals\S have a quarterback who can run when you
pressure him and still make plays,'' Sanders pointed out, and if he
didn't mean to draw a direct comparison of young and mobile Jake
Plummer to Aikman, he made it easy for the rest of us to do it for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Needing a big game, Aikman instead was sacked four times and
threw three interceptions. He wasn't alone in his misery. His
receivers, especially Michael Irvin and Billy Davis, continually
dropped passes and were rarely open. Aikman had no deep threat, no
one who could stretch the Cardinals' defense.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Williams continued to draw flags for false starts and
holding. Guard Nate Newton and center Mike Kiselak missed key
blocks. Trailing 7-0, the Cowboys failed to make a critical
fourth-and-one at the Cardinals' 7 midway through the second
quarter when no one picked up an inside blitz.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches around here have been flayed alive for making calls like
that.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the physical flaws. Worse, though, was that the
Cowboys had the look of a team that really didn't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to want a game like this,'' Sanders said. ``How can
you look at yourself in the mirror if you didn't go out there and
give it your all?''
</P>
<P>
   We should have handed him the pens and notepads, since he was
asking the questions that most needed answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nucleus of this team isn't getting any younger,'' Sanders
said. ``If I was Mr. Jones, spending the money he's spending, I
wouldn't put up with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those of us standing way too close to the fire hydrant couldn't
agree more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
