<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-UNC-ASHEVILLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 2 CLOSE CALLS, HORNED FROGS ROLL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU coach Billy Tubbs figured he had an easy
game coming his way.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that TCU's previous two games had been decided by 20
seconds and four points, he had been hoping for a cakewalk last
night.
</P>
<P>
   He got better. He got North Carolina-Asheville, and No. 24 TCU
simply sleepwalked through for a 101-67 victory at Daniel-Meyer
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the one thing that we failed to do is give these teams
the credit they deserve,'' Tubbs said. ``We didn't exactly demolish
\RUNC-Asheville\S.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs did, however, defeat the Bulldogs without the
last-second, buzzer-beating theatrics that had been necessary in
their two previous games.
</P>
<P>
   Frogs forward Marquise Gainous had to deliver game-winning shots
in TCU's previous two games, against Southwest Missouri State and
Gonzaga. He had a less dramatic, although no less effective, 21
points to lead TCU past UNC-Asheville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't have been a problem if I had had to,'' Gainous
said of another game-winning shot. ``It was nice not to be in that
situation though.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainous highlighted a Frogs stat page that featured five players
in double figures, including 16 points from both Lee Nailon and
Ryan Carroll. Prince Fowler added another 15 while Vladimir Jaksic
chipped in 11.
</P>
<P>
   Nailon's numbers look good, yet, Tubbs said Nailon struggled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, Lee Nailon shot 7-for-21 and usually 12-for-21 is a bad
night for him,'' Tubbs said. ``We got a lot of guys stepping up,
though. Marquise played well. Prince had a good night. This was
more of a team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU (12-2) has gone unbeaten since losing to Oklahoma State on
Nov. 28 and remains unbeaten at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, UNC-Asheville (1-11) extended its losing streak to
nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say we're the best 1-11 team around, but that's
not any compliment,'' Bulldogs coach Eddie Biedenbach said. ``We
weren't able to do it against the people we played.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven of UNC-Asheville's losses have come against teams in the
Top 25, including road losses to No. 11 Purdue, No. 12 St. John's,
No. 13 Michigan State and No. 14 Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   No. 24 TCU actually looked to provide a semi-breather for
UNC-Asheville, looked being a key word.
</P>
<P>
   TCU refused to UNC-Asheville catch its breath.
</P>
<P>
   Gainous and Co. had jumped to a 15-point halftime lead, and
that's with a defense that Tubbs said had played poorly. ``We
weren't able to get out there and dominate defensively,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When TCU finally got its full-court press clicking, about midway
through second-half play, UNC-Asheville finally got overwhelmed.
TCU finished with a plus-14 margin in turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been concentrating on defense all week,'' Gainous said,
``and we'd been practicing good.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU now has a layoff before starting Western Athletic Conference
play against SMU on Jan. 11. That begins a stretch of six WAC games
in 14 days for TCU, with first three being away games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stupid,'' Tubbs said. ``I just want to give all of the
credit in the world to the WAC office for their infinite wisdom on
the schedule.'' Extra points TCU announced that freshman guard
Michael Causey has decided to withdraw from TCU. He had been
bothered by homesickness, and he hadn't been getting a lot of
playing time. He played in seven of TCU's 14 games this season,
averaging 2.7 points .9 assists and .6 rebounds a game.
</P>
</TEXT>
