<SLUG> BC-OLY-COLLEGE-WRESTLING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXANS-LED OKLAHOMA DOMINATE AT LONE STAR DUALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEIDI PEDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ University of Oklahoma coach Jack Spates
has been kind to the Lone Star State. Texas, in return, has been
kind to him.
</P>
<P>
   Spates helped put together last year's first-ever Lone Star
Duals, bringing one of the nation's premier NCAA wrestling teams to
Arlington to help promote the sport in the state. Yesterday, Spates
brought the Sooners back to an even bigger Lone Star Duals at South
Grand Prairie High School, and his team ended the day with three
dual victories in its cap.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma, ranked No. 5 in the nation, defeated Brown, California
State-Bakersfield and Wisconsin to raise its record to 4-1 on the
season. The Sooners also won all three of their duals at last
year's meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked as a team about dominating. We wanted to focus on
ourselves, and wrestle from the start of the match to the end,''
Spates said. ``I really feel that's what we did. I saw a ton of
improvement out here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma defeated Brown, 37-6; CSUB, 35-6; and Wisconsin, 37-3.
The Sooners were one of three ranked teams competing in the event,
which expanded from last year's four-team dual. CSUB, ranked 15th,
went 2-1 yesterday. Oregon State, ranked 14th, went 3-0. Virginia,
Wyoming and Northern Iowa also competed.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma has been helped in its success recently by Texas
athletes. The Sooners have five Texas natives on the roster,
including regular 184-pound starter Tommy Grossman. Grossman didn't
compete yesterday because of a knee injury, but in his place
against Brown was 1997 Grapevine High School graduate Nick Curcio.
</P>
<P>
   Curcio, a former Texas state high school runner-up, fell 9-3 to
top-20-ranked senior Nate Burroughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I was very pleased with the way Nick wrestled,''
Spates said. ``He was competing against a ranked guy, and he didn't
back down. He kept going at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Curcio wasn't the only Texas athlete to compete yesterday.
Marcus graduate and state champion Robbie Rogers was in the lineup
for Brown, losing by technical fall to Oklahoma's Jared Frayer and
beating Wyoming's Justin Gonzalez, 10-5.
</P>
<P>
   The big surprise of the day came in the matchup of Wisconsin
senior Dusty Coufal and No. 1-ranked Oscar Wood of Oregon State at
149 pounds. Coufal, 10-4 on the season, used a first-period
takedown and later an escape and penalty calls to beat Wood 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to go with the upper body, so I tried to stay away
from him and use good fakes,'' Coufal said. ``He walked into my low
single.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUB heavyweight Stephen Neal, also ranked No. 1, went
unchallenged. The defending NCAA champion recorded three pins, the
longest taking 59 seconds, to win the meet's Outstanding Wrestler
Award.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
