<HEADER>
A5879 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-HOCKEY-REPORT-TEX     01-03 1714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HOCKEY-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS UNLEASHING OFFENSIVE HOUNDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While NHL governors and general managers can alter the course of
the game over time with rule changes and mandates to referees,
there is no fraternity that can affect the on-ice product as
dramatically as the NHL coaches.
</P>
<P>
   And it appears the restless feelings fans and players have
experienced from suffocating defensive systems have finally
manifested itself in coaches. More and more, bench bosses are
tinkering with the idea that their teams can be more offensively
creative, that goal-scoring can lead to victories and that taking
some risks can produce big paydays.
</P>
<P>
   Although league scoring hasn't risen above last season's average
of 5.2 combined goals per game, a trend is afoot that signals more
offense. In places such as Toronto, New Jersey, Buffalo _ and yes,
even Dallas _ coaches who have all but perfected defensive systems
are now turning their talents to offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to at some point,'' Maple Leafs general
manager Ken Dryden said. ``The league has gone through trends
throughout its existence, and there is always someone out there
trying to figure out a better way to do things.''
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto, that better way was to get a top-notch goalie in
free-agent Curtis Joseph and then let him help change the way the
team played. Joseph's numbers aren't spectacular _ 2.54 goals
against and .909 save percentage _ but his ability to stop prime
scoring chances on breakaways has allowed his teammates to be a
little more risky. The result? The Leafs are among the league
leaders in offense and also among the top five in victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thought is, if you have a good goalie, why do all this
work to only let him face 20 shots a game,'' Dryden said. ``If you
have a good goalie, you have to trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a dangerous philosophy, but it's working so far. Joseph is
7-0 in games in which he has faced 30 or more shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Sabres have lived on that philosophy for the past
three seasons, taking offensive chances and allowing goalie Dominik
Hasek to clean up the mess. The result is the Sabres have been able
to develop five or six young forwards into dependable goal-scorers
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, rookie coach Robbie Ftorek has done much the same
thing. He hasn't completely released the Devils from their
defensive responsibilities, but he's allowing them to skate even if
it means goalie Martin Brodeur will see more prime scoring chances.
Brodeur's numbers have suffered, but the rest of the team is
excited about the chance to move the puck.
</P>
<P>
   And that might be the bottom line in the coaches' changing their
philosophy. Players generally will do whatever it takes to produce
a win, but they're much happier when they're allowed to skate, when
they're allowed to take chances, when they're allowed to be
creative. By loosening the reins, coaches can better motivate
entire teams, not just the scorers.
</P>
<P>
   And that makes it easier to get the players to ``buy into the
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock is activating his team's defensemen,
allowing them to get more involved in the offensive play. And while
Craig Ludwig, Shawn Chambers and Richard Matvichuk might tell you
it's no big deal to score a goal, you can see their excitement when
they do.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL has been a copy-cat league in the past. When Bobby Orr
revolutionized the position of defenseman, every team tried to
copy. When small, skinny Wayne Gretzky stunned the league with
high-risk passing, every team tried to follow suit. When the
Panthers and Devils found instant success with team defense, many
teams jumped on board.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's a trend toward getting offense back into the game,
and the coaches are endorsing it. That could be the real change the
league has been seeking for the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS BIG BROTHER
</P>
<P>
   Anybody else worried about Colin Campbell's recent decision to
rescind a game-misconduct penalty against the Flyers' Eric Lindros?
The issue isn't whether Lindros deserved the penalty, it's that
Campbell was setting a bad precedent by second-guessing a referee.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros received a five-minute major for a slash on Chris
Chelios and a game misconduct. It was Lindros' second stick-related
game-misconduct, so an automatic one-game suspension was set to
follow. But Campbell reviewed the tape and rescinded the
game-misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   I'm all for review and proper discipline, but the referees have
to be allowed to run the game. If the league can reverse a judgment
call in that situation, why not just review every hook, hold or
offside call that could change a game.
POT O' TROUBLE
</P>
<P>
   No matter how strong-willed Canucks general manager Brian Burke
is, he has to see his refusal to trade holdout winger Pavel Bure is
hurting the Canucks. Last week, frustrated coach Mike Keenan waved
a white flag so prominently, it had to send shivers through his
team. With Bure in Belarus and Alexander Mogilny (knee) and Todd
Bertuzzi (leg) injured, Keenan admitted his team was going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get tired of listening to you,'' Keenan said. ``They need
a kick start or a new coach. That's how you ignite a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Many insiders said Keenan and Burke couldn't work together, and
this might be the sign the relationship is close to cracking.
MENTAL BLOCK
</P>
<P>
   Need any more hints that Owen Nolan's confidence is completely
shot? The San Jose Sharks winger, who once was was so cocky he
called a hat-trick goal against Dominik Hasek in the 1997 All-Star
Game, couldn't even get a shot off on a recent penalty-shot
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan was awarded the shot in a 2-0 victory against the
Vancouver Canucks and skated at the net as if he didn't want the
puck. He eventually fumbled it away and then skated to the bench,
where he looked shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owen is playing with no confidence,'' assistant coach Bernie
Nicholls told the ``San Francisco Examiner''.
GREATEST EVER?
</P>
<P>
   For five consecutive games during the Red Wings' recent losing
streak, legendary coach Scotty Bowman sent his assistants out to
speak to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bowman was sending a mesage to his team. Maybe he's still
suffering after-effects from heart surgery. Maybe he wants his
assistants to learn from the experience.
</P>
<P>
   But the view from here says it's a pretty classless move to
appear to duck the media at the first sign of trouble.
SEEING RED
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock is vehemently opposed to removing the
center red line in order to allow more long passes and eventually
more breakaways. His reasoning is defenses would simply sit back,
and the game would slow down even more.
</P>
<P>
   NHL general managers watching the experiment at the World Junior
Championships in Winnipeg have seen the rule change fail.
THE BUZZ
EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   Cheers to Flyers center Eric Lindros. Knowing the whole city of
Philadelphia revolves around his play, Lindros showed enough common
sense last week to sit out a couple of games after receiving a
concussion. Lindros apparently learned a few things from his
brother Brett, who had his career cut short by post-concussion
syndrome. ... The surprising Panthers are hoping for a boost this
week as injured forwards Dino Ciccarelli (back) and Chris Wells
(hernia) could be back in the lineup. ...They've tallied the
financial total of general manager Bobby Clarke's blunders in
Philadelphia. He has spent $18.1 million in bonuses on players no
longer there _ Chris Gratton, Paul Coffey and Pat Falloon. ...
Islanders goalie Tommy Salo (broken finger) has returned to
practice and could come back this week. ... Dominik Hasek is
playing the best goal in the history of the NHL and it's an even
greater accomplishment when you consider his wife has been battling
chronic back pain. It got so bad earlier in the season he had to
travel with her to the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota. ... Irony of the
Year: Paul Coffey being traded to the Carolina Hurricanes. Coffey
played briefly for the Hurricanes organization when it was the
Hartford Whalers three years ago, but demanded a trade to ``a more
competitive team.'' Isn't that like marrying the girl who stood you
up at the prom? WESTERN CONFERENCE:
</P>
<P>
   And you thought the Southeast was the NHL's worst division.
Think again. Not only does the Northwest not have a team with a
winning record, it doesn't have a team with a winning record on
home ice. The Stars start a run through the Northwest Division this
week and could be welcomed guests. The home rundown: Avalanche at
6-9-1, Oilers at 7-9, Canucks at 8-7-2 and Flames at 5-12-2. ...
Mighty Ducks winger Paul Kariya has quietly become a tougher
player. Bouncing back from a concussion that kept him out most of
last season, Kariya had 43 points through 34 games. ``He's not
taking anything from anybody. He's playing with passion,'' coach
Craig Hartsburg said. ``That's Paul, he wants to be the best
all-around player in the world.''... The Blues continue to search
for offense in the wake of injuries to Pierre Turgeon (broken hand)
and Geoff Courtnall (post concussion syndrome). At some point in
time, does this team have to look to a trade to spark the offense?
... When Todd Gill joined the Red Wings last week, he became the
fifth former Maple Leafs defenseman to play for the Red Wings in
the past two seasons. When they asked Gill what number he wanted,
he responded ``19'' _ the number of Red Wings captain Steve
Yzerman. When asked why he didn't just ask for Gordie Howe's No. 9,
Gill responded: ``There's joking and then there's
stupidity.''...Yanic Perreault was second on the Kings in
goal-scoring last season with 28 and has been a healthy scratch for
the past four games. The Canucks or Blues should look to pick up
this versatile center. ... The Blackhawks have seen improvement
from Doug Gilmour since coach Dirk Graham moved him to a line with
Alexei Zhamnov and Tony Amonte.
THE WEEK AHEAD
Monday
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay at Toronto: Former Leafs captain Wendel Clark bids
adieu to Maple Leaf Gardens. Monday
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver at St. Louis: Coach Mike Keenan returns to the Kiel
Center, the house he almost tore down. Saturday
</P>
<P>
   Colorado at Detroit: With both teams struggling and frustrated,
they might both need a good fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
