<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH WARNS REPUB LICANS TO HEED ELECTION RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY JENNIFER BARRETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Departing House Speaker Newt Gingrich warned Saturday night that
Republicans could wake up after Election Day 2000 to find Al Gore
their president and Democrats the majority party if they don't heed
the wake-up call sent by voters in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a very, very, dismal distance from where we should
be,'' Gingrich told the crowd of more than 200 conservatives
gathered at the posh Arizona Biltmore for the third annual
Repubican gathering, ``The Weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said the GOP party had lost its message, focus and
teamwork in 1998. But he added that it was not too late to turn the
party around, even as he steps aside from the speakership.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that began and ended with standing ovations, and was
punctuated with chants of ``Newt!'' whistles and sporadic applause,
Gingrich told Republicans to stop focusing so much on Washington
and to focus instead on what the American people want.
</P>
<P>
   And what the public wants, he said, is more money in their
pockets in the form of lower taxes.
</P>
<P>
   `If we're not the anti-tax party . . . we have no right to be on
the ballot,'' he said, to a rousing ovation. ``No American should
pay more than 25 percent of their paycheck in taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich recommended the party put a 25-percent cap on federal,
state and local taxes combined, though he conceded that it may take
decades to reach that goal.
</P>
<P>
   He also urged party leaders to create personal social security
funds for Americans, promote private school vouchers and charter
school options for disadvantaged children, and introduce new
``common sense'' litigation reform.
</P>
<P>
   Despite lackluster returns for the Republicans in the 1998
elections, Gingrich said he was optimistic. He told Republicans it
was not too late _ nor too unrealistic _ to prepare for
``astonishing'' successes in the presidential and congressional
elections of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich declined to comment on rumors he may run for president.
But he may have hinted at his own political ambitions when he said
the question was not whether the Republicans would win again, ``but
how rapidly we will succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich added, ``The struggle for freedom is endless. You can
never say `Well, now we have won.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
