<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDS-AIRPORT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS GREET CARDINALS AT AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BARRETT  
 and RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Cardinals! Cardinals! Cardinals!''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 14,000 ecstatic fans staged a raucous party at Sky
Harbor International Airport on Saturday night to greet the
conquering heroes hours after the team's 20-7 trouncing of the
Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Jake! We want Jake! We want Jake!'' they shrieked as
the Arizona Cardinals, fresh from their first playoff victory in 51
years, descended from the plane about 9:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The red birds now go on to face the Minnesota Vikings in
Minneapolis on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And when quarterback Jake Plummer stepped up to the lectern on
the tarmac, he thrilled the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is awesome,'' Plummer said. ``The energy we feel here now
we felt in Dallas. Without you guys believing in us we couldn't
have gotten it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, making a reference to a line from the movie ``The
Waterboy,'' he said, ``It's been a saying for us for the last few
weeks: We can do it!''
</P>
<P>
   That brought more cheers and clapping from the faithful, who
came from as far away as Chandler and New River, babies on their
daddies' shoulders, college students and retirees. They were pumped
up from the amazing upset that naysayers said would never happen.
</P>
<P>
   It was like a block party, with spontaneous cheering, pickup
football games, and a band playing rock and roll songs. Deejay Rich
Creeger of KSLX-FM (100.7) revved up the crowd and Cardinals
cheerleaders danced around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to find out where the hell is Minnesota,'' said
Linda Zacchia, 52, of Phoenix, a pediatric nurse, referring to the
Cardinals' match next Sunday against the mighty Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been five years of tough seasons but I've been with them,
whatever. I love them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rory Rainstorn of Phoenix was dancing with his 4-year-old son,
Michael.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel they had it in the bag until about 15 seconds
left in the game,'' he said. ``I kept waiting for the other shoe to
drop, for Dallas to treat us like they always do, but that never
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   There was whistling, hooting, clapping and waving flags. Air
horns cut the din.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Handmade signs proclaimed, ``You've got to believe,'' and ``We
knew.'' A band played Cardinals parody songs, like, ``Jake Don't be
a Hero,'' and ``Nowhere'' ``Team,'' referring to the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   All eyes peered skyward as the vigil continued, and when the
plane flew into view, an illuminated cardinal on its tail, people
went wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just hope that when the team falls on hard times again, all
these fans will come out,'' said Jeff Grachus, 27, of Phoenix,
wearing a Plummer jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Valley, fans cheered from their living rooms,
automobiles, parties and bars as the Cardinals surprised the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   At Player's All-American Sports Bar, it sounded like New Year's
Eve all over again. The rowdy crowd gathered around a big-screen
television on the patio and counted down the final seconds in
unison, ``10 _ 9 _ 8 _ 7 . . .''
</P>
<P>
   But fans erupted early into applause, knocking empty beer
pitchers to the ground and high-fiving and hugging total strangers
_ well, as long as they were wearing red.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, those in the silver and blue tried to slip out
quietly from the eatery in Phoenix's Arizona Center. Not all were
so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I'm a loser,'' admitted Dallas fan Aaron Carillo, 38,
who lost a six-pack to some Cardinals fans, but kept his faith in
the Cowboys. ``I've always been a fan, although I'm playing it a
little low-key today.''
</P>
<P>
   Carillo, who had driven to Phoenix from his home in Santa Fe,
N.M., to welcome in the new year and watch the game with his
Phoenix friends, counts among his Cowboys gear: a logo leather
jacket and travel bag, six pairs of shorts, and at least 20
T-shirts _ the most inconspicuous of which he wore Saturday. The
grey T-shirt showed a football ripping apart the words ``Dallas
Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Cardinals did to the team on the field as well.
</P>
<P>
   Don Cruz, a security guard at AMC Arizona Center movie theater,
watched the television screen from the atrium of the Arizona
Center. When the Cowboys scored, he whipped out a hand-held radio
and dutifully reported the score to other staff members at the
theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're slow over there,'' he said. ``Everyone's watching the
ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ticket taker Albert Orta, 16, said the theater's staff kept the
breakroom radio tuned to the game as well, sneaking in for periodic
updates.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we managed to do our jobs as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Next weekend, he has taken off so he can watch the game
uninterrupted. The Cardinals will face the Vikings on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Cruz, 25, was reporting the score to friends as well via
cellular phone, but she wasn't smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was about ready to kill those guys behind us,'' she said,
tugging at her Cowboys game shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a Cowboys fan for as long as I can remember,'' added
Cruz, a native Texan and Phoenix resident. ``The Cardinals have
been here for 10 years and no one cared and now suddenly, they have
two sold out games, and they're like, `The Cowboys suck.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Friend and fellow Cowboys fan, Jennifer Thomasson, 24, said she
was willing to wager that at least half the red-shirted fans had
Dallas Cowboys shirts in their closets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could still see the creases in some of their (Cardinals)
shirts. I bet it's the first time they've worn them.''
</P>
<P>
   She has had her blue, numbered shirt for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when Danny White played for them,'' she said
proudly. ``The Cowboys haven't been doing well lately, but I'm
still going to wear my shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Ems, 21, said she is going to wear her shirt proudly as
well _ her Cardinals shirt, that is. She admits it's been awhile
since she wore it out in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been embarrassing,'' she said. ``Every time the Cowboys
came here, they beat us, but to see them (Cardinals) totally
slaughter the Cowboys _ well, we don't have to be embarrassed
anymore to be Cardinals fans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 0144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
