</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA DEFEATS   ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With their archrival on the court and their former
teammates hovering in a near corner, the new-era UCLA Bruins
unofficially severed all ties to their recent past.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Johnson, Toby Bailey and Jelani McCoy watched from a corner
of Pauley Pavilion as Baron Davis and friends delivered the most
spirited and significant win of the season _ an 82-75 victory over
No. 6 Arizona in the Pac-10 opener for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   The new era officially began in November, of course, but until
Saturday night these Bruins had nothing of consequence to call
their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the game that starts our climb to the Pac-10 title,''
UCLA junior forward Sean Farnham said. ``It's the most important
game on the schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA never trailed and never relented, charging to a 20-point
second-half lead and repelling a late Wildcats rally.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins played with hyper-aggression, challenging every pass
and every rebound. Some of it was wasted motion, to be sure. But
where previous Arizona teams were savvy and talented enough to
counteract UCLA's energy, these Wildcats had no answers.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman forward Michael Wright often was one man against five.
Arizona's freshman guards seemed paralyzed by the intensity of
their first conference road game, and the Wildcats' seniors, A.J.
Bramlett and Jason Terry, were ineffective until the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 61-40, the Wildcats pulled to single digits with three
minutes remaining. They were within 81-75 with 20 seconds left when
a botched possession ended their comeback.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 10 Bruins beat Arizona to every loose ball and seemed to
be in two places at once, so much quicker were they. For both teams
the ballhandling was sloppy and the pace frenzied. That combination
created the type of playground atmosphere UCLA has thrived in for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's Bailey or Davis, the Bruins always have _ and
always will _ prefer warp speed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the top-10 rankings, the matchup lacked the national
significance of the UCLA-Arizona collisions throughout the '90s.
Neither team is expected to challenge for a high NCAA Tournament
seed or the Pac-10 title; that is Stanford's domain until proven
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, though, the pressure was on UCLA. Because road wins
will be scarce, the Bruins must protect their homecourt like a
small child. For confidence and momentum purposes, as well, they
viewed Saturday as critical to their long-term success.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a message-type game,'' Bruins guard Rico
Hines said. ``It's a chance to set the tone for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats and Bruins entered the game as equals in youth and
(questionable) credentials. UCLA faced its toughest foes in
November and hadn't been challenged since Oklahoma State four weeks
ago. However, Arizona's schedule featured a slew of lightweights,
and that inexperienced showed in the early going as the Bruins
jumped to a 13-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The margin was a slight surprise considering UCLA's starting
lineup. Reserves Farnham, Rico Hines and Travis Reed started
because they were fit for practice Thursday, whereas Jerome Moiso
and Dan Gadzuric apparently were not. Frustrated, coach Steve Lavin
hauled the Bruins into the locker room and declared: ``The five
guys who practiced are starting.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl Watson and Davis controlled the pace from the outset. Davis
opened the game with a 3-pointer from the left wing, Watson found
Farnham for a layup, then buried a 3-pointer himself for an 8-2.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum shifted several times early in the first half _
UCLA pulling to eight- and 10-points leads, then Arizona edging
close.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins made their first big push with eight minutes left,
when Reed converted back-to-back layins. On the next possession,
one of UCLA's best, Ryan Bailey sliced through the defense and
passed to a hard-charging Matt Barnes for a layup. A few seconds
later, Bailey drained a 3-pointer from the right wing, then Moiso
canned a difficult turnaround to give the Bruins a 32-19 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso struck again with 2:15 left, hitting a 3-pointer from the
top of the key as the shot clock expired. Watson scored on a leaner
from the right side for a 16-point lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 0149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5892 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN     01-03 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE RUNS OUT OF STEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ Some of the reasoning may have centered
around the exertion of energy needed to come back from a 20-point
deficit in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor may have been the 7,000-foot altitude of Walkup
Skydome, which winds a person just walking up the stairs. Imagine
the effect it has on a basketball player not used to the
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cal State Northridge coach Bobby Braswell would have
none of that after the Matadors were blitzed in overtime Saturday
and fell to defending Big Sky champ Northern Arizona 96-79 in the
league opener.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Land scored five of his game-high 23 points in overtime,
when the Matadors were outscored 21-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, we laid a big egg in overtime,'' Braswell said. ``We came
out and they took it to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's my take on (fatigue). When you have a chance to win a
basketball game, and you've got five minutes to go in overtime,
fatigue makes cowards of us all. You either give in to fatigue, or
you say, `I've got plenty of time to rest tonight. I've got five
minutes to win a basketball game.' That's hopefully what they
learned.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks, winners of 20 straight at home, scored 18 of
the final 21 points while the defensive intensity that allowed CSUN
(8-5, 0-1 Big Sky) to force the extra session disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (past success) has something to do with this,''
Lumberjacks coach Ben Howland said. ``Our guys expect to win. They
know they're going to win. That's a sign of a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a game Braswell put a lot of stock into, and it should be
interesting to see how CSUN rebounds for its conference home opener
Monday against Idaho State.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors came to Arizona on Thursday so not be distracted by
the New Year's holiday, and to get accustomed to the surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   The significance was to use Northern Arizona as a barometer for
where the Matadors stand in the conference. The Lumberjacks (9-3)
won back-to-back league titles and went to the NCAAs last season.
And with most of that team back, the Lumberjacks are overwhelming
picks to win the conference again.
</P>
<P>
   But CSUN's improbable second-half comeback was overshadowed by
the ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get outscored 21-4 in overtime, that's not acceptable,''
said CSUN power forward Rico Harris, who scored 16 of his 21 points
after halftime. ``No excuses. They outworked us. We had a chance to
actually win and we let up. We had an opportunity, played hard,
came back and overtime it seemed like we let up.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Matadors were brutal in overtime, but it was an
extra five minutes that shouldn't have existed.
</P>
<P>
   If the Matadors played as strong and tenacious on defense during
the first 25 minutes, they never would have trailed 54-34 early in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   And if Northern Arizona didn't melt in its prosperity, Derrick
Higgins' 3-pointer from the corner with 26.3 seconds left in
regulation wouldn't have meant a darn thing. Instead, it tied the
score at 75-75, and overtime was forced when Land's 3-point attempt
at the buzzer fell short.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had momentum,'' a disgusted Higgins said. ``We're in shape.
It had nothing to do with the altitude.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time CSUN regained its bearings from the frantic finish
of regulation, Northern Arizona had scored a pair of easy baskets
and made four foul shots to take an 86-77 lead with 2:28 left.
After a follow of a missed shot by CSUN's Jeff Parris, the
Lumberjacks scored the last 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw our guys jumping up and celebrating going into
overtime and I think we thought that was it,'' Braswell said. ``We
got to overtime and (Northern Arizona) was going to fold. There's a
reason they're champions, a reason they won the championship two
years in a row. They know how to get through adversity, and,
obviously, we haven't learned to deal with that yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
