<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON'S PLAY A WELCOME SIGHT FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Kings enforcer Matt Johnson will never
develop into a 40-goal scorer in the NHL. But in Wednesday night's
victory over San Jose, Johnson scored his second goal of the season
with the type of play opposing teams would be hard-pressed to stop.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 Johnson gained body position on Sharks defenseman
Bob Rouse _ a large player himself at 6-2 _ in front of the San
Jose net and had only to get his stick on a centering pass from Ian
Laperriere to deflect the puck past goalie Mike Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Larry Robinson said if Johnson wants to make an
impact in the NHL beyond the reputation he's gained as a fighter,
plays such as the one he made against San Jose will have to appear
more frequently in his repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to kind of compare Matty to a Bob Probert (of
Chicago) or a Donald Brashear (of Vancouver),'' Robinson said. ``In
order to play now, you have to do more than just fight. If he wants
to model himself after anyone, those are two guys who worked to get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Johnson's goal against San Jose, Robinson said, ``That's
size, and getting the right position. If you know what to do with
the puck, that's a pretty big mountain to move.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had six goals and 599 penalty minutes in 151 NHL games
before Saturday's game against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Aching Avs: &UR; !off! &LR;  Colorado center Joe Sakic returned to
the lineup after missing seven games with a sprained shoulder, but
the Avalanche remains without defenseman Alexei Gusarov (broken
finger), goalie Patrick Roy (sprained knee) and wingers Shjon
Podein (fractured leg), Warren Rychel (broken hand) and Jon Klemm
(torn patella tendon).
</P>
<P>
   Roy is doubtful for Colorado's game Monday night against his
former team, the Montreal Canadiens. After a slow start, Roy had
regained his form before being injured eight days ago against
Dallas. He owns a 10-12-3 record with a 2.28 goals-against average,
two shutouts and a 91.2 save percentage.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche has lost 167 games to injury this season, two more
than the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Winger Steve McKenna, sidelined with an abdominal
strain, will undergo abdominal surgery Monday and is expected to be
sidelined at least two more months.... Defenseman Doug Bodger
missed his second game with the cervical strain and bruised
shoulder he suffered Monday when checked from behind by Phoenix's
Dallas Drake, who received a four-game suspension from the NHL for
the hit. Bodger is receiving electrical stimulation on the injured
area. He had said Friday morning that he generally wakes up feeling
sore and gets better as the day progresses. That wasn't the case
Friday. ``It was a bad day,'' Bodger said. ``He's going to miss
four games and I may miss five.''... Former Mighty Ducks coach
Pierre Page scouted the game for the Nashville Predators.
</P>
</TEXT>
