<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5898 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     01-03 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S ROOKIES GIVE VETERAN EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Steve Lavin had been coaching the UCLA football
team during Friday's Rose Bowl, we're pretty sure he would have
started Vae Tata and Cheyane Caldwell on defense. It might not have
changed the game's outcome any, but at least there would have been
no questioning anybody's effort.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is dawning on the players that Lavin demands it, but
whatever the reason the Bruins' effort at both ends of the floor in
their Pacific-10 opener against Arizona Saturday night was very
crisp. Indeed, No.10 UCLA ironed out enough of the wrinkles that
had surfaced in the second half of a loss to Maryland, for example,
and in both halves of a win over American University to upset the
previously unbeaten Wildcats, 82-75.
</P>
<P>
   It was a huge win for the Bruins (9-2) _ who lost both games to
Arizona last season and one of two the season before _ and one
small victory for Lavin. If there's one thing the Bruins'
third-year head basketball coach hates worse than an unpressed
dress shirt it's a practice without a lot of starch in it. On New
Year's Eve, Lavin didn't like the unfastidious play of some of his
would-be starters.
</P>
<P>
   So guess what? When the Bruins tipped off against the
sixth-ranked Wildcats, freshman Jerome Moiso was on the bench, just
like classmate JaRon Rush, who was in street clothes after missing
two practices and one game earlier in the week while in the throes
of homesickness.
</P>
<P>
   You could be cynical and say that by benching Rush _ the squad's
third-leading scorer _ for all of the Arizona game, Lavin was
providing the Bruins with a handy alibi in the event the game went
badly.
</P>
<P>
   But then you see that walk-on Sean Farnham has been inserted
into the starting lineup against a perennial Pac-10 power in a game
the Bruins absolutely, positively needed to take control of from
the opening tipoff and you have to say this for Lavin: he's as
dogged as Paul Revere in delivering his message of accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso, whose spot in the opening lineup Farnham took, seemed to
get the word. He spelled the junior a little more than three
minutes into the game _ the Bruins already were ahead 13-4 with one
of the baskets coming from Farnham _ and accounted for 12 of the
Bruins' final 27 points in the half.
</P>
<P>
   He would finish with a team-high 21 points and eight rebounds
and then acknowledge, ``I took the lesson (Lavin) sent. I was ready
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there any hint of a limp or lethargy from Dan Gadzuric.
If the tendinitis in both his knees was bothering him, the
6-foot-10 freshman center sure didn't show any signs of it. He was
a pain in the paint for the Wildcats at both ends of the court and
the way he ran down loose balls you would have thought his name was
Gazelle.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats (8-1) have a wonderful freshman class of their own
and coach Lute Olson, like Lavin, went to them early. Before the
game was eight minutes old there were six freshmen sharing the
court. The only place you're likely to see that many freshmen on
one floor is on the Tuesday primetime drama, ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona first-year player Michael Wright didn't do a whole lot
wrong. He finished with 14 points and his classmate Ruben Douglas,
who attended Bell-Jeff High, added 11.
</P>
<P>
   But Round One of a dogfight that should get even scrappier in
the months and years to come clearly belonged to Moiso, Gadzuric,
Ray Young and Matt Barnes, even if they did combine to outscore the
Wildcats' freshmen by only one (36-35).
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' freshmen brought a lot more energy to the task,
which is to be expected given that they had a rowdy home crowd to
feed off of. And yet, even in the final seconds when it got as
quiet as it did all night because the Wildcats were finishing with
a flurry, Moiso showed no dropoff in his energy level.
</P>
<P>
   He outbattled Wildcats freshman Richard Jefferson for the game's
last rebound to stifle Arizona's surge. No sooner had his sneakers
touched back down on the court than the Pauley Pavilion crowd of
11,453 started serenading Arizona with an exuberant ``Overrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but that's pretty much the same thing Arizona coach Lute
Olson had been screaming to anyone who would listen in the days
leading up to the game.
</P>
<P>
   He called the Wildcats' national ranking ``a joke'' because they
hadn't played any quality opponents. UCLA wanted to make darn sure
the Wildcats wouldn't be able to say that today. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
