A5901 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-CARDIN     01-03 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-CARDINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WE'RE HERE': CARDS' WIN WONDROUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ How long did you hold your breath? &QL; 
Did you turn Cardinals red, then metallic blue?
</P>
<P>
   When did you finally quit watching the clock and wringing your
hands and realize that oh, my goodness, bless their hearts, they're
really going to do it?
</P>
<P>
   Go on, e-x-h-a-l-e.
</P>
<P>
   Now, breathe in. Deeply. Fill your lungs with the fresh clean
air of a new era.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're new. We're here,'' Jake Plummer said, coining the motto
and battle cry of a young and resourceful team that Saturday
finally and convincingly beat the Dallas Cowboys and gave the Wild
Cards their first NFL playoff victory in 51 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   To save you figuring the math, the year was 19-and-47.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Truman was president.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Robinson broke into the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Al Capone died.
</P>
<P>
   Informed of this historical footnote, Lomas Brown, who dressed
after the game in a chalk-striped suit like one Scarface might have
been buried in, looked around the locker room. A room which for so
many years was the Cardinals concrete tomb.
</P>
<P>
   Lomas took in the happy faces. He repeated the score, 20-7,
tasting it, turning it over on his tongue like a candy mint. He
felt the love. He breathed in, savoring the aroma of Jamir Miller's
ridiculous foot-long cigar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet Al turned over today,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen forty-seven.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill was 16 years old when the family
franchise won the title. Bidwill worked the game as a water boy.
</P>
<P>
   Know what movie won the Oscar for best screenplay in '47? ``The
Miracle on'' ``34th Street.'' If pounding the Cowboys in the
playoffs at Texas Stadium _ next week it's on to Minnesota _
doesn't qualify as a miracle, it's at least a wondrous achievement.
The Cards hadn't won here since 1989. They had lost to the Cowboys
16 of 17 times _ twice this season.
</P>
<P>
   But here's a stat for you. Since trailing Dallas 28-0 in that
Nov. 15 game in Tempe, the Cardinals outscored the NFC East
champions, 48-14.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas mathematicians said this wasn't supposed to happen.
Most prognosticators figured the Cardinals would come in and behave
like wide-eyed novices who were just happy to be here.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had playoff experience; the Cards didn't. The
Cowboys had Troy Aikman and Emmitt Smith and Michael Irvin and yes,
Deion Sanders, whose injured big toe apparently and miraculously
healed overnight, for there he was starting at cornerback after a
six-week absence. For Dallas fans, his return was reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   Then the game started.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bidwill carried the water in '47. This time the Cardinals
defense did. Aeneas Williams intercepted two Aikman passes. Tommy
Bennett got got the third. Rookie Corey Chavous, making only his
fifth start, played the game of his life. The secondary's pass
coverage was tighter than Deion's blue do-rag.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals shut out the Cowboys for 56{ minutes, and one play
in particular characterized the defense's tenacity and resolve. In
the second quarter with the Cards leading 7-0, Dallas gambled on
fourth-and-one from the Arizona seven. Linebacker Mark Maddox
dropped Smith for a one-yard loss. The crowd groaned like an old
mattress. Later, restless fans began to boo. Eventually, most
headed for the aisles, and drifted off silently into the cold
night.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen forty-seven.
</P>
<P>
   The date means nothing to players named Plummer and Sanders and
Murrell. They live in the present and play for the moment, and all
three contributed in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   There was Plummer throwing downfield to Sanders, who reached up
with his right hand like an outfielder and brought the ball down,
never breaking stride _ a 59-yard play. There was Plummer
delivering a shovel pass to Adrian Murrell, which worked like a
charm for the Cards' first touchdown. Perfect call.
</P>
<P>
   Murrell wasn't finished. In the third period, he popped through
the line like a champagne cork. His 74-yard run was the Cardinals'
longest play of the season, and it led to a touchdown and a 17-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   How good did this feel? The game over, Larry Centers reached out
and grabbed a TV crew's boom mike. Drawing its fuzzy caterpillar
cover to his face, he closed his eyes and playfully rubbed it
against his cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Center Mike Devlin smiled at a family photo taped to his
cubicle. Devlin's dad died last year. For every Cardinals game,
home and away, Devlin has purchased one ticket. There was one empty
seat at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father,'' Devlin said, ``had the best seat in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   John Omohundro wasn't with the Cardinals in 1947. But he's been
with the team since 1966. As trainer, he knows better than anyone
the pain of losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, long time,'' Omohundro said, eyes shining
with joy.
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Is this worth it?
</P>
<P>
   Omohundro nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer the wait,'' he said, ``the sweeter the wine.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 0233EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
