<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY HURT IN KINGS' VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ It had been a virtual morgue as recently as one week
earlier, but as Saturday night began, the Forum was as lively as it
had been all season, with the Kings leading _ and dominating _ the
Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were in control, and now, right wing Glen Murray, the
team's second-leading scorer and best all-around forward, was using
a burst of speed to beat Avalanche defenseman Aaron Miller to a
loose puck deep in Colorado's zone.
</P>
<P>
   When they reached the puck, Miller hit Murray with a clean, hard
check, riding him into the end boards. But the landing was a bad
one. Murray came down awkwardly, his right leg bent behind him,
with Miller on top.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, 12:48 into a game that had begun so well for the
Kings, the liveliness of the Forum crowd of 13,553 was replaced by
silence, by the sight of Murray screaming in pain and banging the
boards with his hands, and by the realization that on a night when
the Kings were on their way to a 4-2 victory, they had suffered yet
another serious injury to a key player.
</P>
<P>
   It's been the story of their season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you sick to your stomach when you see a guy hurt like
that,'' center Ray Ferraro said later, after scoring the Kings'
first and third goals.
</P>
<P>
   Murray _ who has 15 goals, 13 assists and 28 points, second on
the team in all categories to Luc Robitaille _ suffered a severe
sprain of the medial collateral ligament in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   After being examined on the ice by team physician Dr. Ronald
Kvitne, Murray was removed by stretcher and taken to Centinela
Hospital Medical Center. Initial X-rays were negative, and Murray
was scheduled to undergo a magnetic resonance imaging examination
late Saturday night. It was not clear how long Murray would be
sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt about it, it's devastating,'' coach Larry
Robinson said. ``But losing two starting goaltenders and Rob Blake
was devastating, as well. We've still got games to play. All we can
hope is that it's not that serious and he's back soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Blake, who missed 15 games earlier this season with a
broken foot: ``We've got a major hurdle with Muzz going out. That's
our best player right now. We can't afford to lose a guy like that.
You can't replace what he does for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury to Murray comes at a time when the Kings, who won for
the fifth time in their last six games and have won three games in
a row for the first time this season, appeared to have put behind
them the injury hex of the season's first three months.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling to score goals in the early part of the year,
the Kings' offense _ which had consisted of Murray, Robitaille and
not much else _ has become more balanced recently. And Saturday's
victory over the Avalanche (16-18-3) marked the sixth consecutive
game in which the Kings (13-21-3) have allowed two or fewer goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings went ahead for good 2:40 into the game when defenseman
Mark Visheau fired the puck from the right point, and Ferraro
deflected it past Colorado goalie Craig Billington.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, Robitaille scored on a power play, the 497th
goal of his career and his team-high 19th goal this season, three
more than he scored in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro scored the lone goal of the second period, off a
goalmouth scramble at 8:29. Jozef Stumpel made it 4-0 early in the
third period, and Chris Drury and Adam Foote scored late for the
Avalanche, wrecking Jamie Storr's shutout bid.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray's injury took much of the luster off the Kings'
latest strong effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no dirty hit,'' Robinson said. ``It was just the way he
went in. Murray kind of lost his balance and went down funny.
(After the play) both sides took some time to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how long it will take the Kings to recover
from their latest setback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 0237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
