<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 02:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5905 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LA     01-03 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA BEATS ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With their archrivals on the court and their former teammates
hovering nearby, the new-era UCLA Bruins severed the final ties to
their past in crowded, energized Pauley Pavilion on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Johnson, Toby Bailey and Jelani McCoy watched from a corner
of the arena as Baron Davis and friends delivered their most
significant win of the season _ an 82-75 victory over No. 6 Arizona
that was far more convincing than the score indicated.
</P>
<P>
   The new era officially began in November, of course, but until
Saturday night these Bruins had nothing of consequence to call
their own _ nothing to stand atop their fledgling resume in big,
bold print.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game pushes us over the top,'' Davis said. ``It's a win
over a top-10 team, which we didn't have until this point. To get
that under our belt will really give us confidence for the rest of
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 10 UCLA never trailed _ charging to a 20-point lead in the
second half, then repelling a late Arizona rally. The Bruins (9-2,
1-0) played with hyper-aggression not seen this season. Some of it
was wasted motion, to be sure. But where previous Arizona teams
were savvy and talented enough to counteract UCLA's energy, these
Wildcats had no answers.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman forward Michael Wright (14 points, 10 rebounds) often
was one man against five as Arizona's freshman guards were
paralyzed by the intensity of their first conference road game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half, they played like they were scared to
death,'' Wildcats coach Lute Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   His seniors, A.J. Bramlett and Jason Terry, were ineffective
until the late going. Terry, perhaps the best guard in the Pac-10,
finished with 19 points, but nine came in the last, desperate five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 61-40, the Wildcats pulled within single digits with
three minutes remaining. They were within 81-75 with 20 seconds
left when a botched possession ended their comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get the ball out of Terry's hands and make the
other guys beat us,'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins beat Arizona to every loose ball and seemed to be in
two places at once, so much quicker were they. For both teams the
ballhandling was sloppy and the pace frenzied. That combination
created the type of playground atmosphere UCLA has thrived in for
years.
</P>
<P>
   But these Bruins not only played like previous editions, they
played for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant a lot to us to see Kris, Jelani and Toby over there
and to beat Arizona for them,'' guard Rico Hines said. ``We know
how much they hate Arizona. We gave those guys something they
didn't get last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a statement game.''
</P>
<P>
   No one represents the changing dynamics of UCLA _ and this
rivalry _ better than the Bruins' freshman forward, Jerome Moiso. A
native of Guadeloupe who was educated in France, Moiso knows little
of the passion play that defined the Arizona-UCLA series throughout
the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really into those feelings,'' Moiso said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins made him aware of the importance of Saturday's
game, and he responded with a game-high 21 points, making 7 of 11
shots and grabbing eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played confident today,'' he said. ``Coming from the bench,
I knew I had to bring more energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins played without suspended forward JaRon Rush, who is
expected back for Monday's game against Arizona State. In addition,
Moiso and center Dan Gadzuric began the game on the bench after
they missed Thursday's practice. Sean Farnham made his first-ever
start, joining Hines, Travis Reed, Earl Watson and Davis to form
UCLA's oldest _ and most unusual _ lineup of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to send a message to the players,'' Lavin said.
``We're 14 deep, and you've got to play hard every day. Farnham and
Hines have such a great work ethic on a daily basis, I thought it
was important to reward them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was also our oldest (lineup), with four sophomores and a
junior. For a conference game, they understood the level of
intensity, and it gave the other guys a chance to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats and Bruins entered the game as equals in youth and
questionable credentials. UCLA faced its toughest foes in November
and hadn't been challenged since Oklahoma State four weeks ago.
However, Arizona's schedule featured a slew of lightweights, and
that inexperience showed in the early going as the Bruins jumped to
a 13-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play like an Arizona team in the first half,'' Olson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum shifted several times in the opening minutes _ UCLA
pulling to eight- and 10-points leads, then Arizona edging close.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins made their first big push with eight minutes left,
when Reed converted back-to-back layins. On the next possession,
one of UCLA's best, Ryan Bailey sliced through the defense and
passed to a hard-charging Matt Barnes for a layup. A few seconds
later, Bailey drained a 3-pointer from the right wing, then Moiso
canned a difficult turnaround to give the Bruins a 32-19 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso struck again with 2:15 left, hitting a 3-pointer from the
top of the key as the shot clock expired. Watson scored on a leaner
from the right side for a 16-point lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
