<HEADLINE>
ASU WOMEN FALL TO TROJANS  
 REBOUNDING IS KEY FOR USC 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theresa Jantzen and Leah Combs had not yet turned 2 when Arizona
State last won a women's basketball game over Southern California
at home.
</P>
<P>
   If either of the 18-year-old freshmen posts were healthy enough
to play Saturday, that losing streak might have ended. Instead, USC
used a 23-14 advantage on the offensive boards, and Coach Chris
Gobrecht's familiar defensive intensity to win, 67-54, in the
Pac-10 opener for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave up the weak-side board all game,'' ASU Coach Charli
Turner Thorne said. ``It pains me to no end to watch the display of
rebounding we gave. If you take away the second shots, we win by 10
to 15 points.''
</P>
<P>
   With the 6-foot-2 Combs, the Pac-10's fourth-leading rebounder
(9.5 per game), on crutches because of stress fractures in both
legs and the 6-3 Jantzen limited to warm-ups as she recovers from a
fractured left foot, ASU opened in a zone to stay with the athletic
Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   USC shot 39.5 percent in the first half and even lower (34.4) in
the second, when the Sun Devils went to a man-to-man defense. ASU
made the change after trailing, 36-24, at halftime, the result of
USC's 15-6 edge in offensive rebounds and 16 ASU turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to force the turnover was important for us,''
Gobrecht said. ``And the boards were the difference in the first
half.''
</P>
<P>
   USC (5-5) scored nine of the final 11 points before
intermission, four by freshman guard Tiffany Elmore, to put ASU
(6-4) in a hole that only increased its offensive impatience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them we needed to take a big, fat chill pill on
offense,'' Turner Thorne said. ``I guess that pill dissolved before
tip-off.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristine Sand, starting at power forward in place of Combs, had
16 of her 20 points in the first half, but the other ASU starters
were a combined 0 for 8 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Center Rachel Holt, limited by three fouls to just nine
first-half minutes, scored seven of her nine points in the second
half, and forward Kisha White had eight in her season debut, but
the perimeter never caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Natalie Tucker's nine assists were more than offset
by 10 turnovers. Her USC counterpart, Kristen Clark, had eight
assists and four turnovers. The Trojans recorded an 18-8 edge in
steals.
</P>
<P>
   USC 6-4 senior center Adrain Williams had another big game
against ASU with a game-high 22 points and eight rebounds.
Sophomore forward Tashara Carter had 10 points and 10 boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the kind of things she (Carter) needs to do for
us,'' Gobrecht said. ``She has an excellent basketball body. She
was the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils' best chance to rally came with the score 42-31,
when USC commited its seventh team foul, with 13:59 remaining. But
Kitch Kitchen missed the first of a one-and-one, and a steal by
Carter triggered a three-point play by Williams and 10-2 run that
closed the door.
</P>
<P>
   Now ASU must rebound against ninth-ranked UCLA (9-4, 1-0), which
held off Arizona on Saturday. That game is at 7 p.m. Tuesday,
pushed back a day because of the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both the kind of teams that are going to give this
conference some fits,'' Gobrecht said. ``I wouldn't be surprised if
ASU gets the Bruins.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
