<SLUG> BC-HKN-MCMANAMAN-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYER SAYS FIGHTS GO WITH HOCKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Louie DeBrusk has been up, down and all around this season in
the Coyotes' organization. In the past month, in fact, the
6-foot-2, 235-pound enforcer has changed teams seven times and
changed leagues three times.
</P>
<P>
   From Las Vegas to Springfield. From Springfield to Las Vegas.
From Las Vegas to Phoenix. Back to Las Vegas. Back up to Phoenix.
And ditto twice more. Until Friday, that is, when he was sent back
to the minors after the 2-1 overtime loss to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Before his most recent short stint in the NHL, however, DeBrusk
had some interesting observations that bear repeating. The
conversation shifted to fighting, and DeBrusk, who has collected
153 penalty minutes in 24 games for Las Vegas, was asked how he
feels when fans say the NHL should abolish fisticuffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be totally honest with you, I'd like to meet these people
because I'd love to watch them when a fight happens on the ice and
see what they're doing,'' DeBrusk said. ``Do they really close
their eyes and put their hands up over their face? . . . I'll bet
you their mouths are wide open and they're watching the fight in
awe just like everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never ever to this day met someone that's come up to me
and told me that fighting should be taken out of the game. This is
my eighth year of pro hockey, and I've never had a fan say that. I
know they're out there, but whoever these people are who are saying
this, they just want to create controversy and say what they're
going to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game's changed, I'll grant them that. You can't just be an
enforcer anymore. You've got to be able to play the trap. You've
got to be able to skate. You've got to be able to play good
defensively. And you've got to be a good team guy. If you don't
have those four or five qualities, you're not going to play in the
NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   The game, though, will always allow for rough play, DeBrusk
said. Hard hits are a part of the game. So is intimidation and the
threat of intimidation. So, too, is the occasional fight. Without
it, the star, skilled players would be potential victims every
night.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky has long been in support of banning fighting, but
don't forget, the Great One always had a thug skating on his wing
for protection, whether it was Marty McSorley or Dave Semenko.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say 99.9 percent of the fans like to see a fight, whether
they believe it or not,'' said DeBrusk, who has dropped the gloves
14 times this season for Las Vegas. ``I'm not condoning it or
saying young kids should go out there and play aggressive hockey
and drop your gloves and fight the next kid that gives you a dirty
look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just saying, `Look, it's a physical game and it's going to
happen.' When there's a bench-clearing brawl in baseball, nobody
seems to rant and rave about it. But a couple guys . . . slug it
out, I mean, it's one of the most exciting things in sports. It's
great entertainment. I don't care what anyone says.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are afraid to say it, but myself, I sit down and watch
hockey fights on video all the time. I just love them. I think
they're great. And I respect every guy who drops his gloves. My
hat's off to anybody that's willing to do that.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Trades-R-Us &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The slumping Chicago Blackhawks continue to shake up things in
an effort to get out of their funk. General Manager Bob Murray made
two more trades last week, including a deal that sent veteran Paul
Coffey to Carolina for Nelson Emerson. That move, Murray said, was
a direct result of inconsistent play by youngsters Eric Daze, Chad
Kilger and Ethan Moreau.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation has been well-documented,'' Murray said, ``so I
have to get players who can play with the (Alexei) Zhamnovs and
(Doug) Gilmours now. I hear we're putting too much pressure on the
kids and they don't have the confidence. That's horse (expletive).
It's having a passion for the game. You've been playing hockey
since you were 4 or 5 years old and either you want to win or you
don't. . . . It doesn't seem that losing bothers some of these
guys.' '
</P>
<P>
   Expect to see Kilger, Daze or Moreau dealt before the March
trading deadline. Ditto, perhaps, captain Chris Chelios, who's
become a Windy City landmark. About the only safe Blackhawk at the
moment is Tony Amonte. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Only human &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After his team got shut out by the Buffalo Sabres last week,
Tampa Bay Lightning Coach Jacques Demers boldly pronounced,
``Dominik Hasek is God.''
</P>
<P>
   Three nights later, Hasek got shelled by New Jersey,
surrendering four early goals before getting pulled in a 7-4 rout
in which he gave up three scores on the Devils' first three shots.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night against Anaheim, the Dominator got waxed again,
7-2. This time, Coach Lindy Ruff didn't do Hasek any favors and
left in his star goalie for the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with the two-time defending Hart Trophy winner?
Maybe nothing. Sources, however, say his focus might be distracted
because of a serious back injury to his wife, who just underwent
surgery after a reported fall down the stairs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Unforgettable play &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time you saw a player put a puck into his own
net from the other end of the rink during a delayed penalty? It
happened Tuesday to Edmonton's Janne Niinimaa during a game against
Montreal. His blind pass banked off the side boards and went 180
feet before finding the net.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Recchi, who had been called for tripping moments earlier,
was credited with the goal because he was the last Montreal player
to touch the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a brutal feeling,'' said Oilers goalie Bob Essensa, the
backup that night.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton GM Glen Sather was involved in a similar play several
years ago while playing for the Pittsburgh Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the one and only night I got a hat trick in the
NHL,'' Sather said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, Sather said, was initially credited to a teammate. Two
days later, the NHL officially changed the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it was a write-in hat trick,'' Sather joked. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
