<HEADLINE>
WNHL ON HORIZON?  
 SOURCES: NHL LIKELY TO START WOMEN'S LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the WNBA's more popular slogans is ``We got next.''
</P>
<P>
   Could women ice hockey players be next in line to shout a
similar catch phrase? According to high-level sources in the NHL,
there is a better than 75 percent chance that a women's
professional league will make its debut in North America within the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed league, which has yet to go public with its
intentions and still is in the formative stages, apparently will
mirror the WNBA in principle. For it to succeed, it will need the
financial support and sponsorship of the NHL and, like the WNBA,
franchises likely will be owned and operated by NHL owners.
</P>
<P>
   The league may also take on a similar name as the WNBA _ the
WNHL.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL hasn't formally attached itself to the idea as yet. NHL
officials want to proceed cautiously, sources said, because of
financial burdens affecting franchises such as the Pittsburgh
Penguins, the New York Islanders and a few teams in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get those problems solved, I think it'll be a go,''
one NHL executive said. ``Look, there's no reason to rush this
thing. It wouldn't be fair to the women, and it certainly wouldn't
be fair to the NHL clubs who are going through some tough times
right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need stability first in a few places. Then we can go on the
fly with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Two NHL owners said privately they support the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Cammi Granato, the captain of the 1998 gold medal-winning U.S.
Olympic women's team, expressed guarded optimism when informed
about the proposed league.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more news than I've ever heard,'' said Granato, in her
first season as a radio analyst for the Los Angeles Kings. ``I
mean, I've heard there have been talks about a pro league, but that
there were concerns about the financial backing. But if an NHL
owner is saying that, that's definitely something to get excited
about. That's what it's going to take to get something like that
off the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix has been mentioned as one of the six to eight target
cities the league hopes to initially attract in its first year. An
NHL source said the Valley probably wouldn't get a franchise unless
the Coyotes move out of America West Arena and into a building of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   The women's team would help fill needed dates at the new arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we as athletes would love it,'' said Granato, the
career leading scorer in U.S. women's national team history and
women's international hockey history. ``And I couldn't dream of
anything better.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not going to work at the pro level unless somebody
gets involved like the NHL or a big corporation. Right now, I
thought with so much expansion (in the NHL) and them trying to get
the attendance up in all of the new buildings, the NHL had a lot of
different things to worry about. So I didn't really foresee
anything like this happening. But maybe I just wasn't thinking
positively enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of not want to get your hopes up too much.
Realistically, I think it's still some time away. But don't get me
wrong, it would be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Granato said the league would have to be careful where it places
teams. For instance, she isn't so sure it would sell in Los
Angeles. Or even Boston, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is a place where you'd think a million people will show
up for hockey because everyone's a hockey fan,'' she said. ``But I
don't think it would work in Boston because people are hometown
fans there. They love their Red Sox. They love their Celtics. They
love their Bruins. And that's it. That's not going to change. So
you have to be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Are there enough talented female players to field an entire pro
league? Granato says absolutely. All they are waiting for is an
opportunity to shout ``We got next'' like their basketball sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory is you only need 15 players on a team, too,''
Granato said. ``You don't need 20.''
</P>
<P>
   If the WNHL becomes a reality, Granato may have a difficult
choice to make. Would she stay in broadcasting, a job she has been
getting rave reviews for, or would she ditch the headphones for a
helmet and hit the ice?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, let me just say that first of all, I've been honored to
have this opportunity, and I feel fortunate to have this
opportunity,'' Granato said of her job with the Kings. ``The
organization could not be better to me. Everybody's been so first
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``But obviously as an athlete, my dream when I was a kid was to
be a professional hockey player, too. So if there was a chance to
play in a league, you'd better believe I'd be there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 0303EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
