<HEADLINE>
SUN DEVILS COLLAPSE  
 TROJANS RALLY IN PAC-10 OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
  STATE-USC-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The returning Arizona State players who didn't
want to be reminded of the 46-point loss to Southern California in
the Pac-10 finale last year, who found it absolutely irrelevant to
the present, were right. This ``is'' a new team and a new season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils proved that Saturday by grabbing an 18-point lead
in the first half against the Trojans. But then they let it get
away and the result, achieved differently, turned out the same as
USC came back to win, 72-70, at the Sports Arena in the conference
opener and Pac-10 debut of first-year Coach Rob Evans.
</P>
<P>
   In a complete role-reversal from last year's game here, the Sun
Devils led, 38-20, with 3:43 left in the first half. But then ASU
went scoreless the rest of the half and the Trojans cut the lead to
nine.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils went up by 14 after the break, then it was all
USC. Led by the inside-outside combination of Brian Scalabrine and
Elias Ayuso, the Trojans shot 63 percent in the second half and
snapped the Sun Devils' six-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine, a 6-foot-9 sophomore forward who transferred after
playing a year in junior college, made 10 of 12 shots and had 25
points, 16 after halftime. Ayuso, a 6-2 senior guard who had a
career-high 25 points in last year's blowout, made 4 of 7
three-point shots and scored 18 points, more than twice his
average.
</P>
<P>
   ASU (8-5) committed 11 of its 18 turnovers in the second half
after the Trojans (9-1) got out of an early box-and-one focused on
Eddie House, which didn't work. And when Scalabrine and Ayuso
weren't scoring in the half-court game, USC beat the Sun Devils
down the floor for easy baskets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of mistakes,'' said forward Bobby Lazor, who had
19 points and eight rebounds for the Sun Devils before fouling out
with 11 seconds left. ``They kind of turned up their defense and
ran a run-and-jump sort of thing. They were switching a lot and I
think for stretches, we tried to force things and turned it over or
didn't get a good shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Evans, ``USC was switching defenses on us. We stood around
too much in the second half and didn't execute. We took some quick
shots. We also got too tentative out there, and it hurt us. . . .
We didn't attack the basket like we should have and make them pay
for trapping us.''
</P>
<P>
   House, who began the game averaging 21.2 points and leading the
conference in scoring, made just 2 of 10 shots and had 11 points.
He never got untracked even after USC got out of its box-and-one,
which the Sun Devils exploited to take their big lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played great defense, but I was missing shots I usually
hit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   House, who scored his 1,000th career point, still was in
position to tie the score or even win it after Jarvis Turner missed
a pair of free throws with seven seconds left and USC up by two.
But Quincy Wilder poked the ball from House in the Trojans' end,
and Alton Mason traveled trying to save it, denying ASU a final
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   House played in foul trouble for much of the second half. So did
senior forward Mike Batiste, who along with House and Lazor gave
the Sun Devils three players averaging more than 18 points a game.
Batiste had 14 points and just five rebounds, the third straight
game in which he has had five rebounds or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Rebounding was a point of contention for Evans, even though ASU
had a 30-27 edge on the boards and outrebounded its ninth straight
opponent. USC had six of its seven offensive rebounds in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the middle of the second half we didn't do a good job
boxing them out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to play smarter, we've got to execute and we've got
to take care of details. You take care of details _ box out, handle
the basketball _ then you win these ballgames on the road.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
