r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARIZONA_UCLA-AZR &LR;      01-03 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA_UCLA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA DOWNS ARIZONA  
 BRUINS TAKE EARLY BIG LEAD, HOLD ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For every action, there is always a very opposite
UCLA basketball reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the unpredictable bunch, the Bruins kept up the reputation
in Saturday's Pac-10 opener against Arizona, despite enough
distractions to make Coach Steve Lavin's hair crack.
</P>
<P>
   A star freshman was suspended, another could not start because
of the flu, practices were lackluster, and the undefeated Wildcats
were in town. But for a team younger than junior college squads,
10th-ranked UCLA sure looked cool in turning sixth-ranked Arizona
cold and holding the Wildcats off for a 82-75 victory at sold-out
Pauley Pavillion.
</P>
<P>
   The youthful Bruins (9-2) came out fired up and turned delirious
when it jumped on Arizona (8-1) quickly.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of early three-pointers helped UCLA jump ahead, 8-2,
but it was the Baron Davis-Earl Watson backcourt chewing up Arizona
with penetration from there, whether the Wildcats played man or
zone. Seventeen of UCLA's next 19 points came underneath the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Wildcats were bumbling the ball like a team that
had not seen a quality opponent in a month. Arizona committed 11
first-half turnovers, but made matters worse by missing what easy
chances it did get in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   A 54 percent shooter entering Saturday, A.J. Bramlett had a
five-point first half that included four misses on the post, an air
ball jumper and two layups. His center counterpart, ``sick''
freshman Jerome Moiso, had 12 of his 21 points off the bench in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't shooting the ball, and we weren't competing on
defense,'' Bramlett said. ``It was just lack of effort. You can't
get in a hole in the Pac-10, especially UCLA at L.A., and get down
and expect to get back. At first, guys were scared or nervous or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats missed 19 of 26 shots as a team to find themselves
in a 40-24 rut by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed, embarrassed for some of our players and
the program that we would come out and not get after it,'' Arizona
Coach Lute Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   The ball-hawking defense continued in the second half, but the
Bruins picked up more team fouls, nine, in six minutes than it had
all of the first half. That still could not do Arizona any good as
it missed 4 of its first 5, continued to handle the ball sloppily
and escorted UCLA's offense into the paint.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins scored on eight of their first 10 second-half
possessions and stretched the lead to as much as 59-37 with 12:47
to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a lack of intensity and competitiveness,'' said
Arizona senior guard Jason Terry, who scored a team high 19. ``We
played with no heart, and they played with a lot of enthusiasm and
energy like they wanted the game, and they did.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA was actually a poor perimeter team after a hot start, but
it was moot because of Arizona's pillow-soft interior defense. The
Wildcats got as close as five with 19.8 seconds to play, but UCLA
held off the Cats by playing a whole half with all of its points
coming in the paint or at the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins shot 50 percent for the game, while Arizona shot just
37 percent, despite scoring 30 points in the final nine minutes to
rally. The Wildcats finished with 27 offensive rebounds that they
turned into 27 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
