<HEADER>
A5912 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-KICKERS-AZ     01-03 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-KICKERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACHING THEIR GOALS  
 FIESTA KICKERS LINE UP AS WINNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Football found Jeff Hall in his Winchester, Tenn., backyard. Two
trees were his goal posts, a wood block his tee.
</P>
<P>
   It came to Sebastian Janikowski in Daytona Beach, Fla., where
the teen soccer standout from Poland had moved to be with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the place-kickers for Monday's Fiesta
Bowl can be measured by worlds, not hashmarks. The common thread is
that they are two of the best in the country and could play a key
role in the national championship game. Most believe it will be won
by a three- or four-point margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it comes down to a kick, there's nobody I'd rather have out
there,'' Volunteers Coach Phillip Fulmer said about senior Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had him in the early '90s, we might have won a couple
more championships,'' Florida State Coach Bobby Bowden said about
sophomore Janikowski.
</P>
<P>
   The pair couldn't be more opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski grew up playing soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, in his choir-boy way, will tell you he doesn't have much
use for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski stands 6 feet 2, 255 pounds and is an imposing
presence with his shaved head.
</P>
<P>
   Hall tips the scales at 6-feet, 180 and, frankly, has probably
never imposed on anyone or anything in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for the little kickers that weigh 165-170,''
Janikowski said. ``I know how (other players) treat them, and I
know how they treated me as a freshman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dude can kick a football farther than anyone I've seen in my
life,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski's forte is definitely his leg strength. It's not
uncommon for him to kick a 70-yarder. He was given the Lou Groza
Award for the nation's best kicker this season after making 27
field goals (in 32 attempts) and setting an Atlantic Coast
Conference record.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's strength is consistency. He has earned all-Southeastern
Conference honors four straight years and has hit 11 of his past 12
field goals and 19 of 24 overall this season. He nailed all 47
extra points.
</P>
<P>
   He made game-winning kicks against Syracuse, as time ran out,
and Florida, in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   This may be the biggest difference between the two. Janikowski
has not been required to kick a game-winner this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's won two games for them,'' Janikowski said of Hall. ``I've
got a lot of respect for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Halls considers his most memorable kick the game-winning
34-yarder against Georgia in the second game of his freshman
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave me a foundation to build my career on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Did it ever. He made 64 percent of his attempts as a freshman
and bettered that mark this season with a 79.2 percent effort. He's
had a few rough spots in between, including a back injury, but
overall, he's been one of Tennessee's most reliable players during
the past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Hall's success, Fulmer laughs and credits his
Winchester roots, a hometown the two share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff is a really hard worker and a dedicated person and has
excellent ability,'' Fulmer said. ``When you put those things
together, it lends itself to being a really good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall taught himself to kick as a youth after buying a tee and
reading the accompanying manual, a how-to book by former NFL
standout Jan Stenerud.
</P>
<P>
   In high school he kicked a state record 62-yard field goal as a
sophomore. He did the same thing the next year.
</P>
<P>
   After redshirting his first season at Tennessee, his career took
off.
</P>
<P>
   Hall is known around Knoxville as much for his spiritual talks
as he is for his football. He is an in-demand speaker and often
talks to groups in his spare time.
</P>
<P>
   He also is considered the ultimate nice guy. He recently pulled
over for a homeless man on a Knoxville street, popped the man's
wheelchair in his backseat and took him and several of his homeless
friends to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski is considered a nice guy, too, although his teammates
didn't know what to think when he showed up in 1997 with a shaved
head and a way of speaking ``that was kind of funny,'' guard Jason
Whitaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski, whose father is a former soccer player, had hoped to
play professional soccer, scoring 73 goals as a senior at Seabreeze
High School. But his leg also made an impression with the football
team, and a year later he was off to Florida State on scholarship.
He set a school record with a 56-yarder against Wake Forest as a
freshman.
</P>
<P>
   He would like to try a longer one and has had discussions with
Bowden about potential kicks in the title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked earlier this week, and he said that he might give me
a chance from 64 yards on in,'' Janikowski said. ``It depends on
the situation, such as score and time left.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
