<HEADER>
A5914 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-KEITHJACKS     01-03 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-KEITH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIESTA BOWL WILL BE LAST CALL FOR JACKSON 
</HEADLINE>
 JACKSON-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 60 minutes before kickoff. Coaches are ranting and pacing.
Players are wondering and hoping.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Jackson, meanwhile, is off in his world, relaxing,
thinking, trying to hide.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm going to miss the most,'' said Jackson, the
veteran ABC college football announcer whose last game will be
Monday's Fiesta Bowl at Sun Devil Stadium. ``It's that hour before
the game that's the special time. At least it is if the producer
leaves you alone to let you enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes beyond the pharaohs, when the leader led his troops
into the battle. That's the glorious part, when they first enter
the arena, that minute or two, when there's just something that's
been with mankind since there was a mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosopher, fisherman, golfer.
</P>
<P>
   But it's in college football where Jackson, 70, made his mark
over three decades, speaking his mind, stepping on toes _ and
picking up millions of fans in the process, many of whom can do a
pretty decent Keith Jackson impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like cliches or that homespun stuff,'' ESPN analyst
Beano Cook said, ``but Keith always did it in a way people liked.
He brought a smile to your face. When he first started, I said,
`Boy, those cliches.' But after a while, I said, `This guy is the
best.' He's tremendous, he really is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I think when people go to football games on Saturday
afternoon that they won't feel like they're missing something by
not staying home and watching Keith.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Corso, a former coach at Indiana and now an ESPN analyst,
sometimes wonders whether Jackson might be ``too'' nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard the guy say anything mean,'' Corso said. ``I
remembering thinking at times, `Something has to be wrong.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Commentators and fans alike love doing Keith Jackson
impressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa, Nellie!'' which he often says he never said during a
game, is the favorite. His trademark ``Fumblllllle!'' is another
oft-repeated line, as is ``rumblin', stumblin', bumblin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's game will be a dual milestone: Jackson's finale and the
first one to decide what is being called the true national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a great game, but it will be only one of many that
Jackson has witnessed. He has reported the exploits of Heisman
Trophy winners and run-of-the-mill players; he recalls open-field
runs and missed tackles; he has seen the joy in a player's eyes as
well as the despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always looking for Walter Mitty, and sometimes he would
show up,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson started doing games for ABC in 1962 and has been doing
the game of the week since 1966, when the network acquired the
rights. He first teamed with Jackie Jensen, the former Southern
California All-American running back and Boston Red Sox star. Lee
Groscup, Bud Wilkinson, Ara Parseghian and Frank Broyles preceded
Bob Griese, who joined Jackson 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Jackson prefers to look ahead, he can't help but
marvel at the outpouring of affection and attention he has received
on his farewell tour this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my druthers, I would have kept my mouth shut, and
when my time was up, I would have just walked away and said
goodbye,'' he said. ``It has been somewhat of a strain, but the
people have been so generous and kind. And I'm not used to crying
that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said two of of his prized gifts have been autographed
helmets from Arizona State and Michigan. He has received rocking
chairs, cooking school enrollments, blankets, a gold watch, a cow
bell, and whistles and flags from officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll never forget that day when 110,000 people clapped
their hands at Michigan,'' he said. ``Every time I think of it, I
get chills. I never realized . . . I don't think about that stuff.
I just go out and do the ballgame and go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people came up to me to stick out their hand. It's
something I never expected. It makes you realize that people out
there do like your work.''
</P>
<P>
   Griese said, ``It's been a joy to follow him around this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson wants to maintain a low profile for his finale, and he
says when he signs off for the last time, it won't be sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be emotional at all,'' he said. ``It's not my show.
The game belongs to Tennessee and Florida State and the people who
put it together. I'm gonna bust my chops to make sure it doesn't
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give the final score. That's all that matters. The game
will be treated with the kind of respect and dignity it deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has his opinions on the state of affairs of college
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could create anything I wanted to in college sports, and
if I had the power, I would . . . turn over control of the game and
the administration of the game to institutional control. I would
let the institutions conduct the activities. College presidents
want the money, but they don't want to make the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Jackson suggested a playoff, but his arguments
were rejected. Now, as a championship game approaches, he said the
Bowl Championship Series is a start in the right direction, but he
would do things differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe you need four teams,'' he said. ``But I think
if a community wants to have a bowl game and pay for it, let 'em.
I'm surprised the Rose Bowl went along with this. They could have
sat back and said, `We'll give each of you $15 million.' They could
have upped the ante, but ABC put pressure on them, and they went
along with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway, after all the games, take the top four teams, ranked
by whatever system _ and take four so you don't make mistakes _ and
the winners would play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could make a good case right now that you don't have the
best (No.) 1 and 2 teams, but in this system, you agreed to take
their two teams . . . and the end of the four years, tweak it. I
think you have to accept the fact that you are never going to
expunge provincialism in the pool. We have two very good football
teams here, but if they're the best, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it would be hard to argue if Tennessee wins, but a
Florida State victory would give Ohio State a good argument.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's outspokenness is what fans have found endearing. He
says he never has been reprimanded for his straight talk, probably,
he said, ``because I've always busted my (butt) to try to be
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   A bad call is a bad call, and there have been a lot of them in
the past few seasons, he said. But come Monday night, he may not
care as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good time to leave,'' he said. ``There's a change of
ownership at ABC and a change of philosophy. My wife (Turi Ann) and
I decided that when we reached 70, we would sit back and take a
look at things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're a blank page. We'll get up in the morning and
then decide what we're going to do with the rest of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife plan to take golfing and fishing vacations in
the fall, and he said he may get to one or two games, but his
emphasis will be on enjoying his new lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll leave in late August, and I'll play golf until I scream
and my fingers fall off, and then we'll go fishing. We're booked
for a golf journey (in the football season). The tourists will be
gone, the courses are glorious and the countryside can't be beat.
I've never had a September, October and November to do this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 0307EST &QL; 
