<HEADLINE>
MURRELL LOSES STEAM ON LONG RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardinals running back  &UR; Adrian Murrell didn't mind the ribbing.
His teammates can tease him any time he goes 74 yards off-tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been making fun of him for his wheels,'' offensive guard
 &UR; Chris
 &UR; Dishman said.  &UR; ``Deion (Sanders) caught him from behind. How could
he let that happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Murrell was caught from behind by Sanders, one of the NFL's
fastest players, after running to the Cowboys' 3 early in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the longest run of Murrell's career when he's not playing
against the Cardinals. He had a 78-yard run for the New York Jets
at Sun Devil Stadium two years ago to help the Jets get their only
victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't happy with how we had been running the ball,'' said
offensive tackle  &UR; Lomas Brown of the Cardinals' 11 yards rushing in
the first half. ``It set the tempo and tone for the rest of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Murrell, who finished with a game-high 95 yards, didn't think
his season-best run was a bigger play than the 59-yard reception by
wide receiver Frank Sanders in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Murrell scored on a 12-yard shovel pass for a
7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was big that we got the score early,'' Murrell said. ``The
last time we played them, they jumped to a 28-point lead. We
couldn't dig a hole early.'' &QL; 
__ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Frank Sanders said he was startled that he was able to make a
one-handed grab.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I'd get it,'' he said. ``I just stuck my hand
out and boom.'' &QL; 
__ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker &UR; Ronald McKinnon called linebacker &UR; Mark
Maddox's second-quarter stop of running back  &UR; Emmitt Smith on
fourth and 1 at the Cardinals 7 the game's turning point.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals blitzed, using a defense called goal-line five
clap.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were down on our stoop,'' McKinnon said. ``Mark and I
just shot the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into the game knowing the first thing we had to do was
stop the run. Everyone made a concerted effort. The coaches did a
great job of mixing things up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals used five-men, three-men and four-men defensive
fronts and also inserted safety Pat Tillman in the game as a
linebacker in their cub formation.
</P>
<P>
   __ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Leigh Steinberg, agent for Cardinals quarterback &UR; Jake Plummer
and Dallas'  &UR; Troy Aikman, thinks the victory could have long-range
effects in the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   ``That quaking sound you hear is a changing of the guard,''
Steinberg said. &QL; 
__ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals center  &UR; Aaron Graham, who grew up in nearby Denton,
Texas, used to dream of winning a playoff game in Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He thought it would be in a Cowboys uniform, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``After not being drafted by the Cowboys, I'm just thankful that
I was wearing red today instead of blue,'' Graham said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
