<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-VIKINGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANYTHING'S POSSIBLE' NEXT WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ When the Cardinals move inside the Metrodome
next Sunday for their second-round playoff game against the NFC
Central Division champion Minnesota Vikings, do they have more than
an outside chance to win?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're asking the wrong guy,'' was the terse response from
Dallas Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman, whose team fell to Arizona,
20-7, on Saturday and served as the main course in the Vikings'
Thanksgiving feast, 46-36, at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys receiver Patrick Jeffers was a little more diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time of year, anything's possible,'' said Jeffers, who
caught seven passes for 92 yards against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers should know. Last season, he was a member of a wild-card
Denver Broncos team that plowed through the AFC playoffs on its way
to defeating the Green Bay Packers in Super Bowl XXXII.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minnesota is a tough place to go play, but a few big plays,
and things can turn around,'' Jeffers said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Dallas owner-General Manager Jerry Jones: ``It's a cliche,
but it's not a cliche. Any team is capable of beating another,
especially one with a good quarterback. And Arizona is a team with
a good quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Jake Plummer, the second-year phenom from Arizona
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good quarterback. I'm a Jake Plummer fan. No doubt
about it. I'm a fan,'' Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's defense will have its hands full with Plummer. But
Arizona's defense will face an even tougher test with a Vikings
offense that set an NFL scoring record with Randall Cunningham at
quarterback, Cris Carter and rookie Randy Moss as the primary wide
receivers and Robert Smith in the backfield.
</P>
<P>
   Before Moss was at Marshall, he was enrolled for about a year at
Florida State, where Cardinals rookie defensive end Andre Wadsworth
was one of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best,'' Wadsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Moss' extraordinary ability, the receiver earned the
nickname ``The Freak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He works hard in the weight room and on the field. He's tall,
fast and athletic,'' Wadsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Another rookie, Cardinals right cornerback Corey Chavous,
expects to play a key role, as he did Saturday against the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran left corner Aeneas Williams was occupied with the
Cowboys' Michael Irvin, and Chavous knew he would get a lot of
passes thrown at him by Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   Williams figures to be on Carter or Moss, leaving Chavous . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``You think today was bad, wait until next week,'' said Chavous,
who had five passes defensed and three tackles on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cowboys Coach Chan Gailey said the Arizona secondary
``made our guys not catch the ball cleanly, and they're capable of
doing the same things to other people.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 0308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
