<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-OFFENSIVE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG LINE MEN PROVE THEY'RE GROWN UPS 
</HEADLINE>
 LINE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin showed there is fire
beneath his tranquil demeanor by turning a compliment about the
offensive line against its presenter after Saturday's 20-7 playoff
win over Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, aren't those the guys who were the cause of all our
problems, (the guys who) everyone said couldn't play earlier this
year?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes.
</P>
<P>
   But Tobin had no reason to find fault with the Cardinals'
offensive line Saturday. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   After being sacked five times in two regular-season games
against the Cowboys, Jake Plummer was not sacked once in 36 pass
attempts Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A line with three second-year starters _ Chris Dishman, James
Dexter and Aaron Graham _ did not commit an illegal-motion or a
holding penalty.
</P>
<P>
   After being embarrassed by Dallas in two regular-season games in
which the Cowboys rushed for 334 yards to Arizona's 77, the
Cardinals reversed the tables and outrushed the Cowboys, 133 yards
to 96.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't pretty, and we did some good and bad things, but the
totality of it was that we won,'' guard Lester Holmes said. ``These
young guys I'm playing with have a lot of heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran left tackle Lomas Brown wasn't surprised that his
younger cohorts displayed poise beyond their years in their first
playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' he said. ``We didn't give up a sack or have many
penalties against New Orleans, and San Diego was basically the same
way,'' he said, referring to the Cardinals' final two
regular-season games. ``We're peaking right now. And man, are we
ever doing it at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown thinks the Cardinals are the Cinderella of the playoff
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be. A lot of people didn't think we could do it,'' he
said. ``We got in the playoffs when nobody thought we would. We're
the team that is always coming from behind. We're the exciting team
that can never hold a lead. We have all these negative aspects, but
the one thing they can't measure is your heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have heart and will battle everyone until the bitter
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Dishman, who had the herculean task of going against big
Leon Lett, said he thinks the Cardinals caught the Cowboys by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great game plan and really had nothing to lose,''
Dishman said. ``Everyone was saying we'd made it here for the first
time in 30 years or something like that, and I think they took us
lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get down early and have to play catch-up, things get
a little tighter. But we got the lead early and were having fun.
It's easier to play an error-free game when you have the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Dishman was especially pleased the Cardinals didn't allow a
sack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they got one hurry, though,'' he said. ``Big Leon got
me once high on my arm and got past, but other than that, I played
decently.''
</P>
<P>
   Dishman's former teammate at Nebraska, center Graham, threw the
big block that sprang running back Adrian Murrell for a 74-yard run
on the first possession of the third quarter. That set up a 3-yard
Plummer-to-Larry Centers touchdown pass that gave Arizona a 17-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still not satisfied,'' Graham said. ``There are a lot of
things we'd like to take back, but we got 20 points, and the
defense was phenomenal. It was an outside play where Adrian picks
his hole. He cut it back behind me, and I was sealing my man and
got him down. He never even saw him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
