<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-CORNERBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAVOUS SHINES AT CORNER  
 ROOKIE GETS RIGHT TO POINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The ``Preacher'' proved he was a prophet, and
because of it, the ``General'' was able to successfully complete
his war games Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Preacher is none other than rookie cornerback Corey Chavous,
who finally has supplied the Cardinals' defense with a much-needed
piece _ a right cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   The General? Aeneas Williams, who not only declared war on the
state of Texas but also on Cowboys wide receiver Michael Irvin and
quarterback Troy Aikman, doubling his seasonlong interception total
with two picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gotta give it to him _ Corey made them throw my way,'' said
Williams, who held Irvin to four catches for 32 yards. ``Corey
loves to talk. Whenever you're around him, you're going to hear
him. I think he's going to be called to be a preacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``When rookies tell you something, sometimes you just laugh at
them. But Corey told me, `If I get at that cornerback position, I'm
going to make 'em throw your way.' He made that comment before he
ever got out there to cornerback. He might be a prophet as well as
a preacher.''
</P>
<P>
   He certainly was Saturday. Chavous, who spent much of the season
at safety before a string of injuries to the cornerbacks led
coaches to plug him into the position in a loss to Kansas City, was
as annoying to Dallas receivers as flypaper to flies.
</P>
<P>
   He made three solo tackles and deflected five passes. He even
had a first-half interception negated by a holding call against
him. Even Dallas fans called it a break for the home team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stepped up big for us,'' said safety Tommy Bennett, who
contributed an interception late in the game. ``For a rookie who's
in the playoffs for the first time, you might expect for him to
have wide eyes, or maybe choking under the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he took it all in stride. He's played that way all year.
They haven't really attacked him this year. He came in against
Kansas City and got a pick and covered (Andre) Rison wherever he
went and they've respected him ever since. He proved again today
that he's a legitimate NFL corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavous, a dedicated student of the game, said his performance
was the product of preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked up some things on their splits and the things they
like to do,'' he said. ``I was able to anticipate some of the
routes they were running. I really felt good out there today. My
transition was good, and I was able to make plays on the ball
because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The deeply religious Williams wasted no time declaring war on
Minnesota, the second-round opponent next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anybody looking at me like I've done something
great,'' he said. ``When we left, I told fans at the airport that
there was Desert Storm, then Desert Fox. Now there's Desert We
Gotta Do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to enjoy this for now and when we get together
again, we'll get our artillery together, clean our weapons and get
ready to go to war again.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he wasn't worried Dallas would try to get Irvin
off to a fast start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter once we declared war,'' he said. ``It's like
when the U.S. declared war on Iraq. It didn't matter where their
missiles were, we were going to find them. Our motto the last four
weeks has been `We gotta do it.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
