<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS_COLLAPSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN TAKES IT LYING DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It has been a long time since followers of the
Dallas Cowboys have had an empty feeling such as this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our organization is set up to win a Super Bowl, and when you
don't do that . . . yes, it's very disappointing,'' said Jerry
Jones, the team's owner and general manager, after the humbling
wild-card playoff loss at the hands of the Cardinals on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of moving on to the next round, maintaining their hopes
of earning a record sixth Lombardi Trophy that signifies the NFL
championship, the Cowboys were left battered and bruised.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the man feeling it the most was quarterback Troy Aikman.
Due to Cardinals sacks and pressure, he spent a large part of the
crisp winter afternoon flat on his back looking through the hole of
the Texas Stadium roof.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman threw a whopping 49 passes, completing just 22 for 191
yards and a touchdown to finally put Dallas on the board with 3:33
left in the game. The longest completion went for 19 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggled in a lot of different areas,'' Aikman said. ``You
can place the blame, put criticism on all the (offensive)
positions. We just failed to convert, keep drives going.''
</P>
<P>
   Some failures came as the result of dropped passes. Some came
when Aikman threw the ball poorly. And some came from penalties.
</P>
<P>
   On the outside, Aikman, the Most Valuable Player of Super Bowl
XXVII in 1993, showed no emotion. But inside, Coach Chan Gailey
knew better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy sometimes has the need to carry the team,'' Gailey said.
``It's hard on him. It's hard to do. Everyone does their job and
then no one has to shoulder that kind of burden.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman was asked whether he had varying degrees of
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something like this happens _ it's a matter of the longer
you play _ you don't know how many opportunities you're going to
get,'' he said. ``I feel confident that Jerry (Jones) and Chan
(Gailey) are going to get together and help us do some things so
that we can better ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's guys like myself, Emmitt (Smith, running back),
Michael (Irvin, receiver), Darren (Woodson, safety), just to name a
few, who have been through the better years. But we're not the same
team. We're relying on different people. We're looking through a
different window.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas defense played better than the offense but not good
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Star cornerback Deion Sanders, who was back in the lineup after
missing five games with a sore toe, was matter-of-fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this, how can you look in the mirror and be happy with
yourself?'' Sanders said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
