<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 03:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5920 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-DEFENSE     01-03 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-DEFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSTART DEFENSE UNSADDLES COWBOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It seemed a pretentious idea. The upstart
Cardinals' defense actually believed it could rattle the Dallas
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   C'mon. With Troy and Emmitt and Michael, who have three Super
Bowl rings each?
</P>
<P>
   And didn't the Cowboys ring up two of the three highest scores
against the Cardinals _ 38 in the opener and 35 more in November?
</P>
<P>
   And isn't this the defensive front seven that watched its last
two foes score fourth-quarter touchdowns that made photo finishes
necessary to get the team here Saturday for its playoff opener?
</P>
<P>
   Yes to all of the above. And so what?
</P>
<P>
   ``We really believed if we could get to them early, we could
frustrate them and take their heads out of the game,'' outside
linebacker Jamir Miller said after the Cardinals came within 3:33
minutes of shutting out the Cowboys at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals made key sacks and critical fourth-down stops,
knocked passes down and picked them off in a 20-7 win that moves
them into the second round Sunday at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker Ron McKinnon said, ``We messed them up by
mixing it up. We attacked them relentlessly.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman suffered three interceptions and
was sacked four times _ twice by Miller, who correctly anticipated
the snap count and broke through before Aikman finished his drop.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Irvin, whose consecutive-game receiving streak was
snapped at 117 the last time he faced cornerback Aeneas Williams
and the Cardinals' defense, caught four passes for 32 yards and
generally was not a factor.
</P>
<P>
   And Emmitt Smith, who rushed for 122 and 117 yards against the
Cardinals in the regular season, gained 74, only 23 in the closing
half when the Cardinals successfully protected their lead.
</P>
<P>
   One of the league's most big-game-tested offenses that rolled
undefeated through NFC East competition got 260 total yards.
</P>
<P>
   Up front, the Cardinals used a five-man line to thwart Smith's
rushing, adding down lineman Carl Simpson and taking out a
linebacker. They blitzed Aikman into submission.
</P>
<P>
   According to safety Tommy Bennett, whose interception with 48
seconds left slammed the door, ``The biggest adjustment we made in
this game was bringing a greater sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had been running on us. Maybe all we needed was to be
one step faster in some situations.''
</P>
<P>
   They were plenty fast on two critical stops:
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second quarter, the Cowboys, trailing, 7-0,
marched to the 7. Facing fourth and 1, Cowboys Coach Chan Gailey
eschewed the chip-shot field goal. Linebacker Mark Maddox broke
through and stopped Smith for a 1-yard loss. Usually, Maddox flows
with the motion man. Instead, he shot the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just didn't expect that,'' Maddox said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller sacked Aikman for a 10-yard loss early in the fourth
quarter when the Cowboys went for it on fourth and 1 from their 33.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give away my secrets, but I noticed their motion man
stopped in the same place every time, and that's when they snap the
ball,'' Miller said. ``When I saw the man (receiver Patrick
Jeffers) stop, that's when I started my rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to get a playoff win, but it means even more to
come in to Dallas and get it. This is such a big win. I don't know
what it signals, but it lets the world know the Cardinals are not a
joke.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
