</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SCHOENFELD-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS HOW YOU FIND A NEW COACH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Mike McCaskey is so worried about turning the Chicago
Bears into a winner, he went skiing last Monday after firing Coach
Dave Wannstedt.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Williams, a San Francisco management consultant who is the
creator of an executive search firm to promote African-American
coaching candidates, found out about McCaskey's vacation plans when
he called the Bears on Tuesday. He learned that Bears' offices were
``closed for the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   So while the Carolina Panthers are close to hiring former San
Francisco Coach George Seifert, and the Philadelphia Eagles,
Baltimore Ravens, Seattle Seahawks, San Diego Chargers and
Cleveland Browns are setting up interviews, the man running the
Bears is in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Some names have surfaced on the Bears' list, including Cardinals
defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis. In addition, Dom Capers, fired
by Carolina a week ago, has expressed interest in the job, and
Minnesota Coach Dennis Green has recommended Green Bay offensive
coordinator Sherman Lewis, who every year seems to get passed over
for head coaching positions.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bears are behind the other teams looking for coaches
because Mark Hatley, the team's vice president for personnel, who
is charge of the search, didn't know that McCaskey was going to
fire Wannstedt until the morning it happened.
</P>
<P>
   Hatley doesn't exactly have a lot of confidence that he'll find
the next Vince Lombardi for the Bears. He told McCaskey there was
no guarantee he could find anyone better than Wannstedt.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears are so desperate that some in the organization are
hoping they'll consider Hall of Fame linebacker Mike Singletary,
who has coached as many games in his career as Chicago native
Hillary Clinton has.
</P>
<P>
   Former Bears teammate Tom Thayer has said Singletary would make
a great head coach, even though he has no experience.
</P>
<P>
   Since retiring in 1992, Singletary, 40, has been a motivational
speaker and a corporate consultant. He also has turned down several
NFL assistant coaching jobs, including under Buddy Ryan with the
Cardinals in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Singletary said he was flattered that his name had surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe when the situation is right, anything is possible,''
Singletary said. ``I would only coach the Bears.''
</P>
<P>
   The last person to go from player to NFL head coach was Norm Van
Brocklin, who played for the Eagles in 1960 and became head coach
of the expansion Vikings the next season.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring Singletary would be popular in Chicago but wouldn't
improve the Bears' personnel problems. They haven't had a player
voted into the Pro Bowl in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the skier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to take my responsibility and my share of the
blame,'' McCaskey said before heading to the slopes. &QL;  &QL; 
Country bumpkin
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Larrive, who has been the Bears' radio play-by-play man
since 1985, is moving to the Green Bay Packers next season to
replace retiring Jim Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   One Bears fan can't understand how Larrive could make that move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you going to do your broadcast in orange hunting gear with
a shotgun on your side?'' the fan asked Larrive on Chicago radio
station WMAQ. ``And you have to buy a pickup truck now, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Larrive told the caller, ``This is not the University of Texas
I'm going to.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Far from perfect
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco quarterback Steve Young is 0-8 in his career
against the Green Bay Packers, today's opponent in an NFC wildcard
game.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't think that's accurate, because his first three
loses were with Tampa Bay, and with the 49ers he didn't play in one
game and lasted only one period in another. So he considers himself
just 0-3 against the Packers while with the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay has beaten the 49ers five straight times.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been a roadblock for us,'' Young said. ``It's been
them to the Super Bowl or us, and we haven't gotten over that. When
somebody has beat you a number of times in a row, it becomes a
thing you want even more so to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers' troubles against Green Bay have come in the first
quarter, during which they've been outscored 53-6 in the past five
games. San Francisco also has had trouble protecting Young; he's
been sacked 16 times in the three games he has played.
</P>
<P>
   Young has no touchdown passes and three interceptions in playoff
losses to the Packers the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Packers quarterback Brett Favre, meanwhile, has four TD passes
and no interceptions in those games.
</P>
<P>
   Another Green Bay win could mean the 49ers will fire Coach Steve
Mariucci and try to replace him with the Packers' Mike Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a saying in the streets, `You ain't got no number,' ''
Packers safety LeRoy Butler said. ``That's what the 49ers are going
to tell Mike's agent if they lose. It could be $8 million.
Whatever. Fix this (stuff). How much is that worth to any team for
a guy to come in and fix it? And whoever gets him will be as lucky
as hell.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Latest scapegoat
</P>
<P>
   Unlike five other teams, the St. Louis Rams didn't fire their
head coach last week. That's because it would have cost more than
$10 million to dump Dick Vermeil and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rams still made a coaching move, firing offensive
coordinator Jerry Rhome, who had formerly held the same position
with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want this read as I am blaming Jerry Rhome for our
lack of success offensively,'' said Vermeil, whose offense was
ranked 27th in the league. ``It just didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's why it didn't work out, according to one Rams offensive
starter. He said a frequent play-calling sequence in games featured
Rhome calling the play from the press box, followed by Vermeil
offering suggestions, offensive line coach Jim Hanifan giving
advice, tight ends coach Lynn Stiles putting in his two cents and
quarterbacks coach Mike White also having a say.
</P>
<P>
   While everyone was giving advice, the play clock was running.
Quarterback Tony Banks would signal in for the call, but by the
time it reached him, it bore little resemblance to the original
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe how often this happened,'' one player
said.
</P>
<P>
   Expect Rhome to end up in Atlanta, where he would be reunited
with quarterback Chris Chandler, who played for him on the
Cardinals. &QL;  &QL; 
Short shots
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore owner Art Modell plans to hire a current assistant
coach to replace ousted Ted Marchibroda. Among the possibilities
are Minnesota's Brian Billick, Jacksonville's Chris Palmer,
Pittsburgh's Jim Haslett and Philadelphia's Emmitt Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest coaches in the NFL historically are assistant
coaches who were elevated to the head coaching position,'' Modell
said. ``I'll give you Hall of Famers like Lombardi, (Chuck) Noll
and (Bud) Grant.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's firing of Coach Ray Rhodes was so friendly that
owner Jeffrey Lurie opened the news conference by saying, ``Wow,
what a crowd. You'd think it was a Rolling Stones concert or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver running back Terrell Davis, on reaching 2,000 yards: ``It
was almost like winning a Super Bowl again.''
</P>
<P>
   A banner at the Ravens' regular-season finale a week ago read,
``Hey, Cleveland, we'd rather have the expansion team.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
