<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-SOUTHERN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIXIE GETS ITS KICKS FROM FOOTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  FB-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Atlanta sports bar was subdued as fans from Mississippi
State and Tennessee ate quietly while watching games on the
big-screen televisions.
</P>
<P>
   It apparently was a little too quiet for one Mississippi State
fan, who suddenly stood on the rungs of a bar stool and, in a voice
reminiscent of Foghorn Leghorn, yelled: `Oooooooweeeee, looks like
there might be some Dogs in here!''
</P>
<P>
   As if possessed, seemingly normal, mild-mannered folks quickly
swallowed whatever they were eating and responded the only way they
knew how. They barked. Loudly. Deeply. Passionately.
</P>
<P>
   Their beloved Bulldogs were only eight hours away from playing
Tennessee in the Southeastern Conference Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Most rational Southerners will admit they play some decent
football in other parts of the country. But when it comes to
undying passion, unquestioned loyalty and unconditional love for
high school and college football, there is no place like the
Southeastern part of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   They still pack high school stadiums on Friday nights. On
Saturday afternoons, they ring cowbells, sing ``Rocky Top,'' do the
tomahawk chop and fill stadiums from Tennessee to Florida and from
Louisiana to South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Southeastern schools ranked among the country's top 10 in
average attendance this season. Schools in the Southeastern
Conference averaged about 69,000 in attendance, 19,000 more than
the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   It is a different world out West. The University of Arizona and
Arizona State can't sell out, even when one team is ranked in the
Top 10. In its Rose Bowl season, Washington State couldn't pack its
small stadium. And if a UCLA fan ever hopped up on a bar stool and
growled like a Bruin, his brethren would choke on their Chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State assistant coach Chuck Amato has coached at North
Carolina State and Arizona and has seen the differences firsthand.
When he was at Arizona, the Wildcats traveled to play Southern
California in the Los Angeles Coliseum one year. The Trojans were
ranked No. 1, and Marcus Allen, who went on to win the Heisman
Trophy, was a senior.
</P>
<P>
   On the Friday before the Saturday afternoon game, the Rolling
Stones drew about 105,000 for a concert in the Coliseum. On
Saturday night, they drew another 100,000 people. In between, the
football game drew 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Yeah, we were the halftime show for the Rolling
Stones,' '' Amato said. ``That wouldn't have been that way (in the
South). In Tallahassee, they have three seasons: football,
recruiting and spring practice. It's a passion down there.'' &QL; 
Region of champs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That passion is not only displayed in attendance figures but in
championships. In six of the past 11 years, a Southern team has won
a national championship. That number is likely to grow to seven
this year because No. 1 Tennessee is playing No. 2 Florida State in
the Fiesta Bowl on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Like ingredients for jambalaya, there are many reasons for the
South's passion. None is more important than the others, but each
one adds something to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Some will say it's a result of the region's lack of professional
teams for many years. Some will say it's because football was
something Southerners could take pride in when economic times were
hard and the region was being negatively portrayed nationally.
Others maintain that the passion has roots in the Civil War and
Reconstruction, when many of the SEC schools started as land-grant
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it more a part of the fabric of life than any other
area? I don't know that you can say, `Here's the reason,' '' said
John Ward, who is retiring after more than 30 years of broadcasting
Tennessee's games. ``There are a lot of underlying reasons that go
back certainly half a century or more.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 23 seasons at Florida State, Coach Bobby Bowden's teams
have played in nearly every large stadium in the country. He has
never experienced fans who have stronger emotional ties to football
teams than in the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the Southeastern part of the United States that were
defeated in the Civil War, it's their nature to have something to
ride on, a football team or something,'' Bowden said. ``I think we
put too much into it, actually. People have put too much of their
priorities into football.``
</P>
<P>
   Rivalries become blood feuds. In seasons such as this one, when
Florida State has beaten Florida and Miami, Bowden can travel
through the state peacefully. He has said many times that Seminoles
fans would rather beat Florida than win a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden received a letter recently from an old friend who wrote
that the coach had it exactly right.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `If you win a national championship, that's a matter
of opinion. But if you have a victory over Florida, that's a cold,
hard fact,' '' Bowden said. ``I thought that was pretty clever.'' &QL; 
Who are you? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fans choose loyalties at an early age. Kids in Alabama often
become Crimson Tide fans or Auburn fans before grade school. In
Florida, they pick between Florida State, Florida and Miami. The
same holds true with Mississippi and Mississippi State, Georgia and
Georgia Tech, South Carolina and Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're either Alabama or Auburn,'' said Frank Sanders, a
receiver for the Cardinals who grew up in Fort Lauderdale and
played at Auburn. ``Either you're Florida or Florida State. Who are
you? They always want to make the distinction. What are you, and
what do you believe?''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State quarterback Marcus Outzen of Fort Walton Beach,
Fla., has wanted to be a Seminole for as long as he can remember.
At 12, Outzen was thrilled the day he received an autograph from
Bowden. Tennessee kicker Jeff Hall of Winchester, Tenn., grew up a
Volunteers fan and treasured a jersey with No. 19 on it, the same
number worn by Tennessee quarterback Jeff Francis.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Bible Belt, people are loyal to a lot of things, and
football is one of them,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State offensive lineman Jason Whitaker grew up in Panama
City, Fla., where autumn weekends were comprised of two social
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watched college football on Saturdays and NASCAR on
Sundays,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee, there really is no other game in town. The
Volunteers drew an average of almost 107,000 fans to home games
this season, and their radio broadcasts are carried by 80 stations
throughout Tennessee and parts of Alabama, Kentucky and North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   When Tennessee quarterback Peyton Manning didn't win the Heisman
Trophy last year, Volunteers fans were outraged, as if someone had
attacked the family's honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an emotional commitment among fans here,'' Ward said.
``Life's milestones are measured not by the fact that our daughter
was born Oct. 17, 1982. She was born the year Tennessee broke an
11-year losing streak to Alabama. It's a reference point for life.
Children are named after players. I don't know how many Peytons
there are in Tennessee, but there's a lot more this year than there
were five years ago.'' &QL; 
Reconstruction roots &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ward thinks the roots of the passion reach back to
Reconstruction, when many SEC universities started as land-grant
institutions. Universities had extension agents in nearly every
county, and they worked closely with farm families, giving them a
direct connection to the universities.
</P>
<P>
   The schools were open to anyone in the state, and 50 years ago,
it was a major financial undertaking for many families to send a
child to college. That strengthened the emotional investment in the
university and its athletic teams.
</P>
<P>
   And later, the improvement in interstate roads made traveling to
games easier. What was a seven-hour drive from Memphis to Knoxville
became a little more than a four-hour trip.
</P>
<P>
   The passion also has racial overtones. Gene Stallings, who
played and coached at Alabama, once said that one reason Alabamans
were so passionate about football is that it was one thing in which
they could be proud.
</P>
<P>
   The state was poor economically and troubled socially. The only
thing many Americans knew about Alabama was that Gov. George
Wallace once stood at the doors of the University of Alabama and
vowed not to let Black students attend the school. The football
team, coached by Paul ``Bear'' Bryant, gave residents a reason to
be proud. &QL; 
Learning early &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southern kids learn early that football is important. Sanders
remembers choosing among three different youth organizations in
Fort Lauderdale, each with several different leagues based on age
and ability. In his high school league, the abundance of talent was
unbelievable. Sanders, for instance, played on the same team as
Isaac Bruce, a star receiver for the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Football can't get any bigger than it is in Thomasville, Ga.,
about 35 miles north of Tallahassee, Fla. Thomasville County
Central High has won state championships in five of the past seven
seasons and even has its own football web site.
</P>
<P>
   If you visit the school's lunchroom on Monday evenings, you'll
find members of the booster club reviewing game film. Details of
games played by the seventh grade, eighth grade, junior varsity and
varsity teams are available at the click of the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is as big here as it can get,'' said George Mathes,
who owns George's and Louie's Restaurant, which specializes in
fresh seafood from the Florida coast.
</P>
<P>
   Mathes, too, is a football fan, but he'll be glad to see the
college season end Monday night with the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the games are on, it really affects business,'' he said.
``People just stay home and watch television.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
