GOVERNMENT WITNESS: MAKE WINDOWS A PUBLIC UTILITY Moving in (f)
financial and (w) Washington queues. By ANDREW J. GLASS c.1999 Cox
News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To lift the ``choke point'' that Microsoft Corp.
holds over Internet commerce, the federal courts should treat
Windows, the dominant operating system for personal computers, like
a telephone dial tone, a key government witness will argue when the
historic antitrust case against the software giant resumes on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   William Harris, chief executive and president of Intuit Inc.,
maker of the popular Quicken personal-finance software, advances
his remedy of ``operating system neutrality'' in 47 pages of direct
written testimony. Microsoft's lawyers will cross-examine Harris,
the 11th of the government's allotted 12 witnesses in the landmark
trial, which was recessed for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   After the Department of Justice and 19 states rest their case,
probably in mid-January, Microsoft will present its 12 defense
witnesses _ reserving the right to call chairman Bill Gates as a
surprise rebuttal figure in the trial's final phase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Windows operating system is to computer users and
providers of software applications or Internet services what the
dial tone is to businesses and customers using the telephone: it's
the thing you must have access to if you are going to communicate
with each other,'' Harris wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the court limits Microsoft's ability to expand the
Windows choke point into the Internet, Microsoft's ability to be
the gatekeeper of the Internet will be unchallenged, and
competition on the Internet will be constrained,'' he contended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a result will have implications far beyond the software
industry, as the Internet is rapidly becoming a major conduit for
communications and commerce generally,'' Harris added.
</P>
<P>
   Likening Windows to a public utility, Harris held that
Microsoft's control of the operating system market exerts a huge
pull over how independent software vendors conduct business,
including his own firm.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to the superior market power of Windows, Harris reported,
Intuit reluctantly signed a deal with Microsoft to promote its
Internet Explorer browser _ one that required Intuit ``to forgo any
business relationships with Netscape [Communications Corp.],
because Microsoft guaranteed Intuit placement on the Windows
desktop for Intuit's Internet-based products and services.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris' proposed treatment of Windows as a public utility stems
from a body of antitrust case law known as the essential facility
rule, which has been most often applied in railroad right-of-way
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   It could come into play only during the remedy phase of the
trial should U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who
is hearing the case without a jury, find that Microsoft's business
practices violated the 1890 Sherman Antitrust Act.
</P>
<P>
   Harris underscored Intuit's dependence on the Windows operating
systems because it is ``essential and unique.'' In his discussion
of software industry economics, he noted that ``no other piece of
software has the same centrality and necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   As a leading maker of personal finance, tax and small business
accounting software, Intuit sought a merger with Microsoft in 1994,
until antitrust officials frowned on the planned accord. But Harris
wrote that Intuit pursued that deal out of fear that Microsoft
would leverage its monopoly power to champion its own accounting
product, Microsoft Money, and drive Intuit to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Microsoft cast itself as a defender of open
competition in a free marketplace. It characterized Harris'
proposed ``operating system neutrality,'' remedy as an ``entirely
new and irrelevant concept.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only 'fact' that comes out of Mr. Harris testimony is that
Intuit wishes to use its testimony as an attempt to circumvent
competition in the marketplace by using the government and the
courts against Microsoft.'' The company, it said, ``is competing on
the basis of technology and value, but Intuit seems to be trying to
use the government and the courts to tip the scales against
Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Harris wants to have his cake and eat it too,'' the
Microsoft statement concluded. ENDIT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 1353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
