<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6015 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-MILLER04-COX     01-03 2960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-MILLER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leaving behind a plowed field
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruit
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pairs of spare cowboy boots sit on a garage shelf,
their dog-eared tops neatly aligned, while boxes of books waiting
to be unpacked mark a narrow trail to the back door of the rock
house his mother built more than six decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Zell Miller has moved back home.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the house perched just above a multilaned highway
bearing his name that helped open Georgia's mountain communities.
Back to the college classroom to teach his first loves: history and
politics. Back to the saw-toothed hills that molded the man leaving
office as the state's most popular governor since political polling
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing exactly what I planned to do all along,'' Miller
said as he and his wife, Shirley, begin the transition back to
private life. ``No melancholy. No nostalgia. I've always known I
was going back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 66, leaves a legacy that historians say ensures his
place _ at the front of the line, many insist _ among the state's
most successful governors. His lottery-funded HOPE scholarship
program has sent nearly 357,000 Georgians to college, and helped
push his approval rating to an astounding 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   His pre-kindergarten program, also lottery-funded, has prepped
246,200 youngsters for the classroom. And Georgia now boasts some
of the nation's toughest laws on repeat felons and drunken drivers,
and the highest ratings for financial stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrote the book on modern-day political leadership,'' said
Keith Mason, who as a teenager volunteered in Miller's earlier
political campaigns and later became his top adviser in the
governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   But during Miller's first few years as governor, that book may
have seemed more like a chronicle of political misadventures.
</P>
<P>
   After 16 years as lieutenant governor, Miller walked into the
state's top office in the midst of a recession. With state revenue
shrinking and the state reserve fund depleted, the choices were
simple and distasteful: Cut the budget or raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Summoning lawmakers back to Atlanta for a special summer
legislative session, Miller put a quick end to his honeymoon in
office as he pared hundreds of millions of dollars from the state
budget and axed thousands of state jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so unpopular in 1991 that I had to cancel the
commencement speech at (the University of Georgia) in Athens,''
Miller recalls.
</P>
<P>
   With the budget crisis averted, the new governor began making
good on his promises to get tough on criminals and bolster
education.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on his much-touted Marine sergeant's background, Miller
capitalized politically by funding a series of boot camp-styled
prisons for young nonviolent offenders. Today, the camps have been
abolished or have evolved into other types of incarceration
programs. He set about building the framework for a state lottery
to fund college scholarships and pre-kindergarten for 4-year-olds.
And he launched crusades to eliminate the tax on groceries and to
clamp down on drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you've got to do early on is plow deep,'' Miller advised
a new governors conference in Wilmington, Del., shortly after the
November 1998 elections. ``Then you can spend your later years
smoothing it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, those colorful mountain metaphors or county music lyrics
were the tools Miller used to till Georgia's rocky political soil.
Singer Merle Haggard's musings about ``drinking that free Bubble-Up
and eating that rainbow stew'' were part of Miller's call in the
early '90s to put the state budget on a crash diet. But there were
other tools, such as the quick temper that flared often in his
legislative battles as lieutenant governor against House Speaker
Tom Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a sibling rivalry,'' a mellower Miller now
recalls. ``He could play off me to get things he wanted in the
House, and I could play off him to get things I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   For Miller, who watched his mother work to pay off his college
loan and who saw mountain friends struggle to make ends meet
because they couldn't find good jobs in his native Towns County,
his vision for Georgia was clear once he became governor.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted a state in which rural areas enjoyed the same economic
success as the urban centers, where all children could obtain a
good education if they worked hard enough and where issues like
crime and taxes were tackled with the same wisdom common folk used
in discussions around the kitchen table.
</P>
<P>
   But top advisers remember it also took some ``major
arm-twisting'' inside and outside the Capitol to push through the
hallmark programs that now define Miller's administration.
</P>
<P>
   A lottery devoted to education would be immensely popular among
two-thirds of Georgians, Miller's strategists advised at the time.
But the other third ``will take your hide off,'' his pollster, Alan
Secrest warned. Miller took the chance, and pushed for a
constitutional amendment on the November 1992 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The resistance was immediate and loud. Business leaders backed
away from the plan, newspapers panned it. Opposition grew so strong
that Miller couldn't attend church on Sundays without getting an
earful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't even get a resolution from college presidents to
support the lottery that fall,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many of the critics are converts. Even some who still
object to the lottery recognize how far HOPE has reached into
households.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing but a tax on the poor,'' said the Rev. Creede
Hinshaw, who spoke against the lottery from his church in Columbus.
Yet, ``as conflicted as I am by the belief that it's wrong, I've
got one boy going to school in Georgia on a HOPE scholarship and a
second son who is hoping to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The widespread success of the HOPE scholarship thrust Miller _
and Georgia _ into the national spotlight. President Bill Clinton,
a longtime friend, borrowed the Georgia program's guidelines and
its name for a national HOPE scholarship announced in his 1997
State of the Union address.
</P>
<P>
   But just as lottery-for-education buoyed Miller following his
turbulent first years as governor, an even more controversial
proposal _ changing the state flag _ threatened to sink his
aspirations for a second term.
</P>
<P>
   It was, Miller admits now, a classic example of doing exactly
what he'd long preached against _ getting sidetracked by a social
cause unrelated to kitchen-table issues.
</P>
<P>
   But with the 1996 Olympics three years away, Miller said he was
worried that the Confederate battle emblem on Georgia's flag would
taint the state's international perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a lot of wasted time,'' he admits now. ``My
obstinance in holding onto that position for so long has probably
caused a situation to develop where you couldn't do it now for
years.'' Miller's proposal misfired, and his popularity dipped to
its lowest point. His floor leaders couldn't marshal the
legislative votes to make the change.
</P>
<P>
   Smelling blood in 1994, Republicans turned to multimillionaire
Atlanta businessman Guy Millner for a well-financed bid for the
governorship, seeking to mount a strong challenge against a wounded
governor. Even to some of Miller's confidantes, his re-election
prospects looked grim.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only walk one step ahead of the people,'' said Bob
Short, one of Miller's basketball teammates at Young Harris College
who later helped the future governor get a job in former Gov.
Lester Maddox's administration. ``At times, Zell's tried to get 10
yards ahead. During those times, he's suffered the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the election, with the GOP gaining political momentum
nationwide, Pat Jarvis, a former Atlanta Braves' pitcher and one of
Miller's close friends, offered a shred of optimism from a
conversation overheard at a Willacoochee convenience store as
Miller campaigned nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the SOB that's trying to change the flag,'' Jarvis
heard a customer mutter in disgust as he watched Miller outside.
``No,'' the woman behind the counter responded. ``That's the SOB
that's paying my granddaughter's way through college.''
</P>
<P>
   The November election results followed that same grass-roots
sentiment, and Miller narrowly won a second term. It was time to
smooth that plowed field. Over the next four years, Miller
transformed himself into a near political folk-hero who helped seal
the 1998 election for Georgia Democrats by solidifying support
throughout North and South Georgia's rural areas. The man tagged as
the liberal Zig Zag Zell because he was accused of flip-flopping
positions in his earlier bids for Congress and the U.S. Senate _
and even in his first term as governor _ worked to shed the label
as he saw the nature of the national electorate changing. The new,
politically astute Miller morphed into the kind of fiscally
conservative Democrat that even suburban Republicans could embrace.
</P>
<P>
   His moves to reform welfare, to remove the state sales tax from
groceries and to get tougher on crime by strengthening DUI laws and
imposing ``two strikes and you're out'' for repeat offenders stole
key Republicans issues. Tougher still for the Republicans was
knowing that they had to back the Democratic governor or face the
prospect of being painted as the liberals on their own core issues.
What some would call manipulation, others would call
bridge-building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor was probably the first Democrat in the state that
really included people who weren't his own party favorites if he
felt they could make a difference,'' said Johnny Isakson, Miller's
GOP opponent for governor in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   How did Miller become all things to all people, seemingly
overnight? Murphy, his old nemesis, offers a simple answer: ``I
think the governor has lived by polls the last two to three
years,'' he said. (Not surprisingly, Miller disagrees).
</P>
<P>
   Though Murphy believes Miller went too far on welfare reform and
teen driving restrictions, the House Speaker still concedes: ``He's
made a better governor than I thought he would when he was elected
eight years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after 38 years in politics, Miller's list of vocal critics
is surprisingly short. The closest most will come to an unpleasant
critique is to point to important issues they say Miller shied away
from.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've got left for Roy (Barnes) are the things Zell
didn't want to tackle or would not tackle,'' said Rep. Kem Shipp
(R-Kennesaw), head of the Cobb County legislative delegation.
``Traffic. Air quality and water quality surrounding metro Atlanta.
These are all going to be unpopular.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller readily concedes that transportation gridlock, sprawl and
pollution, and the resulting federal highway funding cutoff for
metro Atlanta, are major dilemmas for the new governor. Georgians
weren't ready, he said, to accept the tough solutions early in his
administration, and still may not be. ``You can't take the public
where they don't want to go,'' he said. ``I've tried.''
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists say he didn't try hard enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't been very accessible to environmental groups and his
administration has been very poor on water quality issues,'' said
Bryan Hager, organizer of the Georgia Sierra Club's Challenge the
Sprawl Campaign. But even Hager is quick to temper the criticism.
Miller ``is not what I'd call an environment-friendly governor, but
he's not been out there pushing bad things, either. In the context
of Southern governors, he's been better than average.''
</P>
<P>
   For many Georgians, the complexities and motivations that define
Zell Miller aren't that hard to fathom. They'd heard his mountain
twang and were moved by the story of his mother, Birdie Miller,
widowed 17 days after her son was born, hauling stones from a
mountain creek to build the family's home.
</P>
<P>
   Some came to know Miller first as a young college professor who
emulated his late father, Stephen Grady Miller, first in the
college classroom and later by winning a state Senate seat. Others
watched him mature in two unsuccessful bids to represent the North
Georgia mountains in Congress, and observed his bitter defeat in
1980 in a tough U.S. Senate primary contest against Herman Talmadge
that opened the door to a Republican senator.
</P>
<P>
   Today, keenly aware of his ability to control how his political
exit is portrayed, Miller won't ``stretch out on the couch'' to
discuss touchy-feely ``psycho-babble'' about his life and
administration, he says. But colleagues offer this insight:
Miller's successes are those of a devoted son living out the
aspirations of a hard-working mother and a talented father he never
knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came to political skills, Zell's father had no
peers,'' Bert Lance, a former Carter administration official and
Miller's grade school seatmate, recalls hearing his own father say.
``I've always felt that throughout his lifetime, Zell was growing
toward those inherited qualities from his dad.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the nation first became acquainted with Miller at
the same time it embraced another Southern governor, Bill Clinton,
during the 1992 Democratic National Convention in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And Miller, so sick from strep throat that day that he'd spent
hours in bed before his keynote address, gave them a stem-winder by
way of introduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush just doesn't get it,'' Miller told the approving
crowd. ``If the `education president' gets another term, even our
kids won't be able to spell potato. If the `law and order
president' gets another term, the criminals will run wild because
our commander-in-chief talks like Dirty Harry, but acts like Barney
Fife.''
</P>
<P>
   Pundits declared Miller _ with a voice ``more barbed-wire than
honeysuckle'' _ a vibrant, emerging spokesman for the party's
moderate wing. Talk quickly began of a future for him in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Only The New York Times managed to briefly puncture the bubble
of Miller's newfound national celebrity. A few weeks after the
convention speech in a photo of Miller and other governors walking
alongside Clinton, the newspaper referred to the Georgia governor
as ``an unidentified man.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, ``He's talking point No. 1 in defense of politics and
politicians,'' said James Carville, the consultant Miller helped
make a household name by recommending him to then-presidential
candidate Clinton. ``The New York Times, they don't get beyond the
mountain twang and the odd first name.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller says the same goes for many of the other people _
especially journalists _ who've tried to pigeonhole him.
</P>
<P>
   One of his biggest regrets, Miller said recently, perhaps only
half in jest, is that he never challenged ``someone at the Atlanta
newspapers to duel over their never-ending bigotry toward rural
mountain people.'' It's a chip he's carried on his shoulder since
he first left Towns County as a student bound for Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   Miller resents that reporters often are more interested in his
cowboy boots, his ties to country music legends like George Jones
and Bill Anderson and his lifelong passion for baseball than in his
appreciation of great literature and classical music.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, maybe I've played to that,'' Miller conceded
recently, perhaps aware of the image he was perpetuating at that
moment on a recent blustery Saturday, sitting in front of the fire,
stroking his two yellow labs sprawled at his feet, his boot heels
flecked with dried Georgia clay. The dogs are named Gus and
Woodrow, they're a nod toward a favorite Miller novel, ``Lonesome
Dove.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more to Zell Miller than country music and baseball.
I'm leaving as a governor who I modestly think has changed the
entire culture of this state, certainly the way we look at going to
college,'' he said, stopping short, as he tries to these days, from
launching into one of his legendary harangues. ``It's not been just
in Georgia, but it's had consequences outside this state. I think
there's a time that we stop the quaint character bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Miller wants to be asked about his love of classical
music. (A favorite teacher cultivated it with season tickets to the
Atlanta Symphony while he was a student at Emory). He wants to be
asked about his favorite passage of Shakespeare. (Fittingly, it's
from ``Macbeth,'' Act 5, where Macbeth reflects on the queen's
death and her legacy: ``Life's but a walking shadow, a poor player
that struts and frets his hour on the stage and then is heard no
more.'') Miller knows he has left a legacy in state government.
Now, he wants to talk about his future outside politics.
</P>
<P>
   His latest project is within arms' reach. A sofa-side table
brims with books and class notes as the former history professor
prepares for the courses he'll teach later this year at Young
Harris, Emory and the University of Georgia. In a syllabus, Miller
calls his class on leadership ``a combination of philosophy,
literature, history, practical everyday living and Marine Corps
boot camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it was only months ago that political observers doubted
Miller would actually quit politics and return to the classroom.
Instead, they figured, he would challenge Republican U.S. Sen. Paul
Coverdell last November. Or accept a Clinton administration
position, which Miller hints could have been his for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   But after appearing on the ballot 22 times, Miller insists that
ceding the political spotlight was the easiest decision he's ever
made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm within three years of being 70 years old. I've had my hour
and more upon the stage,'' he said. ``If I were 10 years younger, I
would have wanted to go to Washington, probably...Now I want to do
my teaching, do some writing and try to piece together a
livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
