<HEADER>
A6032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-LEGIS-AGENDA04-COX     01-03 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-LEGIS-AGENDA04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes likely to put taxes, school discipline, health care at
top of Georgia agenda
 &HT;    By Charles Walston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the General Assembly comes to work at the Capitol
next week, the main items on its agenda will sound familiar to
Georgia voters.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be the same priorities Gov.-elect Roy E. Barnes
emphasized in his campaign last year: a reduction in property
taxes, school discipline and health care reform.
</P>
<P>
   A governor typically enters his first Legislative session with a
long list of things to do, and the Legislature usually reads his
election as a mandate for most of those proposals. Barnes, a
veteran legislator who knows his way around the Capitol as well as
any governor in recent memory, will waste no time in tackling his
pet projects.
</P>
<P>
   His promise to gradually increase the homestead exemption to
$50,000 on houses and family farms is a no-brainer. Although some
lawmakers will push their own tax-cut ideas, nobody is likely to
vote against a property tax cut when it finally reaches the floor
of the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes also wants to increase the use of alternative schools for
disruptive students, and to expand after-school programs for middle
school students. His proposed budget, which will be unveiled in the
first week of the session, will include a request for money to fund
those items, according to Bobby Kahn, Barnes' executive secretary.
</P>
<P>
   His pledge to reform managed health care plans, by making them
legally liable for decisions to refuse treatment and forcing them
to offer patients a wider choice of doctors, will be harder to
pass.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry has warned that Barnes' proposals could
raise premium costs, a claim he disputes. Many businesses are wary
of Barnes' HMO reform ideas, but health care providers are
generally supportive. The issue promises to be a boon for
lobbyists, who will be hired in droves by insurance companies on
one side, and by doctors, hospitals and lawyers on the other.
</P>
<P>
   While Barnes might not have the full support of the business
community on health care reform, he will devote much of his energy
to another issue important to business leaders - suburban sprawl
and public transportation.
</P>
<P>
   A blue-ribbon group of business and local government leaders
recently recommended seven steps to alleviate the air quality
problems that have frozen most federal highway funding for metro
Atlanta. The panel warned that poor air, traffic gridlock and bad
publicity are stifling growth.
</P>
<P>
   Although Barnes didn't talk about sprawl and gridlock as much as
some other issues during his campaign, he has said that tackling
those problems will be his most important task in this session.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes wants to set up a regional authority to manage public
transportation, and has said an east-west rail link through the
north Atlanta suburbs is a necessary component of any regional
transit plan.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes will also probably request a study of the state's water
needs, as a predicate to establishing a regional water and sewer
authority next year, according to Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue Barnes wants to address is juvenile justice. Last
year, the state entered into a consent agreement with the U.S.
Department of Justice after a federal probe found overcrowding and
other shortcomings in the state's youth detention system.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes wants to implement more preventive programs for youths
who commit nonviolent crimes, in the hope of deterring them from
more serious offenses. State Rep. Georganna Sinkfield (D-Atlanta),
chairwoman of the House committee on Children and Youth, is among
the influential legislators who favor that approach.
</P>
<P>
   While lawmakers will likely allow Barnes to set the agenda for
the session, they'll still have plenty of proposals of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charlie Smith (D-St. Marys), who will be the governor's
floor leader in the House, is a strong advocate of greater
accountability in schools. Smith may push a plan to create a
separate office to monitor the performance of schools.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, there has been a debate over whether to abolish
parole, and that almost certainly will continue this year. Barnes
does not favor ending parole for nonviolent crimes, so some
compromise, such as a committee to study ``truth in sentencing,''
could emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, House Republicans repeatedly tried to enact a law
that would prohibit any kind of affirmative action programs. An
example of the type of program that would have been affected is the
admissions policy of the state university system, which considers
the race and gender of some applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans might revisit the issue, but given Barnes' support
for existing affirmative action programs, it seems unlikely that
any such measure will pass this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans and conservative Democrats might push for a new
measure to outlaw sodomy in the state, after the Georgia Supreme
Court struck down the existing law in November. Such a bill has
virtually no chance of passing, however.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Martin (D-Atlanta), chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, is opposed to new anti-sodomy legislation, and even
Republicans will be split on the issue, according to GOP leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Georgia Chamber of Commerce supported a bill that
would have required the losers of lawsuits to pay most legal costs.
The measure failed, but a similar effort is expected this session.
</P>
<P>
   Any forecast of what the General Assembly will be up to for the
next three months must come with a caveat: There is almost always
some issue, barely on the radar screen before the session, that
turns into a major fight.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, the Legislature battled fiercely over a
proposal that would have prohibited oil refiners from owning
filling stations. Last year, a plan to provide health insurance for
children erupted into a major fight. Even though most lawmakers
supported the idea, there was a division over how to implement it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some of those issues that looked like smooth
sailing,'' said Bill Lee, the former chairman of the House Rules
Committee who retired from the Legislature this year. ``Then
something always jumps out of the socket.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
