   1999-ECON (Undated) _ Most economists say that 1999 is going to
look the way they thought 1998 would look. Growth is supposed to
slow sharply, profits to shrink, inflation to creep up,
unemployment to edge up a bit. Sure, they may be wrong. But that is
exactly the kind of soft landing that Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan
and other central bankers have been hoping for. By Sylvia Nasar.
