<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6053 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-CUSTODY04-COX     01-03 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-CUSTODY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family barred from visiting baby angry at legal system after her
death
 &HT;    By Will Anderson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Stan and Deborah Layton had seen their granddaughter
only once before last month, when they walked into the hospital
where the 9-month-old was on life support.
</P>
<P>
   An apparent victim of abuse, Bryanna Marie Hollis lay
unconscious in the intensive care unit, hidden from view by a
curtain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw her move,'' Deborah Layton said.
</P>
<P>
   The child's father and the Laytons' son, Donald Cox, 21, was
with her when doctors removed the machines that had kept her alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nurse did open Bryanna's eyes for Donald to see. She had
the most beautiful blue eyes. He held her in his arms when life
support was turned off,'' said Stan Layton. ``Everyone in the room
... was in tears. She was a very beautiful baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Laytons nor Cox could have foreseen what happened to
the little girl. Barred from visiting Bryanna by her mother's
family, the Laytons and Cox didn't even have a photograph of the
child until her death.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Smyrna family is angry at a legal system they say did
nothing to protect Cox's right to see his own child, a right that
if granted might have prevented her death.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 23, Cobb County police charged Bryanna's stepfather,
Nicholas Stephen Wood, 20, with murder. A warrant for Wood's arrest
alleges he shook the child repeatedly and banged her head on
various objects while baby-sitting on Dec. 21. Her mother,
19-year-old Stephanie Hollis, phoned 911 from their home in
Mableton and told the dispatcher that Bryanna had stopped
breathing, police reported.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have declined to release other details about the
child's injuries, but Stan Layton said her left leg was in a cast
from a previous unexplained injury. Her other leg may have been
broken, too, Stan Layton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know there was abuse. We never got to know this
little girl,'' said Stan Layton, who is actually Cox's stepfather.
``We were at the hospital when she was born, and the following day
we were told by the mother's family that it would take a court
order for us to see Bryanna again.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bryanna was born out of wedlock, the Laytons were
willing to do whatever necessary to take part in the child's life.
Their son made a room in their house into a nursery last February _
one month before Bryanna's birth _ complete with a crib, stuffed
toys and her name scrawled on one wall in big wooden letters
painted to match the colors of the nursery. Cox bought toys and
clothes for the little girl, in hopes of being allowed to visit her
on Christmas day. Now Cox wants to donate all the items to a
charity that helps child abuse victims.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can cut here.)
</P>
<P>
   Two months after Bryanna was born, her mother married Wood and
moved away from Cobb County, Stan Layton said. The Laytons sought
legal advice and learned that their son would have to prove
paternity through DNA testing to be able to visit the child. They
also would have to sue for custody. Meanwhile, the state Department
of Human Resources filed a lawsuit on behalf of Bryanna's mother
seeking child support payments.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Bryanna's mother, Stephanie Hollis, were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to go through all this legal (stuff),'' Stan Layton
said. ``You go for custody hoping you'll get joint custody. We
couldn't see the baby, and we didn't know where they lived.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal wrangling continued until the day Bryanna died. That
day, Stan Layton received a letter from the attorney for Bryanna's
mother, restating the family's intent to prohibit Cox from visiting
the baby. The next day, the attorney called Cox's lawyer to
apologize.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Layton, the baby's grandmother, said the lawsuit still
hurts. ``We don't want Donny to be considered a deadbeat when he
did everything within the law to be a part of that child's life,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even after her death, the Laytons and Cox still are fighting for
the child. Deborah Layton has spoken with an attorney to see if
it's legally possible to change Bryanna's last name to Cox even
after her death _ her son's wish. Despite the tragedy, Deborah
Layton said her heart breaks for both sides of Bryanna's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot imagine the pain she is going through,'' she said.
``I don't know if I could handle knowing that I married a man that
hurt my child.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
