A6054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLYMPIC-KIOSKS04-COX     01-03 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPIC-KIOSKS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fraud, faulty setup alleged by Olympic kiosk investors in
lawsuit
 &HT;    By Jay Croft
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like countless other businessmen in 1996, Raed Halum
thought he could clear a good return on an Olympics investment.
</P>
<P>
   Halum and four friends and family members pulled together
$270,000 to buy 27 kiosks from which to sell souvenirs around
Atlanta during the Games, anticipating profits of more than $1.35
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never happened,'' said Halum, 31, a men's clothing retailer
in New Orleans. ``They took our money and never gave us anything in
return. Nothing _ absolutely nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Halum and 10 other people and corporations sued, alleging they
had been swindled and seeking at least $6 million. Their case
starts today with jury selection in Fulton County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Defendants include Creative Travel Services, the Peachtree City
company that brought about 3,000 teen-agers from across the country
to work at the souvenir booths. In a well-publicized crisis, the
company could neither feed nor house the youths, who returned home.
</P>
<P>
   That trouble is not at issue in this lawsuit, though it
contributed to the company's difficulties, and the kiosk buyers say
their money was improperly used to tend to those other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Creative Travel and related companies sold scores of kiosks at
$10,000 each to 50 to 75 investors, said Vanessa Vargas, a Chicago
attorney representing the kiosk buyers who sued. Sellers told
investors their split of daily gross sales could reach thousands of
dollars a day, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The losses would have happened anyway,'' even without the
mixup regarding the youths, because the kiosk sellers had not
properly prepared, Vargas said.
</P>
<P>
   Halum and the other kiosk buyers allege fraud, theft by
conversion, misuse of escrow funds and violations of the Georgia
Business Opportunity Act and the state racketeering and corrupt
organizations act.
</P>
<P>
   All of the plaintiffs, including former Miami Dolphin receiver
Mark Clayton and former Atlanta Brave Ryan Bowen, live outside of
Georgia, except one part-time resident. They say the defendants
promoted the kiosk deal falsely and then failed to provide the
goods and services needed to make the booths work properly _
including the booths, themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs say they paid a total of $900,000, which the
defendants used to pay for personal operations and profit.
</P>
<P>
   Creative Travel and other defendants ``had a lot of other
operations going on,'' Vargas said. ``This was where they were
getting all of the cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Defendants' attorneys did not return phone calls or declined to
comment last week.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Freeman, who owned 50 percent of Creative Travel, said
during the Olympics he is an honest man who fell victim to huge
mistakes. He called the experience ``the greatest nightmare of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Other defendants include companies the kiosk buyers say were set
up to carry out the sales and their backers. Merle D. Zmak, the
Creative Travel founder, has filed for bankruptcy protection in
Texas and received an automatic stay for protection against
liability in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, defendants deny liability. Some say they were
not agents of the corporations or in control of them. Others say
they were acting as corporate officers and are protected by a
``corporate shield,'' committed no fraud and the losses were the
fault of other people and organizations, including the city of
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   One of the defendant companies, Event Management and Marketing
Associates Inc., is in Chapter 7 bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
