</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-IMAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNFORGETTABLE DANCE IMAGES IN 1998 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By   JENNIFER DUNNING   
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Beaming, beautifully dressed women and handsome men
of all ages surged up the stairs and poured out of the elevators to
the promenade of the New York State Theater in November, soon
filling that vast marbled space with laughter, anecdotes and
embraces.
</P>
<P>
   The parade of 50 years of New York City Ballet dancers, gathered
for the alumni reunion that began the company's anniversary
celebrations, might have been a dance lover's fantasy. It was
certainly one of the happiest memories of the dance year of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The faces looked astonishingly familiar, quickly recalling the
articulation and eloquence of their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Almost no one looked older. But almost all the dancers _ from
the corps to the stars and near-stars of other years _ looked as if
they had found there was life after dance.
</P>
<P>
   Though nothing quite equaled the sumptuousness of this
experience, the year was filled with enough indelible images to
make the memory of dance-going in 1998 contradict those who bemoan
the premature death of the art. Some of the strongest images were
also the quietest.
</P>
<P>
   American Ballet Theater's now-annual fall season at City Center,
a much more intimate setting for the company than its summer home
at the Metropolitan Opera House, had plenty of performing and
choreographic highlights.
</P>
<P>
   Among the choreographic standouts were Twyla Tharp's richly
intriguing ``Known by Heart'' and John Selya's ``Disposition,''
which was revealed as an authoritative and imaginative exploration
of the classical idiom when danced by its second cast. But it is
Anton Dolin's ``Variations for Four,'' a showcase, created in 1957
for British male virtuoso dancing, that stands out most clearly.
</P>
<P>
   It is by now a commonplace to smile over Anna Pavlova's very
deficient technique and the sorry state of British male dancing
before 1956. It was then that the Bolshoi Ballet introduced Soviet
firebrand pyrotechnicists to a male home team relegated by
revisionist ballet history to a dowdiness comparable to the ``mad
old maids in moth-eaten musquash'' who formed, in the words of the
dance writer Richard Buckle, the ballet audiences of the time. The
incandescent, trickily demanding ``Variations for Four'' suggests
not only that there was impressive dancing to be seen in British
ballet but also that pyrotechnics could be just as exciting when
executed with restraint.
</P>
<P>
   There was a similar revelation in Jawole Willa Jo Zollar's
``Hands Singing Song,'' commissioned by the American Dance Festival
and performed there and at the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival this
summer. Though audiences appear to be increasingly immune to
shock-tactic dance and theater, masturbation is still a reliably
difficult theme for many. But that was the subject of one section
of this suite of dances about hands. It was approached with such
delicacy and graciousness _ without at all camouflaging the
activity _ that the dance was received with a rapt silence and then
applause and cheers.
</P>
<P>
   It will be difficult, too, to forget the revivifying sassiness
of some of the year's most entertaining dance. First on that list
is Matthew Bourne's impudent and surprisingly poignant ``Swan
Lake,'' at the Neil Simon Theater through Jan. 23, a treatment of a
hallowed classic that proved to be an unforgettable dance and
theater experience. And who could forget the men of the Alvin Ailey
American Dance Theater, who managed to be both suave and impishly
sensuous in so much that they performed in the company's just-ended
season at City Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Danspace Project helpfully provided a look back into history
in December in the first of its ``Silver Series'' programs
celebrating 25 years of presenting dance at St. Mark's Church in
the East Village. The vehicle was an onstage speech by Stephen
Facey, a church administrator who welcomed the project and pushed
for it to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Facey, an endearing mix of wit, warmth and idealism, did not
mention the misspent childhood of one of the project's founders,
the leading avant-gardist Barbara Dilley, who began her career as
the Sugar Plum Fairy in a Princeton Ballet Society production of
``The Nutcracker.''
</P>
<P>
   But everything else was there: the unruly, persistent artists
who claimed their space in dance of the 1960's, so much a part of
the vital downtown theater scene of the time, and the hope,
imagination and hard work that went into the building and
rebuilding of the church by local youths chosen for the job because
there had been so little hope, meaningful work and imagination in
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   New York dance also looked to the past in 1998 in Kevin Ward's
luminous ``Offering,'' performed by the Dayton Contemporary Dance
Company at the Joyce Theater in September, in homage to Ward's
beloved teacher and mentor James Truitte, who died in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   May there be a Kevin Ward for at least three of the dance
luminaries who died this year: for the incandescent Svetlana
Beriosova, a star of Britain's Royal Ballet; for Protima Bedi, the
vibrant dance activist who founded the young Nrityagram Dance
Ensemble of India, and for Viola Farber, an early Merce Cunningham
dancer who endowed eccentricity with rare grace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 1536EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
