<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOV-ESCAPE-540&AMP;ADD-NY     01-03 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOV-ESCAPE-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOWLS FROM THE PRESS SCUTTLE GOVERNOR'S SECRET ESCAPE PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 BY STEVE BARNES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Any politician would covet one, and Gov.
Mike Huckabee of Arkansas almost had one: an escape hatch.
</P>
<P>
   But dismayed by news accounts of the project, Huckabee has
canceled plans to convert an abandoned dumbwaiter shaft in a corner
of his state Capitol office to an emergency exit. The chute,
long-neglected if not forgotten altogether, would have been fitted
with ladder steps and have enabled Huckabee, a Republican, to
decamp the Arkansas statehouse, a Democratic redoubt, without first
leaving his second-floor suite.
</P>
<P>
   The dumbwaiter shaft, dusty, musty and measuring approximately
six feet by three feet, connects to the Capitol's first floor,
where it opens near a legislative committee room.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Saturday, Huckabee insisted that the idea
originated with his state police bodyguards, who he said were
alarmed at the lack of an alternative to his office's front door in
the event of a security threat. A state police spokesman declined
to discuss Huckabee's security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had nothing to do with it,'' Huckabee said. ``I don't deal
with issues like that.'' But he acknowledged that ``reckless'' news
accounts of the renovation prompted him to order it stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue became moot when I read about it in the paper,''
Huckabee said. ``There's no security value once it's been published
in the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   However, political satirists and Democratic state legislators,
with whom Huckabee has frequently been at odds, found comic value
in the episode. ``A `fraidy hole'!'' smirked one member of the
Arkansas House of Representatives, speaking anonymously. An
editorial cartoon in the Arkansas Democrat-Gazette, the state's
largest daily newspaper, suggested the governor install an ejection
seat with parachute in lieu of a ladder.
</P>
<P>
   The architecture of the Arkansas Capitol and the protocol of
parking have led the state's governors invariably to enter and
depart the building through a first floor rotunda that is heavily
traveled by lobbyists, legislators and the public, and requires
them to pass the cramped press room. Not a few governors have
suggested, with a hard smile, that more commodious accommodations
might be found for the State Capitol news corps _ the basement,
perhaps, or even a tent on the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   It would surprise no one in the Arkansas political establishment
if Huckabee shared that view, so thorny have been his relations
with journalists. Since becoming governor following the
Whitewater-related conviction and subsequent resignation of Jim Guy
Tucker in 1996, Huckabee has chafed at news stories he considered
unfair or inappropriate. Many involved the still undisclosed
sources of speaking fees he received while lieutenant governor.
More recently, leaked documents suggesting that Huckabee and his
family paid personal expenses from an expense fund intended to
maintain the governor's mansion have resulted in a pending
taxpayer's lawsuit demanding that he repay the disputed sums.
</P>
<P>
   If such news coverage rankles the governor, the public has
seemed scarcely to notice it, or at least to pay it little mind.
Huckabee won re-election to a full term last November, capturing 60
percent of the vote.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to denying any wrongdoing, Huckabee, an ordained
Southern Baptist minister, has complained of a ``Jerry Springer
mentality'' among journalists and that he is being held to a
different standard than his Democratic predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Huckabee said any suggestions that he would have used the
aborted exit to escape reporters were ``ludicrous and unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wanted to avoid reporters, there are better ways to do
it,'' Huckabee snipped.
</P>
<P>
   One of his most persistent critics, state Rep. Shane M.
Broadway, a Democrat from Benton, Ark., said in an interview that a
more secure passage from the governor's office was both justified
and overdue. But, added Broadway, ``I think some of it was to avoid
the press. I don't think he has a great trust of you guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
