</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSES-CONNECTIONS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PURSUIT OF MOSES, FROM EXODUS TO `PRINCE OF EGYPT' 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By   EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It doesn't take long before we recognize Moses in Dreamworks'
new animated film, ``The Prince of Egypt.'' He is one of us.
</P>
<P>
   He is a rebel without a cause who eventually finds a cause. The
way he finds that cause is not by hearing the Divine voice from the
burning bush but by doing something much more modern. He discovers
his identity. We already are aware of it, of course, since the
movie opens with those archetypal scenes of the Hebrew babe in a
basket rescued from the bulrushes by the Pharaoh's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But in this film Moses grows up not knowing of his difference.
Yes, he is far more reckless and mischievous than his older
brother, who is heir to the Egyptian throne, but the two are chummy
teen-age adventurers, drag racing their chariots to edges of
cliffs. Only later, by accident, does Moses find out he is not an
Egyptian. Then (in a stunning episode with animated hieroglyphics)
he learns of his Pharaonic father's decree to murder his fellow
Israelites' first-born.
</P>
<P>
   He begins to see the slaves with new eyes. He becomes a stranger
in his own land. When he smites the Egyptian taskmaster and flees,
he cries out to his brother in late-20th-century fashion, ``All I
have ever known to be true is a lie!'' The idea is that we are
enlightened by discovering who we are. This self-knowledge
determines our allegiances and our views of the truth and
eventually leads us to liberation.
</P>
<P>
   This concept is almost painfully contemporary when appended to
this ancient tale. But it shows where our secular culture has been
leading Moses in recent years. The original biblical text in Exodus
is far more laconic. There is no suggestion that Moses thought he
was anything but a Hebrew. When he is grown, he goes out to see his
``brethren.'' There he sees an ``Egyptian man'' smiting one of
those ``brethren.'' The identification is primal, tribal, not a
matter for discovery or revelation. Instead, the revelation comes
in a more elaborate form.
</P>
<P>
   Moses smites the Egyptian, but he does so only after turning
``this way and that'' to make sure there is no one watching before
he does the deed. In a recent, suggestive survey of the Mosaic
literature, ``Moses: A Life'' (Ballantine), the amateur scholar
Jonathan Kirsch argues that this shows this was not an attack done
out of outrage and passion but had a premeditated element. Moses
planned to kill.
</P>
<P>
   But those precautionary turnings provide a rare glimpse into a
personality that lies behind the spare text and mythic elaborations
that have accumulated over the millenniums. Moses feels outrage at
the Egyptian smiting one of his brethren, but he is also afraid. He
is tempted to act but worries over consequences. Revenge may be
called for; it may even be just. But how free is he, after all, to
take such things into his own hands? What sort of retribution will
there be? He must keep his act secret. So when he does kill the
Egyptian, he hides the body in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   But the blood of the Egyptian does not cry out to the Lord from
the ground like the blood of Abel in Genesis. Moses hides the body
from civil authorities, not from divine justice. He does it
stupidly. Coming upon a dead Egyptian taskmaster covered in sand,
who else will be suspected but Moses' Hebrew brethren? The act is
at once noble and cowardly, calculated and impetuous. It is the act
of a man ruled by strong passions as well as strong fears, an
impulsive man tortured by first and then second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the second sentence of this three-sentence tale, we
learn that the next day Moses comes upon two Hebrews fighting. When
he tries to intercede, stopping the ``wicked'' one mid-smite,
Moses' stature is challenged by the combatant: ``Who made thee a
ruler and judge over us?'' Moreover, his secret murder of the
previous day is thrust in his face, as a challenge to his virtue.
``And Moses feared.''
</P>
<P>
   In these few sentences, the elements of the developing biblical
drama are laid out: Moses' mercurial personality, his moral
impulse, his sense of guilt, the challenges from his people, the
problems with becoming a judge when his own hands are stained with
blood. The wicked Hebrew's challenging question about who made
Moses ruler eventually will be answered by the burning bush, but
there will be no simplifying the complications.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a matter of Moses finding his identity. It is not
even a matter of liberation. It is a matter of becoming more aware
of the stakes involved in building a human society that, like all
societies, will contain its fair share of passion, murder,
violation, revenge and warfare. These evils flourish on all sides:
Moses himself orders massacres of women and children after a
battle. But the challenge is to build a society that takes all of
those perilously human frailties into account, reconciling freedom
and the authority of law.
</P>
<P>
   We tend to simplify the intricacies here, partly because these
stories have become so bound up in issues of faith. But they
already bear within them ancient traces of conflicting struggles
over the nature of the authority Moses created. If the story's
divine origins are questioned, the floodgates open. Israelite
priests, scholars have told us, added justifications for their
spiritual authority to the Mosaic tales, elevating the stature of
Moses' brother Aaron as the first high priest.
</P>
<P>
   The paraphernalia of pagan magic also abounds, bearing the
traces of more ancient authorities appealed to in the formation of
a people. Most recently, there have been renewed attempts to give
closer attention to the hypothesis Freud championed: that Moses,
who actually bears an Egyptian name, was really an Egyptian prince
who believed in monotheism and tried to build a new nation around
his faith. Even ``The Prince of Egypt'' suggests that the Exodus
story is a struggle between Egyptian brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The biblical text is a monument of human belief, intricately
overlaying archeological strata from different traditions. Now we
have added another trace to the accumulated interpretations. In
secular culture Mosaic authority is not found in the burning bush
or the accumulations of Deuteronomic law, but in ourselves. We
follow the path of the new Moses, as if we could resolve profound
issues simply by discovering our identities and celebrating them as
the path of liberation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
