<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Jan. 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tranquil weather will return to much of the nation Monday as the
storm that caused record snow in the Middle West and flooding rain
on the Northeast Seaboard carries its assault into eastern Canada.
In the wake of the storm, gusty winds from the west will direct
much drier air to the Eastern Seaboard with ample sunshine and near
seasonable temperatures. Farther west, clouds banked along the
Appalachian mountains will tend to crumble just east of the
mountains as the gusty west winds dry on descent toward the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Narrow bands of intense snow will form to the east of Lake Erie
and Ontario on Monday as frigid air traversing the unfrozen lakes
rises into roiling clouds upon being warmed and moistened. The
snowfall could become quite heavy for a time near Buffalo, N.Y., as
a jet stream disturbance crossing the region enhances the ascending
air currents.
</P>
<P>
   The clockwise circulation around high pressure over Texas will
drive unseasonably cold air into the Deep South on Monday. Clearing
skies and diminishing winds will set the stage for the chilliest
night of the winter season so far as readings drop to near freezing
as far south as Orlando, Fla. Farther west, dry and chilly air will
also cover the southern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Mild but strong winds from the west will buffet the northeast
Rockies Monday with a few locations recording gusts exceeding 60
mph. Dry and generally sunny conditions will cover the West Coast,
though fog will linger in California's Central Valley. It will be
quite warm in the Los Angeles basin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SNOW RECORDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both Rochester, Minn., and Chicago, Ill., broke snowfall records
during this past holiday weekend. On New Year's Day, 1.4 inches
fell in Rochester, breaking the record of 1.0 inch that had stood
since 1956. On Saturday, O'Hare airport measured 18.6 inches of
snow for most snowfall in any 24-hour period in the city's history.
By the time the snow tapered off on Sunday, nearly 22 inches had
fallen at the airport, making this storm the second greatest on
record for Chicago. Surprisingly, Chicago had not measured a foot
of snow in a single storm since 1979, two decades ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
