<SLUG> BC-YOURCAREER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES WITHOUT Y2K PLANS SHOULD BRACE FOR LAWSUITS FROM
EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Tick tock. It's 1999. One more year until 2000, at
which time we'll have read or heard about the Year 2000 computer
problem ad nauseum. Don't get bored yet, though _ especially if
you're a director, owner or executive at a non-Y2K-compliant
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Experts are warning to expect lawsuits from employees who don't
get their paychecks or other benefits on time.
</P>
<P>
   The scurry to fix old computer programs that use only two digits
for a date _ and thus treat the year 2000 as 1900 _ is bringing out
the antacid in board meetings. Board members, as well as those in
ownership or top management positions, should heed this notice
published in ``Director's Monthly,'' a newsletter of the National
Association of Corporate Directors:
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent a company's board of directors fails to adopt a
Year 2000 corrective action plan or acts in a manner which results
in losses to the corporation as the result of the Y2K problem, the
potential for lawsuits from its employees and its shareholder is
high.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential for risk _ corporate and personal _ obviously
depends partly on the size of your company, how much of your
business activity relies on computer programs affected by the Y2K
problem and what good-faith effort your organization is making now
to prevent trouble.
</P>
<P>
   You also should find out what similar efforts your service
providers and record keepers are undertaking. Just imagine if your
pension or COBRA administrator is not Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
   And don't count on an insurance bail-out. Insurance companies
are writing policy disclaimers saying they won't bail out
organizations that failed to exercise expected diligence in fixing
Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K litigation from employees may come hand in hand with
lawsuits from shareholders and customers. You're wise to do what
you can now to protect yourself from being named as a defendant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 1713EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
