<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, A FEARLESS FORECAST FOR THE NEW YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Hey, kids, what time is it? Why, it's Fearless Forecast
time!
</P>
<P>
   That's right! Ready or not, your Uncle Fearless is about to do
his annual high-wire prognostication performance without a net. The
result is usually a pratfall of disastrous proportions, but what
the heck. The only thing Uncle Fearless ever hurts in these bouts
of soothsaying exhibitionism is his pride.
</P>
<P>
   If these exercises in augury are so seldom near the target, you
may ask, then what is the point of the indulgence?
</P>
<P>
   Good question.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of it is the company it allows your Fearless Forecaster to
keep. Some of the most eminent economists on the planet are
humiliated by their prognosticatory urges. The prospect of being
wrong with the best of them is an irresistible temptation. Another
good reason, of course, is that this space cannot be left blank,
and this is a slow time of year.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the matter of demand for the product. There are no
doubt many readers who enjoy seeing Uncle Fearless look foolish. An
editor put it all into perfect perspective a couple of years ago by
topping the Fearless Forecast column with a ``Bozo's back, and...''
headline. Is that recognition, or what?
</P>
<P>
   OK, kids, enough of this serious stuff. Let's get onto the fun
part and start forecasting:
</P>
<P>
   - Economic growth: After two years of a much stronger economy
than many experts anticipated, growth really will begin to slow in
1999. The pace of worldwide expansion slowed from 3.3 percent in
1997 to 1.7 percent in 1998, and this must translate into reduced
U.S. output. After expanding 3.5 percent in each of the last two
years, gross domestic product will grow 2 percent or slightly less
in 1999. The Federal Reserve will do all in its power to keep the
economy moving, and full employment will keep consumers in the ball
game. Something else to think about is that if the expansion keeps
going into early 2000, it will become the longest in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   - Stock market: Low interest rates and Internet-stocks madness
can only fuel the market's unlikely strength for so long before
earnings reality sets in. Unless corporate profits stage an
unexpected rally in 1999, the overall market is likely to back and
fill, with not much potential on the upside. The Dow Jones
industrial average will record a bottom of 7,500 and a top of 9,800
and close the year at 8,600 for its first down year since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   - Interest rates: Accommodative Fed policy, low inflation and
slower growth at home and abroad will combine to keep interest
rates tamped. The 30-year Treasury bond will close the year
yielding 4.25 percent, and the three-month bill rate will end 1999
at 3.65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   - Inflation: The deflation in commodities and competition in the
global marketplace will serve to keep the general price level down.
The Consumer Price Index rise will be below 2 percent for the third
straight year.
</P>
<P>
   That's all, folks! Stop by same time next year, and watch your
Uncle Fearless eat another heapin' helpin' of prognosticatory crow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 1714EST &QL; 
