<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VECSEY-BOWDEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BOWDEN GIVES THIS BOWL GAME THE RIGHT SOUND
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ When football speaks, it does so in a southern
accent. For example, when Bobby Bowden of Florida State voices his
fears that a Tennessee running back will burn him for a long gain,
he calls it ``a big `un,'' and Yankees and Californians and
Dakotans know exactly what he means.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta Bowl on Monday night is a ``big `un,'' bringing
together two southern schools in the arid desert air for a national
championship. With Keith Jackson calling his last couple of dozen
``Whoa, Nellies'' on the tube, the game will come straight from the
emotional heart of ``foo'ball,'' the deep south.
</P>
<P>
   Allie Sherman certainly exemplified the southern tinge during
his regime as coach of the professional New York Giants. Allie may
not have consciously done this, but he surely mastered the
linguistic art of saying defensive backs had to ``he'p'' each other
out, thereby obscuring his own origins amidst the spanish moss and
kudzu vines of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody speaks football better than Bobby Bowden, the gabby
patriarch from Tallahassee, seeking his second national
championship. Bowden is something of a military history buff, but
his main charm is drawing upon the many decades of college football
he has known.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas many college football coaches creep me out with their
edgy sanctimony, Bowden charmed me early in this decade. After
losing to Miami on a swerved field-goal attempt, he appeared at his
mandatory Sunday-morning press wrapup in a serious dark suit, and
somebody asked why he was all dressed up. Bowden chirped, ``Goin'
to church, y'all wanna join me?'' making it sound like an
invitation rather than a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, anticipating only the second meeting in the glorious
history of Tennessee and the rather nouveau history of Florida
State, Bowden was delighted to talk about Tennessee's influence on
him.
</P>
<P>
   Kids in Birmingham are raised to root for Alabama or maybe even
Auburn, but Bowden was impressed by Tennessee at an early age. He
recalled being around 10 years old, ``layin' on the floor,''
listening to Tennessee play USC on the radio _ probably a blocky
Philco, although Bowden didn't get into that. Bowden also had
Tennessee winning, which is a good trick, considering that
Tennessee is 0-4 against USC over the years, but Bowden was right
in that Tennessee generally won, under its first great coach,
General Bob Neyland, as in Neyland Stadium, the gigantic 107,000
stadium in Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee football touched Bowden in a most visceral way when he
was 12 years old and selling newspapers on First Avenue in
Birmingham, where in those pre-Interstate days, the cars from
Knoxville used to rumble into town for the big game with `Bama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the long line of traffic, the cars all decorated
orange and white,'' Bowden recalled Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He also recalled how General Bob's disciples had filtered into
the football cadre throughout the South, to the extent that Bowden
was coached by a Neyland man in high school and a Neyland man in
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I heard was Bob Neyland,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Five or six years ago, Bowden did a favor for Phillip Fulmer,
the current Tennessee coach, and appeared at a football gathering
in Knoxville, where they gave him a Bob Neyland Trophy _ ``my
favorite trophy, out of both of `em,'' Bowden said, surely a
practiced line, but it brought chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   He also made me smile when he explained that he still coaches
``because I like rings; they give you a ring whenever you win your
conference or a bowl game.'' He said he still enjoys recruiting,
going to visit ``the mamas and the papas,'' although he did shudder
a bit about his journey to recruit the current backup quarterback,
Jared Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walla Walla, Washington,'' he said, drawing out every syllable
``I love to say that name. It is hard to get to, however. It takes
four hours to fly to Seattle, a missed flight to Walla Walla, bum a
ride with some guy.''
</P>
<P>
   These are not the proper things to do to a 69-year-old body, but
Bowden seems to be holding up. He said he plans to keep coaching
rather than the only two alternatives he sees _ weeding his lawn,
or keeling over the day after retiring. Of course, he said, if he
loses four games some season, ``some young guy'' is going to have
to repair the mess. Three of his four sons are in his business,
which gets more cutthroat all the time.
</P>
<P>
   The first Bowl Championship Series game, No. 1 vs. No. 2, was
awarded to Arizona, and now the local hustlers are whining because
Tennessee and Florida State fans have not swarmed out here to
create the desired four-digit ticket scalper price. Nevertheless,
Bowden's Alabama twang and Fulmer's Tennessee drawl have given this
game a touch of authenticity. Y'all check it out on your Philco,
y'hear?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
