<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC DEAL WITH AIRTOUCH IS STILL NOT FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Calif.) 
(lb) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Corp. remained in negotiations Sunday to buy
Airtouch Corp., one of the world's biggest wireless telephone
carriers, for more than $45 billion in stock, but an agreement had
not been completed and a final deal remained at least a few days
away, executives close to the talks said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said that while a deal could be announced this
week, it could take until the end of the month for the companies to
finalize the terms of an acquisition. The executives said it was
still possible, though highly unlikely, that the talks could
collapse. Negotiations continued Sunday afternoon at a law firm in
New York, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring Airtouch would catapult Bell Atlantic into a position
of global leadership in the fast-growing market for wireless
communications. Perhaps even more important, acquiring Airtouch,
based in San Francisco, would help give Bell Atlantic the
coast-to-coast wireless network necessary to compete in the United
States against wireless giants including AT&AMP;T Corp. and the Sprint
PCS venture.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, the No. 1 local phone company, could pay as much
as $50 billion for Airtouch, the executives said. The price of Bell
Atlantic's shares fell $3.50, to $54, on Thursday on the New York
Stock Exchange amid concerns that paying so much in stock could
dilute Bell Atlantic's future per-share earnings. Airtouch's shares
rose $3.0625, to $72.4375.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Sunday which issues remained to be negotiated
between the two companies. It is conceivable that reaching a
valuation for the deal could become more difficult as the
companies' stock prices fluctuate in response to reports of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   The executives close to the negotiations said that no other
bidder had emerged for Airtouch. Vodafone Group PLC of Britain had
been thought to be interested in acquiring at least Airtouch's
overseas operations.
</P>
<P>
   Some telecommunications executives think that if a second bidder
were to emerge, it could be MCI Worldcom Inc., which does not have
a big wireless business. But Bernard Ebbers, that company's chief
executive, has said that acquiring a wireless operation could
dilute his company's earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 1733EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ANDERSON-PARCELLS     01-03 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-PARCELLS-2TAKES(900)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS AND THE PLAYOFFS ARE TOGETHER AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ For a pro football coach, the Super Bowl
playoffs are the test tubes of his career. It's where a compelling
coach separates himself from the merely competent, where he
discovers who he is and what his team is, where he learns how to
win because he has learned why he lost.
</P>
<P>
   It's where Bill Parcells will lead the Jets against the
Jacksonville Jaguars next Sunday in an American Football Conference
divisional playoff, the beginning of what could be his fourth
journey to the Super Bowl. It's where he is still doing at age 57
what he does so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't leave any stone unturned,'' the Jets' coach was
saying of this week's practices and meetings. ``You have to be
ready for any eventuality. You have to have all your ammunition,
all your defenses. No surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells knows. He has two Super Bowl rings, from his 1986 and
1990 Giants teams. He also has the scar from losing the Super Bowl
with the New England Patriots two years ago. In only his second
Jets' season after inheriting a 1-15 team, he knows how to win, but
he also knows the pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``One bad play sends you home,'' he said. ``One holding penalty.
One clip. One fumble. One missed coverage. One missed tackle. One
going to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells knows all this because the playoffs have been the story
of his life as a coach. He has endured its emotions from insecurity
to anxiety to success, from depression to euphoria to
disappointment to the next Sunday's unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the active coaches with 100 or more victories in the
National Football League, he has the best playoff record: 10-5.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the coaches with 100 or more victories, his .667
post-season winning percentage shares sixth place on the career
list behind Vince Lombardi (9-1), Weeb Ewbank (4-1), Joe Gibbs
(16-5), Buddy Parker (3-1) and Bill Walsh (10-4).
</P>
<P>
   And now Parcells recounted the story of his life that began in
1984, his second season with the Giants, with a 16-13 wild-card
victory over the Los Angeles Rams in Anaheim, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early that season we lost to the Rams out there, 33-12,'' he
recalled. ``That put us at 3-2 for the season and if we had gone to
3-5, I would've been finished. But we wound up 9-7 and when we won
that wild-card game, it was a confidence builder, especially on the
road. It told me, `Hey, you can do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the divisional playoff in San Francisco, the Giants lost,
21-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the 49ers' best team ever; they were 15-1 and went on
to win the Super Bowl,'' he said. ``We got across midfield five
times and didn't score, but this was the beginning of the Giants'
rise. I got the feeling that the organization was thinking, `Hey,
this may be our guy, after all.'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, the Giants improved to 10-6, then eliminated the 49ers,
17-3, in a wild-card playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Morris was great, 141 yards,'' he said. ``Phil Simms threw
two touchdown passes. The one to Mark Bavaro I can see that now.
Winning that game, we knew we were pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the divisional playoff in Chicago's cold and windy
Soldier Field, the Giants were blanked, 21-0, by the soon to be
Super Bowl champion Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it when Sean Landeta missed the punt out of
our end zone and they recovered and scored,'' he said. ``Sean was
and still is a great punter and he's always said the wind blew the
ball on him, but I still think he missed it because he was looking
at the rush. All I could think about was that the loss meant
another off-season, another draft, another training camp, another
season, another set of playoffs before we'd have another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   On the chartered flight home, Parcells was sitting with Mickey
Corcoran, his mentor, who had been his high school basketball coach
in Oradell, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so mad, I hadn't talked to anybody for about four
hours,'' he said. ``Mickey finally turns to me and says, `Hey,
Parcells, you got to figure out a way to beat these guys.' I knew
he was serious because he called me Parcells like he did when I was
in high school. I knew the organization was kind of satisfied. I
remember Wellington Mara telling me, `Well, we had a good year,'
but I was worse than ever. It just made me more determined to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1986 Giants did it, but not until after Parcells threw a
tantrum and a trash can during the season finale against Green Bay
at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We jumped ahead, 21-0, in the first quarter, but then we
relaxed and by halftime, we were up only 24-17,'' he said. ``I was
so mad. In the defensive meeting, I picked up a big plastic trash
can filled with a week's tape, soda cans and snuff cans, and flung
it all on the players, then I threw the can against the back
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants responded, winning, 55-24, for their ninth straight
and a 14-2 record, then routed the 49ers, 49-3, in the divisional
playoff and the Redskins, 17-0, in the NFC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so windy at the championship game, with gusts up to 35
miles an hour, when we won the toss, we took the wind instead of
the ball,'' he said. ``We scored with the wind when Phil Simms hit
Lionel Manuel, then we drove the ball through the wind in the
second quarter for another touchdown. Phil McConkey caught six
punts in that wind, the Redskins' guy didn't catch any.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, the Giants won their first Super Bowl trophy,
39-20, over the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``At the half, we were behind, 10-9,'' he said, ``but in the
third quarter we had 200 yards and they had 2. Simms had that great
game with 22 out of 25, and our fake punt worked. I had vowed that
I would never go to a Super Bowl until my team was in it, and now
my team had won it.''
</P>
<P>
   But with a 6-9 record in the strike-shortened 1987 season, the
Giants missed the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that success is never final,'' he said. ``You can go
right back into the toilet.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1988 season finale, the Jets knocked the Giants out of
the playoffs, and in 1989, the Giants lost a wild-card playoff to
the Rams, 19-13, in overtime when Flipper Anderson caught a 30-yard
touchdown pass from Jim Everett and kept running into the Giants
Stadium tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only time I can say that an official's call cost me
the game _ pass interference on Sheldon White,'' Parcells said.
``The next play, the Rams scored. I learned how one little mistake
can kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the Giants roared to a 10-0 start but Simms suffered a
broken ankle as the record dipped to 11-3. Jeff Hostetler started
the last two victories and guided a 31-3 rout of the Bears in the
divisional playoff, but no team had ever won the Super Bowl with a
backup quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good team, but nobody knew it,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   Good enough to upset the 49ers, 15-13, for the NFC title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the greatest game I ever coached,'' he said. ``The
49ers were a great team with great players going for a Super Bowl
three-peat. It was the toughest, most physical game any of my teams
have ever been in. When Matt Bahr's fifth field goal went through
to win it, that might be the greatest feeling I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the usual two-week wait, the Giants went straight to
Tampa that Sunday night for Super Bowl XXXV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we went to San Francisco,'' he said, ``I told the
players to bring enough clothes for 10 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells and his staff also had already prepared a Super Bowl
game plan for the Buffalo Bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bills were a high-scoring team; we wanted to shorten the
game with a ball-control offense and we did,'' he said. ``We only
made one mistake on defense, a wrong call. It would've been a shame
if we lost, but when Scott Norwood lined up for that 47-yard field
goal to beat us, Matt Bahr told me, `He'll miss it. He hasn't made
a 47-yarder on grass all year. He'll over-kick it.' He did.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after that 20-19 victory, Parcells resigned as the
Giants' coach. In 1994, his second season in New England, the
Patriots were a wild card, but lost in Cleveland, 20-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our receivers dropped a touchdown pass right in his
chest,'' he said. ``The players didn't realize the level of
intensity in the playoffs. They knew they weren't quite ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Patriots were ready. In a foggy divisional playoff,
they trounced the Steelers, 28-3, then defeated the Jaguars, 20-6.
As the AFC champions, the Patriots and Parcells suddenly were in
Super Bowl XXXI against the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance when we closed to within 27-21,'' he said.
``We were hitting our passes.''
</P>
<P>
   On the ensuing kickoff, Desmond Howard streaked 99 yards for the
clinching touchdown in the Packers' 35-21 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed two tackles right away on that kickoff,'' Parcells
remembered. ``Two tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   It still haunts him. It always will. It's why the Jets' coach
will be reminding his players this week how ``one bad play sends
you home.'' He knows. He has been a loser in the playoffs five
times. But he also knows that on Jan. 31 in the Super Bowl in
Miami, he could be a winner in the playoffs for the 13th time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
