<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-DEFECTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 KHMER ROUGE DEFECTORS END TOUR AND RETURN TO JUNGLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ Two Khmer Rouge leaders ended their
six-day grand tour of the country Sunday and returned to a remote
jungle town that has become a well-guarded haven for defectors from
the Communist movement, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders, Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, came in from the cold
on Dec. 25, then were escorted around a nation that is still
painfully rebuilding from the ruin the Khmer Rouge inflicted
between 1975 and 1979, when more than a million people died.
</P>
<P>
   The tour has been offered to previous defectors, in part to try
to disabuse them of the continuing belief among many Khmer Rouge
that the country is still under the thumb of its neighbor, Vietnam,
and that Cambodians are ready to rise up in the Khmer Rouge's
support.
</P>
<P>
   After being welcomed here by Prime Minister Hun Sen, who was
himself once a member of the Khmer Rouge, they visited the beach
resort of Sihanoukville, then spent a night at the ancient temples
of Angkor.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they returned Sunday to Pailin, a remote town on
the border with Thailand, which has given sanctuary to the Khmer
Rouge in the past. Some 2,000 Khmer Rouge soldiers are also
stationed there, nominally part of the government army following
their defections over the last two years but still answering to
their Khmer Rouge commanders.
</P>
<P>
   In recent statements, Hun Sen has left his options open over
whether to accede to international demands that top Khmer Rouge
figures be put on trial for crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Several, but not all, of these figures _ including the former
Khmer Rouge foreign minister, Ieng Sary _ have gathered in Pailin,
a drab and eerie town populated by men with hard faces and cold
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   If any of the leaders are to be produced for trial, some new
agreement with the Khmer Rouge who control Pailin will be needed,
along with the cooperation of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   The Thais have strenuously denied helping the Khmer Rouge in the
last 20 years, both during and after a civil war in which the
Communist guerrillas fought Hun Sen's troops from sanctuaries along
the border.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to tart criticism of this relationship by Hun Sen,
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai of Thailand said Sunday that Cambodia
was trying to ``pass the buck'' to Thailand and to divert attention
from its own difficulties regarding the handling of Khmer Rouge
defectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
