A6147 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPENDING-PLAN-LADN     01-03 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPENDING-PLAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDING PLAN CAN PREPARE YOU FOR RAINY AND SUNNY DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- You overspent again this Christmas. January is
here and the big bills are coming. You dread it, but feel hopeless
about budgeting for next time.
</P>
<P>
   You're not the only one who dislikes budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Hunt, editor of the Cheapskate Monthly newsletter in
Paramount, Calif., hates the word ``budget.'' Instead, she prefers
the term ``spending plan.'' It may be splitting hairs, but attitude
and outlook carry great weight.
</P>
<P>
   Budgeting brings to mind restrictions, cutbacks in lifestyle and
other awful things. Spending plan carries the connotation of a
strategy that puts the consumer in the driver's seat. As such, it
sounds a lot more palatable.
</P>
<P>
   For people who don't save, who live life on the edge, who
naively hope that it will work out somehow, Hunt said they're
putting themselves at great risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's called being in bondage, living by fear, living on the
edge. That's putting yourself in horrible financial jeopardy,'' she
said. ``Freedom is knowing what you have and how much you are
spending. You've got all the bills paid and you've got something
extra. Freedom is not looking the other way and hoping things will
work out.''
</P>
<P>
   People who don't plan financially are not prepared for life's
curveballs and everyone gets them, Hunt added.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a step-by-step plan to set up a budget:
</P>
<P>
   1. Diagnose the situation. Get 30 or 31 index cards, one for
each day of the month. Track your daily spending. Three bucks a day
for a cafe au lait? Jot it down. Stick the index card in your
wallet. At the end of each month, you might be surprised that you
spent $60 on morning coffee alone. The goal of this exercise is to
look for money leaks and plug them.
</P>
<P>
   2. Categorize your expenses. Don't exceed 20 categories but make
them no fewer than 15 so your categories won't be too general.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you may list expenses under home mortgage, home
maintenance, auto payments, auto maintenance, entertainment,
groceries, consumer debt, utilities, medical bills, gifts, personal
or household expenses, insurance, taxes, child care or child
support, charity and miscellaneous.
</P>
<P>
   3. Keep track of where the money goes. You probably don't
realize how much you're spending at the vending machine at work.
The goal is to trim costs to give you some financial breathing
room. These savings can be used to pay off a credit card bill or
for investing.
</P>
<P>
   4. Once you've identified what you can save, set up an automatic
deposit plan at work where a certain amount, say $50, is taken out
of your salary and put directly into a savings account or mutual
fund. For people without the willpower to save themselves --
there's always something you feel you need to buy -- this is a
no-brainer. What you don't see, you don't miss. It works.
</P>
<P>
   5. Set up a freedom account. This is fun money for vacations and
such. You'll enjoy your vacation or leisure activity more if you
know you're paying for it upfront, not piling the cost on your
credit cards. You also may want to set up a savings account to pay
for next year's Christmas presents.
</P>
<P>
   These easy steps can make a dramatic impact on your life.
Imagine the stress you'll avoid by actually having money tucked
away for expenses.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 1758EST &QL; 
