<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6148 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ST.CROIX-CASINO-800&AMP;A     01-03 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ST.CROIX-CASINO-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. CROIX BETS IT FUTURE ON CASINOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Miss.) 
(mk) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. CROIX, U.S. Virgin Islands _ When Lisa Newkirk-Svarczkopf
heard that casinos would soon open in this, the biggest of the
three U.S. Virgin Islands, she moved her clothing store to a
location three times the size of the old one in anticipation of a
tourism boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was getting a jump start on things by moving to a
bigger spot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the move was four years off and Ms.
Newkirk-Svarczkopf had to move back to a smaller store. But her
excitement and that of other St. Croix residents has not abated as
the first casino is scheduled to open here this fall. In a region
battered by four major hurricanes in the last decade, casinos are
seen as a catalyst to help bring back the economic prosperity that
all but vanished in September 1989, when Hurricane Hugo left 90
percent of the buildings damaged and more than 20,000 people
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the beginning of our turnaround,'' Ms. Newkirk-Svarczkopf
said. ``We know it's just a matter of time because we know what a
beautiful island this is.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Caribbean is full of islands with casinos, the
American Virgin Islands, where tourism accounts for two-thirds of
the economy, had resisted starting their own for years. In a 1992
referendum both St. Croix and St. Thomas voted the idea down,
concerned with the unsavory aspects of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   But the economic need for more tourism in St. Croix, a less
popular tourist destination than St. Thomas and St. John,
increasingly made residents here see casinos as a necessary evil.
In another referendum four years ago, St. Thomas still said no but
St. Croix's 60,000 residents relented.
</P>
<P>
   Moving cautiously, however, the U.S. Virgin Islands' Legislature
has limited the number of casinos to a maximum of six and allowed
them only as a means to increase the number of hotel rooms in St.
Croix, which now stands at about 1,000, or half of what it was
before Hurricane Hugo, officials here said. In order to get a
license, a casino operator would have to build a hotel or renovate
an existing one to add new rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never talk about casinos. We talk about casino-hotels,''
said Eileen Petersen, a former territorial court judge who chairs
the islands' new Casino Control Commission. ``Our goal is to
surpass what it was before the hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotels are vital to what government officials describe as an
economic chain reaction _ more hotels mean more tax dollars to
promote tourism, which would in turn lead to more visitors, more
airline flights from the mainland, where most visitors to the
islands come from, and, it is hoped, lower fares.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines usually carry that most desirable breed of tourist _
the overnight guest. Government figures show that, in 1997, 1.6
million cruise ship passengers spent $288.3 million in the American
Virgin Islands. Land-based travelers were far fewer that year,
410,000, but spent almost as much, $281.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruise ships are really not doing it,'' said Noel Loftus,
president of the St. Croix Chamber of Commerce. ``Cruise ships are
getting larger and have their own stores. Passengers are spending
less and less money.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Croix, however, lags behind its two sister islands in all
tourism. In the first three quarters of 1998, government figures
show, St. Thomas and St. John together welcomed more than 315,000
airline visitors and 1.2 million cruise passengers. St. Croix
received 111,000 airline passengers and fewer than 126,000 cruise
ship visitors during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   St. Thomas has made a name for its duty-free shopping district,
and St. Jones, most of which is an unspoiled national park, for its
natural beauty. But St. Croix, which combines elements of the two
and has found it more difficult to create a separate identity, is
bigger, friendlier and offers less predictable attractions, like
West Indian and Danish colonial historic sites, its residents note.
</P>
<P>
   Cruzans, as the locals are known, blame favoritism in government
advertising for much of their woes, a charge government officials
explain by saying that promotional dollars come from hotel taxes
and St. Thomas has four times as many.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're rather paranoid about feeling they always get the
short end of the stick,'' the American Virgin Islands tourism
commissioner, Wylie Whisonant, said of St. Croix. ``It's like a
sibling rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, even if more tourists were directed St. Croix's
way, ``Where are people going to stay?''
</P>
<P>
   Enter casinos.
</P>
<P>
   St. Croix's first casino is scheduled to open in September in
the island's scenic eastern end, on the grounds of a hotel resort
that was destroyed by Hurricane Hugo and is now being rebuilt as
the 200-room Divi Carina Bay Resort and Casino. The hotel, owned by
Grapetree Shores, Inc., is expected to open a few months ahead of
the casino, in April or May.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The casino license went to Grapetree Shores' partner, Treasure
Bay Corp., a Mississippi casino operator that is investing $6.8
million here, moderate by industry standards, on a
10,000-square-foot casino with 275 slot machines, 12 table games
and an estimated 132 employees. By law, the government will take 8
percent of the casinos' annual gross revenue for the first two
years, and up to 12 percent by the fifth year. The casino has also
agreed to give at least 80 percent of the casino jobs to Virgin
Islands residents.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Burkholder, president and CEO of Treasure Bay, said he
expects his property to capture about half of what he estimates is
now a $20 million casino market in St. Croix. He said the market
has great potential for growth if more tourists come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there's a lot of competition in the Caribbean,'' he
said in a telephone interview from Biloxi, Miss. ``A big percentage
of tourists are going to come from the United States and they'll
fly over the Bahamas and Puerto Rico and other places with casinos
to get to St. Croix.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``We feel a well-executed, quality property will
be able to compete. We will compete well against the older, more
dated properties.''
</P>
<P>
   In the shopping district of Christiansted, store owners said
they expected nothing but economic good from the first casino
venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will help bring in the Marriotts and the Hiltons,'' said
Rob Low, owner of The Gold Shop jewelry store. ``This is going to
give the bigger-name hotels a reason to come. Then the airline
would start adding flights.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Casino Control Commission, the hope was to earn respect
as a world-class gaming jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to feel that when they gamble in the Virgin
Islands the games are fair and honest,'' Petersen said. ``The best
that can happen is that we have six fabulous, widely recognized
casino-hotels and that the community is happy that it invested
time, money and energy in this venture.''
</P>
<P>
   With so much at stake, Treasure Bay officials cannot help but
feel the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned sometimes that maybe the expectations are too
high and people would be disappointed,'' Burkholder said. ``I know
a lot of people are watching _ the people in St. Croix, the
investment community.''
</P>
<P>
   But while casinos are not a panacea for the island's troubles,
he said, they could make a difference if their success helps
stimulate other investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the catalyst but we won't by ourselves double the
tourism,'' he said. ``But in two or three years that can happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
