<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ A key government witness in the
Microsoft antitrust trial, which resumes Monday after a two-week
break, calls on the courts to make the Windows operating system a
public utility, lifting the ``choke point'' that the software giant
holds over the Internet. (Glass, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GA-MILLER _ ATLANTA _ As Zell Miller leaves the political
spotlight after more than 30 years, including eights as governor,
his popularity among Georgians is the highest for a governor since
polling began. Immediately upon taking office, he embarked on his
get-tough on criminals promises and built his plan for a Georgia
lottery, which was approved toward the end of his first term. ``I
plowed deep the first term, and smoothed it out the second term,''
Miller said in an October interview. The national political
audience met him as one of the keynote speakers at the 1992
Democratic National Convention, when he delivered a fiery address
laiden with echoes of the Democratic Party's roots in Roosevelt and
social responsibility. But three weeks later, The New York Times
called him an ``unidentified man'' in a front-page photo of Clinton
walking with governors at a National Governors Association meeting.
It was not until the Georgia Lottery became a model for school
funding that Zell Miller was in the national headlines to stay. 85
inches. (Pruitt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GA-LEGIS-AGENDA _ ATLANTA _ When the General Assembly comes to
work at the Capitol next week, the main items on its agenda will
sound familiar to Georgia voters. They'll be the same priorities
Gov.-elect Roy E. Barnes emphasized in his campaign last year: a
reduction in property taxes, school discipline and health care
reform. (Walston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FLA-MARRIAGE-LAW _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Florida couples must
consider the consequences of divorce before they can get married
under a new law that court clerks predict will create more turmoil
than romance. (Moore, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BABY-CUSTODY _ ATLANTA _ When 9-month-old Bryanna Hollis died
last week, the victim of alleged abuse, her grandparents and
natural father had only seen her twice - the day she was born and
the day she was hospitalized before her death. Now her
grandparents, Stan and Deborah Layton of Smyrna, are angry at a
legal system that they say kept them from gaining custody of the
baby. The Laytons sued along with Bryanna's father, Donnie, 21, to
gain custody of the child last summer, but it was not to be. With
update on investigation into Bryanna's death and some details about
injuries to the child. (Anderson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
18-20. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIC-KIOSKS _ ATLANTA _ A lawsuit goes to trial today in
Fulton County Superior Court, filed by people who bought kiosks to
sell souvenirs during the Olympics, against Creative Travel, the
same group that brought in teen-agers from all over the country to
work in the kiosks and then couldn't put them up anywhere. This
suit is NOT about the teen-agers, though; it's about the people who
bought kiosks trying to get back money they invested in what they
called a scam. They want $6 million. Defendants reaction in court
papers is essentially, it wasn't our fault or, you can't prove it.
(Croft, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
