</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-EURO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFILING TO FIX CODING 
BRITAIN KEEPS ITS DISTANCE AS THE EURO IS BORN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also U.S.-EURO and the Outlook article 1999-EURO) 
(mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Holding back on the brink as it has at every turn
towards European integration, Britain observed the birth of the
euro single currency as a nation apart this weekend, its leaders
mute even as the banks that power the City of London financial
district prepared to trade the new money by the trillions.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Prime Minister Tony Blair, on vacation in the
Seychelles, nor Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown had
anything to say about the inception of the currency, from which
Britain has initially excluded itself, and which has been cast as
an event of momentous proportions for the 290 million people in the
11 countries participating in it.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a single, historical clue to Britain's reticence it
lay, perhaps, in lines penned almost 70 years ago by Winston
Churchill, which have defined Britain's ambiguity toward the great
land mass across the Channel ever since: ``We are with Europe, not
of it. We are linked but not comprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain is by far the most significant _ politically and
economically _ of the four countries outside the euro zone; the
others are Denmark, Sweden and Greece. It is arguably the only
major European power in which public debate about the euro has
flourished _ to such an extent that divisions over Europe provided
one of the many reasons for the defeat of the Conservatives in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   But it is no coincidence that the defining maxim should have
come from Churchill, Britain's wartime leader who rallied a
lonesome nation against the Nazi swamping of Europe in 1940. Then,
as now, in the euroskeptic view, Britain stands alone, its
sovereignty on the line. ``The classic argument'' among the
euro-skeptic newspapers that have driven the discussion, said Peter
Riddell, a newspaper columnist, ``is that it's Britain vs.
Germany'' _ Germany being depicted not just as the bulldozing power
behind the euro's creation, but also as the driving force of a
United States of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   And, as the euro became reality in global electronic trading
Sunday night, those opposed to the new currency raised alarms anew
that the currency is no more than a Trojan horse for a European
super-state in which the essence of British-ness would be lost.
``How can the government keep pretending that it is just about
currencies when the Continentals are clearly out to create a new
country and a new government?'' said John Redwood, a leading
euro-skeptic from the opposition Conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, no one in financial circles here seemed in the
least bit uncertain that, with such a vast euro market lapping at
its shores, Britain would really escape the tidal pull of the
currency. Even though Britain is outside the euro zone, London
provides Europe's biggest stock, bond and foreign exchange markets.
</P>
<P>
   Swapping pinstripes for blue-jeans, some 30,000 bankers and
back-room staff toiled over the weekend to prepare the trading
floors for an anticipated euro deluge when markets here open
Monday, turning 11 separate European currencies _ from the German
mark to the Spanish peseta _ into expressions of the euro and
converting a mass of financial data in what some depicted as a
less-than-thrilling exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as excitement is concerned, it was a bit of a dud,''
said Rich Silverman, a spokesman for Merrill Lynch. ``You had the
sense that you were part of history. But not every part of history
is exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The euro's penetration, however, is likely to run deep.
</P>
<P>
   Already, said Grant Phillips, head of the euro program at
Barclays Corporate Banking, some 30,000 British corporations, large
and small, have opened bank accounts in euros with his bank _
Britain's biggest _ alone. Indeed, some leading companies with
Continental business ties have let it be known that they will favor
suppliers who deal in euros, abandoning Britain's cherished pound
sterling. There is even talk of some companies offering euro
salaries to enable British employees to access cheaper mortgages at
the lower euro interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   With this ``creeping euro,'' Phillips said, ``we are fast
getting to the stage of the euro strolling _ if not galloping _
through the British economy.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments strengthen those who argue that, by abstaining
from the first wave of the euro, Britain is repeating its
historical mistake of denying the inevitable in Europe. ``The
tragedy,'' said the Observer Sunday newspaper in an editorial, ``is
that once again the British political and media establishment have
made sure Britain is not in a vital European project at the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   By this argument, Britain is missing out not just on
decision-making about the currency of its main trading area, but
also on a great opportunity for cheaper money in the
low-interest-rate euro zone and cheaper trade in a vast region free
of foreign exchange risks and costs. The counter-argument comes
back to the question of Britain's ability to steer its own economy,
manage its own interest rates and taxes, and preserve its own blend
of low unemployment, low taxes and relatively cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
   The euro, said Lord David Owen, a former Labor foreign
secretary, would mean far greater European ``involvement in tax,
even welfare, hours of work, working conditions.'' And, he said as
he launched a new anti-euro movement Sunday, ``essential parts'' of
British budget-making would ``now be decided in euroland'' _ the
term widely used for the 11 participating countries, which share
fixed common interest rates set by the European Central Bank in
Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   The European Central Bank, like most other European financial
institutions, said Sunday that its preparations for the euro had
been completed smoothly. The currency formally came into being on
Jan. 1. Since then, European markets have been closed and many
bankers say the real test of the conversion to the new currency
will come only when major European markets open Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Against all the hoopla surrounding the euro across the Channel,
it seemed typical of Britain's introversion that the main political
issues this weekend related not to the new currency but to
lingering brushfires over the resignation last month of Trade
Secretary Peter Mandelson _ and to a tussle over Blair's decision
to let his children defy government education policy and miss
classes at school this week while they complete their Indian Ocean
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, though, Blair's government is widely seen as being
friendlier to the euro than its Conservative predecessor, to the
extent, said Riddell, the newspaper columnist, that ``it's when
rather than if with Blair.'' The government's stated policy is to
postpone a decision until a referendum after the next general
election. Under Britain's electoral law, a national election need
not be held until the year 2002 _ a date by which the rest of
Europe will have completed the transition to using euro notes and
coins and much of British business will already be conducted in
euros.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the delay, Blair and his colleagues may be hoping for a
triumph of pragmatism over pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most obvious factor is whether the euro is a success,''
said Gerald Segal, director of the International Institute for
Strategic Studies here. ``If he is going to take Britain in, he
needs to be seen as going into a positive exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   But will the euro be a success? Andy Meadows is the curator of
an exhibit at the British Museum charting currency unions from
ancient Greek tridrachms through the silver denarii of the Roman
Empire and on to the euro. History, it turns out, reinforces the
mantra of the market-and-mirrors 1990s. ``If a coin is persuasive,
then people will accept it, and if people accept it, it becomes a
model,'' Meadows said in an interview. And if the marketplace needs
a common currency, ``then the market takes over'' _ euro-watchers,
please note.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 1839EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
