<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SYRACUSE-MCNABB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURED MCNABB MISSES THE MARK IN FINAL COLLEGE GAME
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Donovan McNabb was among the last to leave the Syracuse
locker room early Sunday morning. He emerged wearing an olive suit
and white shoes and feeling some heartache beneath his ever-present
smile.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb, the option quarterback who accounted for more than
10,000 yards running and passing in his career, had spent time
trading hugs and handshakes with the 11 other Syracuse seniors
whose last game became a nightmarish 31-10 loss to Florida in the
Orange Bowl on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're upset about the loss,'' McNabb said. ``But mainly we're
upset about leaving. Hopefully we'll stay in touch, but it's not
going to be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb had said he wanted the Orange Bowl to be his best game,
so it could serve as a springboard for Syracuse (8-4) next season.
It was anything but. He threw for 192 yards, but completed only 14
of his 30 passes, lost two of the team's three fumbles and threw an
interception. He rushed for 72 yards on 20 carries. Florida shut
down an Orangemen offense that was averaging 42.5 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was off his mark,'' Syracuse offensive coordinator Kevin
Rogers said. ``Passes he usually completes in his sleep were
one-hoppers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers noted, however, that Florida put more pressure on McNabb
than any other team this season, or probably any season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're going to find out three or four years from now
that they probably have 10 or 11 guys on that defense playing in
the National Football League,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, which finished 10-2 and became the first Southeastern
Conference school to win at least 10 games for six consecutive
seasons, sprinted to an early 14-0 lead that grew to 28-3 by
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very emotional in different parts of the game,'' McNabb
said. ``Especially in the third quarter when we were down 28-3. We
weren't playing like Syracuse. With all the firepower we have, we
should have been doing more, and that was really upsetting. It's
unfortunate it had to happen in a bowl game, but we have to move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a fizzle instead of a pop, the McNabb era at Syracuse
is over. He was named the Big East Conference offensive player of
the year the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sad right now for a lot of reasons,'' the senior defensive
end Marc Pilon said. ``One thing I think about is you're never
going to play with a Donovan McNabb again.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Pasqualoni, the Syracuse coach, said: ``We wish Donovan
McNabb the absolute best. He's a great kid and great competitor. I
think Donovan will go down as one of the outstanding players we've
had.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb said it was difficult to put his Syracuse years in
perspective in the hot glare of defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mainly what I'll remember is the close friendships I've made,
friendships I'll have for the rest of my life,'' he said. ``It's
going to be hard sitting back on Saturdays and watching a team I
was a part of for five years.''
</P>
<P>
   To the Syracuse fans, who embraced him with such fervor, he
said: ``I just want to thank them for welcoming me with open arms.
Since I was a freshman, the crowd's been there giving me love and
warmth _ their hearts were there and I just tried to provide
nothing but the best for them.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb's likely heir at quarterback is Madei Williams, a
redshirt freshman from Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a strong arm and he's very intelligent and he has a lot
of fun,'' McNabb said. ``That's one of the main things I stressed
with him, just having fun. If you're relaxed and have your mind on
what you should be focusing on, good things will go your way. Madei
is a guy who works hard and competes, and I think he'll do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Then McNabb smiled again, turned and walked into the night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
