<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6178 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILHARMONIC-REVIEW-N     01-03 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILHARMONIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: OHIO, CALIFORNIA ) PHILHARMONIC VIOLINIST STEPS FORTH AS A
SOLOIST 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By ANTHONY TOMMASINI  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In September, Sheryl Staples, a violinist originally
from Los Angeles, was appointed principal associate concertmaster
of the New York Philharmonic. Previously she had been associate
concertmaster with the Cleveland Orchestra, a post she earned when
she was just 26.
</P>
<P>
   Like many instrumentalists in major orchestras today, Ms.
Staples has also pursued a solo career, having played concertos
with some 40 orchestras nationwide. On Saturday afternoon she added
the Philharmonic to the list, when she was the soloist in
Tchaikovsky's Violin Concerto, with Kurt Masur conducting, at Avery
Fisher Hall. Her impressive performance said much about the current
high level of competition for jobs with major orchestras and the
depth of talent within their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Staples is a technically assured violinist, and little in
this dauntingly virtuoso work posed problems for her. She is a
perceptive musician, who plays with great rhythmic integrity and a
lucid sense of phrase structure. Her remarkable instrument is a
rich-toned Guarnerius from about 1720, which is on loan to her from
the Mandell Collection in Southern California, and she draws a
wonderful array of vibrant and luminous colors from it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps for some listeners, Ms. Staples' playing lacks that
charismatic, slightly neurotic quality that turns a fine performer
into a star. But I found her interpretive honesty and unmannered
elegance refreshing and, in its understated way, exciting. Indeed,
the audience broke into enthusiastic applause even after the first
movement.
</P>
<P>
   A little glitch in the finale, when Ms. Staples dropped some
notes in a fearsome passage, probably bothered her more than us.
This was a most rewarding performance. The Philharmonic clearly has
a strong new musician in a crucial position.
</P>
<P>
   The program also included a performance of Tchaikovsky's
Symphony No. 6, the ``Pathetique,'' which was dedicated by Masur to
the memory of Judith Arron, the artistic and executive director of
Carnegie Hall, who died last month at 56. The orchestra played
splendidly, though Masur drove the third movement, a blazing march,
unrelentingly.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, it took some time for the final movement, the
grieving Adagio Lamentoso, to settle down. But over all the
performance was bold and affecting, a fitting memorial to an
important cultural figure in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 1846EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
