A6179 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT &LR;      01-03 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: TOASTING RODGERS AND HART, THE TOASTS OF BROADWAY;
GRAND   VENETIAN STYLE IN WASHINGTON; DEVELOPING TALENTS OF 5
CHOREOGRAPHERS; CELEBRATING POULENC'S BIRTHDAY 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Washington)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were just a couple of confident young men from Columbia
University. Their names were Richard Rodgers and Lorenz Hart.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Garrick Gaieties'' in 1925 to ``Pal Joey'' in 1940,
the composer Rodgers (1902-1979) and the lyricist Hart (1895-1943)
were the toast of Broadway. Beginning at 8 p.m. Wednesday, PBS'
``Great Performances'' will offer a reprise of their partnership
called ``The Rodgers and Hart Story: Thou Swell, Thou Witty.''
Produced and directed by David Thompson, the man behind the series'
profiles of Busby Berkeley and Arthur Freed, the one-hour show
features performers like Christine Ebersole, Rebecca Luker and Jane
Krakowski and songs like ``Falling in Love With Love,'' ``The Lady
Is a Tramp'' and ``My Funny Valentine.''
</P>
<P>
   Evening's Work
</P>
<P>
   Music in the grand Venetian tradition arrives at the National
Cathedral in Washington at 8 p.m. Friday and 7:30 p.m. Saturday,
when the Folger Consort offers Monteverdi's ``1610 Vespers,'' a
choral work regarded as a monument of the Baroque. Said to be the
first complete performances in Washington in more than a decade,
these will highlight vocal and instrumental soloists. Joining
Robert Eisenstein and Christopher Kendall, the artistic directors
and founding members of the Consort, will be 10 soloists, the
Boston Shawm and Sackbut Ensemble and a period-instrument orchestra
led by Ryan Brown. Information: (202) 544-7077.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping Forward
</P>
<P>
   On dancing feet set in motion by the artistry of five
choreographers, a new year of Altogether Different begins at 8 p.m.
Monday at the Joyce Theater. This segment of the series, created in
1986 to present talents in the process of developing and expanding
their companies and audiences, runs through Jan. 17. Each of the
five choreographers will give three performances. In order of
appearance, they are Sean Curran, Kevin Wynn, Lisa Giobbi, Sally
Silvers and H.T. Chen. Information: (212) 242-0800.
</P>
<P>
   Who's Counting?
</P>
<P>
   Chances to observe the 100th anniversary of the birth of Francis
Poulenc, hear his music and renew acquaintance with Babar the
Elephant in the company of the actor Tony Randall coincide at 7
p.m. Thursday, courtesy of the New York Library for the Performing
Arts. In celebration of the centenary of the French composer
(1899-1963), the library's ``Principally Poulenc'' series will
present a program at the Great Hall at Cooper Union, where the
pianist Grant Johannesen, a leading Poulenc interpreter, and
Randall will perform Poulenc's ``Histoire de Babar,'' an evocative
setting of Jean de Brunhoff's beloved tale. Besides this work for
narrator and pianist, the program includes Poulenc's ``Animaux
Modeles,'' based on La Fontaine's fables, and ``Suite Francaise.''
Information: (212) 642-0142.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 1849EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
