<HEADER>
A6193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-CHRISTIAN-CULT     01-03 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CHRISTIAN-CULT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI POLICE ARREST CHRISTIAN CULTISTS PLANNING MILLENNIUM
SUICIDE
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Colo., Ohio, Mass.) 
(DW) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli police officials Sunday arrested eight
American members of a Denver-based apocalyptic cult who the
officials said were planning to mark the millennium by committing
suicide or provoking their own killings in the streets of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the eight belonged to the Concerned Christians
cult, whose members disappeared early last fall, emptying out their
houses and leaving Colorado without a trace. The cult members
planned to destroy themselves shortly before the millennium in
order to hasten the Second Coming of Christ, the police officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They planned to carry out violent and extreme acts in the
streets of Jerusalem at the end of 1999 to start the process of
bringing Jesus back to life,'' said Brig. Gen. Elihu Ben-Onn, an
Israeli police general.
</P>
<P>
   The cultists specifically wanted to create a catastrophic event
by provoking a deadly shootout with the police in the Old City,
where by Christian tradition the tomb of Jesus lies, in the Church
of the Holy Sepulcher, a police official said.
</P>
<P>
   Their leader, Monte Kim Miller, a former marketing executive for
Procter &AMP; Gamble who claimed he could speak in the voice of God,
had predicted that he would die in Jerusalem in 1999. But he was
not among those arrested and the authorities here do not believe he
is in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The eight were to be brought before a judge within 24 hours, but
the Israelis plan to deport them rather than to prosecute them.
They also intend to track down what they say may be dozens more
cult members who have eluded the police.
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. Hezi Leder, the police attache at the Israeli Embassy
in Washington, said of the arrests, ``There probably will be
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli police officials fear that this may be the beginning of
a wave of apocalypse-seekers who could descend on Jerusalem in
advance of the millennium. Already, dozens of American Christians
have settled here in anticipation of the year 2000. Some of them
have rented rooms at the base of the Mount of Olives, to secure
what they hope will be a bird's-eye view of Christ's reappearance
at the spot where the Gospels recorded an apocalyptic vision of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli authorities are courting Christian pilgrims to
celebrate the millennium here, but some experts on the millennium
have warned them that they could be playing with fire. Many insist,
though, that the potentially dangerous groups will be a minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't say there are not fundamentalists or extremists, but
it's all out of proportion to think only of them,'' said Uri Mor,
the deputy director of the Religious Affairs Ministry, who oversees
relations with the Christian communities here. ``Of course, you
have to take care, but in proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the police made it clear that with these arrests they
were drawing a line in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police will continue to work in every legal way possible
to allow for freedom of religion and ritual in Jerusalem and in
Israel for all religions in the years of the millennium,'' said
Gen. Yair Yitzrak, chief commander of the Jerusalem Police
District. ``However, we will act firmly against the attempts of
extreme groups to block access to other Christians in the year
1999.''
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, relatives of the cult members said they had
expected the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were going to deport them a couple of weeks
ago,'' said John Weaver of Lakewood, Colo., whose daughter used to
be a member of the group. ``Israel is trying to set an example that
they don't want these millennial groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday afternoon, the police, together with Shin Bet
security agents, took the eight adults, together with six children,
into custody after a raid on two suburban-style homes in the
western outskirts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The members, whom they did not identify, had been living quietly
in two relatively affluent neighborhoods, surviving on their
savings and on donations from abroad, said police officials, who
are working in conjunction with the American authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see them here sitting around all day,'' said Nir
Hanuni, a neighbor in the suburb of Mevasseret Zion. ``You could
call it idleness. The children, of course, were not registered at
any school around here. ``
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, some relatives of the sect members have been
frustrated by the refusal of the Israeli Embassy in Washington to
provide a list of members of the group who have been located in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't anybody tell me where he is?'' Jennifer Cooper said
in Denver, speaking of her father, John Cooper. Cooper disappeared
with the group last summer. Citing electronic messages sent to her,
she added, ``We have been led to believe that he is not in
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   An American expert on millennial movements predicted that after
Easter the number of Americans millennialists converging on
Jerusalem would swell.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the Easter season, you can expect hundreds there
unless the Israelis are pushing hard to get these people away,''
said Richard Landes, director of the Center for Millennial Studies
at Boston University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
