<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JAGUARS-PATRIOTS-     01-03 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-PATRIOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRUSTRATED BRUNELL LIFTS JAGUARS PAST PATRIOTS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ The Jaguars' quarterback, Mark Brunell,
despite being ahead of the New England Patriots by 12 points late
in the first half Sunday, seemed extremely agitated. He screamed at
the head coach. Once, after he was sacked, Brunell slammed the
football to the turf. The Pro Bowl quarterback was frustrated by
his play, since he wasn't sharp after a month-long layoff with a
severe ankle sprain. But Brunell was angry about something else _
he knew the Jaguars should have been winning by 30 points.
</P>
<P>
   New England played as badly as it could early, but Jacksonville
managed only a 12-0 halftime lead. Suddenly, in the third quarter,
the Patriots woke up. Instead of a clumsy offense that at one point
went 0 for 7 on third-down conversions, the Patriots suddenly
became sharp during a 17-play, 85-yard touchdown drive. Instead of
quarterback Scott Zolak playing as if he were allergic to the end
zone, he suddenly got into a zone.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than letting the game _ and the season _ slip away,
the Jaguars finally took the game by the throat. A touchdown catch
by Pro Bowl wide receiver Jimmy Smith and a late turnover by New
England sealed Jacksonville's 25-10 playoff victory before a crowd
of 71,139 at Alltel Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars advanced to the second round of the American
Football Conference playoffs and will play the Jets next Sunday in
Giants Stadium. The story line all week will be about Jacksonville
Coach Tom Coughlin going against his close friend and mentor, Bill
Parcells, a subject that did not make Coughlin exactly misty-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I enjoy this win before we start talking about that . .
.?'' Coughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Coughlin did talk about how proud he was of his team, since
the Jaguars this season won their first AFC Central Division title,
as well as 11 regular-season games to become the National Football
League's first expansion team to qualify for the playoffs three
times in its first four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Jaguars are going to get back to another conference
title game by beating the favored Jets, then Brunell must simply
play better. Clearly, Brunell's high ankle sprain is limiting what
he and the Jacksonville offense can do best. Bootlegs and
sprintouts, a Brunell staple, are simply not options now.
</P>
<P>
   He completed only 14 of 34 passes for 161 yards, and the offense
stalled in the second and third quarters as the pain increased,
because as Brunell goes, so goes the Jacksonville offense.
Brunell's ankle became so bothersome, that he and Coughlin had a
discussion about whether or not Brunell should take himself out of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I twisted the ankle before halftime and came out for the third
quarter and wasn't feeling all that great,'' Brunell said. ``We
didn't get into an argument. I just encouraged him, I should say,
to keep me in there. It wasn't a confrontation. He felt I could
continue and I felt the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for Jacksonville, Brunell played on. After a Robert
Edwards one-yard score helped cut the Jaguars' lead to 12-7 and a
Adam Vinatieri 27-yard field goal made it 12-10, there was a
momentum swing. Clearly, if the Jaguars did not score soon, they
were in danger of losing.
</P>
<P>
   That was when the Jaguars went to Smith, who was single-covered
by one of the top three cornerbacks in football, Ty Law. Smith ran
a deep go-route, and got a full step on Law, which has probably
happened against Law five times all year. Brunell threw a perfect
pass for the 37-yard score on way to a 19-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any excuses,'' said Law, who had nine
interceptions this season. ``I got beat on that play.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that pass, Zolak, playing for Drew Bledsoe, who has a
broken finger and who was on the sideline in civilian clothes, was
hit hard by defensive end Joel Smeenge. The ball dribbled loose and
was recovered by defensive lineman Tony Brackens. The turnover led
to a Mike Hollis 34-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The momentum changed with the turnovers,'' said Coughlin.
``They had three turnovers and we did not turn the ball over, which
has been key for us all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots Coach Pete Carroll also alluded to the turnovers. ``We
made a couple of careless mistakes early and the defense kept us in
the game,'' Carroll said. ``The offense came alive and 12 points
didn't seem too much. You just have to close it out when you make
those drives and we didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars were up by 12 points again, only this time there was
less than six minutes to play and they had learned their lesson.
They attacked the Patriots, not allowing them to catch their
breath. The last chance for New England to get back in the game
came on a fourth-and-15 at their 31-yard line, but Zolak was sacked
by Brackens.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Jaguars just handed the ball to running back Fred
Taylor on their next-to-last possession, and he ran the ball six
consecutive times, finishing with 162 yards on 33 rushes.
Jacksonville added a field goal _ this one from 21 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is a rookie-of-the-year candidate, though he will most
likely be beaten out by Minnesota wide receiver Randy Moss. The
Jets will likely make him the focal point of their defensive
attack. Taylor's 162 yards against a good Patriots defense were the
third-highest total by a rookie in a playoff game, behind the
Washington Redskins' Tim Smith in 1988 (204) and the Los Angeles
Chargers' Paul Crowe in 1961 (165).
</P>
<P>
   ``There were rumbles out of New England that they were more
physical than we were,'' Taylor said. ``So the offensive line
wanted to come out and play physical. They did that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
