<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6202 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-700&AMP;AD     01-03 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE SHORT AND THE LONG OF A SENATE TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Miss., S.D., Ark., Mo., Fla.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH-SENATE) 
(mk) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The immediate politics of impeachment, to most
senators and to President Clinton, argue against a fullblown trial
_ with lengthy arguments, witnesses for and against the president,
and a requirement that senators sit there silently day after day,
listening.
</P>
<P>
   Since nobody except perhaps Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the
majority whip, appears to believe that the Senate might really vote
to convict Clinton and remove him from office, the argument goes,
why not get it over with quickly?
</P>
<P>
   Some quick resolution, including a censure, seems to be the goal
that Sens. Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Tom Daschle, D-S.D., the Senate
leaders, are pursuing with many other senators. Still, Sunday's
television chat programs made it clear that they have not found the
path to that end. And with the Senate, finding a direct route to
anything is almost unnatural.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a case for a trial. It is heard most often from the
president's critics in Congress who insist that when the
Constitution says, ``The Senate shall have the sole power to try
all impeachments,'' it offers no discretion.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., said on the CBS News
program ``Face the Nation'' Sunday: ``I would be very skeptical of
bypassing what I think is our constitutional responsibility to have
a full airing of the evidence. I don't think that we should ever
stop thinking about the Constitution and the importance of setting
a precedent that is responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   For some in Congress who advocate a full trial, the hope that a
dozen or more Democrats will be persuaded to vote with Republicans
to remove the president springs eternal. For others in the House,
there is at least the hope of tarnishing the president's image
still more, and a sense that they did their part, and now the
Senate must do its duty.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another case for a trial, and it has support from
scholars who think that the case for impeachment made by the House
is frivolous.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that the Senate should weigh the risk that a quick
end to its proceedings would only serve to trivialize presidential
impeachments, and encourage the House in future exercises of
outrage that lack the gravity impeachment should demand.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Remini, university historian at the University of
Illinois at Chicago and biographer of Andrew Jackson, the only
president to be censured by the Senate, said Sunday he feared that
the consequence of a Senate ``short-circuit'' would be this lesson:
``You can impeach any time, and the Senate doesn't have to do
anything.'' But he said he was concerned that a trial would amount
to shutting down the government, or at least the Congress. But then
he mused, ``What would they do if they don't have a trial lasting
several months?''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Silbey, a Cornell historian, said he once thought the
Senate had to show respect for impeachment or it would encourage
irresponsible House actions in the future. But now, he said, ``most
of these guys are operating by short-term politics. If we dignify
this thing, then we're trapped. As constitutional as the procedure
is, the prospect of Monica Lewinsky being asked physical questions
_ where is the dignity?''
</P>
<P>
   Hans Trefousse, a retired historian at Brooklyn College and
biographer of both Andrew Johnson, the only president impeached
before Clinton, and his chief antagonist, Rep. Thaddeus Stevens,
said he thought that ``to short-circuit a trial is very
questionable'' in the long term. But he said ``it may be in the
national interest'' because of what testimony would actually
involve. ``This pornography that Starr raked up is not good for the
country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another argument for a full proceeding came from Ross Baker, a
Rutgers political scientist. ``For the Senate to breeze through it
manifests some contempt for the House,'' he said, and begs the
``basic constitutional question, the seriousness with which a
Senate, regardless of its partisan composition, has got to deal
with an impeachment when presented by the House.''
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that ``comity between the two houses is not a very
exciting issue, but it goes to the long-term relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Summary judgment,'' Baker said, ``is not what the framers had
in mind.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One reason to avoid a trial is speed. Members of both parties
would rather fight about legislation than wait a few months while
they deal with Clinton's affair with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is their anticipation of what testimony they
would put before the nation, unless they blacked out part of the
trial from television, as Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., suggested
might be done.
</P>
<P>
   On the television news programs Sunday, House Republicans who
want a trial sought to minimize that political fear.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark. (the senator's brother), appeared on
the ABC News program ``This Week'' and was asked, ``Would you want
to ask her the same kind of questions Judge Starr was criticized
for including in his report? How they conducted their assignations,
for instance?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, absolutely not,'' Hutchinson replied. ``I do not believe
it is necessary for an evaluation of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., another of the House impeachment
managers, said Ms. Lewinsky would have to be a witness, too, but
that the public was wrong to think ``that there would be a lot of
salacious questions asked.'' Appearing on ``Fox News Sunday,'' he
said, ``I don't anticipate the House managers are going to ask her
every one of those little questions that were so inflammatory.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not, but their articles of impeachment accuse Clinton of
lying under oath about ``the nature and details of his
relationship'' with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   And even if an impeachment trial is fundamentally more political
than judicial, if the House managers seek to use Ms. Lewinsky's
testimony from Starr's grand jury, it is hard to imagine Senate
Democrats or White House lawyers not demanding that she be brought
forward for cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   And while no one should discount the political nature of either
the process or the 100 senators/jurors, even when they talk about
being above politics, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, made a useful
observation when he said on the NBC News program ``Meet the
Press'': ``Seems to me we're too preoccupied with what is good
politics for senators and not enough preoccupied with what we
should do to fulfill the constitutional process. I think we can do
it quickly. I hope we don't have to have witnesses, but we've got
to hear from the House and from the president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
