<SLUG> BC-1999-SMALL-CAPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE EXCEEDS RETURNS IN THE SMALL-CAP UNIVERSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Minn.) 
(lb) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom has held that small companies grow faster
than big companies, small companies are nimbler than big companies,
and over time, small stocks outperform big stocks. But recent
experience has cast doubt on how valid these precepts still are.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of small companies _ those with a market value of $300
million to $1.5 billion _ lagged behind their larger cousins last
year for the fifth consecutive year, despite a growing economy and
low interest rates. And some professionals are questioning the
viability of small stocks as an investment class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not anti-small cap,'' said Frederick Taylor, vice
chairman and chief investment officer at U.S. Trust Co., ``but
there is no guarantee that small caps will outperform just because
they haven't for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons to be skeptical. Earnings of small-cap
companies, which historically have outpaced those of big companies
when the economy is expanding, have trailed the earnings of the 100
biggest companies for most of the last five years, according to
statistics from Leuthold/Weeden Research, a Minneapolis-based
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   It has become clear in the last few years that ready access to
credit is a distinct edge large-cap companies have over smaller
concerns. And that edge, analysts say, is not likely to disappear
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access to credit is an even bigger issue today than it used to
be,'' Taylor said. ``The big guys don't have to go to the bank to
get it. They can issue their own debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the agility issue. As developments through much of
the last two decades have shown, big companies are well aware that
they can no longer compete unless they are lean enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the small-cap track record of the last five years,
investors have remained hopeful. From 1992 until the end of 1997,
assets in small-cap mutual funds skyrocketed, to $136.1 billion,
from $22.1 billion, according to Lipper Inc. Through the end of
November, total net assets in small-cap funds fell to $127.2
billion, even as $5.7 billion in new money was added.
</P>
<P>
   Small-cap stocks do have advantages _ and champions. To start
with, as a group, they are cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small-cap stocks are where all of the bargains are in the
market,'' said Joel Tillinghast, lead portfolio manager of the $9
billion Fidelity Low-Priced Stock Fund. Compared with big stocks,
``relative valuations are as compelling as they have been since I
started managing the fund,'' at the end of December 1989, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison is even better than that, said Satya Pradhuman,
director of small-cap research at Merrill Lynch. ``Valuations are
at a 20-year low, with respect to big stocks,'' he said. ``That
suggests the risk levels in small caps currently are probably
lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pradhuman worries that a big dive in major market
averages _ which are the exclusive domain of big-cap companies _
would bury small caps. It happened in the third quarter, and could
happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts _ like Claudia Mott, director of small-cap
research at Prudential Securities _ are hopeful that last summer's
steep sell-off may have decreased the appetite for big-cap
companies.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Pradhuman suggested, if the past is any guide, recent
interest-rate cuts by the Federal Reserve Board should also help
small-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rate cuts have tended to be very good catalysts for the
market,'' Ms. Mott said. ``Small- and mid-cap stocks have tended to
outperform in periods following rate cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   That has not happened yet, however. The Russell 2,000 index fell
more than 3 percent last year _ and is 14 percent below its peak in
April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the back is broken on the new Nifty Fifty big-cap
stocks, something that almost happened in August and September,
small caps won't outperform large caps,'' said John Laporte,
manager of T. Rowe Price's $4.7 billion New Horizons and $1.8
billion New America Growth Funds.
</P>
<P>
   Those considering an investment in small-cap stocks should pay
close attention to how the group does this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the small-cap market lags in January, it usually lags for
the year,'' Ms. Mott said. ``Since 1926, there have been 16
Januarys when small caps underperformed big caps. In only three of
those years did they end up beating the big caps'' for the entire
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
