<HEADLINE>
`OUT OF SIGHT' VOTED BEST FILM OF '98 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Mass., Ill., Calif.) 
(lb) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Out of Sight,'' Steven Soderbergh's frisky adaptation of an
Elmore Leonard crime novel, with Jennifer Lopez and George Clooney
as shrewd, sexy opposites who attract, was voted best film of 1998
by the National Society of Film Critics, a 51-member group
consisting of critics from New York, Boston, Los Angeles, Chicago
and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh's zesty and entertaining genre film became an
unexpected winner after several earlier ballots had favored
``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``Affliction.'' Those became the best
film runners-up.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh was also voted best director, followed by a tie
between Steven Spielberg and Terrence Malick for the year's huge
World War II epics, ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``The Thin Red
Line.'' Those war films also stood out in the cinematography
category, where John Toll's work on ``The Thin Red Line'' was voted
the year's best.
</P>
<P>
   The group's choice of best actor was Nick Nolte, who won
resoundingly on a first ballot for his performance as a New
Hampshire man struggling with relentless, escalating pressures in
the wintry drama ``Affliction.'' He was followed by Ian McKellen,
who played the debonair ``Frankenstein'' director James Whale in
``Gods and Monsters,'' and Brendan Gleeson, who played wily Irish
gangsters in ``The General'' and ``I Went Down.''
</P>
<P>
   Best actress honors went to Ally Sheedy, who played a stellar
photographer and bewitching, decadent recluse in ``High Art.'' She
was followed in that category by Fernanda Montenegro of ``Central
Station'' and Cate Blanchett for playing the title role in
``Elizabeth.''
</P>
<P>
   In a very big year for that British queen, Judi Dench won the
best supporting actress award for also playing Elizabeth I, this
time in ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   In the best supporting actor category, Bill Murray's
``Rushmore'' performance, as a crafty tycoon matching wits with a
schoolboy, was cited. Murray was followed by Donald Sutherland, as
the sage track coach in ``Without Limits'' and Billy Bob Thornton
in ``A Simple Plan.''
</P>
<P>
   In a close vote, Scott Frank's adaptation of Leonard's ``Out of
Sight'' was named the year's best screenplay, immediately followed
by ``Shakespeare in Love''' and ``Rushmore.''
</P>
<P>
   Among nonfiction films, the group chose ``The Farm: Angola,
U.S.A.'' by Liz Garbus and Jonathan Stack for its tough,
compassionate look at the lives of inmates in a notorious Louisiana
prison. Other documentaries cited were Frederick Wiseman's ``Public
Housing,'' an enveloping, fly-on-the-wall look at many facets of an
inner-city housing project, and Werner Herzog's ``Little Dieter
Needs to Fly.''
</P>
<P>
   The group, which met at the Algonquin Hotel in New York on
Sunday and whose chairman is Peter Rainer of New York magazine,
selected the Iranian film ``Taste of Cherry'' by Abbas Kiarostami
as best foreign film.
</P>
<P>
   It also voted a best experimental film award to Alexander
Sokurov's ``Mother and Son,'' describing the film as ``a powerful
and moving exploration, through nontraditional narrative means, of
the intense relationship between a son and his dying mother.''
</P>
<P>
   And it voted a special award to Walter Murch, Rick Schmidlin,
Bob O'Neil and Jonathan Rosenbaum, the team responsible for
reassembling Orson Welles' ``Touch of Evil'' in a form that fit his
long-thwarted original intentions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
