<SLUG> BC-BKC-GA-WOMEN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lady Dogs ebb Tide in stretch
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ A lowly strength of schedule number has been the
only nick on an otherwise perfect season thus far for No. 4
Georgia, but Sunday's 85-70 victory over 14th-ranked Alabama may
raise more than a computer calculation.
</P>
<P>
   Before 4,124 at Stegeman Coliseum, the Lady Dogs (12-0, 1-0)
opened their SEC schedule and put away their first ranked opponent
of the season by shooting 67 percent from the field in the second
half and limiting Alabama All-American Dominique Canty to just two
field goals in the last 13:12.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia showed signs of elevating into a full-fledged threat not
only in the SEC but beyond. It's just one league game, of course,
but Alabama had won two in a row from the Lady Dogs, who play host
to No. 20 Florida on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The real season started today,'' said forward Angie Ball, who
had 11 points before fouling out midway in the second half. ''We
can gauge ourselves a little bit more because we played a Top 15
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia turned a tight affair into a double-digit lead in the
final five minutes of the game, thanks primarily to a zone defense
that denied Canty penetration. Alabama (10-4, 0-2), which had only
four field goals in a 10:55 second-half span, made just one of nine
3-point shots all afternoon. Canty equaled her average of 21
points, while Latrish Jones had 17 for the Crimson Tide.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Miller, who scored 27 points and had seven assists and
five rebounds for Georgia, made three of four 3-point shots,
improving her marksmanship from that distance to 9 of 11 over the
past three games.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's Deana Nolan, playing in her fourth game since becoming
academically eligible, handled Canty well one-on-one in the first
half. The lanky sophomore, nicknamed ''Tweety'' because of her
droopy eyes, also had 11 points and displayed flashes of pure
athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's pretty exciting to see Tweety play well,'' Georgia coach
Andy Landers said. ''She answered the Bell with Canty, but she ran
the floor and pulled up for the jumper. She just played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan brushed aside full credit for the work on Canty: ''Our
plan was to give her a lot of different looks out there. She's
pretty tough. She's got a lot of good moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Coco Miller didn't play in the first half because of what
Landers described as ''practice problems.'' But in the second half,
she heated up for 14 points in 18 minutes. Her 3-pointer with 9:24
left gave Georgia a 61-55 lead, and Alabama got no closer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
