<HEADER>
A6226 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-BOWL04-COX     01-03 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-BOWL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    College football's battle for No. 1
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ This much we know. The winner of tonight's Fiesta
Bowl between No. 1 Tennessee and No. 2 Florida State will get at
least a share of the national championship. But as the 1998 college
football season draws to a close, there are still a number of
questions surrounding the future of a sport that remains popular,
but very controversial, in the way it handles its post season.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's game marks the culmination of the first Bowl
Championship Series (BCS), a four-bowl rotation that includes the
Rose, Sugar, Orange, and Fiesta. Each year a different bowl gets
the ''national championship'' game and the Fiesta had the privilege
of going first. The Sugar Bowl in New Orleans gets the big game
next season which is set for Jan. 3, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS succeeded in its primary mission of getting the two
top-ranked teams together in one mega-game for the natonal
championship, giving college football the closest thing it has ever
had to the NFL's Super Bowl. Tickets to this game have a face value
of $135 and are going on the street for considerably more. Brokers
in Arizona said that if there were not two Southern teams playing
in the game, creating more nationwide interest, the street value of
those tickets would have easily topped $500 each this week.
</P>
<P>
   Media interest in tonight's game has broken every post-season
football record ever kept. Over 1,000 credentials have been issued
to print and electronic media, including 300 to ABC, which will
televise the game.
</P>
<P>
   While college football now has its ''big game,'' it has not
eliminated the controversy, criticism, and questions that follow
the sport because it does not have a post-season tournament to
determine its national champion like every other NCAA sport,
including the three lower divisions of football.
</P>
<P>
   That criticism and controversy, as it turns out, was not
necessarily a bad thing in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had more people talking about college football this season
than at any time I can remember,'' said SEC Commissioner Roy
Kramer, the coordinator of the BCS. ''Talk shows that almost never
discuss college football were arguing over the merits of the BCS.
People were interested. Even if they were mad, they were
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   And those interested fans continue to raise key questions about
the sport, all the way up to tonight's Fiesta Bowl game. For
instance:
</P>
<P>
   _ Did the BCS computer formula really work?
</P>
<P>
   Depends on who you ask. The argument continues over which of the
once-beaten teams should be facing undefeated Tennessee (12-0)
tonight. The computer formula used by the BCS weighed several
factors and chose Florida State (11-1). Ohio State (11-1) feels
very strongly it should have been in this game.
</P>
<P>
   _ So does the winner of the Fiesta Bowl automtically win the
national championship?
</P>
<P>
   Only half of it. The American Football Coaches Association,
whose members vote in the USA Today/ESPN coaches poll, have already
determined that the winner of tonight's game will get their
national championship trophy. The Associated Press will conduct its
media poll right after the game, and those voters are free to pick
any team for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   _ So if Florida State wins, is there still a shot for 11-1 Ohio
State?
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes, who beat Texas A&AMP;M 24-14 in the Sugar Bowl Friday
night, have been lobbying for about a week that they should get
some national championship consideration if Florida State beats
Tennessee. They were No. 1 for nine weeks before losing to Michigan
State 28-24.
</P>
<P>
   The odds appear long.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Tennessee wins I've got no argument,'' said Ohio State
coach John Cooper. ''But if Florida State wins, I think we can
claim it (the national championship) as much as anybody. We still
think we have the best team in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Will the BCS change the complex formula it used to pick its
top two teams?
</P>
<P>
   There will be some tweaking of the formula in the offseason,
Kramer indicated, and it may with the computer poll component of
the formula. That was the portion that most fans found confusing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Because of the BCS structure, Big East champ Syracuse (8-4)
got into the Orange Bowl while Kansas State got left out with an
11-1 record. Why don't they just pick the best teams for the big
bowls instead of worrying about the conference champions?
</P>
<P>
   Any agreement among the bowls and the conferences must take care
of the conference champions. If not, that conference will simply go
out and cut its own deal with a bowl and refuse to participate.
</P>
<P>
   _ How long is the BCS going to last and, with all the
controversy, are we any closer to a playoff?
</P>
<P>
   The BCS has a four-year contract with ABC through the 2001
season with an option for a three-year extension. The plan is to
get to 2001 and take another survey of the financial landscape. A
Swiss-based company, ISL, is floating a plan for a 16-team
tournament that would pay the 112 Division I schools about $300
million per year, or $2.4 billion over eight years. The current
bowl system generates about $140 million for the schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ So why don't the schools just take the money and do it?
</P>
<P>
   While more and more coaches are in favor of a playoff, the vast
majority of university presidents are against it. They are already
concerned that football is the athletic tail wagging the academic
dog and aren't sure they want it to get any bigger than it already
is. The commissioners aren't in favor of a playoff because under
the current system, they control the money. Under a playoff, the
NCAA would control the money.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, this is the reality college football officials work
with every day. The sport is in great shape. Television ratings are
fragmented, but as a total are higher than ever. College football
attendance hit an all-time higher this year for the second straight
year. Some bowls are struggling, but there is more money in the
bowl system than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   But how long can college football maintain this level of
interest under the current system of bowls versus playoffs? That is
the ulitimate question the sport must face as it heads into the
next century.
</P>
<P>
   SO WHO'S NO. 1?
</P>
<P>
   The winner of tonight's Fiesta Bowl game will automatically be
declared national champions by the USA Today/ESPN coaches poll. But
the Associated Press will wait until after the game to conduct its
media poll and its national champion will be declared early Tuesday
morning. A look at the teams which could conceivably claim the
national title:
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE (12-0): If the Vols beat Florida State tonight, it's a
no-brainer. The SEC champions will be one of two unbeaten teams
(Tulane is the other) and will have defeated three BCS teams:
Syracuse, Florida, and Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA STATE (11-1): If the Seminoles beat Tennessee, they
would have gone 12-1 against the fourth toughest schedule in the
country. They would have beaten three BCS teams: Texas A&AMP;M,
Florida, and Tennessee. No other team can touch FSU's
non-conference schedule of Texas A&AMP;M, Southern California, Miami,
and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO STATE (11-1): The Buckeyes, who beat Texas A&AMP;M in the 24-14
in the Sugar Bowl, were No. 1 for nine weeks before losing to 6-6
Michigan State 28-24. If Florida State beats Tennessee, Ohio State
believes they have as much claim to the AP national champion as any
team with one loss. Coach John Cooper believes the fact that his
team lost by only four points while Florida State lost 24-7 to N.C.
State should be a consideration.
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN (11-1): The Badgers had only one bad game this season,
a 27-10 loss at Michigan in its next to last game of the season.
But Wisconsin did not play Ohio State during its Big Ten schedule
and in the minds of the voters, the Buckeyes are a superior team.
</P>
<P>
   TULANE (12-0): If Florida State defeats Tennessee, the Green
Wave will be the only undefeated Division I team left standing. But
Tulane beat only two bowl teams in Louisville (7-5) and Southern
Mississippi (7-5), both fellow members of Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA (12-1): The Wildcats had only eight minutes of bad
football this year, when UCLA scored 28 unanswered points to turn a
close game into a 52-28 blowout. Arizona had the Pac-10's best
rushing defense and held five opponents to a touchdown or less. The
win over Nebraska in the Holiday Bowl put the perfect finish to the
best season in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
