</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUMMER-FIESTA04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lady Luck has been Tennessee's 12th man
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Having run out of ways to bleed a few more days
or dollars from the college football season, we come to tonight's
computer-generated, corn chip-sponsored national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, four days into the new year, as soon as Florida State
receiver Peter Warrick trips over a Gila monster just short of the
goal line, or Vols kicker Jeff Hall's winning 60-yard field goal is
aided by a freak desert dust storm, Tennessee's amazing run will be
done.
</P>
<P>
   Then coach Phillip Fulmer will be free to drive to Las Vegas,
put his new Tennessee contract on red and let it ride on one spin
of the wheel. When you're hot, that's not the time to back off.
</P>
<P>
   There are all kinds of good, solid football factors at play
tonight between No. 1 Tennessee and No. 2 FSU. It is the battle
between voracious defenses. It is a parade of electric skill
players. It is grim business at the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the one issue that gets into grayer areas: It
is pretty well agreed that the Vols have spent this season with a
horseshoe lodged securely somewhere on their collective body. No
one has been able to knock it loose yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we have been fortunate,'' Fulmer said. ``I like to be
good and lucky, then you've got something special going.''
</P>
<P>
   The gut says that the Seminoles will deny Tennessee its first
national title in 47 years. The ruthless makers of odds have made
the No. 2 Seminoles solid favorites. Bobby Bowden is 15-3-1 (.816)
in bowls at FSU, Fulmer 4-2 (.666) at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Vols have gotten the pass interference
call they needed to win at Syracuse, the missed 32-yard field goal
to beat Florida in overtime, the immaculate fumble to overcome
Arkansas. I was on the sideline, 20 feet from Clint Stoerner's
stumbling fumble, and still don't know if I could testify to a
grand jury that it actually happened. Every review of the Tennessee
seasons reads as fortunate as the diary of an heiress.
</P>
<P>
   This creates the belief that something wondrous will arise to
save the Vols tonight. Some weird turn, some phenomenon, some
convulsion of fate that will favor Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   This also slightly stains the 12-0 record it brings into the
evening. As if the Vols were merely passengers delivered to the
Fiesta Bowl by happenstance. They'd like to think they had
something to do with the past four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people feel like we were lucky and that we shouldn't
be here,'' receiver Peerless Price said. ``We are going to put all
those doubts to rest (tonight). We were the underdog (at) Georgia,
at home against Florida and on the road against Syracuse. We've
proven the doubt wrong all year long.'' Luck is a four-letter word,
almost dirty in certain parts of Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, it's not as if FSU hasn't had a little help. It can
lose to North Carolina State and win a national championship in the
same season _ one of the strangest turns yet. ``Ohio State had to
lose. UCLA had to lose. Kansas State had to lose. But nobody's
talking about how lucky Florida State has been to get here,'' Vols
receiver Cedrick Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Florida State is the practical, nuts-and-bolts pick. If
you happen to side with forces unseen and the concept of destiny,
then Tennessee is your team tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
