<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIESTA BOWL CAPSULE: SEMINOLES HAVE EDGE
</HEADLINE>
 CAPSULE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida State (11-1) vs. Tennessee (12-0)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7 tonight
</P>
<P>
   Location: Sun Devil Stadium, Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   TV: ABC
</P>
<P>
   How they got here: Tennessee is champion of the Southeastern
Conference and Florida State champion of the Atlantic Coast
Conference. That assured each team of a spot in the Bowl
Championship Series. They're playing for the national championship
because the final BCS computer rankings had Tennessee No. 1 and
Florida State No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Retrospective: The Seminoles are making their 17th consecutive
bowl appearance and 27th overall. They're 16-8-2. The Volunteers
are making their 10th consecutive bowl appearance and 39th overall.
They're 21-17-0.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents: They played one common opponent, Florida. Tennessee
beat the Gators, 20-17, in overtime. Florida State beat the Gators,
23-12. Opponents' records _ Tennessee, 69-52; Florida State, 77-44.
</P>
<P>
   What you need to know: Tennessee is seeking its first national
championship since 1951. Florida State won its only national
championship in 1993. This is the 12th time the nation's No. 1 and
No. 2 teams have played in a bowl. The top-ranked team has won six
times.
Who has the edge? Rushing offense Florida State: 150 yards per game
Tennessee: 211 yards per game Edge: Tennessee
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers win the old-fashioned way. They like to line up
and pound the ball downfield. Sophomore tailback Travis Henry (970
yards, seven TDs) is a powerful runner who won't break the big play
but seems to always get positive yards. The Seminoles have a game
breaker in sophomore tailback Travis Minor (857 yards, seven TDs),
but he gained fewer yards in more carries compared to Henry.
Passing offense Florida State: 251 yards per game Tennessee: 187
yards per game Edge: Tennessee
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, it would appear the Seminoles have the better air
attack. But with inexperienced Marcus Outzen at quarterback,
Florida State will keep things simple. The Seminoles have several
big-play receivers, led by Peter Warrick (12 TDs, 20 yards per
catch). Tennessee QB Tee Martin had 19 TD passes and only six
interceptions. His favorite target is Peerless Price (61
receptions, 10 TDs).
Rushing defense Florida State: 80 yards per game Tennessee: 94
yards per game Edge: Even
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have the size and speed to bring a lot of force to
the point of attack. The Volunteers, in particular, like for the
other team's offense to try to pound the ball on the ground. Junior
tackles Jerry Johnson and Corey Simon are the Seminoles' main run
stoppers. Each team allowed only five rushing touchdowns all
season.
</P>
<P>
   Passing defense Florida State: 135 yards per game Tennessee: 209
yards per game Edge: Florida State
</P>
<P>
   If Tennessee's defense has a weakness, it appears to be in its
secondary. Opposing quarterbacks completed 52 percent of their
passes and averaged nearly 12 yards per completion. Florida State,
which leads the nation in pass defense, allowed opposing QBs to
complete only 41 percent. And that helps explain why Seminoles
opponents converted only 19 percent of their third-down situations.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching Florida State: Bobby Bowden (33rd season, 292-84-4)
Tennessee: Phillip Fulmer (7th season, 66-11-0) Edge: Even
</P>
<P>
   Bowden has won 12 of his past 13 bowl games. But the past two
times the Seminoles have been in position for the national
championship _ the 1996 Sugar Bowl and last season against Florida
_ they lost. Fulmer leads active coaches in winning percentage. And
there is much to be said for his effort this season in guiding a
team few considered would contend for a championship to within a
victory of the title.
Special teams Edge: Florida State
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have excellent kickers _ Jeff Hall for Tennessee and
Sebastian Janikowski for Florida State. However, Janikowski has
more range, both on field goals and kickoffs. Each team has
returners capable of breaking the big play, but the Seminoles
appear to have a slight edge there. Both punters are solid.
Prediction: Florida State 24, Tennessee 21  &LR; name:_ Wendell
Barnhouse
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
