<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRITIC'S-NOTEBOOK-2TA     01-03 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRITIC'S-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: THE HIGH-WIRE ACT OF PLAYING FROM MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two contrasting images stand out from among the last year's
evenings in the concert hall. One is of a young violinist, a
well-trained, interpretively astute contest winner, who played a
Mozart sonata at his debut recital. I have forgotten the details of
his reading, and even his name, but what I remember is that he
stood before a music stand and played the sonata from the score.
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't see that very often. Soloists usually play standard
repertory works from memory. Audiences have been conditioned to
expect as much, and although this violinist's listeners may have
admired his performance, they are bound to have felt slightly
shortchanged.
</P>
<P>
   That may be unfair, not least because the work would not have
had memorized performances in the drawing rooms of Mozart's time.
But fair or not, when a recitalist plays familiar music from the
score, audiences read it as a lack of preparedness or commitment.
</P>
<P>
   The other image is of Eighth Blackbird, a new music sextet fresh
out of the Oberlin Conservatory. The group opened its debut concert
with Fred Lerdahl's ``Fantasy Etudes,'' a complex work of
continually changing balances, in which precision is a must. The
ensemble performed the work from memory, and added choreography _ a
slow wandering around the stage _ that underscored the work's
shifting combinations of flute, clarinet, violin, cello and
percussion.
</P>
<P>
   This was doubly surprising. Chamber ensembles, in both new and
old music, almost invariably use scores to prevent train wrecks.
And just as one expects standard repertory to be memorized, the
presumption with complex new works is that they will be played from
the music. Context is everything: With a new work, the presence of
the score may emphasize its newness or lend authority to the
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The Eighth Blackbird players said that memorizing the Lerdahl
was an experiment, and they used scores for the other works on
their program. But the performance left an indelible impression,
not only because it was so finely polished, but also because we
read the memorization of contemporary chamber works as a sign of
commitment beyond the call of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this business of memorization is not as clear-cut as it
may seem, and musicians and colleagues with whom I've discussed it
have taken positions all over the map.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, few major soloists would dream of playing
standard repertory publicly with a score before them, nor would
they allow their students to do so. Some go as far as to insist
that all memorization is not equal. This school holds that visceral
memory _ having the music in one's fingers as the result of playing
it hundreds of times _ is not true memorization at all, but purely
a question of mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   A musician, even an amateur, who has learned a piece through
repetition can play it absentmindedly while reading or watching
television. Once it's in the fingers, the player knows what to do.
But it's all or nothing. Ask a musician with a visceral memory of a
work to play its bass line or to isolate an inner voice, and he's
in trouble. That requires a more intellectually rigorous form of
memorization, built on a thorough study of the music.
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, musicians who insist that memorization is
overvalued. They hold that visceral memory is sufficient, that once
the fingers know what to do, the mind is free to direct them in
matters of interpretive nuance. Having the score onstage, they say,
is a security blanket that helps stave off memory slips.
</P>
<P>
   And they point to a double standard in today's musical culture:
Concert goers demand the perfection they hear on recordings, yet at
recording sessions, musicians virtually always use scores, to say
nothing of the editing techniques that make idealized performances
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Where memorization is concerned, there are double standards and
hierarchies of all kinds. A soloist is expected to have a work
memorized, yet the accompanist sitting a few feet away is cut more
slack.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only fair. Accompanists are hired hands who may be
juggling five or six programs in a week. Besides, their scores may
bear penciled reminders of tempos and emphases that the
soloist-du-jour prefers, information a busy accompanist need not
commit to memory.
</P>
<P>
   For an accompanist, though, having the music can be a
double-edged sword. With the printed music before him, the
accompanist is expected to be a life raft when the soloist is at
sea. If the soloist gets lost and begins to vamp, the accompanist
must lead the way home without calling attention to the soloist's
lapse _ or at least, that's the ideal.
</P>
<P>
   In one famous if possibly apocryphal story, Fritz Kreisler had a
memory slip while playing a Beethoven violin sonata with Sergei
Rachmaninoff. As Kreisler improvised in search of the thread, he
whispered, ``Do you know where we are?'' Rachmaninoff's mordant
reply was ``Yes, we're on the stage of Carnegie Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been cases, too, when soloists have minimized the
advantage that their score-reading accompanists have. The cellist
Mstislav Rostropovich once took his seat onstage, raised his bow
and looked to see if his accompanist, Samuel Sanders, was ready to
begin. After fumbling through his score for a moment, Sanders
walked offstage with his music, leaving Rostropovich looking
impatient.
</P>
<P>
   What the audience didn't know was that Rostropovich, in an idle
moment, had glued a Playboy centerfold into Sanders' score.
Backstage, Sanders removed the photograph, and the show went on.
</P>
<P>
   Now and then, a musician for whom I have great respect confounds
expectations and performs from printed music. Andras Schiff used a
score in his recent traversal of the Bartok piano concertos at
Carnegie Hall. Schiff is a superb interpreter of Bartok and much
else; I can't imagine that any serious listener's respect for his
work was diminished as a result.
</P>
<P>
   What, on the other hand, does one make of Luciano Pavarotti? He
has memorized many of the great tenor roles in the Italian opera
repertory, but although his concert repertory is tiny _ he has
juggled the same program-and-a-half's worth of art songs,
Neapolitan lollipops and favorite arias for the last 25 years _ he
never gives a recital without a music stand.
</P>
<P>
   The stand doesn't actually have music on it, just the song
texts, in large print. Is it too much to expect him to have
memorized those texts by now?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One charitable colleague argued that musicians should be allowed
to take their scores onstage. ``Expecting a musician to perform
without the score is like expecting a high-wire artist to perform
without a net,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I don't buy it. A high-wire artist who falls risks serious
bodily harm, perhaps even death. A musician who has a memory slip,
and no score to quickly check, might be embarrassed. It's not the
same.
</P>
<P>
   The real question is what we want from a concert performance.
There are, of course, the lofty expectations that art engenders. We
want our emotions and intellect to be engaged, and we want to
glimpse sublime truths between the notes of a great work in a
transcendent performance.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a musician reading from a score can create that
experience. Clearly, it's possible on recordings. But in the
concert hall, our eyes are engaged as well as our ears, and they
tell us that a score-reading soloist is too tightly bound to the
mundane world of dots on a page to touch a higher plane.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a degree to which musical performance is a
high-wire act. Ever since Mozart and Beethoven dazzled audiences
with daring improvisations, and Paganini and Liszt stunned
listeners with seemingly inhuman technical display, audiences have
expected virtuosity as part of the concert experience.
</P>
<P>
   Memorization is an aspect of the challenge. It is the difference
between virtuosity and mere muscularity. And for this special
species of daredevilry to work, there can't be any nets in sight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
