<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH ADVISES REPUBLICANS TO LIE LOW FOR AWHILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Rep. Newt Gingrich may be on his way out of the
speaker's office, but his mind is still actively concocting grand
strategies to save the Republican majority in Congress that his
critics say he nearly destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, he told a group of conservatives here,
Republicans need to present themselves as the party of tax cuts.
His big mistake last year, he said, was failing to push for
substantial tax cuts early in the year and then being too exhausted
to focus on them later, when Washington became enveloped in the
impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But he also urged his party to lie low for the next two years to
regroup and rethink its approach to keeping the House and winning
the presidency. Such passivity seemed a curious retreat for the
self-declared leader of the Republican revolution, but it reflected
what his friends said was his belief that Washington had become too
ferociously partisan to get anything done.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the standpoint of the House and Senate,'' Gingrich said,
``if we can adopt as our primary slogan `Do no harm' and simply
block liberal measures for two years and set the stage for a
Republican presidency, that is probably the most we can hope for,
given the nature of the current Washington environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he encouraged his party, if indirectly, to press forward
with the impeachment process _ a process that he was rebuked for
over-emphasizing during last fall's elections and that helped push
him out of the speakership.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, he said, should ``calmly and directly stand for the
rule of law and do so without embarrassment'' and ``stand for the
Constitution no matter what the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends said Gingrich was determined not to attack Clinton in
his speech. The phrase ``rule of law'' has become Republican
shorthand for pursuing Clinton for perjury, even as the president's
supporters dismiss his actions in the Lewsinky scandal as a minor
breach. But that was Gingrich's only remark that drew resounding
and sustained applause, and it won him a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke here Saturday night at a banquet that concluded a
four-day annual New Year's conference of about 300 conservatives
called The Weekend but known as the Dark Ages. Many of the
attendees spent the afternoon before Gingrich's speech at a nearby
shooting range firing rifles and automatic weapons at an event
sponsored by the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich officially gives up the speaker's gavel on Wednesday,
two months after he announced his resignation from the speakership
and from Congress. He plans to write, tour the lecture circuit and
divide his time between Washington and Atlanta, where he will work
as a strategic consultant to corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich will also continue to raise money for Republican
candidates. Joe Gaylord, his long-time adviser, said that Gingrich
had raised more than $200 million over the last four years, making
him the party's top fundraiser.
</P>
<P>
   Gaylord said that Gingrich, 55, would not be a candidate for
president in 2000, ``but who knows after that?'' He added: ``He
doesn't feel old. He's not hanging up the spurs.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Gingrich is formulating a vision for his party, making
lists, like six things Republicans should do to expand their
majority, and ruminating about the end of his House career.
</P>
<P>
   He quit, he said, ``in part because I believed that it was
impossible in the current situation in Washington to have any
opportunity to focus on vision and strategies at a time when those
in fact were our most important challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested that he had emphasized the wrong issues, like
impeachment over taxes. Again, he did not mention impeachment
directly but suggested that he had allowed the media to overblow
his role in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick issues that the liberal media elite cannot distort,'' he
told the audience. ``This was my biggest mistake in 1998 _ it was
partly a function of focusing too much on managing the House,
partly it was a function of exhaustion and trying to deal with the
complexity of Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``In the information age, you cannot allow the elite
media to define the election or they will always define it on the
left. We should have had a much bigger fight in the spring over tax
cuts and we should have stayed with the tax-cut message all summer
long and we should have unified the party by using brute
persistence, and there I think frankly that exhaustion was a big
factor.''
</P>
<P>
   As for conservatives, he told them to be bold and practical,
rather than theoretical. It has been a big mistake, he said, for
politicians to go on the Sunday television talk shows and ``talk in
abstract code words in a cynical, pompous and negative way about a
topic that doesn't matter'' to most people. ``Normal people,'' he
said, prefer to watch football.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the audience found Gingrich's speech inspiring. ``The
party needs someone to be a visionary and keep us on a core
national agenda,'' said Scott Bundgaard, a state senator from
Arizona. ``He's recognized his mistakes and he's stepping back up
to the plate to refocus us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
