<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SHOULD DELAY STATE OF UNION MESSAGE, SOME SENATORS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., S.D., Wash., Conn., Texas, Pa., N.J., Ky., Vt.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH-ASSESS, REPUBS-POLITICS) 
(mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a new Congress set to be sworn in this week,
several influential senators said Sunday that President Clinton
should postpone his State of the Union message if the Senate is
still grappling with an impeachment trial when he is scheduled to
appear before a joint session of Congress on January 19.
</P>
<P>
   The call to delay the president's annual policy address _ from
Republicans and Democrats alike _ underscored how the 16th
Congress would convene Wednesday under the same shadow of
impeachment that so sharply divided the 105th Congress and turned
its last days into a brutally partisan confrontation over the
president's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful that months more could be consumed by a trial of the
president on the two articles of impeachment approved by the House,
Sens. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, and Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., the minority leader, have been working across party lines
for the past few weeks in an attempt to forge a compromise that
would end a trial quickly and without witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But with conservatives in both the House and Senate opposed to
short-circuiting a trial, it was not yet clear whether Lott would
be able to sell such a proposal to Republicans, who will caucus for
the first time on either Wednesday or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The divisions among Republicans were clear on the television
talk shows Sunday as Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., defended a plan he
has drafted along with Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., to condense
a trial into a matter of days. The opposite view was expressed by
Sens. Phil Gramm, D-Texas, an influential conservative, and Arlen
Specter, R-Pa., a moderate, who said a trial with witnesses was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Keenly aware of the fluid situation, senators who appeared on
NBC's ``Meet the Press'' expressed their discomfort with the
spectacle of Clinton appearing in the House of Representatives to
address a joint session of Congress under such a cloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be unseemly and distracting for the president
to be giving a State of the Union address to Congress while he was
under trial in the Senate,'' said Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., said, ``It's inappropriate to
report on the state of the union as long as the president is under
impeachment, because the state of the union from the perspective of
his administration is unclear.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gramm, recalling the days before the State of the Union
message became an elaborate ceremonial setpiece that allows the
president to set out a new agenda for a national audience, said,
``The president can simply, as presidents did until the era of
television, the president can submit the State of the Union address
in writing.'' He added, ``The president should not be speaking to
Congress when he is under this cloud, under the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kennedy, a spokesman for the president, said the White House
would not comment on the calls for a delay. A year ago, Clinton
proceeded with the address just days after the scandal over his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky burst into public. Despite the
scandal, he set the policy agenda for the year with his call to
save a new budget surplus for ensuring the long-term solvency of
the Social Security system, and his public-approval ratings
rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   After midterm elections that gave Democrats five more seats in
the House and failed to produce Republican gains in the Senate,
Republican leaders are now anxious to make their own mark with
issues like Social Security and tax cutting.
</P>
<P>
   But a key question is whether Lott, trying to weave a path
between his party's moderates and conservatives, can persuade
enough Republicans to allow the Senate to dispense with impeachment
expeditiously to make way for a broader agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has been sounding out Republicans on the bipartisan
proposal by Gorton and Lieberman to have an expedited trial with no
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, prosecutors from the House would make the case,
a week from Monday, for Clinton's conviction and removal from
office. The next day the White House would present its defense. On
Wednesday, with William Rehnquist, chief justice of the United
States, presiding, senators would forward questions to the two
sides. On Thursday, the Senate would take a ``test vote'' on
whether the articles of impeachment for perjury and obstruction of
justice, even if proved, rose to a level that demanded the
president's removal of office.
</P>
<P>
   If, as expected, the test did not produce the 67 votes that
would be needed to remove Clinton from office, the trial would not
continue and the Senate could move on to consider censure. That too
is a tricky proposition, with some senators of both parties
opposing censure of the president and others disagreeing sharply
over what the terms of such a measure should be.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats appear united against Clinton's removal, a
critical question is how the Senate's 55 Republicans divide up.
Senators say that Lott would most likely move forward with the
bipartisan compromise proposal only if a majority of the
Republicans supported it.
</P>
<P>
   The first critical caucus of the Republicans that could make or
break the proposal could come on Wednesday, when senators are sworn
into office, or on Thursday when Senate Republicans meet on their
agenda for the new year. Democrats are holding their own party
caucus Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., said he had ``not a clue'' how
Republican sentiment would divide. ``It's pretty hard to get a
handle on this until we meet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell said that if the Gorton-Lieberman plan was not
acceptable, another route the Senate could take would be an
expeditious up or down vote on the articles of impeachment
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have enough testimony to make that decision,'' he
said in an interview. ``There may be others who think we don't. If
the conclusion is we need more testimony, we could do it in closed
session with the transcripts fully released.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But other powerful figures and factions inside the Republican
Party are still arguing for a full trial with an array of
witnesses. Among them are the House Republicans who have been named
to prosecute the case before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm of Texas, who often holds powerful sway among Senate
Republicans, expressed opposition on ``Meet the Press'' to any
''resolution that lets us reach a judgment without hearing the
facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said that facts about the president's attempts to cover up
his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky were in dispute. ``We've got to
hear from both sides to do justice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed polls showing that Republicans have damaged their
party's standing in the drive to impeach Clinton. ``Following the
constitutional process is the right thing to do,'' he said, ``and I
believe in the end that the people of Texas, wise people, fair
people of Texas, didn't elect me to read those polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter, who has spoken out in the past against removing Clinton
from office, said he too thought senators had a duty to hold a
trial, and suggested a ``managed trial with long trial days, 9:30
to 5 as we had at one time in the Philadelphia criminal courts.''
He also called for the president to come forward and testify before
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has yet to be suffused with the fierce partisanship
that tore apart the House as it considered impeachment and that may
prove to make the House ungovernable this year.
</P>
<P>
   But some fear the tone in the Senate could change quickly if
impeachment proceedings became protracted. Lieberman, also
appearing on NBC, said the impending State of the Union message was
one reason why the Senate had a ``very short window here to try to
work out a procedure for this trial.'' He also warned, ``If we
don't, we are going to descend, I fear, to the kind of partisan
rancor that characterized the House proceeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Rancor is already evident between Senate Democrats and the House
Republicans selected to prosecute the case, who want to call
witnesses before the Senate whom they never questioned in their own
House proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're acting like this is a high school exam,'' Sen. Patrick
Leahy, D-Vt., said tartly of the House managers in an appearance on
CBS' ``Face the Nation.'' ``They flunked the exam in their body.
They hope to do a make-up exam in the Senate, and that's not going
to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
