<SLUG> BC-R-NY-CANCER-COMPETE-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITALS BATTLE OVER LUCRATIVE CANCER-CARE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add art note. No other changes.)  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photo of Dr. Michael Gruber is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The vast prestige, power and, critics would argue,
arrogance of Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center can be measured
by its physical space.
</P>
<P>
   It is on York Avenue on the Upper East Side and, like many
prestigious New York City hospitals, inconvenient to public
transportation. Many of its hospital floors feel grim and dated,
with harsh lighting and nurses' stations enclosed in Plexiglass.
Its parking lot is dismal, and some waiting areas are about as
welcoming as the average public hospital's.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Sloan-Kettering has been the place to go for
cancer treatment in New York because of its prestigious doctors,
esteemed reputation for clinical research and the promising drugs
trials it conducts. Ambiance has never been the point.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, curious things have been happening at
Sloan-Kettering. It is building a new ambulatory care center at
53rd Street and Third Avenue, smack next to several subway lines.
The main hospital is undergoing a face lift: peach-toned walls with
still-life paintings are replacing blinding white ones,
sand-colored carpeting is being added and nurses' stations are now
open and accessible. In recent years it also opened a modern,
attractive center for breast cancer patients on East 64th Street,
complete with comfortable furniture and a shop that sells hats,
scarves, jewelry and the like.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, Sloan-Kettering's 72-year-old president, Paul A.
Marks, said he would retire next year, perhaps paving the way for
further changes in the center's way of doing business, which has
nearly ignored the managed-care movement.
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly enlightenment in a vacuum. Cancer is hot in New
York, and across the city the major medical centers are
aggressively attempting to nibble away at Sloan-Kettering's market
share. While this concentration on cancer patients is a nationwide
phenomenon, experts say the new competition is particularly fevered
in New York, where there are already more centers that have the
official designation of the National Cancer Institute _ and its
funding _ than in most other regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, New York is the hotbed of competition,'' said
Christopher Demby, who runs the Oncology Round Table program for
the Advisory Board, a health care research firm. ``There is action
being taken by every player in the market now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals are building new centers devoted to the disease and
poaching some of the country's biggest names in cancer care _ some
from Sloan-Kettering itself _ to run and staff them. They are
investing in expensive technology, adding all manner of
consumer-friendly fringe benefits like support groups and libraries
to their cancer wards and pouring money into advertising campaigns
that hawk cancer treatments in a way once reserved for innovations
like birthing centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to show that Memorial is no longer the only game
in town,'' said Marilyn Halper, executive director of Beth Israel
Medical Center's gleaming new cancer center, in the Zeckendorf
Tower on Union Square _ a public transport hub for lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Carving off one disease and homing in on it is an important
trend in medicine, especially chronic diseases that require
long-term care. Diabetes, for instance, is also getting lots of
attention. But few illnesses have attracted quite the same focus
and investment as cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is largely financial: Cancer is big business. The
increasing numbers of new cases alone make cancer an essential part
of any hospital's business. Experts believe that cancer will soon
overtake cardiovascular disease as the No. 1 killer in America as
the population ages and cardio-care becomes more advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer offers other financial incentives beyond the sheer flow
of cases: The disease is still fairly immune from managed care
penny pinching, while treatment advances have helped to streamline
care. And there is constant excitement in the field: More than 300
cancer drugs are in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the activity involves the opening of outpatient clinics,
which are starting to flourish across the country as new
technologies and changing medical economics allow patients to have
chemotherapy and radiation treatments without staying overnight in
a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Continuum Health Partners, which runs Beth Israel and St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center, built the new Union Square
out-patient center and beefed up its breast cancer program at St.
Luke's. It has poached several doctors from other far-more
prestigious cancer centers to run many of its programs, and spent
over $400,000 last year on cancer advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Over at New York University, the medical center has carved off
neuro-oncology as its brightest attraction, investing $10 million
alone in a rare Gamma knife that administers beams of gamma
radiation without surgical incision to the brain, and $2.5 million
more on special MRI machines, which enable doctors to rule out
malignancies without a biopsy. It also lured Dr. Michael Gruber, a
prestigious neuro-oncologist from the University of California in
Los Angeles, to run the unit.
</P>
<P>
   St. Vincent's Hospital, which had almost no profile as a cancer
treatment center, has hired an outside company to build its cancer
clinic. Mount Sinai Medical Center in Manhattan and Montefiore
Medical Center in the Bronx have made similar deals with Dr.
Bernard Salick, the California physician-entrepreneur whose
24-hour-for-profit cancer clinics have raised the customer-service
bar.
</P>
<P>
   Importantly, all of these hospitals and their doctors are well
versed in the ways of managed care, and are in a position to take
the increasing load of patients who are enrolled in HMOs and can
only afford to go to centers that honor them. Sloan-Kettering has
all but shunned the managed care movement, which also can cost a
hospital important drug trial money. ``In order to have enough
patients to do these trials you need a cross section of patients,''
said Joann Schellenbach, a spokeswoman for the American Cancer
Society. ``Not just those who can afford to go to elite
physicians.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is almost impossible to track the cancer business market
share _ most of the hospitals guard their numbers more closely than
any privately held company, and many experts think that New York
City's community hospitals are simply getting slices of a growing
market rather than stealing business from Sloan-Kettering.
</P>
<P>
   But since 1996, when Beth Israel opened its Union Square center,
the number of patients seen there has risen to 21,174 from 15,027.
Further, the hospital's in-patient cancer business has grown 12
percent since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   At NYU, new-case growth is similar. In 1993, its department of
neuro-oncology saw five patients. In 1997, that number grew to 275.
And if Salick's success in California is any indication, new cases
at hospitals where he is affiliated should certainly swell this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Salick, whose mere name tends to raise hackles in more
traditional circles, can be credited with helping to push New
York's medical centers toward a greater emphasis on
patient-friendly cancer care.
</P>
<P>
   He began opening for-profit centers in 1986 in California and
expanded to Florida. He says his niche is the 24-hour comprehensive
service that patients can get in his centers, and that his deep
knowledge of managed care, prevalent in California for a decade but
still fairly new to this area, gives him an edge. He also provides
the financing, badly needed by hospitals with dwindling resources,
to get clinics off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a highly credible reputation of running very cost
effective facilities,'' Salick said in an interview. ``You have
wonderful hospitals and wonderful doctors in New York but there is
a breakdown in the delivery system. You go to these places at 9 at
night and no one is there. Cancer is a disease that happens to go
on 24 hours a day. All these other hospitals are doing is opening a
center and sticking some doctors in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cancer experts have expressed concerns about Salick's
for-profit model, arguing that health care surpluses should go back
into the hospitals that generate them, not in shareholder's
pockets. Others deride his approach as either impractical or
non-threatening. ``Not too many people want radiation at 4 a.m.,''
said Dr. Warren Enker, the associate director of Beth Israel and
St. Luke's cancer center. ``So it's not that great a gimmick.''
</P>
<P>
   But Enker's colleague, Ms. Halper, admits that Salick has
underscored the importance of focusing on customer service. ``The
for-profits have taught us the importance of being
patient-friendly,'' she said. ``This is a service.'' A wig shop,
wooden furniture designed in Vermont and a light-soaked atrium of a
lobby are all part of Beth Israel's efforts in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   And patient friendliness has traditionally been the Achilles
heel of Sloan-Kettering's reputation. Doctors who have worked at
the hospital and some patients who have received care there
describe an imperious and at times cold atmosphere, where waits can
be long and doctors hard to reach.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, warmth wins over clinical reputation. Michael
Berkowitz learned he had lung cancer in 1996. His wife was
pregnant, his life as a successful Wall Street lawyer was thrown
into turmoil and he had to make some decisions about treatment,
fast. First, he went to Beth Israel, then to Sloan-Kettering for a
second opinion. He decided to go with Beth Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says to be cured, you have to go to Sloan because
they have the reputation,'' he said. While he was impressed with
the doctors, he found the hospital to be ``a scary and
institutional place,'' he said. ``It feels big, and you feel small.
I felt that I did not have the same personal connection as I did to
the Beth Israel doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   Some former Sloan-Kettering physicians say a lack of warmth
toward patients was an unfortunate byproduct of working in a highly
elite institution. ``Sloan-Kettering is one of the institutions
that has an exceedingly cumbersome administration,'' said Enker,
who left in 1995 for Beth Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surgeons there are very dedicated to their patients,''
Enker added. ``But it is a very busy environment. You can't see
hundreds of patients each year and not have patients feel rushed.
And I hear repeated complaints that the medical oncologists are
lacking in compassion and part of the arrogance becomes `Look I am
the expert, you came to me for my opinion so listen to me or you're
dismissed.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan-Kettering doctors and administrators are not unaware of
their reputation. But they also argue that it is more myth than
reality. ``There is a misperception that we are an ivory tower,''
said Dr. James B. Dougherty, deputy physician in chief of clinical
affairs at Sloan-Kettering. ``This is a very patient-centered
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Dougherty and his colleagues have made
customer-friendly cancer care a focus in recent years, even
studying the hospitality industry for clues, and have adopted
things like a more room-service style approach to patient meals as
a result. Getting patients out of the hospital and into its new
200,000-square-foot out-patient center on 53rd Street, where care
will be more streamlined, is a goal.
</P>
<P>
   Just as universities and corporations go after big names to
attract new business, so do medical centers. Cancer is no
exception. In the last few years, Sloan-Kettering has lost several
doctors to various centers, including four to Beth Israel alone.
St. Luke's poached Dr. Alison Estabrook, now head of its breast
center, from Columbia Presbyterian. In addition to Gruber, NYU
recently recruited Dr. Patrick Kelly from the Mayo Clinic and
several prominent doctors from other states. In turn, Beth Israel
took three doctors from NYU.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to go after patients is through building your
talent base,'' said Uwe Reinhardt, a health economist at Princeton
University. What is more, they attract drug companies and other
institutions needed to get drug trials going, which are another
major attraction for critically ill patients.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan-Kettering is not just content to spiff up its New York
City hospital. It is encroaching on the cancer business of some
regional hospitals by opening satellite centers elsewhere that
enable patients to get things like chemo and radiation without
having the trek into Manhattan. There is one in Long Island, two in
New Jersey and one in the suburbs just north of New York City, and
plans for more, Dougherty said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, hospitals in Long Island are not cheering. ``There is
considerable concern in Suffolk County over Sloan-Kettering's
plans,'' said Demby of the oncology round table. ``And what that
will mean to local facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the cancer war promises to expand outside the immediate
region, experts say. ``Cancer is to the 1990s what heart disease
was to the 1970s,'' said Gruber of NYU. ``It puts a center on the
map, and that begets business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
