<HEADLINE>
SHIP-SHAPE IN SAN FRANCISCO
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK   &HT;    -  Joan Kron , whose new book, ``Lift'' (Viking; $23.95) is
about ``Wanting, Fearing and Having a Face-Lift,'' was here
recently in the middle of a multicity tour promoting the book.
 &HT;    What makes San Francisco special in the field of face-fixing is
the particular popularity of Botox (poison injected into wrinkles
to flatten them) and the reticence of most locals to have their
skins stretched to the max. ``San Francisco is probably closer to
Boston than Los Angeles,'' said Kron. ``Women here want to look
natural. But what is natural?''
 &HT;    Kron, 70, has had two face-lifts and foresees the possibility of
one more. ``There is no natural. We do our hair, we pluck our
eyebrows. If you never cut your hair or wash your face, maybe
that's natural. But I don't know what natural is.''
 &HT;    Kron's book has only an ``after'' picture on the back cover;
there's no ``before.''
 &HT;     - Quentin Crisp , who just turned 90 and whose ``Evening With
Quentin Crisp'' is running in New York, says that San Francisco is
the only city where he received unanimous bad reviews. ``They
thought I went up and down the breadth of the land issuing
manifestos,'' said Crisp. ``When they found out I never mentioned
homosexuality at all, their love for me died in an instant. I'm
afraid I also lost the love of the entire homosexual community when
I said that Princess Diana  was trash and got what she deserved.''
 &HT;    - We're No. 2: San Diego is the fittest city in the country,
says Men's Health magazine, and San Francisco is No. 2, followed by
Denver, Seattle and Baltimore.
 &HT;    The ratings are based on such factors as smoking, drinking and
overweight percentages, chronic disease mortality rates, air and
water quality, health club memberships, parks, numbers of sporting
goods stores and number of ``burger joints.'' San Francisco was
hurt, says the magazine, ``by having the worst EPA watershed rating
in our survey.''
 &HT;    The five least fit cities are (from worst up) New Orleans,
Columbus, Ohio; Milwaukee, El Paso, Texas; and Indianapolis.
 &HT;    - Former San Francisco Ballet dancer  Heidi Guenther , whose
death in 1997, when she was 22 years old and weighed 93 pounds, is
the subject of a ``Dateline NBC'' story to be broadcast January 4
at 10 o'clock. San Francisco resident  Patti 
 Harrington , Guenther's mother, will be interviewed, as well as
former San Francisco ballet dancer  Devani Maijala .
 &HT;     FLASH 
 &HT;    - Taking down the Christmas tree: Most touching Christmas card
of the season was sent by the Stanford Band, addressed to the Ghost
of  Herb Caen  at The Chronicle. And singer  James Brown  says that
his Christmas present has had a downside. ``I got an upper plate
put in,'' said Brown. ``I used to have a gap between my front
teeth. Now that that's gone, I can't hit the high notes. I lost two
octaves.''
 &HT;    -  Morgan Thomas  noticed that a flyer enclosed with her Pacific
Bell phone bill advises English-speaking customers, in English,
that the basic human needs are food, water and phone; and advises
Spanish-speaking customers, in Spanish, that the basic human needs
are health, money, love and phone. She doesn't know whether to feel
deprived or ``nervous about what else I might be missing out on.''
 &HT;    - he star of a new version of ``Lassie'' broadcast by the nature
network Animal Planet has a contract that specifies first-   class
travel for the dog. Advertising Age says that this
 Lassie , a descendant of the original Lassie, is the first to
travel in such luxury.
 &HT;    Individual airline executives agreed to honor the terms of the
contract, with the provisions that pilots on each flight have the
final say. One captain did eject the dog from the first-   class
cabin last spring, ``resulting in a significant delay,'' says Ad
Age, ``as the airline unloaded the canine's baggage.''
 &HT;    - A memo from presidential assistant  Harold Ickes  to Secretary
of Health and Human Services  Donna Shalala , dated Oct. ober  10,
1995 and reprinted in the Washington Monthly, complains that the
president's name wasn't mentioned in Arkansas press coverage of a
federally funded sex education program.
 &HT;     WHO SAID WHAT 
 &HT;      ``Rock and roll had two effects on music. One was of 
 tremendous liberation, and the other was a license for a lot of 
 idiots to decry the efforts of more craftsman-like writers.'' 
 &HT;     Elvis Costello , who collaborates with  Burt Bacharach  on a
new album, ``Painted From Memory.'' Costello was quoted in Musician
magazine.
 &HT;      
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
