<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GRIFFIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCELYN GRIFFIN, 89, WHO STUDIED ANIMAL BEHAVIOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Mo.)  (lb) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jocelyn Crane Griffin, a research zoologist who studied the
behavioral patterns of tropical species, died on Dec. 16 at Emerson
Hospital in Concord, Mass. She was 89 and lived in Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Griffin spent decades in exotic places investigating exotic
creatures. She concentrated on the likes of jumping spiders,
praying mantises, butterflies and fiddler crabs.
</P>
<P>
   The ways of the fiddler crab were a mystery until Mrs. Griffin
discovered why and how it could change color like a chameleon, keep
track of time and feed furiously after being frustrated in combat
or at the mating game. Her research from many voyages around the
globe resulted in an authoritative monograph, ``Fiddler Crabs of
the World.''
</P>
<P>
   She spent her scientific career as an ethologist with the New
York Zoological Society, now the Wildlife Conservation Society. She
retired 30 years ago as director of the William Beebe Tropical
Research Station, a branch of the society in Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Griffin then delved into art history and, in 1991, received
a doctorate in the field at the Institute of Fine Arts of New York
University. Among her areas of specialty was the evolution of human
communicative hand gestures.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Griffin, a St. Louis native, graduated from Smith College
in 1930. She joined the staff of the department of tropical
research at the Zoological Society when the department was directed
by its founder, the naturalist, ornithologist and author William
Beebe. She became a research zoologist in 1942 and assistant
director of the department 10 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Griffin is survived by her husband of 35 years, Donald
Griffin, who retired as a scientist from Rockefeller University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 2007EST &QL; 
