<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDWEST SNOWS SEND SHIVERS THROUGH NEW YORK REGION 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York region's first major storm of the winter
churned out of the snowbound Midwest Sunday with a deluge of
lashing sleet and record-setting rains that disrupted air travel,
flooded roads and whole neighborhoods and caused hundreds of
traffic accidents, including a 50-car pileup in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   No deaths or serious injuries were reported, although scores
were hurt in collisions on icy roadways. But there was widespread
damage in flooded homes, including basements in a 30-block area of
the Springfield Gardens section of Queens, where water rose
waist-high and some residents had to be evacuated to shelters.
</P>
<P>
   For most who did not have to work or travel, it was a day to
stay indoors, to dismantle the holiday trappings, read a book or
sit by a window and take in the show: the clouds swelling like dark
bruises, the rain falling in silver cataracts, mists drifting
against glistening streets or stark suburban woods.
</P>
<P>
   But for those determined to get somewhere, it was hellish.
Coming at the end of the long holiday weekend, the storm _ and the
ripple effects of a blizzard that paralyzed airports across the
Midwest _ stranded or delayed thousands of travelers at Kennedy, La
Guardia and Newark International Airports as airlines scratched or
rescheduled flights and threw out their timetables.
</P>
<P>
   With water a foot deep on the expressway leading to Kennedy
Airport, traffic was halted for more than two hours at
midafternoon, and witnesses told of chaos as riders abandoned
stalled taxis and cars and, with luggage and children in tow,
streamed like refugees for the terminals a mile or two away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extremely frustrating,'' Adena Muchnik, 26, of
Brooklyn, said as she and her husband, David, hobbled along the
roadside, struggling with three suitcases and two small children in
strollers, trying to catch a 3:45 flight to Australia. It was
already 3:15, and the dream was dying. ``If we don't make the
flight to Melbourne, we might be out of a vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   The rain, which fell hard for six hours in the morning and early
afternoon, turned highways across the region into running rivers,
downed power lines in parts of Connecticut, caused 200 accidents on
the New York Thruway, and toppled rainfall records in Central Park,
where 2.42 inches eclipsed a 1936 mark for the date by more than an
inch, and in Bridgeport, Conn., which had 2.71 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Even more rain, though no records, fell in parts of New Jersey,
the National Weather Service reported: 3.43 in Chatham in Morris
County, 4.23 inches in Ocean Grove, in Monmouth County; 4.42 inches
in Middlebush, in Somerset County, and an astounding 5.78 inches in
the Morris County community of Morris Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Harsh as it was, the storm might have been much worse if
temperatures, which hovered in the 40's most of the day, had been
10 or 15 degrees lower, and the precipitation had turned to snow,
weather experts said. A meteorological rule of thumb is that every
inch of rain would have been a foot of snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a big snowstorm,'' Todd Miner, a
meteorologist with Pennsylvania State University, said. ``As it
was, all the snow was dumped in the Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   The powerful winter storm over the weekend struck Chicago with
22 inches of snow, and left deep drifts from Nebraska and Iowa to
Michigan and Ohio, shutting down airports and stranding hundreds of
thousands of travelers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
