<HEADER>
A6268 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUZZWORDS-SFCHRON &LR;      01-03 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUZZWORDS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Buzzwords Aid Communication, Confuse the Situation  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
It's 1999. Time to ramp up for a paradigm shift. Take ownership of
your core competencies, envision a win-win situation, and you'll
find yourself best of breed into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Translation?
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Make some New Year's resolutions and have a good year! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Across America, companies and employees are framing their
own futures in buzzword-laden language that is frighteningly
similar to that first paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   1998 produced a bumper crop of business buzzwords. When the
economy grew, buzzwords grew, too. When the economy faltered a bit,
the buzzwords kept growing.
</P>
<P>
   By now, almost anyone in the working world has his or her own
list of the Top 10 Most-Hated Buzzwords.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe yours includes ``synergy.'' Or ``world-class.'' Or
``thinking outside the box.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Scott, a software developer in Southern California, really
hates ``proactive.'' ``This is a word for people who aren't active
enough to look in the &LR;   &LR; dictionary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Minneapolis software engineer Laura Thurston has a grudge
against use of the term ``resources'' to refer to human beings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear it from salespeople who tell clients they'll send a
resource to fix their computer,'' Thurston said. ``They don't send
technicians, they send `resources.' My skills are resources _ I
personally am not one.''
</P>
<P>
   People use buzzwords for a variety of reasons _ some good, some
bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``People use technical buzzwords to feel like they fit in,''
said Benjamin Yoskovitz, author of ``The Buzzword Bingo Book.''
``Managers throw them out there so they sound like they know what
they're talking about, even if they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the positive side, they're shorthand for things that would
take a long time to explain otherwise,'' said Scott Adams, creator
of the comic strip ``Dilbert,'' which someday may be studied by
historians as a satirical record of 1990s business buzzwords.
</P>
<P>
   ``They allow you to capture amorphous things that you might have
trouble explaining, like saying `I've been Dilbertized.'''
</P>
<P>
   For every instance that a buzzword clarifies an idea, though,
there are probably three other times that buzzwords muddy things
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big problem with buzzwords is that rather than clarifying
meaning, they obscure it,'' said Daniel Levine, editor of the
online business magazine Disgruntled. ``Sometimes they're used to
create a code for people who are `in the club.' Other times,
there's an Orwellian component where black becomes white.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a buzzword sounds brilliant the first time you hear
it. Then, by the end of the week, you've heard it often enough to
gag.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a Top 40 song,'' said Richard Moran, a partner at
Andersen Consulting in San Francisco and author of the book ``Fear
No Yellow Stickies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so good the first time you hear it, but by Labor Day you
want to kill the next DJ who plays it.''
</P>
<P>
   For those of you fed up with the buzzwords of 1998, take heart:
They probably won't be around forever.
</P>
<P>
   Take the prefix ``cyber.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, everyone was talking about cyber-everything:
cybervision, cybercash, cybersex.
</P>
<P>
   Now cyber has faded is gone  &LR; _ but the prefix ``e'' is in. As
in: e-mail, E-Trade, eToys, e-commerce. Why? Certainly Wall
Street's infatuation with anything Internet-related has fed the
spread of e-jargon.
</P>
<P>
   `` `E-' just means, `Give me more multiple on my stock price,'''
said Adams.
</P>
<P>
   To help you ease into the New Year, here are some 1998 buzzwords
that many people would be very happy never to hear again in 1999:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Solutions.  &LR; No one in Silicon Valley sells computers or
software anymore. They're all too busy providing ``business process
solutions'' or ``global enterprise solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   I suppose we didn't really bomb Iraq last month; we initiated a
``recalcitrant dictator solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Me? I used to be a newspaper reporter. But these days, I guess
I'm a provider of ``business information solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Content provider &LR; . On the other hand, maybe I'm a content
provider.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Shakespeare, Kenneth Starr, Dear Abby, J.S. Bach,
Madonna, Michelangelo, eToys, Larry Flynt, Mrs. Quong's
fourth-grade class, and the National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Have any universities replaced their English, art, philosophy
and music departments yet with a ``Department of Content Studies''?
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Merger of equals.  &LR; This phrase was touted a lot to put a nice
gloss on 1998's flood of corporate acquisitions. But some equals
are more equal than others. Like, for instance, NationsBank and
Bank of America. 'Nuff said?
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Synergy. &LR;  This might win the prize for most universally hated
buzzword of 1998. Webster's Collegiate Dictionary defines it simply
as ``combined action or operation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the business world uses it as a way to promise a lot more
than that _ to promise something like 1+150 zillion.
</P>
<P>
   Want to merge Don's Ski Hut with Lockheed Martin? Tell people it
makes sense because of synergy. They'll nod and look impressed ...
until big losses next year show that most people buying a pair of
cross-country skis can't be easily sold on an F-22 fighter plane as
well.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Ramp up. &LR;  As in: We're ramping up for the next round of widget
production. We're ramping up for the annual sales meeting. We're
ramping up for house-training that new Labrador puppy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have `ramped up' so many things this year that we've
installed a trailer hitch in the conference room,'' said Rick
Pflugradt, director of marketing and administration at ProTemps, a
staffing firm in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Paradigm shift.  &LR; Physicist Thomas Kuhn invented the term
``paradigm shift` more than 25 years ago to describe major shifts
in scientific thinking that altered the way people viewed the
universe. Now companies use ``paradigm shift'' to describe
everything from a software upgrade to a new way of filing expense
reports.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Core competencies.  &LR; Whatever happened to good old ``skills''?
</P>
<P>
   Mark Miller, an engineer at Tut Systems in Pleasant Hill, got so
sick of this phrase that he coined a counter-buzzword: Core
incompetencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am working on raising my core incompetencies,'' Miller said.
``If I screw up enough, no one will ask me to do anything for them
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Downsizing, rightsizing and smartsizing.  &LR; These euphemisms for
laying people off have been around for quite a while, but they
don't seem to go away. Some jaded layoff victims have added another
phrase: After downsizing, rightsizing and smartsizing comes
capsizing.
</P>
<P>
   Some firms try to sugar-coat layoffs by calling them
``decruitment.'' Or there are the two new terms heard in 1998 by
outplacement consultant John Challenger _ ``deverticalization''
(i.e., getting rid of all those vertical layers of middle
management) and ``simplification initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One company called its layoffs ``Project Simplify,''
Challenger said. ``Another said it would have a `strategic review
of its strategies.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Empowerment.  &LR; Companies that genuinely treat their employees
well don't have to talk about ``empowering'' anyone. If your firm
is talking about empowering you, watch out: It may be code for
giving you lots of responsibility over completely trivial things.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Mindshare. &LR;  Companies now jockey to win consumer mindshare
rather than brand recognition. PR firms promise to increase
mindshare rather than popularity for political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   It may only be a matter of time until sixth-grade teachers start
hollering, ``Class, sit down and give me your complete mindshare!''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Associates. &LR;  A growing number of firms use the term
``associates'' rather than ``employees'' to refer to low-paid staff
such as burger flippers, room cleaners and sales clerks. Is the
theory that, if you give people a snazzy enough job title, they
won't mind being paid $6 an hour?
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Thinking outside the box. &LR;  I can't help it: This one always
makes me think of the cat box. And in my house at least, there's a
fair scattering of litter granules and sometimes even kitty
droppings outside the box as well as inside.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Into the next century. &LR;  Impress your audience by telling them
that your new product will dominate the market ``into the next
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Or go even further and say it will be the market leader ``into
the next millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Does it matter that the next century/millennium is now only 12
months away? And that your product will be obsolete long before
your driver's license expires?
</P>
<P>
   Nah. The audience probably isn't even listening to a word you
say. That intent look on their faces comes from thinking about
which freeway to take home, and whether to get takeout pizza or
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Situation.  &LR; This means ``problem.'' As in, ``Uh, Jeff, we've
got a situation developing here.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Action item.  &LR; This can also mean ``problem.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Red flag.  &LR; This can mean ``problem'' too.
</P>
<P>
   It's immensely relieving to know that American business is
running so smoothly _ no problems, just a few situations, action
items and red flags.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of buzzwords.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 2009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
