<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6269 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      01-03 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 `Dynamic' Employee Is Manic  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I'm president of the board of directors of a small &LR; 
 &LR; nonprofit. The problem is our highest-level paid employee. He's &LR; 
 &LR; very good at his actual job, energetic, full of ideas and &LR; 
 &LR; charismatic. He's perceived as dynamic. But what he is, it's &LR; 
 &LR; clear to me, is manic. He frequently commits our organization &LR;   &LR; to
big expensive projects without proper authorization. Now &LR;   &LR; he's
pushing more costly new ideas, even though we are &LR;   &LR; financially
strapped and can't afford them. If it were up to &LR;   &LR; me, I'd put him
on notice that his job is at stake if there are &LR;   &LR; any more
shenanigans. But the other board members think he &LR;   &LR; walks on water.
And our board turns over every year, so people &LR;   &LR; aren't aware of
the problems he created in the past. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  It's not unusual for the board and the CEO of a
nonprofit to occasionally see things differently. That tension can
be a good thing _ like checks and balances in government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small, new organizations need a brilliant, driven person to
lead them,'' said Jan Masaoka, executive director of The Support
Center for Nonprofit Management in San Francisco. ``But brilliant,
driven people sometimes are impractical. So one good role that a
board can play is to be the practical side.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tell from your brief summary whether this staff
person's initiatives are really threatening the future of the
organization or whether he's just a bit more entrepreneurial and
risk-tolerant than you are.
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume he's turned a deaf ear to your concerns and that
he's really about to send the organization down the tubes.
</P>
<P>
   You need to do your best to convey your worries to your fellow
board members. Sit down with them one on one: Educate them. Lobby
them. Marshal the facts, and make as strong a case as possible for
why they should rein in this otherwise-successful executive.
</P>
<P>
   What if your colleagues still think he can do no wrong?
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much more you can do right now. But in the long run,
you can try to develop a more independent, critical minded board by
lobbying for longer board terms.
</P>
<P>
   One-year terms for nonprofit board members are extremely
unusual. It's more common for board members to serve for three-year
terms so that they will have enough time to develop a critical
understanding of their organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the entire board turns over every year, they're failing to
fulfill part of their governance function,'' said Matthew O'Grady,
associate director of The Management Center, a nonprofit consulting
group in San Francisco. ``Even if you can get just a few board
members to stick around for three or four years, you would increase
the institutional memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Want more tips on how to be an effective nonprofit board member?
The Support Center offers a free newsletter for board members by
e-mail or fax: Call (415) 541-9000 or contact  &LR; boardcafe(AT
SIGN)supportcenter.org. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The National Center for Nonprofit Boards offers numerous books
and pamphlets aimed at board members: Call (800) 883-6262 or go to &LR; 
www.ncnb.org. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Show Me the Money
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently I left my job at a state agency. Due to state
accounting procedures, my final check was not issued until November
18 and was short two days' pay. It is now late December and I am
still waiting for that two-day check. Isn't it illegal to make
employees wait this long? And don't state labor laws apply to
government workers?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: The California Labor Code requires private-sector
employers to pay final wages to departing workers on their last day
of work or within 72 hours of the time they stop work, depending on
whether the worker gave advance notice of quitting.
</P>
<P>
   And employers who don't do this can face penalties of up to one
day's pay for every day that final wages are late.
</P>
<P>
   But the labor code doesn't apply to state and local government
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Your situation is instead covered by federal law, which isn't
nearly as helpful to employees in your position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal law says the employer must pay people at the normal
time that their paycheck would be due,'' said George Friday,
regional administrator for the U.S. Department of Labor's wage and
hour division. ``If the employer goes past that, it's a violation
of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are no penalties for late payment under federal law.
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. labor officials can only force your employer to pay you
the equivalent of federal minimum wage, or $5.15 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   So let's say you were earning $10 an hour at your job, and
putting in eight-hour days. You should have gotten $160 for those
two days of work. But the Department of Labor can only order your
employer to pay $5.15 an hour, which would come to $62.40.
</P>
<P>
   What should you do? Start by sending one more request for
payment in writing to your old employer. If that doesn't work, file
a wage claim with the Department of Labor at (415) 744-5590.
</P>
<P>
   That will get you at least some of your money. It might even get
you all of it, by bringing this mess-up onto the radar screen of
higher-ups at the agency.
</P>
<P>
   If the federal wage claim process doesn't get you everything
you're owed, Friday said, you could also file a small claims suit
to recover the difference between minimum wage and your actual rate
of pay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
