<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6272 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRTOUCH-SFCHRON &LR;      01-03 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTOUCH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AirTouch May Be Close to Merger  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
AirTouch Communications Inc. is reportedly nearing a $45 billion
merger agreement with Bell Atlantic Corp., the nation's largest
telephone company, according to executives close to the companies.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's AirTouch, the nation's second-largest wireless
phone carrier, could be acquired in a deal that could be announced
as early as Monday, the New York Times reported last night.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts familiar with both companies said they had heard
similar rumors of a $45 billion stock takeover of AirTouch.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal goes through, it would be among the 10 largest
mergers in history. AirTouch's stock rose $3.06 to $72.44 on news
of the rumored takeover. Bell Atlantic's stock fell $3.50 to $54.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers say the pairing would give Bell Atlantic a
better chance at competing for wireless customers against AT&AMP;T
Corp. and Sprint Corp. while giving AirTouch access to more
customers and a bigger national footprint.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic offers limited wireless phone service on the East
Coast to about 5 million subscribers, but it has been losing
customers to AT&AMP;T, which offers a single rate nationwide. AirTouch,
with its 35 million customers worldwide, would give Bell Atlantic
the boost it needs to compete across the country and
internationally, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes a lot of sense,'' said Michael Balhoff, managing
director of the telecom group at Legg Mason Wood Walker in
Baltimore. ``Bell Atlantic aspires to be a national player, and the
combination with AirTouch strengthens its wireless capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   AirTouch demonstrated its desire to be a national player earlier
this year when it bought US West Media Group, a wireless company,
for $5.7 billion. That purchase made AirTouch the No.2 wireless
carrier behind AT&AMP;T Corp.
</P>
<P>
   It also made AirTouch a more appealing takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   ``AirTouch has been an attractive property for long time,'' said
Jeffrey Kagan, an Atlanta telecom analyst. ``(AirTouch CEO) Sam
Ginn has built a great organization and was just waiting for an
offer he couldn't refuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it doesn't currently offer nationwide service, Bell
Atlantic has been losing customers who travel, he said. ``The only
way to combat that is to either expand your footprint or strike up
more roaming agreements. Companies lose money on roaming
agreements, so it makes sense to get a bigger footprint.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic tried to expand its reach this summer when it
announced a $64 billion merger with GTE Corp. The deal, which is
still pending antitrust approval, would allow the companies to
offer one-stop-shopping for communications needs such as local,
long-distance, data and wireless services.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic is also likely to become the first Baby Bell
allowed to offer long-distance service in its own territory.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of an AirTouch/Bell Atlantic merger have been circulating
for months, and the two companies are not strangers. They both own
50 percent of PrimeCo Personal Communications, a digital wireless
phone venture in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That partnership may be another reason why Bell Atlantic is
interested in AirTouch.
</P>
<P>
   When Bell Atlantic announced the merger with GTE, there was talk
that the Baby Bell would have to sell its stake in PrimeCo because
of a noncompetitive clause with AirTouch. GTE is an AirTouch
competitor. If an AirTouch/Bell Atlantic deal goes through,
however, neither company would have to shed its lucrative PrimeCo
investment.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said regulators would probably require Bell
Atlantic to divest some of its interests before approving any
merger. And several questioned whether regulators, who are growing
increasingly critical of corporate megamergers, would look
favorably upon two simultaneous, huge deals by Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hard pressed to remember two mergers of this size at the
same time with the same company,'' Balhoff said.
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly added that for a company to survive today, it
needs to be a national player. The addition of GTE and AirTouch
will help Bell Atlantic compete against bigger players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regulators have been bent out of shape over the megamergers
out there, but we've already got national players in MCI WorldCom,
AT&AMP;T and Sprint,'' Balhoff said. ``Most of these regional players
realize they have got to be national if they are going to be among
the major players in the future. It's not like we're putting
together the old Bell system.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of AIRTOUCH () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Bell Atlantic and other companies want to be able to compete on a
national level because the telecom industry is extremely lucrative.
Wireless is a big part of that as demand for the service soars and
technology improves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wireless is a key component for success for service providers
and Bell Atlantic wants to be a leader,'' Kagan said. ``Expanding
their geographic footprint, customer base and revenues is a big
step in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of AIRTOUCH () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
