A6277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BIG-EAST-NYT     01-03 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG-EAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH 4 TOP-25 TEAMS, BIG EAST HAVING A RESURGENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RON DICKER 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Big East Conference's mediocrity in men's basketball in
recent years is spawning a resurgence. No player left early for the
National Basketball Association last season, giving the conference
some much-needed continuity.
</P>
<P>
   The Big East leads the nation with a 9-8 record over ranked
opponents and boasted four teams in the top 25 through Sunday: No.
1 Connecticut, No. 12 St. John's, No. 18 Pittsburgh and No. 22
Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   The flow of Big East underclassmen to the pros will likely
resume next season. Connecticut's star, the junior Richard
Hamilton, is nearly certain to enter the draft, and the Huskies'
sophomore guard, Khalid El-Amin, is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's sophomore forward, Ron Artest, is maturing so rapidly
that talk of him departing early has also begun. In the Red Storm's
77-73 victory last Saturday, he carried St. John's with 25 points
and 8 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Jarvis hopes Artest has such a great year that the
NBA becomes a viable option. ``Whatever decision he makes,'' Jarvis
said Sunday, ``as long as he does it for the right reasons, will be
good for him and St. John's.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ST. JOHN'S &LR;  (11-2, 3-0), is riding an eight-game winning
streak, and will face Niagara on Monday night. Jarvis has hammered
home the point that a loss to a team from a lower conference could
damage the team's tournament chances more than a loss to a Big East
team. The Red Storm has responded by blowing out every soft touch.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's could be facing the conference's toughest defense at
Miami (8-2, 2-0) on Wednesday. The Hurricanes have limited their
last five opponents to under 40 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play against teams like that,'' Jarvis said, ``you
can only get better.''
</P>
<P>
   The centers Albert Richardson and Donald Emanuel continued their
spotty production, not scoring against Rutgers. Jarvis is
determined to give them minutes to spell the regulars and prepare
them for the future.
</P>
<P>
   `'We're 11-2,'' he said. `'I'm getting production out of the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONNECTICUT  &LR; (11-0, 3-0) has coach Jim Calhoun fretting over
the No. 1 Huskies' lack of focus against overmatched teams. ``We
played scoreboard the rest of the way,'' Calhoun said after UConn
raced out to a 14-2 lead over Georgetown before coasting to an
87-64 victory last Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's scoring average is down to 19.4 points a game,
putting more of a burden on the other forward, Kevin Freeman (13.7
points). El-Amin (14.6 points) and the defensive specialist Ricky
Moore continue to blur the distinction as to who the real playmaker
is. Moore, normally assigned to guard the opponent's best scorer,
has six more assists than El-Amin and has taken 62 fewer shots.
El-Amin scored 22 points and had just 1 assist against the Hoyas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be games this year when I'm going to get
people involved as the point guard,'' El-Amin said. `'And there are
other games where they're going to need me to be the scorer.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn travels to Boston College (3-7, 0-2) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SETON HALL  &LR; (9-4, 3-1) had its seven-game winning snapped by
Providence on last Saturday, but it is still floating above the
middle of the pack entering Monday night's game against Georgetown
(7-5, 0-3). Consistent scoring from the wings Gary Saunders (16.2
points, 54 percent shooting) and Rimas Kaukenas (14.5 points, 55
percent shooting) has been an important asset. Shaheen Holloway
remains a generous point guard at 6.8 assists a game, but his 10.4
scoring average and 35 percent field-goal percentage limit the
Pirates' options.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUTGERS  &LR; (9-4, 2-2) gets a week off to absorb a 77-73 loss to
St. John's after squandering a 14-point lead. ``We're learning
about ourselves,'' coach Kevin Bannon said. ``We know our
limitations. We had a chance against the No. 12 team in the
country. I'm very happy with my team.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PROVIDENCE  &LR; (9-4, 2-2) is proving to be more than just ``Jamel
Thomas and others.'' The Friars followed triumphs over Purdue and
Pittsburgh with a 66-49 victory over Seton Hall last Saturday. The
49 points was the Hall's lowest total this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our halfcourt defense over the last two games has
been the best it's been all season,'' coach Tim Welsh said. ``We
are finally understanding what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Providence plays host to West Virginia (7-6, 2-2) on Tuesday.
The Mountaineers are 0-4 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PITTSBURGH &LR; 's Vonteego Cummings is slumping. The other guard,
Kellii Taylor, has not played the last two games for personal
reasons. The result is a three-game conference losing streak and a
certain fall from the top 25. So much for the comeback of the
Panthers (8-5, 0-3).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NOTRE DAME &LR;  Troy Murphy, a freshman from Sparta, N.J., is
averaging 19.4 points and 9 rebounds. Murphy scored in double
figures in his first 12 games. The Fighting Irish (7-6, 1-1) play
host to Pittsburgh on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
