<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THREE REASONS FOR A NEW CHINA POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A couple of Shanghai prostitutes let themselves
into a hotel room occupied by a Chinese man who had discussed human
rights in a local teahouse. With a quick couple of zips, the girls
stood naked. Moments later, police entered the room and arrested
the dissident for patronizing prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   This old entrapment-and-blackmail dodge run by the frightened
men ruling China is their crude way of trying to discredit the tiny
group that wants to start a labor union and perhaps a non-Communist
political party.
</P>
<P>
   Why this transparent subterfuge? Because the nationwide
crackdown on dissidence, begun as President Clinton visited China
and hailed Jiang Zemin as his partner, is not playing well in the
world press and may not be going down well inside China.
</P>
<P>
   But why should Beijing go to the trouble of disguising the
jailing of a relative handful of troublemakers? Intellectuals and
students do not a counterrevolution make.
</P>
<P>
   The logical reason for the iron fist is instability in the
Forbidden City at the prospect of economic hard times. A generation
anesthetized by ever-rising prosperity is growing restive at slower
growth. In the vast countryside, we have reports that farmers are
grumbling, unable to market bumper crops; in the jammed cities, an
army of the underemployed posits a threat of unrest.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist leadership knows that the Soviet breakup began
with Solidarity, supported by Lane Kirkland's AFL-CIO, and the
stress on the state-stagnated system of Reagan's arms race; the
ensuing dissatisfaction of workers and farmers was ignited by a
cadre of underestimated dissidents. Fear of that scenario explains
the desperate need of Jiang to squelch every peep of opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Here in America, we are beginning to discover how brazenly the
sclerotic Chinese regime has stolen our missile technology, and how
it played on the naivete and financial need of our politicians to
influence our trade policies.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the bipartisan Cox Committee revealed the tip of the
iceberg of espionage penetration. Stimulated by a Jeff Gerth
article in The New York Times, it began investigating China's
illegal acquisition of all sorts of national-security secrets.
Because the committee tracked some of the Chinese spy successes
back to Republican administrations, it was able to issue a
unanimous report even in these times.
</P>
<P>
   If the White House allows enough of the 700-page report to be
declassified, it will show that the worst hemorrhage of secrets
took place in recent years. That's partly because our
counterintelligence was flummoxed by Larry Wu-tai Chin's
successors, but mainly because Clinton flip-flopped on trade with
China. Restrictions came off; we now pump $60 billion a year into
the regime. Worse, he steered the regulation of technology transfer
to the complaisant Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Col. Liu, a Chinese intelligence agent,
daughter of a top general, who channeled money through
Asian-American fronts to the Clinton-Gore and other campaigns.
Where stands the prosecution of the notorious ``China connection''?
</P>
<P>
   Becalmed. After nearly two years of resisting independent
counsel lest it embarrass the White House, the deeply conflicted
Reno Justice Department made a show of activity by charging a few
small-fry with being China's conduits to the Democrats. Then the
foot-draggers of Justice ran into the new ``Turn 'em Loose Bruce''
on the federal bench.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton must be happy to have this case in the hands of his
Democratic appointee, Paul Friedman. This judge has further
crippled the lame Justice investigation by throwing out most of the
counts against Maria Hsia, Charlie Trie and Pauline Kanchanalak.
Under his curious reading of election law, Saddam Hussein and the
KGB would be free to contribute millions to the Democratic National
Committee so long as it is ``soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the box score: one serious investigation of Chinese
penetration suppressed because it's secret, the other stymied
because of incompetence and misjudgment.
</P>
<P>
   In the light of (1) China's desperate duplicity on human rights;
(2) the 38 secret recommendations by the House to stem the flow of
secrets to China and then to Iran and North Korea, and (3) the
botched and scotched investigation into the change of trade policy
amid heavy contributions _ isn't it time to rethink our
``partnership''?
</P>
<P>
   Forget ``Who lost China?'' Consider ``Who Shanghaied America?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
