<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIENNA-MUSIC-REVIEW-N     01-03 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIENNA-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SALUTE TO VIENNA': INVOKING A NEW YEAR'S TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not that the New Year's concerts of the Vienna
Philharmonic are in any way sacrosanct. Far from it.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to tell from the hopelessly scattered and
horrendously overproduced PBS broadcast ``From Vienna: The New
Year's Celebration 1999'' on Friday exactly what happened in the
hall this year, with Lorin Maazel conducting (and playing violin,
drum and cymbal). But one thing was clear: The shtick was far more
heavy-handed and cloying than any this listener saw there a decade
or so ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the ``Salute to Vienna'' presented on Friday afternoon at
Avery Fisher Hall by Attila Glatz Concert Productions as a
``re-creation of the world-famous New Year's concert of the Vienna
Philharmonic,'' with music by Robert Stolz, Lehar and Kalman as
well as the Strauss family, was doomed by its own pretensions.
</P>
<P>
   For one obvious difference, the Orchestra of St. Luke's, as fine
an all-purpose band as it is, is no Vienna Philharmonic, especially
in quintessentially Viennese repertory; here, it was underrehearsed
and without some of its best players.
</P>
<P>
   For another, Avery Fisher Hall, even with a stageful of flowers,
is no Musikvereinsaal in Vienna; however well the latest acoustical
encumbrances may have served their purpose, no one has ever called
them pretty, let alone festive.
</P>
<P>
   The invocation of the Vienna event may have helped fill the
house, but it also raised inevitable and unfair comparisons. It may
also have tempted the performers, notably Peter Guth, an Austrian
conductor (who, like Maazel and Johann Strauss himself, played
violin at times), into excess.
</P>
<P>
   The program, with several numbers sung by Izabela Labuda, a
Polish soprano, was long, and made longer by unsolicited reprises
of two vocal items. And Guth carried shtick to lofty heights,
presenting one group of string players in garish ``Gypsy'' garb for
an aria from Kalman's ``Countess Maritza'' and trooping another
group down an aisle in the ``Radetzky March'' of the elder Johann
Strauss. It was hard to tell which was more uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Former dancers of the New York City Ballet were also on hand,
adding but little to the gaiety of the event and much to the
overall impression of unwieldiness.
</P>
<P>
   No matter; the large crowd seemed pleased for the most part,
though to judge from tepid applause on one occasion, it did see
through Ms. Labuda's unidiomatic performance of Gershwin (``By
Strauss'') if not the orchestra's unidiomatic performances of
Strauss. And to be sure, for a listener as susceptible to this
captivating music as any, there were elements enjoyable on their
own terms, shorn of invidious comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, would that the broadcast from Vienna had
offered a better representation of the great New Year's tradition
of the Vienna Philharmonic. All in all, a rocky start to the new
musical year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
