<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TV-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WHITHER THE TUBE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Jan. 4:
</P>
<P>
   No one in the television industry has enjoyed the past year. The
networks _ six of them now _ preside over a steadily falling
audience share, and NBC has even considered suing Nielsen Media
Research for what the network says is under-reporting of the
critical 18-to-34-year-old viewing audience. Nielsen's measurements
allegedly cost the network $60 million in advertising revenues.
Meanwhile, network programmers have left their jobs in droves, and
the networks have begun to replace them with programmers from
cable. The production costs of prime-time shows have gone through
the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Digital television, perennially in the offing but now getting
really close, will soon increase the number of channels to around
1,500, fracturing the audience into ever smaller shards and
enticing phone companies and Internet providers onto the tube.
Channels like MTV and the A&AMP;E Network have begun to spawn and morph
as fast as fruit flies. Meanwhile a clear racial divide between
black and white audiences has emerged, leading one producer to
speak of ``a chitlin circuit on TV.'' One of the few bright spots _
speaking only of revenue _ has been the WB network, which has a
popular lineup of shows for occult teen-agers and a big hit called
``Dawson's Creek,'' a kind of Titanic in a skiff watched every week
by teen-age girls on the phone with other teen-age girls.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious question _ besides ``What's on?'' _ is ``What does
it all mean?'' One answer is that for years an extremely narrow
bandwidth _ three channels representing three networks _ severely
compressed the TV-visible demographics of this country. As the
bandwidth has expanded _ as the number of channels has increased _
TV has begun more accurately to reflect the diversity of audience
markets in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is that it costs a lot of money to
produce television shows: it is an inherently expensive medium. A
cable channel or a network may begin by seeking a niche market. But
the economics of television work only if that niche market rapidly
broadens. That is what provides value to advertisers, if not to
viewers. Established networks and cable channels have an enormous
advantage, even as they clone themselves, because they already
control a stockpile of paid-up shows. That is why when digital
channels begin to multiply we will be watching a lot of leftovers.
Luckily, Americans are used to that.
</P>
<P>
   But does anyone besides the executives at ABC, NBC and CBS
really miss the days of network domination? Only, perhaps, to the
extent that we miss the forced passivity of having so few choices.
There is, in fact, a certain danger in the recent fractionating of
TV. Some of the ways the audience has been sliced _ Fox's Boyz and
Girlz channels, the marginalizing of black programs _ are
potentially harmful. But to the lament that we are losing a sense
of national community as television grapples with its recombinant
future, there is only one thing to say: Get a life.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
