<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6297 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTABOWL-HNS &LR;      01-03 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTABOWL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
TEMPE, Ariz. _ Bobby Bowden has heard all the rhetoric emanating
from New Orleans and Columbus, Ohio. Having been in similar
situations before, he can even be a little sympathetic with a
colleague's plight.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even so, the 69-year-old Florida State coach isn't interested in
engaging in any debate beyond the one to be settled at Sun Devil
Stadium beginning a little after 7 tonight. If Ohio State and coach
John Cooper feel left out of the party well, the fact is, the
Buckeyes weren't invited.
</P>
<P>
   Get over it, OK?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame John one bit for feeling the way he does,''
Bowden said Sunday on the eve of his 11-1 team's Fiesta Bowl
showdown with 12-0 and No. 1-ranked Tennessee. ``John might have
the best football team in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if Tennessee wins this ballgame, they're going to be
national champions. And if we win this ballgame, we're going to be
national champions.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the idea, at least, and a breathless rush of postseason
activity has done little to upset the Bowl Championship Series
scheme hatched by Southeastern Conference commissioner Roy Kramer
in the interest of creating a consensus No. 1-vs.-No. 2 matchup for
all the chips.
</P>
<P>
   If Tennessee wins, there will be no room for discussion. The
Vols will be 13-0, and coach Phillip Fulmer will have exorcised all
demons, including any rattling around from last year's 42-17 Orange
Bowl pounding by national co-champion Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the next step, a big hump for us,'' Fulmer said. ``We
like being at the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   If Florida State, a 5{-point favorite despite an early-season
loss to North Carolina State, should prevail to finish 12-1, the
Seminoles will point to a schedule that included eight bowl teams.
(FSU also could point out that its loss came on the road to a bowl
qualifier, while Ohio State was defeated at home by 6-6 Michigan
State.)
</P>
<P>
   So adios, Buckeyes. After a season of debate and criticism, the
BCS gives you Tennessee and Florida State as its defining act _ a
would-be team of destiny against one given new life by a rash of
upsets that made this trip possible.
</P>
<P>
   For a bit of extra spice, throw in one coach trying to win his
first national title and another seeking to enhance an
already-healthy legend.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, a few of the other subplots aren't so bad,
either:
</P>
<P>
   Who might crack at quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's Tee Martin has stepped out of the shadows of
Volunteers legend Peyton Manning to lead the school to its
first-ever 12-win season, emerging as a more-than-competent passer
in the season's second half.
</P>
<P>
   His counterpart, FSU's Marcus Outzen, was third-team coming into
the season before injuries knocked out Dan Kendra and Chris Weinke.
But Outzen earned a spot in Seminoles lore with a sometimes-lucky,
sometimes-good afternoon in a win over Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Peerless or Peter?
</P>
<P>
   Peerless Price has been Tennessee's big-play man at receiver,
turning around the Southeastern Conference Championship Game with a
fourth-quarter touchdown against Mississippi State. The Seminoles'
Peter Warrick, in turn, caught a big touchdown pass and threw for
another in the season-ending win over the archrival Gators.
</P>
<P>
   How many Travises does it take to win a national title?
</P>
<P>
   (This is not an Aggie joke.)
</P>
<P>
   After losing gifted tailback Jamal Lewis to a season-ending knee
injury, Tennessee turned to Travis Henry (970 yards) and Travis
Stephens (477) to fill the void. Florida State's top ball-carrier
is Travis Minor, who finished with 857 yards despite missing two
games because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The burden, to me, is on Minor and Henry and the tailbacks of
Tennessee,'' Bowden said. ``Those are the guys who can win the
ballgame and probably will.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to score first or at all?
</P>
<P>
   Florida State ranks No. 1 in the nation in total defense, giving
up just 214.8 yards per game, and is second in scoring defense
(11.5 points per game). Tennessee is No. 6 against the run (93.9
yards), No. 9 in scoring defense (14.4 points) and 17th in total
defense (303.0 yards).
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense is for real,'' Bowden said. ``Ours is ranked
higher _ I don't know how _ but they look about like us.''
</P>
<P>
   One kick for all the marbles, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   FSU's Sebastian Janikowski made 27 of 32 field-goal attempts
this season. Tennessee's Jeff Hall converted 19 of 24 field goals,
including a last-second game-winner at Syracuse and an overtime
game-winner against Florida.
</P>
<P>
   So you like a little suspense?
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee needed that last-gasp field goal to beat Syracuse, the
OT kick against Florida and an Arkansas collapse in the final
minutes to keep this championship dream alive. Even in the SEC
title game, the Vols seemed destined to join Kansas State and UCLA
in a ``Big Three'' trifecta of nose dives before pulling things out
against Jackie Sherrill's Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State needed Outzen, making only his second career
start, to come up big against Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The new kid or the legend?
</P>
<P>
   After enduring no shortage of whispers that he couldn't win the
big one, Fulmer finally got past Steve Spurrier and Florida this
year. Now, all Volunteers fans want is the national championship
they have been waiting for since the school claimed its first and
only one in 1951 _ 21 years before Fulmer graduated.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, of course, has done this before, but not often. This is
the 11th straight season in which his Seminoles ranked among the
top five in the Associated Press poll by the end of the season, but
he has just one national title (1993) to show for all that
excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first national championship, it was not a feeling of
elation; it was the fact that it got the monkey off my back,''
Bowden said. ``When we finally won one, it was a feeling of, `Thank
goodness.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If we won another one, I think it would be a little more
exciting. I think I'd enjoy it more than the last one.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the folks who exited New Orleans whining?
</P>
<P>
   Put up the snow shovels, break out the chips and hot sauce, sit
back and enjoy the show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
