<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUISED INTEL TO FIGHT BACK  
 BY DAN FOST
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - INTEL   &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The continuing competition between computer chipmakers Intel
Corp. and Advanced Micro Devices will flare up again today, when
Intel announces faster chips for cheap computers.
</P>
<P>
   Although AMD bruised Intel in 1998, winning some market share
and returning to profitability, Intel is fighting back in a big
way. The Santa Clara giant, the world's largest chipmaker, will
launch a New Year's assault by bringing out products that are more
powerful, cost less and reach the marketplace sooner than its
earlier offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever Intel stumbles, AMD has a bigger opportunity,'' said
analyst Mona Eraiba, cq  &LR; with Gruntal and Co. in New York. ``But it
appears Intel has picked itself up and is performing.''
</P>
<P>
   While the two companies battle, consumers stand to benefit
because faster, cheaper chips mean faster, cheaper personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with the business media today in San Francisco, cq
 &LR; Intel Executive Vice President Paul Otellini is expected to unveil
a new version of its Celeron chip. The Celeron was Intel's belated
entry into the inexpensive end of the PC marketplace, introduced in
April after AMD and National Semiconductor's Cyrix unit established
the popularity of PCs that sell for less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Chairman Andy Grove has acknowledged that the company
missed a significant market shift to sub-$1,000 PCs. The challenge
for Intel is how to compete at the low end of the market while
still selling chips at its accustomed high profit margins. In other
words, will a 400 MHz Celeron _ to be unveiled today _ eat into
sales of pricier Pentium IIs at similar speeds?
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Intel) pushes Celeron too hard, it will eat into its sales
of higher-priced chips,'' said Fred Zieber, president of Pathfinder
Research, a semiconductor analysis firm in San Jose. Although
Intel's first Celerons were a flop _ they performed slower than
comparable chips _ the company quickly fixed the chip by making it
faster. Intel reported strong Celeron sales by the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's work continues: Analysts say the company originally
planned to put the 400 MHz Celeron on the market in June or July,
then moved the date up to March or April and then moved it up again
to this week. Until today, the fastest Celeron in stores was 333
MHz. The company cut Celeron prices last month by about 30 percent
to reflect new manufacturing efficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Celeron is a brand-new brand name, said Mike Sullivan, an Intel
spokesman. ``We need to build consumer awareness and consumer
preference, in addition to making it even faster and more
affordable.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, according to Mercury Research, an Arizona firm that
tracks the semiconductor industry, AMD has eroded some of Intel's
strength. In the third quarter, Intel's share of the sub-$1,000 PC
market dropped from 68 percent to 56 percent, while AMD's share
rose from 19.5 percent to 24.1 percent, Mercury analyst Mike Feibus
reported.
</P>
<P>
   But Intel still is the dominant chipmaker. Zieber, at Pathfinder
Research, said Intel still holds 96 percent of the consumer
microprocessor market.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Even though AMD has garnered a fair amount of market share
at some price points, they've got a long way to go to make major
inroads into Intel's profits,'' Zieber said.
</P>
<P>
   AMD, in Sunnyvale, hopes to move into Intel's bread-and-butter,
the performance PCs. Those computers, most of which contain Intel
Pentium II chips, sell to businesses and home users who are doing
more than just word processing and surfing the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   AMD's next chip, code-named Sharptooth, could give Intel some
competition, according to Anand Lal Shimpi, who runs a Web site
that analyzes computer hardware,  &LR; www.anandtech.com &LR; . Shimpi, a
16-year-old junior at Enloe High School in Raleigh, N.C., said a
person close to AMD gave him the Sharptooth chip, which he doesn't
expect to hit shelves until February.
</P>
<P>
   AMD will say only that Sharptooth will be out in the first
quarter of this year. The chip, which Shimpi anticipates will be
called the K6-3, ``is very promising,'' he said. ``It doesn't look
like there's any downside to the K6-3.''
</P>
<P>
   Feibus, at Mercury Research, said the K6-3 will be ``a hot
product.'' He expects that it will sell in the $200 range, which is
high for an AMD chip.
</P>
<P>
   AMD isn't giving specifics yet, except to say it's added cache
to the popular K6-2 chip. Cache is high-speed memory built next to
the main processor, making for faster retrieval of frequently used
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes as no surprise that Intel has done what it said it
was going to do,'' said AMD spokesman Scott Allen. ``We've been
competing with them forever. The key to our success has been
execution, which has been excellent _ cross your fingers _ and the
value proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   AMD plans to continue to offer chips that either sell for less
than similarly performing Intel chips or outperform Intel chips at
the same price level. Its K-7 chip, the next competitor for the
Pentium II, will be out by June, Allen said. ``I think we're
looking at a real interesting 1999,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
