A6313 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETFILES-SFCHRON-THEN     01-03 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET FILES/JON SWARTZ  
 
 
 BUSINESSES AUTOMATING SLEW OF E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - THE NET FILES   c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
The answer is in the e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   For many consumers, getting the skinny from their financial
institution or the nearby computer store has become a matter of
tapping a PC keyboard instead of punching a phone pad.
</P>
<P>
   That's because banks and other service-intensive companies
increasingly are investing in automated e-mail software packages to
answer a deluge of questions from customers _ many of whom are
logging on in record numbers to corporate Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The information age rages on.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a major influx of e-mail,'' says Cameron King,
executive vice president of Countrywide Home Loans, a Pasadena
mortgage company. ``With this technology, we can process up to
1,000 queries a day. Before, we had one person individually answer
e-mail inquiries.''
</P>
<P>
   Manually routing and answering e-mail can be time-consuming and
expensive. High-tech firm Forrester Research places the cost of
dealing with each message at $2.75.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet can be either the least expensive or the most
expensive customer channel,'' says Brightware CEO Chuck Williams.
``Using specialized software can reduce the cost of dealing with
e-mail questions and feedback to as little as 25 cents apiece.''
</P>
<P>
   Brightware of Novato is one of several software-makers that has
developed technology that lets big businesses answer e-mail
questions from customers within seconds. The
artificial-intelligence program is used by Wells Fargo, Egghead
Software and others with major Web sites to ease the
service-support headaches caused by thousands of e-mail messages.
The programs typically answer repetitive customer-service requests
like bank balances or the status of orders.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: E-mail avoids the per-minute charge of a phone call,
is widely available, can be answered quickly and complements the
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   It does come at a cost, though. Setting up a service or
assigning someone to answer or delegate the torrent of e-mails is
pricey, and most customers don't like generic replies to e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Auto-reply systems from Brightware and Aptex Software go for
$75,000 to $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Voice vendors Lucent Technologies and Aspect Telecommunications
are expected to integrate e-mail capabilities into their systems
during the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sth  &LR; DEPT. OF CLARIFICATIONS: A perturbed Wade Randlett,
Democratic political adviser for TechNet, called to chide me for
last week's item on Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Randlett took umbrage at suggestions that the VP wasn't
tech-savvy because he had yet to register Web addresses bearing his
name for a certain presidential run in 2000. He says Gore merely
was following federal election law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until he announces and files for the presidential nomination,
he can't spend a dime on his campaign, and that includes
registering domain names,'' Randlett says. ``You don't horse around
with federal election law. If anything, Vice President Gore was
being law-savvy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem is a system that lets citizens secure the
rights to domain names and then offer them to the highest bidder,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Weinstein, the San Francisco man who registered several Web
addresses with Gore 2000 references, says he merely was securing
them before they were snapped up by political foes. He is offering
them to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there are scores of ``cyber-squatters'' whose
motives aren't as honorable. Many selfishly hoard domain names
containing famous monikers, such as Madonna.com or Computer.com,
with &UR;  &LR; the intent of auctioning them off.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Microsoft last week sued a pair of companies _
TexasRGV.com and TrademarkDomains.com _ for trademark infringement
for registering such online addresses as  &LR; www.microsoftwindows.com &LR; 
and  &LR; www.microsoftoffice.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sth  &LR; WILD, WILD WEB, PART III: If you thought the travails of
Atbigger.net couldn't get any stranger, check out this latest
dispatch from the online world's version of ``The Twilight Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site of Brigadoon.com, the financially challenged
Internet service provider that acquired the bankrupt Atbigger.net
last year, posted the following message last week: ``Our e-mail
server has been hacked. The nature of the attack prohibits you from
logging on to e-mail. We realize how maddening this is for you all.
We have someone working as fast as possible to rebuild the server.
Please stand by for more updates.''
</P>
<P>
   If your memory needs refreshing, Atbigger.net is the San Jose
operation that promised lifetime Internet access for $60. That was
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What a tangled Web they weave.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
IMAC REDUX: A month ago, we floated the rumor that Apple would
slice and dice the price tag of iMac, its best-selling $1,299
Internet computer, to $999 early this year to compete with
sub-$1,000 PCs. We also suggested that a second iMac model _ with a
faster processor and more disk space _ was in the works in 1999 for
$1,299.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, MacWeek.com ( &LR; macweek.zdnet.com &LR; ) reported that both
models should emerge, like groundhogs, in February. The Apple
comeback continues ...
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sl,1  &LR; SITE OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Seeing is disbelieving. Dead celebrities are digitally
resurrected at  &LR; www.virtualceleb.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
