<HEADER>
A6321 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITALBAY-SFCHRON-DI     01-03 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITALBAY-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL BAY/TOM ABATE  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - DIGITAL BAY   Thanks to Steve Jobs, Mac's Faithful Flock Has a Reason to 
 Believe 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The computer world's true believers will descend on San Francisco's
Moscone Center starting tomorrow for the annual Macworld Expo.
</P>
<P>
   For years, it has required a certain suspension of disbelief to
stick with this digital underdog. And even this year, with Apple
Computer finally back in the black and winning acclaim with its
innovative new designs, faith is still the price of admission to
the Mac circle.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it's faith in Steve Jobs, the unconventional
genius who has led Apple's turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   If one were to pick a song to exemplify Jobs, it would have to
be Frank Sinatra's ``My Way.'' Whereas most companies have chief
executives, Jobs has only accepted the job in an interim capacity.
He has not taken payment for his work. And he holds but a single
share of Apple stock, having sold, at an embarrassingly low rate,
the 1.5 million shares he earned when former CEO Gil Amelio brought
him back into the company.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, ironically, Jobs has not profitted financially from the
tripling of shareholder value that his own leadership has wrought.
</P>
<P>
   What Jobs' success has purchased, however, is an outpouring of
praise for his leadership and, more importantly, a respite from the
annoying question that has plagued Apple for years _ can it remain
a stand-alone company or must it merge to survive in today's
bigger-is-better corporate world?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not suggesting that Apple is sick. To the contrary, Jobs has
taken a company that was bleeding and patched it up. But he did so
mainly by amputating thousands of jobs and several superfluous
products in order to make a smaller but stronger company. Nowhere
else in today's corporate world is smallness considered a virtue.
</P>
<P>
   And even when Apple was twice its present size in sales and
market share, analysts were wondering whether the company could go
it alone forever. It still seems to be a question that begs an
answer.
</P>
<P>
   But not the least of Jobs' accomplishments is the fact that he
has taken complete control of Apple's public agenda. Whereas his
predecessors were always responding to outside criticism or events,
Jobs has scripted every step in the turnaround, deciding which
questions to answer and when, silencing critics with his imperious
personality _ backed up by the verdict of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   So I'll shut up, too, other than to opine that Apple cannot
survive indefinitely on its own and that Jobs, in his own secretive
fashion, is probably out there right now trying to conjure up some
deal that preserves the company's creative essence and rewards
shareholders _ while enhancing his own reputation.
</P>
<P>
   That last point is no small consideration because all available
evidence indicates that Jobs has a huge, if unusual, ego. There's
no reason to believe he that cares what you or I might think, but
he does seem concerned with the verdict of history. In interviews,
he has a habit of talking about what will or won't ``change the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   By that, I don't think he means ending hunger or bringing peace
to the planet. Jobs' world is the world of computing. And in that
universe, the thing that's really changed is the relative position
of Steve Jobs and Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Jobs towered like Zeus above the landscape of computing.
Gates was one of the satyrs prancing at his feet. The 1997 Macworld
show in Boston offered a visual reminder of their role reversal,
when the televised image of Gates dwarfed the real-life Jobs, who
drew jeers for announcing Microsoft's token investment in Apple.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy the notion that Jobs feels a compulsion to retake the
digital heights, take another step down the speculative path.
Imagine Disney as the buyer in a merger-a-trois with Apple and
Pixar that makes Jobs heir-apparent to Michael Eisner _ giving him
an empire that could over-awe Gates.
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK, so this sounds nuttier than most screenplays. But a
little more than two years ago, before Amelio bought NeXT Inc.,
wouldn't you have scoffed at a prediction that we'd be heading into
Macworld '99 with Steve Jobs at the head of Apple?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
