<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NBA-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOBODY BUDGES, BUT PLAYERS STILL HOPE FOR SEASON
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With four days left to save the National Basketball
Association season, Billy Hunter wants the owners to negotiate,
David Stern wants the players to capitulate and no one _ neither
the league commissioner nor the union executive director _ is
budging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're closer than people think,'' Hunter said Sunday night,
adding that he was hopeful that there would be a shortened season.
``We want to negotiate, whether it be in small groups or large
groups. This comes down to whether or not David Stern wants to have
a season. If he doesn't want to negotiate, we'll have none.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a settlement, Stern had said he would recommend to the
league's board of governors at a meeting Thursday in Manhattan that
they scrap the rest of the season. Eight days ago the union
rejected what the league called its final offer in the last round
of talks. After being rebuffed when he requested a meeting, Hunter
has not delivered what he calls the union's final proposal to the
league.
</P>
<P>
   With no talks scheduled it appears both sides are gearing up for
doomsday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's changed here,'' said Russ Granik, the league's
deputy commissioner. ``We have a meeting on Thursday. If we don't
have a deal, we'll recommend letting the season lapse. Our board
will be happy to have the last offer the players give them. But if
it's not a lot like our last offer, the board will not accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   The union made a better argument for a possible settlement last
week when it divulged part of its final offer, which included
agreeing to the league's concept of capping salaries of all of its
players.
</P>
<P>
   But the two sides remain far apart on total revenue
distribution. The players are wedded to the notion of receiving 57
percent of defined income in the final year of a six-year plan _
the amount that was devoted to salaries last season. The owners
have offered no more than 54 percent in the final three years of
the deal. As total revenue is expected to be $2.5 billion to $3
billion, the gap represents $75 million to $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   A number of other issues remain to be hashed out. These relate
to flexibility for players to move to other teams and to employ
escape clauses in contracts _ issues that the league feels
translate to more income for the players.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter especially has his work cut out for him this week. Beyond
trying to convince the owners to meet with the players and put
together a deal, he has to make sure the union's solidarity remains
intact.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Inquirer reported that more than 20 players had
contacted the former union president Isiah Thomas about mediating
the dispute and appeared to be interested in putting the owners'
proposal to a vote, something Stern has implored the players to do.
</P>
<P>
   Though the agents for two of the players mentioned, Shaquille
O'Neal and Grant Hill, denied that their clients had spoken to
Thomas, at least five players have publicly asked for the owners'
latest proposal to be put to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If their strategy over the next few days is to gamble whether
there is going to be a vote, we're not going to have a season,''
Hunter said. ``They have made the high-end guys an issue. We gave
them that. I'm ready to talk again. If not, let Stern be the fall
guy. If there is no season, he's responsible for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said the union's 19-member negotiating committee would be
in Manhattan on Tuesday, leaving only two days for the two sides to
bargain before Thursday's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   More than three months of the season have been lost, and the
players are expected to lose more than $500 million in salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kerr, a reserve guard for the Chicago Bulls, said the call
for a vote was playing into Stern's hands. ``If I'm going to lose
half a million dollars, let's try and get something good for the
majority of players,'' Kerr said. ``If guys are going to start
calling for a vote, that's their prerogative. But I'm not so sure
it would pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr said he was not only frustrated by the lockout, but also by
the proposals currently on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole objective coming in was to help the middle class,''
he said. ``The only thing we've done is bump up the minimum
salaries and probably secure an average salary exception that's
well below the average salary. That's not a whole lot, considering
we've lost half a season.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
