<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6325 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUTURE-SFCHRON-FUTURE     01-03 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE FICTION WRITERS MAY HAVE ENVISIONED THE FUTURE
OF  TECHNOLOGY  
 BY DAVID EINSTEIN
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - FUTURE   &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Gates or Steve Jobs might be able to guess what computers
will be like in a few years. But if you want insights into the
technology of the next century or two, the place to go is science
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Sci-fi writers have proven prescient many times. Jules Verne
penned a 19th century story about a trip to the moon. In 1931,
``Brave New World'' by Aldous Huxley presaged Prozac. And George
Orwell, in his 1948 masterpiece ``1984,'' envisioned a time when
the government could use technology to keep track of people.
</P>
<P>
   Today's science fiction is no less instructive. In fact, it
often tells us where we're going before we get there. In his 1984
novel, ``Ender's Game,'' Orson Scott Card described a global
network eerily similar to the Internet _ almost a decade before the
arrival of the World Wide Web. One of Card's protagonists uses the
equivalent of Internet newsgroups to distribute propaganda and
become the most powerful man in the world.
</P>
<P>
   One reason why science fiction sometimes foretells science fact
is that many modern writers in the genre are accomplished
scientists. David Brin and Gregory Benford, two of the most
successful sci-fi writers on the scene, are both physicists. Brin
has a doctorate in astrophysics and has served as a consultant to
NASA. Benford teaches physics at the University of California at
Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that all modern science fiction has the ring
of potential truth. There's still a lot of stuff that challenges
the imagination. Writers routinely disregard the known limits of
physics, for instance, to send space travelers flying faster than
the speed of light. In their defense, it's the only way you can get
across the galaxy, which is thousands of light years from end to
end.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, however, the stuff of science fiction is merely an
incremental step into the future, requiring no great leap of faith.
That's because the technological revolution has spawned ideas and
devices that themselves would have qualified as science fiction a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many technology companies and government research agencies are
hard at work developing things that even Jules Verne would have
considered far-fetched. Microsoft, for instance, has experimented
with ways to use the human nervous system to control a computer. At
IBM's Almaden Research Lab in San Jose, there's a project to create
a computer capable of understanding human expression. And SRI in
Menlo Park is hard at work on artificial intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, science fiction usually is a step ahead of reality. Here
are a few of the most enticing innovations rippling through today's
sci-fi literature:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Intelligent Agents: The glut of information on the Internet already
has spawned the development of rudimentary programs that can go out
and sift through mounds of data to find stuff that's important to
you. In the future, these programs, called intelligent agents, will
be essential sidekicks, bringing you news, prioritizing your e-mail
and doing research.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``Earth,'' Brin calls such agents ferrets. Tad
Williams, in ``Otherland,'' takes it a step further with an
intelligent agent that takes the form of a mechanical pet. It talks
in a human voice, plugs itself into an outlet when it gets tired
and has wireless access to just about any public network.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Artificial Intelligence: Computers that think like humans have been
a staple of science iction for years. The late Isaac Asimov
immortalized them in the form of robots. One in particular, named
Daneel (cq)  &LR; Olivaw, plays a central role in guiding humanity
through thousands of years of turmoil in the ``Foundation'' series.
</P>
<P>
   Today's chief proponent of sentient computers is Greg Bear, who
calls them thinkers. In his work, they're basically supercomputers
that have become self-aware.
</P>
<P>
   Most scientists believe that it will be decades before computers
can approach the thought processes of humans, and nobody expects
them to have an id or an ego. But a generation ago, no one would
have foreseen a computer handily beating the world chess champion,
either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Nanotechnology: Nothing has captured the fascination of modern
sci-fi writers like nanotechnology, microscopic machines made of
biological material. In the real world, it's being developed for
medical and industrial purposes. In the not-too-distant future,
nanotech could be used to repair a blocked artery or a damaged
kidney without surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Science fiction has had a field day with nanotech. Bear writes
in ``Slant'' about material that fashions itself into complex
weapons. In William Gibson's ``Idoru,'' nanotech is used to build
buildings. And Neal Stephenson makes it the central theme of ``The
Diamond Age,'' in which entire residential areas are constructed
using it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bioengineering and Implants: Gibson, Bear and others write of a
time when medical science and computer science will blend,
providing fascinating new ways to enhance the human body. Implants
will let us live longer and improve the equipment that nature gave
us. Implanted microprocessors, for instance, could give us better
vision or control over our emotions, or the ability to easily
understand complex mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   Today, you can have an identity chip implanted in your cat or
dog. And no less a light than physicist Stephen Hawking predicts
that the next frontier for science will be the re-engineering of
human DNA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Virtual Reality: Although it's a hot topic in the technology
press, virtual reality so far has been limited to experimental
video games and esoteric government research. It has remained for
Gibson to define the shape it eventually could take.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Neuromancer,'' the seminal work about cyberspace, he
sketched a near-future in which virtual reality is nearly
indistinguishable from reality itself. Put the electrodes on your
head or the goggles over your eyes and dive into a world of danger
and intrigue, where you can be a hero or get your brain fried.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson, in ``Snow Crash,'' creates an entire virtual city in
cyberspace where much of the action takes place. And incredibly
sophisticated online virtual reality games are the main settings in
``Otherland,'' as well as Alexander Besher's ``Rim.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Superluminal Travel: At the heart of much science fiction is the
idea that outer space can be navigated like just another freeway.
Writers have cooked up any number of easily explained theories to
allow us to break the light-speed barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Kirk simply says, ``Maximum warp,'' and Captain Picard
intones, ``Make it so.'' Asimov got around the problem with what he
called ``the jump,'' which let you hop through space like a kid on
a pogo stick.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so easy. Light zooms along at 186,000 miles per second,
and so far, the best our rockets can muster is less than 25,000
miles per hour. Not only that, but the laws of physics say nothing
can go faster than light. Period.
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, several theories endorsed by top physicists
that could make FTL (faster than light) travel possible. For
instance, because space curves in on itself, it may be possible to
use ``worm holes'' or other anomalies to disappear in one region of
the universe and reappear in another.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, that sounds more like science fiction than most
science fiction. But if science has taught us anything, it's that
if you can think of something, it probably can be done. Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
