<HEADER>
A6330 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-MAYOR-NYT &LR;      01-03 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A RESOLUTION FOR THE MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Jan. 4:
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's war with the New York City Council on
homeless shelters has led the administration to serve an eviction
notice on a Brooklyn community psychiatric center that serves 500
mentally ill outpatients. That was a peculiar way to celebrate the
holiday season. It is also dreadful policy making that should be
allowed to die with the old year.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has been angry about a bill regulating homeless
shelters sponsored by Councilman Stephen DiBrienza. When the
council overrode the mayor's veto and passed the bill into law last
month, Giuliani announced that the city would have to open new
shelters as a result, particularly in DiBrienza's district.
</P>
<P>
   The administration soon centered on a building in Cobble Hill
that houses a number of community services, including a
well-established psychiatric center. The building already had the
zoning necessary for a homeless shelter, but the fact that it was
in DiBrienza's home turf was obviously the main attraction.
</P>
<P>
   This stacks up as revenge politics, no matter how the mayor's
aides spin it. The Giuliani administration originally said the new
shelter would be needed because of restrictions contained in the
DiBrienza bill. It now says the facility is required simply because
some of the older shelters in Manhattan and Queens are too large
and need to be replaced. That sort of switched signals is a good
sign that the mayor's real agenda is personal rather than
programmatic.
</P>
<P>
   The administration appeared to have changed its mind last week,
when several state and city officials said the eviction papers had
been served by mistake. But Joseph Lhota, the deputy mayor for
operations, later insisted that the eviction, which is effective
late this month, would stand.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and his aides should celebrate the new year by ceasing
and desisting in this destructive battle. There is no emergency
that justifies displacing hundreds of mentally ill outpatients from
a location they have used for 20 years, and which the community
supports. Sites for new homeless shelters should be selected by
normal procedures, which do not include telling the community that
they are getting the facility as a punishment for their council
member's voting record.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's position on what it dislikes most about
DiBrienza's bill has changed at least twice since the measure was
passed. The new law includes significant new reporting requirements
for the Department of Homeless Services, demands the mayor has
castigated as ``micromanagement.'' It is true that among the needs
of the city's homeless population, more paperwork ranks near the
bottom. But Giuliani brought this on himself by encouraging his
agency heads to stonewall the council's requests for information.
</P>
<P>
   At his year-end press conference, the mayor said his New Year's
resolution would be to give more credit to other people in his
administration. A better goal would be to develop greater tolerance
for dissent and to curb the bellicosity that threatens to
overshadow all the accomplishments of this administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 2047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
