<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-LAURENDI-NYT &LR;      01-03 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LAURENDI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 NATALE LAURENDI, 75, LAWYER AND LIE-DETECTION EXPERT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Natale Laurendi, a New York criminal investigator
whose expertise with lie detectors helped convict the guilty and
clear the innocent for many years, died on Dec. 21 at his home in
Brooklyn. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was leukemia, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Laurendi joined the New York City Police Department in 1951 and
was assigned to the Manhattan district attorney's squad, which put
him to work on major rackets cases. At the behest of Robert F.
Kennedy, then the chief counsel of a Senate investigating committee
on organized crime, he testified at the panel's hearings on
racketeering in the Teamsters union.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Frank S. Hogan, the renowned Manhattan district
attorney, selected Laurendi to study polygraphy, and turned him
into the police department's star lie detector. He retired from the
force in 1975 and started Nat Laurendi, Certified Lie Detection
Inc., a private investigation and polygraphy firm in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Polygraph tests are designed to determine whether a person is
telling the truth by measuring the subject's physical reactions to
questions and recording them on a graph. Laurendi championed the
procedure as ``an excellent investigative tool for the defense, the
prosecution and the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most celebrated cases in which his work played a
vital role was the Janice Wylie and Emily Hoffert ``career girl''
murder case of 1963. Painstaking detective work, including
Laurendi's tests, helped to free a wrongly convicted defendant and
convict the real killer.
</P>
<P>
   He also figured in Patricia Hearst's 1976 bank robbery trial in
San Francisco. He served as a consultant, testified at hearings,
lectured, contributed articles and recently finished a book
manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   Laurendi was born in southern Italy but grew up in Brooklyn. In
World War II, he served as a special agent, investigator and
interpreter in the Army Counterintelligence Corps in Italy, winning
the Bronze Star with four battle stars.
</P>
<P>
   He was certified as a polygraphist at the National Training
Center in 1963. In 1969, he received an associate degree in
psychology from City College.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 52 years, Laura Autelitano; two
sons, Domenick and Robert, of Brooklyn; three daughters, Adrienne
Renzetti, Loretta Laurendi and Diana Allocca, all of Brooklyn; two
brothers, Joseph, of Ocala, Fla., and Anthony, of Levittown; a
sister, Matilda Cherney of Staten Island, and eight grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 2048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
