<HEADER>
A6332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      01-03 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CLINTON'S BUDGET OPPORTUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Jan. 4:
</P>
<P>
   A new year always presents the president with an opportunity to
outline his domestic agenda in a State of the Union message and a
budget. This year, the impeachment furor seems all-consuming, but
by most accounts President Clinton is preparing a sensible,
measured program likely to gain broad support in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He apparently plans to stick to his cautious formula of keeping
the budget balanced, limiting new initiatives to a few critical
areas, opposing broad new tax cuts and husbanding projected budget
surpluses to shore up Social Security. Republicans are so fractured
over budget fundamentals that they will find it hard to shift these
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The White House's centrist thinking on the budget is politically
logical at a time of turmoil in Washington. It also makes sense in
light of the overriding need for the next Congress to deal with
Social Security, which will start to run a deficit when the baby
boomers retire in the next decade or two. There is no better time
than now to fix the nation's biggest retirement program, when
prosperity has supplied the budget surpluses to help do the job. If
Clinton can use his political skills to coax a deal on Social
Security, then there ought to be a debate about how to spend
whatever surpluses are left over.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem unrealistic to expect that Clinton, hobbled and
discredited by scandal, could wield much influence in Congress for
the remainder of his term. But consider what happened last year,
when he was able to draw paradoxical strength from his impeachment
troubles and win on the budget. It helped that in the House the
GOP's moderates and its tax-cutting social conservatives squabbled
among themselves all year. But the Republicans yielded to Clinton
on many of his spending programs because they did not want a budget
fight to draw attention away from the president's scandals, and
they knew that their own insistence on more tax cuts was not
gaining much sympathy beyond their own core supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is clearly gearing up for the same fight to be
replayed this year. By most accounts, Clinton intends to showcase a
small number of high-profile spending initiatives for next year,
paid for by budget cuts or unspecified closing of loopholes in the
tax laws. These will probably include programs to combat pollution,
subsidize school construction, provide long-term care for the
elderly and disabled, and offer tax breaks for child care. Clinton
announced over the weekend that he would propose that the military
receive a $4 billion increase in the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   On all these budget issues, the Republican Party is more
disorganized than at any time since the 1970s. The budget fiasco of
last year, followed by the electoral debacle in November, led to
the resignation of House Speaker Newt Gingrich. After Rep. Robert
Livingston, R-La., came and went as his replacement, House
Republicans settled on an unknown and untested deputy whip as
speaker, Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. Early on, he will have to
decide whether to listen to the confrontationalist right wing or
the moderates who are ready to make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Democrats in Congress, their hard core of liberals
and labor leaders want spending increased and will likely argue
that the election results strengthened their hand. But for now the
best policy is to use the surplus for Social Security and then have
a debate over whether to use whatever is left for tax cuts, as
Republicans want, or for the spending initiatives pushed by the
Democrats. For all the uncertainty in Washington, Congress may be
so desperate to achieve something, anything, that it will choose
bipartisan cooperation on a major domestic issue for a change. It
is not as unrealistic as it sounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
