<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NASA LAUNCHES PROBE ON 11-MONTH JOURNEY TO MARS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MARK CARREAU &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ NASA's Mars Polar Lander rocketed from Earth on
Sunday, initiating an 11-month journey to the Red Planet where
scientists hope it will search for water _ a key ingredient for
life _ frozen amid the frigid terrain of the South Pole.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,300-pound probe blasted off from the Cape Canaveral Air
Force Station in Florida at 2:21 p.m. CST aboard a Boeing Delta II
rocket, rising through cloudy skies.
</P>
<P>
   Just over an hour after liftoff, the probe had successfully
separated from the rocket's third stage to begin its lengthy
interplanetary journey, transmitted data back to Earth through its
ground station network and deployed two power-generating solar
arrays.
</P>
<P>
   The probe's navigational system, however, took longer than
expected to find and ``lock'' onto a collection of guide stars that
were to keep the spacecraft on course. The Polar Lander is to
follow a 470-million-mile-long celestial pathway that will take it
first toward the sun, then outward into the solar system to
intercept Mars.
</P>
<P>
   John McNamee, NASA's Mars Polar Lander project manager, said the
spacecraft was pointed at the sun as intended as its journey began
but was making a slow circular motion as it searched for guide
stars. ``The spacecraft is doing exactly what it's supposed to do
at this point in time and will continue to do so until it does find
a solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Polar Lander was developed by NASA's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory of Pasadena, Calif., to search for evidence of ice
embedded below the surface after making a soft landing in the
desert-like Martian polar terrain. The lander and a pair of tiny
companion probes called Deep Space 2 were designed to work in
concert with NASA's Mars Climate Orbiter, which was launched by a
Delta rocket on a nine-month trajectory to the Red Planet on Dec.
11.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers believe the latest collection of small spacecraft
headed for Mars can determine whether the Red Planet still harbors
any of the water that pictures gathered by earlier probes suggest
once flowed in abundance over the now cold, arid landscape. With
conditions more like the Earth's, Mars could have been hospitable
for life, some scientists reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to follow the water if you're looking for life,''
Ed Weiler, NASA's chief of space sciences, told reporters before
Polar Lander lifted off. ``We have a lot of reasons to believe
there is water on Mars in the form of ice. But until you actually
land there and find it, you can't say for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The space agency has invested nearly $360 million in the Polar
Lander and Climate Orbiter missions in a bid to gather
confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   The Polar Lander probe is scheduled to reach the Martian surface
on Dec. 3, using techniques pioneered by NASA's much-larger Viking
probes of the late 1970s to touch down.
</P>
<P>
   The lander was engineered to make a direct, high velocity
descent into the Martian atmosphere. It will be slowed first by the
friction of the planet's thin atmosphere, then by parachutes. A
dozen small braking rockets should bring the less than 4-foot-tall
lander to a gentle, upright stop on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Using electrical power generated by new solar arrays unfurled on
the Martian terrain, the robotic spacecraft will direct a more than
6-foot-long mechanical arm into the surrounding soil to scoop up a
sample.
</P>
<P>
   The soil will be deposited into an oven-analyzer on the lander,
where it will be heated and surveyed for the presence of water
vapor. The lander is also equipped with cameras, temperature and
pressure probes as well as a cloud monitor that should operate for
about three months.
</P>
<P>
   Before it plunges toward the south pole of Mars, the spacecraft
will also release a pair of small basketball-sized probes dubbed
Deep Space 2. They are designed to smack into the surface at
velocities of nearly 500 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   The tremendous force of the impact will drive small
bullet-shaped probes about three feet into the ground. Drills will
gather small subsurface soil samples, which will also be heated and
analyzed for water vapor.
</P>
<P>
   The Climate Orbiter is designed to reach Mars in September. It
will orbit Mars rather than land, functioning much as a weather
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The Climate Orbiter is equipped to track the movement of water
vapor and dust through the atmosphere between the equator and polar
regions over the course of a Martian year. Scientists theorize that
as the seasons on Mars change dust and water from the equatorial
regions of the planet are deposited at the poles.
</P>
<P>
   The Climate Orbiter will double as a communications satellite,
relaying signals from the Polar Lander and Deep Space 2 probes to
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Polar Lander is also equipped with a small, privately-funded
microphone that designers hope will record and relay to Earth the
first sounds heard on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what we will hear,'' said Weiler. ``I don't
think we will hear Elvis. At least, I hope not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
