<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE DISSIDENT ON A HUNGER STRIKE LEAVES HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Chinese dissident on a weeklong hunger strike to
protest China's crackdown on a fledgling democratic party was
released from Bellevue Hospital Center Sunday after being taken
there Saturday, a hospital spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The dissident, Wang Xizhe, one of China's first pro-democracy
activists, began his hunger strike during a protest on Dec. 27 in
front of the U.N. headquarters, said Wang Bingzhang, an organizer
of the protest. Wang Xizhe returned to his home in Elmhurst,
Queens, Sunday, but has still refused food and hopes to continue
his hunger strike for at least two more days, Wang Bingzhang said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Chinese government sentenced three men in China
to prison terms of more than a decade each after they tried to
organize the Chinese Democracy Party as a formal opposition to the
Chinese Communist Party. Wang Xizhe, chief secretary of the
overseas committee of the Democracy Party, was joined by about 15
others who staged shorter hunger strikes last week, said Wang
Bingzhang, who is also an adviser to the Democracy Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We organized this hunger strike to protest the arrests by the
Chinese government and to urge the United Nations and international
society to do something to stop these persecutions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-democracy activists had hoped that the Chinese government
would relax political controls after President Clinton's trip to
China in June, and leaders began applying to register their party
with the government. But those expectations were quickly abandoned
after the first arrests and a speech last month by President Jiang
Zemin, who said that challenges to one-party rule in China would be
``annihilated.''
</P>
<P>
   Party members who remained free after the crackdown have phoned,
written and sent e-mails to support Wang Xizhe and to ask about the
hunger strike, said Wang Bingzhang, who is no relation.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Xizhe, 50, was one of the first Chinese critics of
totalitarian rule in China to become known to the West, said Andrew
Nathan, a political science professor at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Bingzhang said he and Wang Xizhe are scheduled to testify
about the arrests later this week before the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We advised him to eat,'' Wang Bingzhang said. ``He has to
recover his health to go to Washington.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 2056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
