<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6341 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LEGIS-NYT     01-03 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTISAN TONE EXPECTED AS LEGISLATORS RETURN TO ALBANY 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With the capital's political landscape left
virtually untouched by the November elections, lawmakers return
here this week for a 1999 legislative session that experts say is
likely to yield the same sort of partisanship and acrimony that
have become synonymous with Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gov. George E. Pataki, a Republican, and his Democratic
rivals in the Legislature enter the new year with their hands
strengthened by voters. Pataki won a second term by handily
defeating all three of his major opponents, while Democrats
increased their large majority in the Assembly by one seat.
</P>
<P>
   The election results seem to have emboldened these bitter
adversaries as they prepare to confront a host of important policy
issues from proposed utility rate cuts to criminal justice
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and legislative leaders must also grapple with the
main business of Albany, adopting a state budget. The Legislature
has failed for the last six years to enact a budget by the April 1
deadline, becoming mired instead in long and bitter legislative
sessions that have regularly plunged the state into fiscal
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   The budget is expected to be among the most contentious issues
again this year, largely because the state has a ballooning budget
surplus that Democrats and Republicans are already deeply divided
over how to spend. Experts contend that the surplus could total as
much as $2 billion by March 31, when the state's 1998-99 fiscal
year ends.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers note that at least they will not face the same kinds
of highly partisan issues that divided them in previous years, like
revamping the state's welfare and rent-regulation laws. Zenia
Mucha, the governor's spokeswoman, said, ``If partisan politics do
not become the focal point, I think we can have a relatively
productive session.''
</P>
<P>
   But the work awaiting the Legislature in 1999 would be difficult
to resolve even in the most collegial environment. Democrats in the
Assembly say they intend to push a plan to cut electricity rates by
reducing the Pataki administration's role in reorganizing New
York's electric power industry. Pataki has resisted that proposal
in the past, though he also strongly advocates cutting electric
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats are also seeking to ease what they and others
assert are the state's Draconian drug penalties, though Republicans
have made no effort to change them even as they acknowledge that
the penalties should be more flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and his Republican allies who control the State Senate
say they will renew their call for a sweeping overhaul of the
state's juvenile justice system, seeking harsher sanctions and the
flexibility to prosecute youths as adults for certain violent
crimes. Democrats have expressed a willingness to compromise on
this issue in the past but have failed to pass a bill that
Republicans would support. Pataki and Senate Republicans also want
to pass a package of bills that would stiffen penalties for sex
offenses and crimes committed in schools.
</P>
<P>
   A looming complication for 1999 could be Pataki's apparent
ambition for national office. After proposing an election-year
budget last year that was criticized by fiscal conservatives
nationwide, the governor plans to offer the kind of austere budget
that he championed in his first two years in office. His aides say
he mainly wants to hedge against a downturn in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move could also help enhance his standing among
conservatives who dominate the national Republican Party, even as
it potentially angers Assembly Democrats who battled against deep
spending cuts that he proposed in 1995, his first year in office.
</P>
<P>
   Anger between Pataki and the Legislature would be nothing new.
They clashed fiercely over a surplus last year after Pataki vetoed
hundreds of millions of dollars in programs approved by both houses
of the Legislature. The items vetoed were largely Democratic
initiatives, like a plan that would have spent $500 million to
refurbish existing schools and build new ones.
</P>
<P>
   The hostility stirred by that action has yet to subside as
Pataki's main nemesis in the budget debate, Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver, indicated in a recent interview. ``I don't think
the public will let the Governor get away with his partisan
vetoes,'' Silver, a Manhattan Democrat, said. He added that
Pataki's ``right wing'' agenda was ``out of step with New
Yorkers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
