<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-RUTGERS-TENN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LADY VOLS SOLVE THE ZONE BEFORE RECORD GARDEN CROWD
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It would have been an outstanding accomplishment, one
that might have given Rutgers its biggest victory of the season and
sent tremors through women's college basketball. It would have made
the Scarlet Knights defensive legends and had every team from Rhode
Island to California studying videotape of their game against
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   But late in the first half of Sunday's historic contest at
Madison Square Garden, Semeka Randall declared that one of
Tennessee's three preseason all-Americans would solve Rutgers' zone
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up the slack for her sluggish star teammates, Chamique
Holdsclaw and Tamika Catchings, Randall scored 8 points in less
than four minutes to lift the Lady Vols from a deficit to a
halftime lead that they would never surrender. Then, as Holdsclaw
and Catchings continued to struggle after intermission, the least
celebrated of the ``Three Meeks'' pierced the hearts of the Scarlet
Knights with hustle and midrange jump shots to score a game-high 18
points and lead second-ranked Tennessee (11-1) to a 68-54 victory.
</P>
<P>
   While Rutgers did an excellent job of controlling Holdsclaw and
Catchings, it was too much to ask of the Scarlet Knights to stop
all three of Coach Pat Summitt's headliners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all great players,'' said Rutgers Coach Vivian
Stringer, who employed the hectic matchup zone made famous by
Temple Coach John Chaney. ``The zone did what we needed it to do,
but it doesn't cover everything.''
</P>
<P>
   To the chagrin of the record crowd, the zone did slow down
Holdsclaw, the native of Astoria, Queens, who was making only her
second collegiate appearance in New York. To allow the three-time
all-American to play before a hometown audience, Summitt and
Stringer had worked together to bring women's college basketball
back to Madison Square Garden for the first time since December
1981.
</P>
<P>
   And with the game billed as ``Holdsclaw's Homecoming,'' 15,735
fans, the largest crowd to watch a women's college game at the
Garden, showed up to cheer on both Holdsclaw and No. 15 Rutgers
(10-3).
</P>
<P>
   But the 6-foot-2-inch do-everything senior had her worst game of
the season, failing to score in double figures for the first time
this season and for only the seventh time in her distinguished
career. Missing 7 of 9 field-goal attempts, Holdsclaw scored 8
points, only 3 above her career low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, you're going to be disappointed when you come home,
but I know what I can do,'' said Holdsclaw, who entered the game
averaging 21 points. ``I don't think I was nervous. I just never
really got into the flow of the game. But I know this won't happen
again because I want to be the best, and in order to be the best, I
have to wake up and respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Stringer knows Holdsclaw will not have many games like Sunday's.
``She is the finest basketball player in America,'' Stringer said.
``Period. The End. She is all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Catchings, the daughter of the former National Basketball
Association player Harvey Catchings, is not far behind Holdsclaw.
In fact, the 6-1 sophomore broke most of Holdsclaw's freshman
records in earning all-American status last year. But against the
Scarlet Knights' energetic defense, she managed only 11 points, 5
below her season average, on 2-of-11 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Randall, a 5-10 sophomore who averages 12 points, was not the
only Lady Vol to fill the gap. Center Michelle Snow, a 6-5
freshman, started in place of the injured Teresa Geter and
displayed a soft shooting touch in recording 16 points and 9
rebounds. And the senior point guard Kellie Jolly (10 points) hit
four jump shots of 15 feet or more.
</P>
<P>
   While Stringer played down talk of a moral victory, she had to
take some consolation in the improvement her team showed against
Tennessee. In last year's National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament, the Lady Vols bounced Rutgers from the final 16 in a
92-60 rout.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game was actually closer than the final score
indicated. Though Rutgers trailed by 16 points, it was never a
rout. And the Scarlet Knights were quite impressive early in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting the taller Vols to one shot offensively and feeding the
sophomore center Tammy Sutton-Brown for 9 of her team-high 12
points, Rutgers grabbed leads of 17-13 and 22-19. But Snow buried a
16-footer, Catchings followed with a short jumper and Randall awoke
to score 8 of her 9 first-half points as Tennessee ended the half
with a 15-6 run.
</P>
<P>
   Her club ahead by 34-28 at the start of the second half, the
athletic Randall made two long jump shots, a layup and two free
throws to help push the lead to 51-36 midway through the half.
Rutgers pulled no closer than 9 points the rest of the way, as
seven missed layups and a couple of unforced errors kept it from
challenging.
</P>
<P>
   With two of Tennessee's three stars playing poorly, Stringer
knew her club missed an opportunity. ``We got layups, we got
bunnies,'' she said. ``If we hit them, it would have been a totally
different story.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
