<HEADER>
A6344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-NYT     01-03 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BCS IS ALREADY A WINNER BEFORE THE NATIONAL TITLE GAME
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ In the summer, the Bowl Championship Series
organizers took their charts around the country and explained how
the voting polls and computer rankings would conspire to make the
Fiesta Bowl a true national championship game. When Tennessee and
Florida State take the field here Monday night, the public opinion
campaigns will be over and all that interfacing will have indeed
produced an undisputed title game.
</P>
<P>
   The only numbers that will matter are the old-fashioned kind.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles (11-1) will line up the nation's No. 1 defense.
The Volunteers (12-0) will try to bludgeon that unit with the
nation's 17th-ranked rushing offense. Florida State will try to get
the ball to a flashy wide receiver, all-American Peter Warrick, who
averages 20.2 yards a reception and 102 yards a game. Tennessee
will try to sling it to the aptly named Peerless Price, who
averaged 15.1 yards a catch and found the end zone 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   On one sideline will be Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer, whose
.857 winning percentage is the best among active coaches. He is 48
years old, a meticulous, low-key man _ one best summed up by Price
as ``the only coach I've ever seen tuck in his sweat suit'' _
trying to capture his first championship and cap a dream season
that has already earned him national coach of the year honors and a
new contract worth $1 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   On the other sideline is Florida State's Bobby Bowden, who, at
69, has won 12 of his last 13 bowl games, won more games than any
other coach in the 1990s, including a national title in '93, and is
revered for offering dadgummits and laughs in numbers that dwarf
his high-scoring offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never accomplished so much sitting on the couch,'' he
quipped of the final day of the season, when his team leaped from
No. 4 to the Fiesta Bowl when previously unbeaten Kansas State and
UCLA were upset.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing over the past six days of the bowl season occurred to
diminish Monday night's Fiesta Bowl as The Game and the BCS as a
viable measuring stick, despite what Ohio State coach John Cooper
and the Buckeye faithful want you to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Big Ten went 5-0 in the bowl season, but Ohio State's
24-14 victory over Texas A&AMP;M in the Sugar Bowl does not seem to be
convincing enough to earn the No. 1 ranking in the Associated Press
news media poll even if Florida State wins an ugly game over
undefeated Tennessee. The coaches' poll has declared that its No. 1
will go to the Fiesta winner.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the BCS ranking looks prescient when you consider what
happened to three teams that were in the race for the title game
until the final week.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State appeared to be rightfully locked out of the big
games when that untested bunch rolled over against unranked Purdue,
37-34, in the Alamo Bowl to finish with consecutive defeats. UCLA
also found back-to-back heartbreak at the hands of its lax defense,
beaten by Wisconsin, 38-31, in the Rose Bowl. And Florida, one of
eight bowl teams Florida State beat this season, flattered both
teams by pasting Syracuse, 31-10, in the Orange Bowl. The Gators'
only losses in a 10-2 season were to the Seminoles and Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it worked for what it was set up to do,'' Bowden
said of the BCS as he entered the Fiesta Bowl with a team that had
won 10 consecutive games after a September loss to North Carolina
State. ``Despite all the criticism, they did a great job of putting
that thing together.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Cooper, whose Ohio State team finished 11-1, Bowden
added: ``Don't blame John for feeling the way he does _ he might
have the best football team in the nation. But if Tennessee wins,
they'll be national champions, and if we win, then we'll be. That's
the way they've drawn it up this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Fullmer: ``All I want to be able to do is say that we won
Monday night. As I've said a number of times, the BCS system worked
itself out just as good as it could be. I don't think anyone's
questioned our invitation.''
</P>
<P>
   At quarterback, Tennessee junior Tee Martin did what Peyton
Manning could not, drive the Volunteers to the championship game,
by winning four games in the fourth quarter. Manning's passing
records are safe, but Martin has gotten better. In his last seven
games, he has thrown for 214 yards an outing, 10 touchdowns and
only two interceptions, and has raised the Vols' average offensive
total 64 yards to 423.7 a game.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback for the Seminoles, the sophomore Marcus Outzen _
dubbed the Rooster by his teammates for his red crewcut _ will be
making only his third college start. Outzen, whom Bowden recruited
as a backup, inherited the starting job when Chris Weinke injured
his neck in the 10th game of the season. Bowden compliments
Outzen's toughness, ``his swagger,'' but says his passes flutter
and wobble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a guy making his third start _ they got one making
his 13th,'' Bowden said of Martin and what he considers an
advantage for the Vols.
</P>
<P>
   But both coaches say the game could come down to the
place-kickers. Florida State will rely on the Lou Groza Award
winner as the nation's best kicking specialist, Sebastian
Janikowski, a former member of the Poland's under-17 national
soccer team. He has made 27 of 32 career field-goal attempts, 42 of
43 extra-point attempts and, at a mammoth 6 feet 2 inches and 255
pounds, booms the ball on kickoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``His kick sounds like a howitzer,'' Tennessee kicker Jeff Hall
said. ``I may just pull a lawn chair up on the 50 and watch him
warm up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall is the Southeastern Conference's career scoring leader with
371 points and connected on 19 of 24 field-goal attempts this
season, including game-winners against Syracuse and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Hall is close to his coach _ he and Fulmer both are from
Winchester, Tenn. _ Janikowski enjoys a certain kinship with
Bowden. Both are candid. Both are funny.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he wanted to kick the game-winner, Janikowski
nodded an arduous no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather we score a touchdown,'' said the player known as
the Polish Powder Keg. ``I know a lot of kickers don't say that.
But we all think it.''
</P>
<P>
   So the national title will be decided on the field Monday night.
John Cooper and poll voters won't be able to upstage the Rooster
and the Polish Powder Keg. The BCS worked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
