<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-GRETZKY-2     01-03 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-GRETZKY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE GOAL GRETZKY DOES NOT HAVE IS A FAREWELL TOUR
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His best moments are still as great as ever, even in
his 20th season, even in the month of his 38th birthday. When Wayne
Gretzky of the Rangers controls the puck behind the net on the
power play, he seems like a master puppeteer, feinting and faking
and making two teams jump and dance like sets of marionettes. These
moments, when the Rangers have the manpower advantage and the
checking is light and the offense is in place, bring out Gretzky's
best talents: his ability to create, to anticipate and to pass to
the open man. These moments bring cheers and murmurs of
appreciation even on the road. These moments produce points, most
of them assists, which keep Gretzky among the top 20 scorers in the
National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Other moments are not as pleasant. When teams are at even
strength, when the tempo is high, when defenders are aggressively
checking him or taking away his passing options, Gretzky sometimes
gets frustrated. You can see it in the way he swings his stick at
the ice shavings and lifts one skate over the other as he shakes
his head on his way to the bench after a long shift. Even on the
road, fans wince when he gets up slowly from a hard hit, with a
grimace on his angular face, because he does not avoid collisions
as well as he once did. On these nights, when he and his
ever-changing cast of linemates get penned up in their defensive
end or trapped up ice, Gretzky might record no goals or assists or
even shots. In these games, he might lead his team only in
turnovers or in complaints to the referee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always worn my heart on my sleeve,'' Gretzky said. ``I
still hate to lose. Obviously, I know the spotlight is on me more
than anyone else.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Obviously, when people ask him how much longer he will play,
Gretzky knows the unspoken implications. ``I'm smart enough now to
realize I'm at a point in my career where it's year to year,'' he
said. ``But I don't sit in the locker room and say: `Oh, I'm done.
This is my last year.' On the other side, I don't sit here and say,
`I'm going to play another two or three years.'''
</P>
<P>
   This is his third season with the Rangers, the fourth team of
his NHL career. The only standard of comparison for Gretzky is
himself _ 5, 10, 15 or 20 years ago. Heading into Monday night's
game with the San Jose Sharks at Madison Square Garden, Gretzky
leads the Rangers in points with 37, on 6 goals and 31 assists. For
his career, he holds the NHL record for goals (891), assists
(1,941) and points (2,832). In the history of the sport, the only
players who rank with his legend are Gordie Howe and Bobby Orr.
Howe may have played too long, retiring at age 52 in 1980. And Orr
didn't play long enough, retiring prematurely at age 30 in 1978
because of a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   What about Gretzky? He has one season left on his contract. It
is an option year in which his salary would drop from $6 million to
$5 million. The option is the Rangers'. Neil Smith, the general
manager, and Mike Barnett, Gretzky's agent, both say they have not
discussed Gretzky's future. Smith said, ``If he keeps going the way
he is going, barring any unforeseen circumstances, we would want to
renew it.'' Smith has said in the past that Gretzky and the Rangers
will mutually agree on the appropriate time for his retirement.
Gretzky has often said that the Rangers will be his last team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any other player, he's had nights when I don't think he's
been happy with his play,'' Smith said. ``I think, generally, his
play has been very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky's statistics would seem to suggest that. But his unique
style of give-and-go passes and reverses against the flow is not an
easy fit on this roster. His linemates this season have included
Esa Tikkanen, Aleksei Kovalev, John MacLean, Kevin Stevens, Petr
Nedved, Mike Knuble, Niklas Sundstrom, Todd Harvey and Adam Graves.
Smith has been under pressure to trade for a sharpshooter who can
complete the scoring chances that Gretzky creates. But they have
players who can score goals; Graves has 16 and MacLean has 12. Is
everyone out of step but Gretzky, or is it difficult, as Luc
Robitaille once said, for players to blend their skills with his?
</P>
<P>
   ``When he went to St. Louis, people said, `Brett Hull and Wayne
Gretzky together will be unbelievable,''' Smith said. ``And it
didn't work. And I don't know why it didn't work.'' Now, Smith
feels pressure to obtain Pavel Bure, the Vancouver superstar, who
has demanded a trade. Bure, some say, would be as good on Gretzky's
wing as Jari Kurri was back when they played with Mark Messier for
the Edmonton Oilers' championship dynasty of the 1980's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we find that Jari Kurri-type guy?'' Smith said. ``It
might not be the obvious, Pavel Bure.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of Gretzky's most difficult nights this season have been in
losses in Buffalo. After the first one, a member of the Sabres'
checking line, Vaclav Varada, said it was easy to stop Gretzky
because he just skated around the neutral zone. This angered
several Rangers, who collided hard with Varada in their next
meeting. At the end of the second game, when Varada scored an
empty-net goal, Harvey chased Varada and punched him in the back of
the head, earning a one-game suspension. Given a chance to amend
his remarks about Gretzky, Varada repeated them. ``It's the
truth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Varada's comments, Gretzky said that ``everyone
is entitled to their own opinion.'' Gretzky said such words would
have hurt more coming from Sabres stars like Mike Peca or Dominik
Hasek. As for Varada, Gretzky said, ``Probably the only thing him
and I have in common is we'll both be playing golf in about three
years.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates are protective of Gretzky, even when acknowledging
his limitations. Mike Richter, the Ranger goalie, said Varada's
observations offended the Rangers because they were ``inaccurate
and not an easy thing to hear.'' As for Gretzky's occasional
frustration over his level of play, Richter said it might be a
natural thing that happens to veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maturing throughout your career is insidious,'' Richter said.
``Quietly, it starts to put limitations on what you are able to do.
Wayne sees the game probably better now than ever. But it's a
cruelty of sports that when you are mentally at your peak, you
start to deteriorate physically. He has so much willpower that he
overcomes whatever level of deterioration his body has had. And so
he masks it very well. He knows what he needs to do. He can still
be an incredibly effective player.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York phase of Gretzky's career has seen limited success
for the team. In his first season, the Rangers surprised the league
by reaching the third round of the playoffs. In his second,
1997-98, they failed to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky raves about the quality of Manhattan life for his wife,
Janet, and their three children. The two boys play in a youth
hockey league at Chelsea Piers. They wear their first names on
their jerseys, not their last, because ``Gretzky'' would bring
added pressure. Their numbers are 14 and 5, not the 99 that Dad
made famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fit in with the other parents,'' Gretzky said. ``I bring
doughnuts, sit there and drink coffee. I don't tell the coach, `We
should do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nor does he advise the Ranger coach, John Muckler, or Smith. In
Los Angeles, from 1988 to 1996, it was often suggested that Gretzky
decided which teammates, or even coaches, would come and go. ``I
was starting to get accused of things that were not true,'' Gretzky
said. Smith said he assumed from afar that this was happening in
Los Angeles, but that Gretzky has no input regarding the Ranger
roster. But it is also true that Muckler was hired in part because
he coached Gretzky in Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I said that I didn't take Wayne into consideration when I
hired John, I'd be lying,'' Smith said. ``I definitely did. I was
thinking about Wayne.'' Muckler's assistants, Craig MacTavish and
Charlie Huddy, were friends of Gretzky's when they all played for
the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett, the agent, said Gretzky calls him every day, usually
after games, to talk about how he has played. Smith said Gretzky is
a ``hockey yenta'' who likes to keep informed of rumors and
scuttlebutt through his extensive grapevine, but that Gretzky
``avoids confrontation'' whenever possible. Gretzky denies holding
any bitterness toward Messier, who left the Rangers as a free agent
after they reunited here for only one season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here and moved my family here to play with Mark and
play with the Rangers,'' Gretzky said. ``I understand this business
probably better than any other athlete in this room. I was traded
in '88, from Edmonton to Los Angeles, after winning four cups and I
don't know how many MVPs. I wish Mark nothing but good wishes.
Obviously, I wish he'd stayed here.''
</P>
<P>
   They come around, they go around, and Gretzky is a believer in
karma. ``If you are a good person, and you are good to people, good
things will happen,'' Gretzky said. ``If you treat people poorly
and you are not a good person, eventually it will bite you in the
rear end.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this explains the generosity of Gretzky, who is aware of
many special moments as his era nears an end. When the Rangers
played their final game in Maple Leaf Gardens in Toronto last
month, Gretzky autographed several sticks he used and gave them to
special people. One was to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine says, `To Neil, with thanks, Wayne Gretzky,''' Smith
said. ``And he put the date on it and I'll keep it forever. He knew
it was a historic event. He was humble about it, but yet, at the
same time, he knew its significance. It's an interesting
combination. Most people are either egotistical or so humble they
wouldn't dare do that. But Wayne is very unique.'' Gretzky has
saved every puck from every goal he has scored as a Ranger,
although he admits he does not yet know what he will do with them.
</P>
<P>
   There are many people who want Gretzky to announce his
retirement at the beginning of his final season, so that he can
have a farewell tour the way Kareem Abdul-Jabbar did when he left
the National Basketball Association. There would be pre-game
ceremonies, presentation of gifts, long standing ovations for the
man who defined his era and is still the only hockey player some
Americans have ever heard of. Such a tour, Gretzky said, is out of
the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would be fair to these guys to have a
farewell tour,'' he said. ``Every game would be set back and the
focus would not be on what is most important: the game. The fans
have been great to me. I like to think I've worked hard and did the
best I could to help sell our sport. The game owes Wayne Gretzky
nothing. The fans owe Wayne Gretzky nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean that to sound ignorant or not appreciative.
Everything I have I owe to the NHL. When it's done, it's done.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6354 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATS-JAGUARS-HNS &LR;      01-03 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATS-JAGUARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ In the war of attrition that is the NFL
season, the postseason is sometimes left with the tattered remnants
of what had been good football teams.
</P>
<P>
   So it was at Alltel Stadium on Sunday afternoon, when the
Jacksonville Jaguars, with 13 players on injured reserve and
quarterback Mark Brunell limping on a sprained ankle, beat the even
more decimated New England Patriots 25-10.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were missing their quarterback, Drew Bledsoe; their
top receiver, Terry Glenn; and their two best linebackers, Ted
Washington and Todd Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Jaguars _ except for rookie Fred Taylor (162 yards
on 33 rushing attempts) _ were especially imposing. Brunell hadn't
played in a month, and the inactivity showed. A scrambler by
nature, he was confined mostly to the pocket, and his passes often
sailed high.
</P>
<P>
   ``My footwork wasn't where it needed to be,'' Brunell said. ``I
twisted my ankle before halftime, and I wasn't feeling that good in
the third quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tom Coughlin considered pulling him when the Patriots made
the score 12-7 with 4:27 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I encouraged him to keep me in there,'' Brunell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me a solid argument,'' Coughlin said, ``so I let him
stay in.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a good decision, because early in the fourth quarter,
Brunell broke the game open with a 37-yard touchdown pass to Jimmy
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   As the Jaguars left the huddle, Smith intended to run an 18-yard
comeback route. But when Brunell surveyed the defensive alignment,
he saw All-Pro cornerback Ty Law just a yard in front of his
favorite receiver.
</P>
<P>
   So Brunell gave Smith a hand signal to go deep. Smith outran Law
and caught the ball diving and stretching in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a boost,'' Brunell said. ``Things were going their
way, and it changed the momentum for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith caught 78 passes this season for 1,182 yards, but he
didn't expect many opportunities working against Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shut down Keyshawn Johnson (of the New York Jets) and all
the big-time receivers,'' Smith said. ``I caught a lot of short
routes today, which I hate doing. I like to let Keenan (McCardell)
catch those. I'm the long receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, the rusty Brunell was having trouble hitting long or
short. He completed only 14 of 34 passes for 161 yards. Patriots QB
Scott Zolak also was erratic, completing 21 of 44 for 190.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in this game was Taylor's running.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard rumbles out of New England that we were a finesse
team,'' Taylor said. ``We wanted to show them who was smash-mouth
and who was soft. Early in the week, our offensive line made a
dedication to be more physical.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, meanwhile, were shut down on the ground. Robert
Edwards, who gained 1,115 yards during the regular season, was held
to 28 yards on 17 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed they knew every time we were going to run the ball
and had the right blitz called,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Even without starting center Quentin Neujahr, the Jacksonville
line consistently opened holes for Taylor. Backup center John Wade
sealed off the middle of the Patriots' line as Taylor sprang the
longest play of the day, a 46-yard scamper in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the biggest hole I had all season,'' Taylor said. ``I
should have scored a touchdown, but No. 21 (cornerback Steve
Israel) ran me down.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Jaguars had to settle for the second of four field goals
by Mike Hollis.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Taylor's breakaway and Smith's TD catch, there wasn't
much excitement in this game. Perhaps that's what the local
citizenry anticipated, judging from the gaps of empty blue seating
in the middle of the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the game lacked, the Patriots at least made a contest
of it in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jaguars were dropping in zone coverage a lot,'' Edwards
said, ``and it opened up a lot of underneath routes, and Zolak took
advantage of opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Zolak: ``We had guys down, and we had to rally around other
guys, including myself stepping in for Drew. We were undermanned at
times, but we overcame a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith echoed a similar theme _ what might be possible with
better health.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had all our guys back, we'd be tough to stop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jaguars will have to go on the road to play the Jets
next Sunday with what they have. Unless Brunell sharpens up quickly
and Taylor runs as well as he did on his home field, they may not
have enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
