<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6366 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GREENBAY-49ERS-CO     01-03 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GREENBAY-49ERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    49ers snatch victory from Packers in wildcard thriller
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Eight seconds from yet another cheesy ending to
their season, the San Francisco 49ers' recent past haunted them and
the future appeared satisfied to simply ignore a once-proud
franchise perilously close to sliding into the nearby bay.
</P>
<P>
   One play removed from the ignominy of a first-round playoff exit
_ and, worse, a sixth consecutive defeat to the Green Bay Packers _
third-year wide receiver Terrell Owens decided it was time for
somebody to consider the present.
</P>
<P>
   Who better, Owens figured, than him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Time to redeem myself and time to redeem this team,'' Owens
quietly recalled in the locker room when asked to conjure up what
went through his mind seconds before his 25-yard touchdown catch
lifted the 49ers to an improbable 30-27 victory which sends them to
the Georgia Dome on Saturday for a rubber-match with the Atlanta
Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   The NFC West foes split their regular-season series in '98, each
team winning at home, but the 49ers still are clearly chafed by
their 31-19 loss at Atlanta on Nov. 15. In the wake of that defeat,
San Francisco strong safety Tim McDonald vowed his team would fight
hard to earn another shot at the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   While they will wait until this morning to fret over how a shaky
defensive front seven might even attempt to contain Falcons running
back Jamal Anderson, the 49ers will relish a fantastic finish that
at least allows them the opportunity to try.
</P>
<P>
   For that, they can thank Owens, who pulled in Steve Young's best
pass of an otherwise shabby performance by the quarterback with
only three seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The reception reversed a difficult day as well for Owens, who
unofficially had three drops in the game, including a third-quarter
bobble in the end zone when he had beaten Packers cornerback Craig
Newsome by four yards.
</P>
<P>
   It also made this a game for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts had speculated the rare first-round matchup of
teams more accustomed to battling for the conference title might
result in the finest wildcard contest of all-time. It may not have
reached that level, but the end result was that the Packers and
49ers provided great drama and pathos.
</P>
<P>
   ''When they scored,'' said Packers coach Mike Holmgren, who
politely refused to discuss his possible departure from Green Bay,
''you saw every emotion possible on that field. Their guys cried
tears of joy and our guys tears of despair. You don't just lose a
game like this. It goes a lot deeper than that. It becomes one of
the worst things that ever happened to you. This is a bitter,
bitter pill, believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   Four minutes before his game-winning catch, Owens let a
third-down pass slip through his fingers. The drop provided life
for the Packers and Brett Favre took advantage by moving his team
89 yards in nine plays. Favre's 15-yard pass to wide receiver
Antonio Freeman, who beat Niners corner Darnell Walker with a nifty
spin move, catapulted the Packers into a 27-23 lead with 1:56
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ''At that point, I think a lot of guys felt like, 'Here we go
again,' '' said tailback Garrison Hearst, who offset a sagging
passing game with 128 yards on the ground. ''But this is a game
about character and we proved we have it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a corner of the San Francisco locker room, hidden beneath a
pile of towels and tape and rolled-up sweat socks, was a stuffed
monkey. One of the 49ers defenders, and no one was volunteering
names, had ripped the stuffing out of the fake simian. The trite
yet true symbolism was apparent. After losing three straight to
Green Bay and having three seasons end in playoff defeats to the
Packers, the monkey was off the backs of the 49ers at last.
</P>
<P>
   ''Next stop,'' said Walker, the former Falcons corner who still
makes his home in the Suwanee, Ga. area, ''is Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-99 2123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
