</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A GARDEN EMBRACE FOR HOLDSCLAW
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Waiting outside the locker room Sunday in the arena
in which Chamique Holdsclaw dreams of playing professionally was
Dawn Staley, a pro point guard of renown who was, fittingly enough,
hoping to get paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got my money, girl?'' Staley asked Holdsclaw, with her hand
extended, palm turned up. ``I take checks.''
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw was not yet ready to ante up for the 3-point shooting
contest she lost, according to Staley, sometime last year. Instead,
she gave Staley a hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always cracking on my game,'' Holdsclaw said after
giving Staley more ammunition, shooting 2 for 9 as Tennessee
handled Rutgers, 68-54, in Holdsclaw's first appearance at Madison
Square Garden. ``She's been e-mailing me all season, saying, `Shoot
the 3!' So I was coming down court once and I heard her yelling,
`Shoot the 3!'''
</P>
<P>
   Staley said, ``No, I was yelling, `Don't shoot the 3.'''
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw rolled her eyes and said, ``See what I'm saying?''
</P>
<P>
   Amidst a crowd of 15,735, a Garden record for a women's college
game, were Holdsclaw's one-time teammates and coaches at Christ the
King High School in Queens, her relatives, and friends, a group to
which Staley apparently still belonged. Holdsclaw said she could
take the barbed critiques, as much as she could live with one of
the worst offensive games of her four-year college career. Anyway,
she had nine rebounds, played spirited defense, her team won, and
the comedian Rosie O'Donnell was in the house. The day remained
special for a young woman from the playgrounds of Astoria, who had
been given this homecoming gift, a thank you for all she had done
for the program, by her coach, Pat Summitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a player impact our team as much as Chamique,
and that's saying a lot because we've had more all-Americas and
Olympians than anyone in the history of the sport,'' Summitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Three seasons down, three national championship banners up in
Knoxville, Tenn. Despite one defeat going into next weekend's
showdown at top-rated Connecticut, Tennessee remains the favorite
for the Final Four in San Jose, Calif., next spring. If everything
goes according to the master plan, Holdsclaw will present a
bachelor's degree to her grandmother, as promised, and be back at
the Garden in a Liberty uniform by summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nowhere else I can say I'd like to go now,'' Holdsclaw
said.
</P>
<P>
   She meant that there is no more rival league to the Women's
National Basketball Association, which is good news for the Garden,
bad news for her banker. With the folding of the American
Basketball League last month went three years worth of
leverage-building by the most telegenic collegian, No. 23 with
braids, in the history of the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   The gurus who run the WNBA will surely let Holdsclaw play in New
York because it makes dollars and sense for them. But she will be
joining David Stern's women's annex along with all those talented,
hardened refugees of the ABL. She will not get as much as she would
have last year, in a competitive market, before the ABL
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WNBA has full control over women's pro basketball now,''
said Staley, who saved herself the trouble of being put out of work
by recently quitting the ABL for the WNBA. ``You've got overseas,
but if you want to play here, you're at their mercy. That's the way
it's going to be, even with a union.''
</P>
<P>
   The same union, by the way, Stern and company have been so
generous with for the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw could have avoided the coming bear market by skipping
her senior season, and by now would have already pocketed three or
four hundred thousand, had a summer of pro ball under her belt. At
the Final Four last year, she said she didn't see the advantages of
turning pro. Sometimes, it takes a person older and wiser to point
them out. Sometimes, as Dean Smith did for Michael Jordan years ago
at North Carolina, it takes the coach to tell the player he or she
should go.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was $20 million, I could see it,'' Staley said. ``But
for three or even four hundred thousand? You're better off getting
your degree.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a debatable point, at worst. Had Holdsclaw played in the
WNBA last summer, she could have been back in Knoxville, without
missing a class. She and Summitt obviously made other plans, hoping
to write a fourth championship chapter, to go with the
autobiographies the coach authored after each of the last two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Then it will time to turn pro, where, Staley said, Holdsclaw
might have a few more days like Sunday, when she lost the ball in
traffic and clanked jumpers off the side of the glass. Good as she
is, there are levels of this sport, just as there are for men.
``She'll probably be inconsistent at first,'' Staley said, ``but in
a year or two, she'll be a franchise player. She's over six feet,
she can handle the ball, she understands the team game and she can
shoot, except when I'm around.''
</P>
<P>
   With Staley watching, Holdsclaw scored 8 points. ``I know I can
get 30 the next night,'' she said, softly, almost apologetically.
``The sky's the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   For points. Not pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
