<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-49ERS-PACKERS-NYT     01-03 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-PACKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ER OWENS MAKES A CATCH THAT ELIMINATES THE PACKERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There were two Green Bay Packers behind him and
two more in front of him, and by the time the pass play was over
there were two more around him, all falling into a pile smack in
the middle of the Green Bay end zone. That made six, more than half
of the Packers on the field, on the heels of Terrell Owens when the
clock struck three seconds. When time in 3-Com Park nearly stood
still.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers beat the Packers, 30-27, here Sunday afternoon in a
National Football Conference playoff game that will stand forever
as one of the most memorable not only in 49ers' history but also in
National Football League history.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ball is thrown down the middle like that in that
situation, you never think it is going to be caught,'' said Green
Bay Coach Mike Holmgren. ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Young looked left,'' said Packers free safety Darren
Sharper, who was standing in the end zone in front of Owens on the
play and who was the first to collide with Owens. ``Then Steve
Young came back underneath with the pass to Terrell Owens. Owens
went up and made a play. We just didn't jump. We didn't go for the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Packers end Reggie White was desperately trying to sack Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't see it,'' White said. ``I just heard it. I heard
the roar.''
</P>
<P>
   And he knew what had happened. Just like all of the Packers did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a blur,'' said Packers receiver Antonio Freeman, in
shock on the Packers sideline. ``Stuff like that doesn't happen.
It's going to be tough to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't seem real. Owens jumped highest. Did you see it?
Certainly, you heard it. The roar. The blur. Time stood still. And
then this stadium, these 65,506 fans, this San Francisco 49ers team
that looked drilled one more time by Green Bay, got up and wiped
the dust away and rewrote history.
</P>
<P>
   And they won it on Young-to-Owens, a 25-yard touchdown pass,
with 3 seconds left. Green Bay, only 1:53 earlier, had grabbed the
lead on a Brett Favre to Antonio Freeman touchdown pass of 15 yards
that had given Green Bay a 27-23 lead. It looked like Green Bay had
made it six consecutive victories over San Francisco, four straight
in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And then Young-to-Owens.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers have had so many big, winning plays, from Joe Montana
to Dwight Clark for The Catch and from Montana to John Taylor to
win a Super Bowl. So many more, but for this group, this was their
own thing, their own destiny, a chance to shine and reach for
something that few in this crew had ever experienced. They move on
now with a 13-4 record to play the Atlanta Falcons on Saturday.
Green Bay's season ended with an 11-6 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never made a bigger catch in my life, never played in a
bigger game and never been more thankful to the Lord that I got a
chance to redeem myself to my teammates,'' Owens said of his
winning score, the most unlikely of plays that actually began with
8 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you can call it The Redemption,'' Owens, 25, said,
smiling, flashing braces, a 6-foot-3-inch 217-pound receiver from
Tennessee Chattanooga who is in only his third pro season.
</P>
<P>
   Owens had dropped four passes Sunday and had fumbled once.
Through most of the game he looked as if he were in a mental funk.
Owens said the Packers had begun taunting him in the third quarter.
He said they chided, ``You haven't made a play all day! Hero!
Zero!'' It hurt, he said. So, when he made the winning catch, he
was in tears. Tears of joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thankful,'' Owens said of his emotion. ``I have
been thinking about beating Green Bay since last season, for all of
this season. I have wanted us to get the chance to do something
about the way they have handled us. I was open over the middle on
the play before. Steve this time just came right back to me. I saw
it all of the way. And once I was there, I wasn't going to let them
knock it away or knock it loose.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a game that Green Bay led, 17-10, at halftime. Young
threw a 1-yard touchdown in the first half, Favre threw a 2-yard
score and Packers back Dorsey Levens ran for a 2-yard score. But
San Francisco won the third quarter by 10-0 to take a 20-17 lead,
and that set up the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams hit field goals to start the quarter, making it
23-20. Then came Freeman's catch. Then came Owens' catch.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco started its drive at its 24 with 1:56 left.
Young's 17-yard pass to J.J. Stokes began the drive. Then another
pass to Stokes for 9 more. Short stuff by Young kept moving the
ball, chipping away. Green Bay adjusted by doubling its defense on
the edges, trying to keep the sideline defensed and forcing the
49ers to try something risky over the middle. Young passed to Rice
for a 6-yard gain to the Green Bay 41. Replays showed Rice fumbled
when hit but it was not called. The drive would go on. History
would move forward, subtly changing. Young with :08 left tried a
pass toward Stokes again and it hit Packers cornerback Craig
Newsome squarely in the hands. Newsome bobbled it. Dropped it.
</P>
<P>
   History kept moving forward. Subtly changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't lose a game like this; it's the worst thing
that can happen,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   But 49ers cornerback Marquez Pope countered: ``To go through
something like this, to beat that team this way after what they
have done to us, it is very special. To win this game and it being
a playoff game and win it like this? We have much more football to
play, but this will last a lifetime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
