<HEADLINE>
BRUINS LIVE UP TO THE HYPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The accolades began before they set foot on
campus. Longtime UCLA watchers called it the best freshman class
since Wooden. Recruiting gurus tagged it the nation's No.1 class.
</P>
<P>
   But it was empty praise until Saturday night, when the Bruins'
JaRon Rush-less freshmen combined for 36 points and 16 rebounds in
an 82-75 victory over No.6 Arizona. In particular, center Dan
Gadzuric (10 points, three blocks) and forward Jerome Moiso (21
points) had impressive Pac-10 debuts.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, the rookies earned their highest compliment
to date from Wildcats coach Lute Olson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an unbelievably talented basketball team,'' Olson said.
``I've been (in the league) 16 years, and I've never seen a better
freshman class than that one. I've never seen anybody even close to
the ability of the two big freshmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Minute men: A depleted roster Saturday whittled UCLA's 10-man
rotation to seven and forced several Bruins to play more minutes
than normal.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were without Rush, the suspended forward who's
expected back tonight against Arizona State, and forward Matt
Barnes was limited to six minutes because of an ankle injury
suffered during Christmas break.
</P>
<P>
   Baron Davis played 34 minutes, six more than his previous high.
Moiso hit the 30-minute barrier for only the second time this
season, and guard Ryan Bailey topped 20 minutes for the first time
in a month.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Steve Lavin said fatigue was a factor in the final
minutes, when Arizona chopped a 20-point deficit to five, and he
canceled Sunday's practice to give the Bruins a chance to recover
for Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   Taking care of Terry: UCLA geared its defense to contain Arizona
point guard Jason Terry, perhaps the best guard in the Pac-10 and a
potential first-round draft pick. The Bruins used a two-pronged
strategy: a zone press that force Terry to distribute the ball in
the backcourt, then a tight man-to-man that denied him return
passes in the halfcourt offense.
</P>
<P>
   It worked well. Terry made two field goals in the first half and
scored just 10 points in the first 35 minutes, as UCLA built its
20-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great playmaker, so we tried to get the ball out of his
hands,'' guard Earl Watson said. ``We watched the video, and teams
backed down and let him get the ball near halfcourt. We just denied
him. We didn't back down.''
</P>
<P>
   Erasing the memory: Ten months ago, Davis cried in his locker
after missing a last-second jumper against Arizona in the season
finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about that before (Saturday's) game, how I
missed the shot to send it to overtime,'' he said. ``I have so much
more confidence and poise this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is steadily regaining strength in his surgically
reconstructed left knee, improving his quickness and jumping
ability by the week. Saturday, he had 20 points and six assists and
was closer to his former self than at any point this season.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA vs. ARIZONA ST.
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:30 p.m., Pauley Pavilion &QL; 
TV/Radio: Fox Sports West 2; XTRA-AM (1150) &QL; 
UCLA (9-2, 1-0) update: The Bruins have won seven straight and must
avoid an emotional letdown after a spirited victory over Arizona.
Freshman forward JaRon Rush will play _ but not start _ after
serving a one-game suspension for missing two practices and a game
because of homesickness. Forward Matt Barnes (ankle) is expected to
play limited minutes. Bruins were outrebounded 48-31 by Arizona and
must get more production from center Dan Gadzuric, who had two
rebounds in 19 minutes. &QL; 
Arizona State (8-5, 0-1) update: Sun Devils haven't won in Pauley
Pavilion since 1987 and have lost 19 straight overall to UCLA. They
have three of the league's best players in guard Eddie House and
forwards Bobby Lazor and Mike Batiste. They combine for almost 16
points per game. Under new coach Rob Evans, ASU plays with more
discipline than in past years, which could cause UCLA problems. &QL; 
_Jon Wilner
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
