<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG TROJANS FEEL PAC-10 INTENSITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Several of USC's players got their introduction to
the Pacific-10 Conference during Saturday's victory over Arizona
State, and noticed it was no longer as relaxing as playing American
University or Arkansas State.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a lot more prepared for us than other teams,''
center Brian Scalabrine said. ``The guys are stronger. (Arizona
State forward) Michael Batiste is really strong. I'll get used to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Quincy Wilder also picked up on the increase in the game's
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a different type of game. A lot of defense, not a lot
of transition baskets,'' Wilder said. ``A lot of halfcourt
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in case newcomers like Scalabrine and Wilder didn't
understand that the season changes during Pac-10 play, they got a
little speech from senior guard Elias Ayuso.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only have 20 more games in my college career. This is it for
me and I told the guys this is the big show,'' Ayuso said. ``This
is the biggest show. The nonconference games, you play teams that
are good but not that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Washington: With his career-high 13 points, and penetration,
USC fans got their first chance to see Wilder demonstrate the
ability that earned him the title Mr. Washington three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him for four years. I have been waiting for that,''
said Scalabrine, who played at Highline Community College in Des
Moines, Wash., with Wilder. ``That's typical of Quincy when it
comes down to big games. That's exactly how he is. He's
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Averting an upset: USC (9-1, 1-0) overcame an 18-point deficit
to defeat Arizona State, and more importantly, avoided dropping its
home opener. That would have been devastating considering how
competitive the conference is expected to be this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have hurt because you don't lose at home,'' Ayuso
said. ``That's our goal, not to lose at home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been real tough because Arizona is coming in
(today) and we'd be 0-1,'' Scalabrine added. ``You can't lose home
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Equal time: USC picked up its ninth victory Saturday, which
equals its total for all of last season, when the Trojans were
9-19.
</P>
<P>
   No. 6 ARIZONA AT USC
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 p.m., Sports Arena. &QL; 
TV/Radio: No TV; XTRA-AM (690). &QL; 
Arizona (8-1, 0-1) update: The Wildcats had their first loss of the
season Saturday against UCLA, and will be trying to avoid opening
conference play by getting swept. Senior guard Jason Terry is
averaging 20.2 points while center A.J. Bramlett is averaging 15
points and 11 rebounds. The Wildcats are young, starting two
freshmen _ forward Michael Wright and guard Richard Jefferson _
along with sophomore forward Justin Wessel. &QL; 
USC (9-1, 1-0) update: After surviving a scare against Arizona
State, when they trailed by as many as 18 points, the Trojans get a
much tougher test today. A key to the game could be point guard
Quincy Wilder's defense on Arizona's Jason Terry. Wilder helped
shut down Arizona State's Eddie House with his defense Saturday.
Brian Scalabrine, who scored 25 points against Arizona State, is
averaging 23 points in his past three games. &QL; 
_ Scott Wolf &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
