<SLUG> BC-FLATOW-TERRORISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIL LAWSUIT AS A TOOL AGAINST TERRORISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ORANGE, N.J. _ Amid the staggering shock and numbing grief
after his daughter Alisa, 20, was killed in April 1995 in a
terrorist bombing while studying in Israel, Stephen Flatow fell
back on his instincts as a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   He was determined to make the culprits pay, even if they were on
the other side of the world. But how?
</P>
<P>
   Khaled al-Khatib, 22, the Palestinian who crashed a van packed
with explosives into a bus Alisa was riding through the Gaza Strip,
died in the blast. Other suspects have since died or are in foreign
prisons and are unlikely to be extradited. As for so many others
whose relatives have been killed by terrorists, justice seemed
elusive.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Flatow, whose expertise is in title insurance, set
off into the murky waters of international law and foreign
relations. In March 1998, in federal court in Washington, he won a
landmark $247.5 million judgment against the government of Iran for
supporting Islamic Holy War, the terrorist group that claimed
responsibility for the blast, which killed Alisa and seven Israeli
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   He has found that trying to force Iran to pay up is an even more
daunting task. Flatow, who is seeking to seize Iran's former
diplomatic properties in the United States, has become a thorn in
the side of State Department officials. His efforts threaten to
complicate further the two countries' relations.
</P>
<P>
   Flatow presses on. ``I am not sure I know what closure is
anymore,'' he said at his home here. ``It's a word that the
psychiatrists and the psychologists talk about. When you have a kid
snatched from you, I don't think it ever really closes.''
</P>
<P>
   Flatow's civil lawsuit against Iran, brought under the 1996
Antiterrorism Act, is part of what legal scholars say is a growing
global interest in finding new ways to achieve international
justice. The ruling against Iran was the first time a foreign state
had been held liable in a U.S. court for a terrorist act committed
outside the United States. But even though Congress passed two
amendments to the law to help strengthen Flatow's case, he has yet
to collect a cent.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth ruled
against Iran, federal lawyers stepped in to block Flatow's legal
team from seizing Iran's former embassy and other diplomatic
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in international law agree that diplomatic property is
sacrosanct. But Flatow and his lawyers are back in court,
determined once again to set a precedent. They have lobbied
President Clinton's national security advisers and accused
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright of siding with Iran over an
American citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Until the death of his oldest daughter, Flatow (pronounced
FLAY-toe) was never one to take up causes. If he is an unlikely
crusader, it is less surprising that Alisa was his inspiration.
Flatow, a round-faced man who wears a yarmulke, was not an
observant Jew until 4-year-old Alisa insisted on attending an
Orthodox Jewish day school.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi who was the principal of the school assured Flatow
that Alisa's attendance would not change the family's lifestyle.
``He lied,'' Flatow said, saying that he and his wife, Rosalyn,
felt compelled to reinforce the lessons Alisa learned at school by
becoming more observant. ``The Israeli experience was part of
her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flatow is not alone in his battle. Sen. Frank Lautenberg,
D-N.J., happened to be in Israel when Alisa was killed and has
taken a personal interest in the case. Lautenberg and Rep. H. James
Saxton of Mount Holly, N.J., sponsored the amendments to the
antiterrorism act.
</P>
<P>
   Other victims of terrorism, including the families of Matthew
Eisenberg and Sarah Duker, U.S. students killed in a Jerusalem
bombing in 1997, are planning similar suits. Flatow's lead lawyer,
Steven Perles, an authority on international law who has sued and
represented several foreign countries, mostly in commercial
litigation, contends that civil lawsuits can be an effective weapon
against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to be hounded for the rest of your life,
there will be no safe haven,'' Perles said. ``That will have a
deterrent effect. If you know you may be tried as a criminal before
an international tribunal, that will have a deterrent effect. And
if a nation knows it is going to be on the receiving end of
enormous civil judgments, that will be a deterrent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian government ignored the Flatow action. After the
ruling, Iran's U.N. mission issued a statement saying Iran ``has
consistently condemned terrorism in all its forms.'' The statement
said the Flatow lawsuit was based on ``legislation that flouts one
of the most fundamental principles of international law.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials express sympathy and support
for Flatow's claim, but he has clearly made life more difficult for
State Department officials charged with conducting policy toward
Iran. The two countries have not had diplomatic relations since the
seizure of hostages from the U.S. Embassy in Tehran in 1979, though
there have been recent hints of a possible warming in ties.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's former embassy and ambassador's residence in Washington,
properties Flatow's lawyers hope to seize, remain in the custody of
the State Department, which has been renting them out and has kept
the proceeds in a bank account. Officials have cited numerous
reasons for keeping the properties from becoming enmeshed in the
Flatow case, including concerns about insuring the sanctity of U.S.
diplomatic properties abroad.
</P>
<P>
   There are also legal complications surrounding the properties
dating back to the 1979 crisis, including efforts by Iran to
reclaim them. ``We are confident that we are protecting U.S.
interests as a whole,''a State Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   Flatow has been traveling the country giving speeches about
Alisa to raise money for Israel and other Jewish causes, including
a scholarship fund established in Alisa's memory that helps send
American students to Israel. Flatow and his wife have four
surviving children, whom they continue to send to Israel. A
daughter, Francine, 19, is studying there now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The terrorist, his idea, his goal, is not only to kill the
people on the bus or in the marketplace,'' Flatow said. ``It's also
to accomplish a political motive by getting Flatow to stay home,
getting someone to leave Israel. It's this randomness that, on the
one hand, makes it so scary, and on the other, it makes you say,
you have to fight back. And you get the tool to fight back by
living your life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
