<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK ACTION CALLED ONLY ALTERNATIVEW TO TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As senators continued bickering over a proposal to
accelerate a presidential impeachment trial, a chief architect of
the plan warned Sunday that the deal is in danger of dissolving if
members fail to embrace it this week.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Joseph I. Lieberman, the Connecticut Democrat who joined
forces with Republican Senator Slade Gorton of Washington to form
the bipartisan proposal, said there was only a ``very small
window'' of time that the plan could prevail. After that,
constitutional procedures would kick in, probably accompanied by
growing party discord.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't have an agreement, I fear we're going to slide
back into the pit of partisanship and rancor we saw in the House,''
Lieberman said. ``I think if we don't have this worked out by the
end of this week ... we're going to revert to what the Senate rules
at this point provide for a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The admonition came as members of the House and Senate trickled
back into town, many trumpeting their views on the trial in the
days before the 106th Congress is called to order on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats presented an almost united front, supporting the
Lieberman-Gorton notion of a pretrial trial in which the Senate
would hear limited evidence, then vote on whether to move ahead to
the full case. It would take 67 votes for a trial to start; if the
vote &UR;  &LR; failed, a move to censure Clinton could begin.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, no trial is expected to start until all members of
the Senate have been sworn in as jurors and Supreme Court Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist is summoned to preside _ not until,
presumably, next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, continued to disagree with not only
Democrats but with one another, arguing Sunday whether it is legal
to consider censure, whether it is constitutional to hold an
abbreviated trial, whether presidential testimony should be
required and what to do about the State of the Union address,
scheduled for Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Phil Gramm, Republican of Texas, said he was in favor of
an ``expedited trial.'' But when it came to the Lieberman-Gorton
proposal, Gramm said he could not envision a constitutionally sound
way of bypassing trial proceedings, saying he did ``not see how you
can begin the trial, and then turn right around and vote without
hearing all the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing it quickly is not as important as doing it right,''
Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Senator Arlen Specter, Republican of
Pennsylvania, also repeated his opposition to the proposal,
describing himself as a ``stickler for the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter added a new wrinkle to the debate: insisting that
Clinton not only stand trial but also testify as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he was determined to hear from Clinton, saying that
``what the trial would offer, which we have not had until the
present time, is the testimony of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be my hope that the president would come forward
voluntarily,'' Specter said on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican, however, disagreed. Arkansas Representative
Asa Hutchinson, a member of the House Judiciary Committee who has
been designated as a trial manager, said of Clinton's proposed
testimony, ``That's his choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be acquitted through all of this,'' Hutchinson said
on ABC's ``This Week with Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson also said he believed a trial could move quickly
without a purposely accelerated schedule such as the one proposed
by Lieberman and Gorton. It ``would not be a protracted endeavor
unless the White House wanted it to be a protracted endeavor,''
Hutchinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Members also touched on the timing of the president's State of
the Union address, which is mandated by the Constitution. Some said
the president should not address the country until a trial is over.
Lieberman said a delay is part of his proposal and that if an
abbreviated trial appeared nearly over on that date, Clinton should
postpone the speech. But if he would have to wait several weeks,
Lieberman said, he would be wise to proceed with it.
</P>
<P>
   Partisan rancor spilled over slightly into the debate among
senators, as members of each party tried to cast their own ideas as
better for the nation at large. Gramm reminded his colleagues
Sunday that an impeachment trial would not be about punishing
Clinton but was instead ``about protecting the republic.'' Later,
Lieberman said avoiding such a trial through his proposal was ``in
the national interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bipartisan proposal is not made to make it easier for
senators,'' Lieberman said. ``If there's not two-thirds prepared to
remove the president, then the net effect of carrying on a trial
... will only hurt the country and the Senate. I surely hope we can
avoid that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
