<SLUG> BC-NY-EXCONGRESSMAN-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SECOND-GUESSING FOR PAXON AS HE LEAVES CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, N.Y. _ Bill Paxon, the exuberant five-term Republican
congressman who many people thought could have been the next
speaker of the House, was maneuvering his Ford Tempo through a cold
rain recently when his cell phone rang. It was an urgent call about
the house. The one in Alexandria, Va., that is, with the torn-up
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   In his clipped Buffalo twang, Paxon instructed his wife, former
Rep. Susan Molinari, to make sure their contractor did not damage
any electric lines. Then he hung up and refocused on the business
of the day: saying goodbye to his district staff and preparing to
start life anew in a strange land called the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   So goes life out of the political lane for a man who has ridden
in it for nearly half of his 44 years. But Paxon has yet to show
any sign that he regrets his decision to retire from Congress last
year, just months before his dream job, speaker of the House,
became available _ twice.
</P>
<P>
   Paxon, who will begin work this week as a senior adviser to the
influential law and lobbying firm of Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP;
Feld, says he is completely at peace with his decision, even though
it will require leaving a profession he describes as narcotic and
an institution he calls ``the world's best fraternity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I convinced my dad to run one last time for judge in the
1970s, and he lost,'' Paxon said, looking rather uncongressional in
cowboy boots, a flannel shirt and khaki pants. ``He always said _
and he was right _ `There is a time to put this stuff aside.' He
had been in office since the '40s. You have to know when to fold
'em in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people felt this was not Paxon's time to quit. Politics _
conservative, Reaganesque politics _ seems to have boiled in his
veins since his childhood in Akron, south of Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Displaying the aw-shucks grin and boyish optimism that would
remain his trademarks for two decades, Paxon was elected to the
Erie County Legislature in 1977 at age 23, fresh out of Canisius
College. He went on to serve in the state Assembly from 1984 until
winning a seat in Congress in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Paxon became an acolyte of Newt Gingrich, the
Georgia Republican, and their fates seemed to rise and fall
together. In 1993, Paxon became chairman of the National Republican
Congressional Committee, helping to engineer the 1994 campaign that
gave the Republicans control of the House for the first time in 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   When Gingrich became speaker the following year, Paxon was part
of his inner circle, becoming the chairman of the Republican
leadership, a position Gingrich created for him. Paxon was viewed
by many Republicans as the rightful heir to the speakership.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, a group of conservative Republicans started, then
aborted, a coup against Gingrich. Though it is widely thought that
Paxon had nothing to do with the revolt, the plotters let it be
known that they were interested in making Paxon the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that some of his closest friends considered naive,
Paxon resigned from the leadership, sacrificing himself to help
reunite the fractious Republican caucus. Yet his standing in the
caucus seemed to grow. Amid simmering dissatisfaction with both
Gingrich and the House majority leader, Dick Armey of Texas,
Republicans again began to float Paxon's name for one of those two
posts in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Paxon openly joined the campaign, saying he was
seriously considering challenging Armey after the 1998 elections.
As majority leader, Paxon would be next in line to replace Gingrich
if the speaker quit Congress to run for president, as Gingrich was
then hinting he would.
</P>
<P>
   (As it turned out, Gingrich resigned shortly after the
Republicans' weak showing in last November's elections. A month
later, his designated replacement, Bob Livingston of Louisiana,
announced he would resign after disclosing that he had had
extramarital affairs.)
</P>
<P>
   But last February, Paxon stunned his staff and Congress by
announcing that he would retire at the end of 1998. He said he
wanted to spend more time with his wife and their daughter, Susan
Ruby, who is 2. The couple are expecting their second daughter
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, skeptics wonder why he threw in the towel. Some say
Paxon knew he could not defeat Armey and could not face a future as
a backbench congressman with no clout. Others say Armey or his
allies threatened him, which Paxon denies.
</P>
<P>
   What made up his mind, he insists, was the realization that he
would not see his daughter grow up if he joined the leadership. In
his methodical way, he had concocted a chart showing the days he
would need to spend fund raising, campaigning for members and doing
district work. The slice labeled ``family'' was alarmingly small.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being speaker of the House or majority leader would have
required me to spend the last eight months traveling instead of at
Chuck E. Cheese or Discovery Zone,'' he said. ``I wouldn't trade
one minute of that time with my child to be the speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   What helped, he said, was watching his wife, who quit an equally
promising political career to work in television, an ill-fated job
that she has since left. ``I looked at Susan, who I always felt had
a much greater political future than I did, that she was able to
just put it down, walk away, start something else, close the
door,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It was family that dominated his conversation at a farewell
lunch for his staff in the 27th District. Over a club sandwich and
fried calamari, Paxon reflected on Susan Ruby's obsession with
Barbie dolls, her bright-eyed wonderment at the family Christmas
tree, her penchant for announcing, ``You have no power here!'' when
she is angry with him.
</P>
<P>
   Though one aide shed a tear as Paxon distributed gifts _ the
same ones he gives every year: White House Christmas ornaments _ he
seemed not the least bit wistful.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is because he does not plan to be out of politics
completely. Paxon said he will continue to help candidates he
likes, including perhaps the Republican nominee for president in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to maintain his close ties to the man who is
expected to become the next speaker, Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
(The two men share a passion for antique cars). Though Paxon says
he will not lobby Congress, his relationship with Hastert and other
senior Republicans could greatly benefit the Fortune 500 companies
he will advise.
</P>
<P>
   Paxon was never much for legislating _ he sponsored only 21
bills over the last six years, fewer than many freshman members do
in a single year. And as he reflected on his Washington career, he
expressed the most pride in his political work, particularly in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the greatest achievement I could ever have is being
involved in us winning that majority,'' he said, pointing to
reductions in the welfare rolls, tax cuts and the balanced budget
that he says resulted from that majority. ``The nuances of
continuing to govern are best left to others, not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxon is not concerned about the impact of his retirement on New
York's congressional delegation, already weakened by the departures
of other senior members. His seat will be filled by his friend
Thomas Reynolds, the former minority leader of the state Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you leave a legislative body, in your mind you might be
leaving a huge hole,'' he said. ``But the reality is, it's a hole
that's like a hand coming out of a bucket of water. It fills
quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
