<SLUG> BC-NYC-HOMELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE COLD, SOME HOMELESS FIND WAYS TO AVOID SHELTERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a frigid night gave way to a dismally wet morning,
homeless people across New York City Sunday continued what for many
will be a winter-long ritual: the search for a warm place to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Some trickled into city shelters, lured from streets where
temperatures dropped to an overnight low of 24 degrees. Others
clung tenaciously to their coats and blankets and vowed to stay out
of the shelters for as long as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, Melvin Ford and Ronald Joyner kept each other
company on the steps of the Broadway-Lafayette Street subway
station, thawing for a while before stepping out again to ask
passers-by for change. Sometimes, they said, they sat inside a
fast-food restaurant a while or hunted for an extra-long church
service
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me, these shelters are trouble, said Ford, 45. ``They
get crazy there and maybe they steal your sneakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the shelters began to fill up over the last week, said
Patrick Markee, an advocate with Coalition for the Homeless, a
private group that monitors city shelters. Last Wednesday, when the
temperatures dropped to 17 degrees, extra cots were set up at two
men's shelters, in Harlem and Washington Heights.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter system for single adults can accommodate about
7,400. So far this winter, Markee said, an average of 7,000 have
stayed there each night.
</P>
<P>
   Most homeless people with children had little choice but to turn
to the city-shelter system. There, dozens of them out on the floor
of a city office, despite a long-standing court order and recent
legislaton to prevent such a situation. On Saturday evening,
according to advocates for the homeless, 55 families _ with 65
children among them _ camped out on the floor and slept on chairs
at the city's Emergency Assistance Unit, the main intake center for
homeless families, on East 151st Street in Mott Haven, the Bronx.
Most of those families have bounced for months between the intake
office and 10-day temporary placements across the city, while their
eligibility for more-permanent shelter is reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   The number of families on Saturday was nearly twice the center's
nightly average of about 30, according to Steven Banks, director of
Legal Aid's Homeless Rights Project.
</P>
<P>
   Such overnight stays are exactly what the City Council sought to
stop with the ordinance it passed over Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's
veto two weeks ago. One of the ordinance's provisions requires the
city's homeless agency to provide families with a bed for the night
_ and a crib, when needed. Families should be transferred to a
nearby shelter overnight and returned in the morning so city
investigators can continue verifying their claims of homelessness,
instead of waiting at the intake office overnight, the bill's chief
sponsor, Stephen DiBrienza, said Sunday,
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing we are trying to avoid is the sleeping on desks,
chairs, the floor,'' the Councilman said Sunday, ``One could argue
they are breaking the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The new law echoes previous court orders that also barred the
city from keeping homeless families in city offices overnight and
imposed substantial fines if they were kept there for more than 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, it wasn't unusual to find families staying at the
Bronx office for several days. Now, city officials say, the wait is
less than 24 hours. The city has already paid $5 million in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, a spokeswoman for the city's Department of Homeless
Services, Susan Wiviott, would not say how many families had stayed
overnight at the Bronx office in recent days, nor how many homeless
families were currently being evaluated. But she said that the
city's shelter system could sufficiently accommodate families in
legitimate need of a home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have plenty of space,'' Ms. Wiviott said.
</P>
<P>
   But while city officials maintain that enforcing eligibility
rules for shelter help keep out those with other housing options,
advocates for the homeless contend that genuinely needy families
are turned away.
</P>
<P>
   The overnight stays at intake center are ``completely a function
of the city's refusal to make use of available shelter beds rather
than any new influx of families,'' said Banks, whose group has
turned to the courts to enforce its earlier ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Edith Nunez, an HIV-positive mother of two, sat bundled up in a
blanket on the floor of the Bronx intake center all night long,
with her husband and her 17-month-old daughter at her side. In the
middle of the night, she said, an ambulance took her younger
daughter, barely 4 months old, to a hospital emergency room to be
treated for a throat infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent the night here, but who the hell can sleep here?'' Ms.
Nunez said Sunday afternoon, awaiting another transfer to yet
another motel. ``It's loud and everyone inside is dying to find a
place to live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
