<HEADER>
A6437 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN     01-03 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PATCH ADAMS' DELIVERS SWEET MEDICINE DESPITE STORMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Universal's medical comedy ``Patch Adams''
continued writing a winning prescription at the nation's box office
but severe snow storms kept many Middle Americans at home during
the New Year's weekend, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patch Adams'' easily topped the Friday-Sunday period with
$19.6 million at 2,752 theaters to give the Universal release $66
million after 10 days. However, the Robin Williams project might
have matched its $25.3 million opening weekend if Midwest weather
had not been so fierce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The box office was decimated,'' said Robert Bucksbaum,
president of the Reel Source service, who noted that grosses on
Saturday -- usually 40 to 50 percent above Friday -- came in under
Friday's performance for the first time in memory. One executive
estimated at least $30 million in lost business as the Indiana,
Illinois, Michigan, Minnesota and Ohio markets were virtually
closed down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say the couch potatoes won this weekend,'' said movie
analyst Arthur Rockwell, pointing out the plethora of football on
TV also held down grosses. He noted the current slate is strong
enough to recapture some of the weekend's lost revenues eventually
but added, ``A lot of that business is lost for good.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the storms not hit, Bucksbaum said, overall grosses would
have topped the record-setting $148.3 million total set during the
three-day Christmas weekend. He pointed out the box office had also
suffered an unexpected blow during the pre-Christmas weekend due to
President Clinton's impeachment, adding, ``It's really been
Murphy's Law at the box office lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Two films aimed at the date crowd battled for second with Sony's
second weekend of ``Stepmom'' leading with $15 million at 2,358
theaters, followed by Warner Bros.' third weekend of ``You've Got
Mail'' with $13.9 million at 2,776 sites. ``Stepmom'' has topped
$50 million overall while ``Mail'' has delivered $77.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   A trio of family films took the next slots, led by DreamWorks
SKG's third weekend of ``The Prince of Egypt'' with $11.5 million
at 3,202 theaters, followed by the seventh weekend of Disney and
Pixar's ``A Bug's Life'' with $10 million at 2,551 locations and
Disney's second weekend of ``Mighty Joe Young'' with $8.7 million
at 2,544 screens. ``A Bug's Life'' has passed $137 million and
could add $25 million more.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's second weekend of ``The Faculty'' finished seventh
with $7.5 million at 2,365 theaters, followed by Disney's seventh
weekend of ``Enemy of the State'' with $5 million at 1,539 sites to
go past $97 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enemy'' will soon become the 13th movie released in 1998 to
top $100 million, and ``Patch Adams'' is a certainty to join that
club. ``You've Got Mail'' and ``Stepmom'' also rate as strong
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were Paramount's fourth weekend of
``Star Trek: Insurrection'' with $4.8 million at 2,516 screens and
Warner's fourth weekend of ``Jack Frost'' with $3.1 million at
2,135 theaters. Final figures, due out today, may replace ``Jack
Frost'' with Miramax's critical sensation ``Shakespeare in Love''
with an impressive $3 million at only 299 sites.
</P>
<P>
   Two milestones were reached during the weekend: Paramount's
seventh weekend of ``The Rugrats Movie'' grossed $2.8 million at
2,002 theaters to top $89 million and beat DreamWorks' ``Antz'' as
the highest-grossing non-Disney animated film; and Disney's ninth
weekend of ``The Waterboy'' took in $2.3 million at 1,142 screens
to become the 59th film to go past $150 million in domestic
grosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great mix of films right now, and people still want
to see these movies,'' Bucksbaum said. ``I think they'll have great
legs in January.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell agreed, saying, ``I think the month could match the
levels in January 1998, even though that's when the `Titanic'
frenzy took hold.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
