<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' MURRAY OUT 8-10 WEEKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ A magnetic-resonance imaging examination on
the right knee of right wing Glen Murray revealed a torn medial
collateral ligament, and as a result, the Kings will be without
their best all-around forward for 8-10 weeks, the team announced
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old Murray _ second on the Kings in goals, assists
and points to Luc Robitaille and a strong component on the
power-play and penalty-killing units _ was injured in the first
period of Saturday night's 4-2 victory over the Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who has 15 goals and 28 points, was injured when he
landed awkwardly after a clean check into the boards by Colorado
defenseman Aaron Miller. He is expected to be placed on the
injured-reserve list today but is not expected to need surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's injury is the latest in a season full of serious
injuries to primary Kings players. Defenseman Rob Blake missed 15
games with a broken foot, No.1 center Jozef Stumpel was sidelined
sporadically with hip and ankle injuries for the season's first two
months, and goalies Stephane Fiset and Jamie Storr both have
battled groin strains.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, defenseman Doug Bodger missed a month with a
broken wrist and now is sidelined with a cervical strain and a
bruised shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also have been without winger Russ Courtnall (broken
ankle) for more than a month, and wingers Sandy Moger (back strain)
and Eric Lacroix (broken sternum) are close to returning after
extended absences because of their injuries. Winger Steve McKenna
is scheduled to undergo abdominal surgery today.
</P>
<P>
   Murray had been one of the Kings' most durable players,
appearing in 128 of 129 games since his acquisition from Pittsburgh
for Ed Olczyk in 1997. He missed one game last season because of
the flu, and hadn't missed a game because of injury since he was
with the Penguins in 1995-96.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
