<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 1/3/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Jan. 3, 1999 -- 1999-COHEN, 1-3 -- Abby
Joseph Cohen, the chief investment strategist at Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co., did not flinch in August when the stock market sank. Instead,
Cohen telephoned her clients and told them the same thing she told
them a year earlier when the market seemed to be in free fall:
``Stay the course.'' ``When we do a retrospective of 1999 we'll be
saying, 'It wasn't so bad after all,''' says Cohen. (Angel
Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Jan. 3, 1999 -- DANCE-IMAGES, 1-3 -- Sheri
Williams and Alvin Rangel of the Dayton Contemporary Dance Company
in Kevin Ward's ``Offering,'' a tribute to dancer James Truitte at
the Joyce Theater in September. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Jan. 3, 1999 -- NY-CANCER-COMPETE, 1-3 -- Dr.
Michael Gruber, a prestigious neuro-oncologist from the University
of California in Los Angeles, was recruited by New York University
to run the NYU Medical Center neuro-oncology unit. ``Cancer is to
the 1990s what heart disease was to the 1970s,'' says Gruber. ``It
puts a center on the map, and that begets business.'' (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Jan. 3, 1999 -- REPUBS-POLITICS, 1-3 -- With a
stick in one hand, a water bottle in the other and no gavel in
sight, Rep. Newt Gingrich, the outgoing House Speaker, climbing
Camelback Mountain near Phoenix Sunday during a Republican retreat.
Gingrich spoke Saturday night at a banquet that concluded an annual
New Year's conference of about 300 conservatives called The Weekend
but known as the Dark Ages. (Jeff Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) JERUSALEM -- Jan. 3, 1999 -- ISRAEL-CHRISTIAN-CULT, 1-3
-- Israeli police officers carrying boxes from a home on
Jerusalem's outskirts where members of a American-based apocalyptic
cult and their children were living. Israeli police officials
Sunday arrested eight members of the Concerned Christians cult, who
officials say were planning to mark the millennium by committing
suicide or provoking their own killings in the streets of
Jerusalem. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CALCUTTA, India -- Jan. 3, 1999 -- INDIA-AIDS, 1-3 --
Literate prostitutes teaching others to read at a Calcutta health
clinic. The prostitutes hired by the clinic to mobilize against
AIDS, have become a force in the power structure of the Sonagachi
red-light district. Like missionaries spreading the gospel, scores
go forth from brothel to brothel, preaching to madams, pimps and
other prostitutes about the importance of safe sex. (Celia W.
Dugger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Jan. 3, 1999 -- FOLK-HARDY-2, 1-3 -- Jack
Hardy, a folk singer who conducts song swaps reminiscent of the
1960s, in his Greenwich Village flat, listening to Tim Robinson.
Robinson, 35, a magazine illustrator from Brooklyn, is a regular at
the swaps and performs almost every week at a handful of clubs that
present acoustic music. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Jan. 3, 1999 -- FOLK-HARDY-1, 1-3 -- Jack
Hardy, a folk singer in his Greenwich Village flat, has for the
last 16 years conducted what many musicians consider to be a
laboratory for performers seeking to be part of what remains of the
modern folk tradition that emerged in the early 1960s. Some
songwriters trek to Hardy's flat from as far as Boston and
Philadelphia to be part of song swaps reminiscent of the 1960s.
(Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Jan. 3, 1999 -- 1999-DECADE, 1-3 -- Richard
Leone, president of the Century Foundation, formerly the Twentieth
Century Fund, a public policy research foundation. For Leone, what
is ``new under the sun'' in this decade is the aging of the world's
population, thanks to improvements in public health and a dramatic
drop in birth rates. ``With everyone living longer, attitudes about
the importance of saving and investment are going to proliferate,''
says Leone. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CHICAGO -- Jan. 3, 1999 -- 1999-TRAVEL, 1-3 -- Air travel
accounts for a big chunk of companies' travel and entertainment
budgets. Business and other travelers at Chicago's O'Hare and other
airports are likely to feel the pinch if fares rise as expected
this year. Many major companies are cutting back on the number of
employees who travel and replacing some travel with
videoconferencing and teleconferencing. (Todd Buchanan/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- Jan. 3, 1999 -- 1999-SOFTWARE, 1-3
-- A work station for Sally Rosenthal of Palo Alto, Calif.,
includes from left, a Motorola cell phone, a Metricom Richochet
wireless modem and a Palm Pilot electronic organizer. (Steve
Castillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
