<HEADER>
A6451 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GREENBAY-49ERS-NO     01-03 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GREENBAY-49ERS-NOTES-COXA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFC Notebook: Stick a fork in White; he's done
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While neither of the coaches involved in
Sunday's game would discuss their respective futures, Green Bay
Packers defensive end Reggie White held firm to his contention that
his NFL career is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put too much into this game for it not to hurt and guys
like Brett Favre already are saying to me, 'Reggie, you cannot go
out like this,' `` said the NFL's all-time sack leader following
San Francisco's 30-27 victory. ``But I'd like to think this game
won't diminish what I accomplished. It's time to move on now and do
the Lord's work. If I could do this all again, I would in a minute.
But this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   After tying for the league lead in sacks in '98, White was
rendered invisible on Sunday by San Francisco offensive right
tackle Kirk Scrafford. He finished with two tackles, both coming in
the fourth quarter, and got little pressure on Steve Young. In some
of the blocking schemes designed by Niners offensive line coach
Bobb McKittrick, the feisty Scrafford got some help from fullback
Marc Edwards, but not often.
</P>
<P>
   Haley's back
</P>
<P>
   Veteran defensive end Charles Haley, signed by the 49ers on
Saturday after two years of retirement, had two assisted tackles
and a pass defensed. Haley, 37, logged about 20 snaps and played
extensively on Green Bay's final offensive possession when the
Niners needed pressure on Favre. Unofficially, Haley had two
quarterback hurries. ``Obviously, I am sucking wind right now,''
Haley said. ``I'm nowhere near game shape. But I only do one thing
anyway, rush the quarterback, and I've still got some moves.''
Because of so many injuries, the 49ers rotated defensive linemen
all day. Right end Chris Doleman, playing with a torn pectoral
muscle, lined up on the left side. Left end Roy Barker, who hasn't
practiced in 2-1/2 months because of a balky knee, played the right
side. Former Green Bay starter Gabe Wilkins, who had been playing
tackle since the season-ending injury to Bryant Young, lined up all
over.
</P>
<P>
   Old rivals
</P>
<P>
   Tailbacks Dorsey Levens of Georgia Tech and Garrison Hearst of
Georgia both had very strong performances. Levens had 27 of the
Packers' 28 rushing attempts and finished with 121 yards. He also
had a team-high six receptions for 37 yards. Hearst carried 22
times for the 49ers and rang up 128 yards. He added 15 yards on
three catches. ``My men went out and knocked people down for me,''
said Hearst, who left the field late in the game with leg cramps.
``The line was tremendous.'' Hearst on several occasions easily got
to the outside on the Green Bay defense. His 128 yards represent
the second-best postseason rushing performance in franchise
history. Roger Craig had 135 yards in '89.
</P>
<P>
   Light serving of Rice
</P>
<P>
   Niners wideout Jerry Rice finished with just one catch for 6
yards and Young threw to him only four times all day. Unlike his
past tantrums at not getting the ball enough, Rice was gracious in
the locker room. ``I'm happy for Terrell Owens,'' said Rice. ``The
catch he made will be a signature play in his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay coach Mike Holmgren now has a 21-day window in which
he can field job offers from other teams. ``I've still got to play
quarterback if he goes, but I hope to hell Mike sticks around,''
Favre said. . . . Cornerback Marquez Pope, who has missed much of
the season with a back injury, started for the 49ers. . . . San
Francisco left guard Ray Brown played much of the game with a
concussion and bruised forearm. . . . Green Bay wideout Antonio
Freeman had two touchdown catches and absolutely froze Darnell
Walker with a move that led to the second score, which put the
Packers ahead 27-23 with just under two minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
