<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASTRONOMERS-CONVENTIO     01-03 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRONOMERS-CONVENTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Astronomers star in big Austin event
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _Get ready, Austin, for the superbowl of
astronomy.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Tuesday, more than 1,700 professional astronomers from
the United States, Mexico, Canada and Europe will fill the Austin
Convention Center through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the big ideas up for discussion by these international
members of the American Astronomical Society is a curious
acceleration of the universe's ongoing expansion, which the journal
Science named the scientific discovery of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Spectacular new photographs of the universe by the Hubble Space
Telescope also are on the meeting's agenda, as are some newly
discovered entries in the celestial zoo, all carefully being kept
secret until their scheduled public release by some of the 100
science journalists expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the most part, members of the society will spend the
week getting reacquainted with colleagues they often exchange
e-mail with but seldom see, attending 1,000 scientific
presentations, and interviewing employment-seeking graduate
students for whom the society's national meetings are mini-job
fairs.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this national meeting, the first in Austin by the
astronomical society since 1988, is not open to the public, and no
public events are planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a professional meeting and the members pay the cost to
put it on,'' said Anita Cochran, a University of Texas research
astronomer, who is the meeting's official chairperson. ``Most of
what's going on wouldn't be interesting to the public because it's
very technical. There will be some people attending sessions all
day long. It's pretty intense.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the least astronomically informed layman, however, would
appreciate the musical comedy entertainment Cochran has booked for
Friday night's farewell banquet: The Austin Lounge Lizards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love them,'' Cochran said. ``A lot of people aren't going to
know what to make of them. But everyone in the (UT astronomy)
department said, `Wow, that's great.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the society's scientists, who spend their lives worrying
about what's going on in galaxies far, far away, are a staid and
serious bunch.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, tentative plans the society made several years ago
to meet in Las Vegas fell through when prospective hotels announced
they would charge higher-than-usual prices. The hotels said there
was no other way for them to make money since their research had
found that most astronomers don't drink or gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Austin caterers, who normally provide one bartender for every
100 guests at events, figured the society would need about 17
bartenders for its 1,700 guests at the meeting's opening reception
Tuesday night. Cochran told them to figure on no more than four
bartenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a party-hat crowd,'' Cochran said. ``Most of them,
anyway. A large number will be looking for jobs and trying to
showcase themselves, so they won't do anything foolish.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Maran, the society's astronomer-press officer, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our scientists get high on the universe,'' Maran said. ``They
don't need artificial stimulants.''
</P>
<P>
   UT President Larry Faulkner is scheduled to welcome the
scientists Wednesday morning at the meeting's official opening, but
some attendees will have to start making themselves at home in
Central Texas earlier.
</P>
<P>
   On the meeting's schedule for Tuesday, for instance, is a bus
trip to Waco to see how Raytheon Corp. is coming along on refitting
a Boeing 747 jetliner to carry a German 2.5 meter research
telescope.
</P>
<P>
   This aerial observatory, dubbed SOFIA, for Stratospheric
Observatory for Infrared Astronomy, will make regular research
flights into the stratosphere, about 41,000 feet high, to gather
information from infrared wavelengths from stars and other objects.
Infrared wavelengths are invisible to ground telescopes because
they are absorbed by atmospheric moisture below 40,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   SOFIA is the replacement for the Kuiper Airborne Observatory of
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, whose adventures
millions of schoolchildren have followed on television and the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   UT lost a 1996 bid to manage SOFIA to the Universities Space
Research Association, a consortium of 80 American universities _ in
which UT plays a minor role _ which will keep the 747 at the
Kuiper's old base near San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the American Astronomical Society's
meeting this week in Austin, see http://www.aas.org/.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Stanley writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
