A6566 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-SUPERFAN-C     01-03 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-SUPERFAN-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAILGATER MAKES PALS WITH FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you Tennessee and Florida State fans whip out a card table
in a parking lot of Sun Devil Stadium before today's Fiesta Bowl
and pile it high with sandwiches and chips and six packs, you'll
probably think all you're doing is tailgating.
</P>
<P>
   The way Joe Cahn sees it, you're selling yourself short. A
full-time professional tailgater (I'll explain momentarily), Cahn
sees the pre-game ritual as nothing less than a higher calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it the most-ideal neighborhood,'' he said. ``It's the
utopia of neighborhoods. You're not judged by religion, politics,
race. You're judged on one criterion _ what color jersey you're
wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cahn sounds a little over-the-top about tailgating, that's
because he is. Ask him a question about it and he's likely to
answer with a stack of superlatives, piling one atop the other as
if he were building a Dagwood sandwich. Which he could no doubt do.
</P>
<P>
   A professional chef and the former owner of a New Orleans
cooking school, Cahn gave it up a few years ago, bought a motor
home and decided to travel the country _ with a tasty twist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see travel through food,'' he said last week from New
Orleans, shortly before driving to Tempe for the big game. ``When
we talk about food, we open up to everybody. It's the common
denominator. If you understand a community's food, you really
understand that community. People are fiercely proud of their
food.''
</P>
<P>
   You won't find that pride in restaurants, he figured, so he took
a different approach. He wanted to eat in people's homes. Any
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started knocking on doors around dinner time _ `Excuse me,
can I eat with you?' '' he said. ``I wasn't received that well.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a surprise. So he modified his plans and three years ago
decided to tailgate at every NFL stadium. The next year, he went to
college and pro games. This year, Kentucky Fried Chicken came
calling, and asked him to help pick the Top 10 Tailgating Colleges.
(Penn State won; Tennessee finished ninth and Florida State tied
for 10th, with Navy.)
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, traveling around as much as he does, Cahn has picked
up some tall tailgating tales. For instance, there was the Ohio
State fan who had a deed (signed by Woody Hayes) to his parking-lot
space, where he had parked since 1961. Two years ago he had a heart
attack. Then . . . perhaps you can guess where this is leading.
</P>
<P>
   ``While recuperating, he had an ambulance bring him to his
tailgate party,'' Cahn said. ``He sat for the party. Then they took
him back to the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, the question of what really constitutes
tailgating.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some people it is a six-pack of beer and some chips and
some dip,'' Cahn said. ``To some people it is taking an elaborate
grill and putting china on the table. Some people have a string
quartet playing while a butler serves their meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Aw, come on. Where?
</P>
<P>
   ``The University of Southern California.''
</P>
<P>
   Ha. Figures.
</P>
<P>
   Cahn recommends something a little less elaborate for Vols and
Seminoles tailgaters today. It is, after all, an away game for
both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep it simple,'' he said. ``Wear your team colors, fly your
flags, decorate. Come early, get a good spot. That's important.
Have a big sign that everyone is welcome. All you need is good
friends, some good food. Meet people. Go around and talk to people.
Make new friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Cahn will be there, naturally, in his motor home. Best seat in
the house, as far as he's concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the corporate goings-on at the Fiesta Bowl, everyone
has it in their power to have their own private suite,'' he said,
``and that's out in the parking lot. Tailgating is everyman's
luxury suite.''
</P>
<P>
   I like it. Tell you what, I'll bring the pickles. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
