<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S STRENGTH VS. STRENGTH  
 VOLS' OFFENSE, SEMINOLES' DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
 ST-DEFENSE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tennessee's runners managed to average an eye-opening 211 yards
during their 12 victories this season. Florida State's defense
allowed an average of just 79 yards per game this season.
</P>
<P>
   Which will have the advantage during tonight's Fiesta Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's leading rusher, Travis Henry, gained 970 yards. In
this day of 2,000-yard rushers, Henry's numbers may not leap out.
But he started just four games and was responsible for five of the
nine 100-yard-games by Tennessee running backs. (Injured Jamal
Lewis had three in four starts, and backup Travis Stephens had
another.) And Henry's 5.5 yards per carry average definitely has
caught the attention of Florida State's defensive coaches.
</P>
<P>
   But the Volunteers have run up against few defenses capable of
matching Florida State's team speed. That speed will be the
Seminoles' main asset in trying to neutralize Tennessee's ground
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're such great athletes,'' said Tennessee's
All-Southeastern Conference left tackle Chad Clifton. ``They've got
speed, size, strength. They get great pad leverage. They do not
stay blocked. Our motto is: Block 'em twice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers have been transformed from the Peyton Manning
passing attack into a run-first, pass-later attack under Tee
Martin's direction. They outrushed 10 of their 12 opponents in
reaching the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been our strength the whole year,'' Clifton said.
``It's no secret: For us to have success, we've got to run the
ball. That's a source of pride for us. When we lost our No. 1
running back (Lewis), we took it on ourselves as a challenge to
make sure the holes were there to run through and there would be no
drop-off.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is Martin's scrambling ability. In many ways, it
was easier to plan a defensive strategy against Manning and his
NFL-style offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a defensive coordinator, I would think it would be
tough with the receivers we have running man-to-man routes that I
could just take off and run 40 or 50 yards,'' Martin said. ``Peyton
had his way of playing, and I have mine. We're both different.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how Tennessee chooses to attack, it will have its
work cut out for it. Florida State ranks No. 1 nationally in total
defense (214.8 yards per game), second against the run, first in
pass-efficiency defense, and second in points allowed (11.5 per
game). North Carolina State, which scored 24 in the second week of
the season, was the only opponent to score more than 14 against the
Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have great, physical runners,'' Florida State defensive
end Tony Bryant said. ``It's hard to simulate what those can do in
games during our practices. Every game presents a new challenge,
and you always have to adjust to whatever style the other team has.
We've shown the ability to adjust pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   The toughest part for the Volunteers may be running wide against
Florida State's ultra-quick defenders. That leaves them to try to
pound the Seminoles inside, behind an offensive line that averages
304 pounds per man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody ever said it was going to be easy,'' said Tennessee
fullback Shawn Bryson. ``They do have fast guys at nearly every
position. But so do we. I'm looking at two very good teams playing
each other, with each doing good things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
