<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6569 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-TENN-SECON     01-03 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-TENN-SECONDARY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLS GO MAN TO MAN TO ATTACK WARRICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The list of defensive backs who have been trashed by Florida
State wide receiver Peter Warrick is a long one, filled with some
impressive names.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick badly wants to add the names of Steve Johnson and Dwayne
Goodrich, the Tennessee cornerbacks who will draw the assignment of
trying to stop the player considered the most dangerous receiving
threat in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Goodrich say they are ready for the challenge.
Tennessee will not do anything different for tonight's Fiesta Bowl
than it did in winning all 12 of its regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers will place Johnson and Goodrich in man-to-man
coverage against the Seminoles' wide receivers, which include
Warrick and the tandem of Ron Dugans and Laveranues Coles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go with what we did all year,'' said Johnson, a senior.
``Our coaches are confident to put us out there on an island with
those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers will attempt to become only the second school to
play a man-to-man against Warrick, who caught 61 passes for 1,232
yards and scored 12 touchdowns. The only other school to do so,
North Carolina, never had a chance against the Seminoles, losing in
Chapel Hill, N.C., 39-13.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, defended by Dre Bly that afternoon, caught only three
passes but burned the Tar Heels for 125 yards, including a 56-yard
touchdown. Goodrich has watched that game's videotape five times,
learning a bit more each time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of solely playing up on the line of scrimmage, a few
yards in front of Warrick and trying to knock him out of his pass
routes by bumping him, Goodrich believes a cornerback must also
drop back a few yards and simply try to remain with Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Dre did was wrong,'' said Goodrich, a junior with nine
career interceptions. ``You have to mix it up if you're going to
play Warrick man-to-man. He only played the bump. Once Peter knows
what kind of coverage you're giving him, he knows how to get by
you. That's where I'll be different.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with trying to bump Warrick at the line of scrimmage
is the possibility of missing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they stick me man-to-man, it really motivates me,''
Warrick said. ``I had a great game against Dre because I was
especially focused. I know they'll come up and press me at the
line. But if they miss, it's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what Florida State will be hoping for and
Tennessee defending against.
</P>
<P>
   Seminoles cornerback Dexter Jackson believes he has come up with
a perfect defense to stop Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter is the very best receiver in the country,'' Jackson
said. ``The only way I can think of to stop him is to triple-team
him. I honestly think that might work. I feel for anyone who has to
go against him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
