A6570 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRE-FORECASTERS-LADN     01-03 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-FORECASTERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE FORECASTERS GET SMOKED OUT IN CUTBACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Ron Hamilton isn't a circus performer, but he
does breathe fire for a living.
</P>
<P>
   But like the famous circus performers the Flying Wallendas,
Hamilton might soon become a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is a professional fire-weather forecaster -- and thus a
member of a popular but dying breed.
</P>
<P>
   Obsessed with wind speeds and humidity charts, willing to camp
out on the fire lines to help combat dangerous blazes, these
forecasters are popular with fire departments for providing a
steady stream of relevant weather data.
</P>
<P>
   But in a controversial move, the National Weather Service is
phasing out these jobs and replacing them with nonspecialty
positions. The same person who spends one day forecasting fire
conditions might spend the next working on meteorology or marine
forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Weather service officials said the changes, scheduled to take
place over the next several years, will make the agency more
efficient. But the proposal is getting a hostile reaction from
agencies ranging from local fire departments to the U.S. Forest
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to compromise firefighter safety, and we do
not want to do that,'' said George Ewan, the U.S. Forest Service's
acting assistant director for Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   During Sunday's blaze near suburban Porter Ranch in the San
Fernando Valley area northwest of downtown Los Angeles,
firefighters had to make due with a four-day-old fire-weather
forecast, said Brian Humphrey, spokesman for the Los Angeles city
Fire Department. He speculated the lack of updated reports was due
to the holiday, rather than staffing changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Weather Service did give reports, but they were
not fire-specific,'' he said. ``We were scrambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said he also worries about jeopardizing what he labels
a ``buddy-buddy-type'' bond between firefighters and forecasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you work with (firefighters) every day and you know them
on a first-name basis, they really believe what you have to say,''
said Hamilton, 56, who has been a fire-weather forecaster for 14
years. ``They trust you because they've worked with you before.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is one of six such forecasters in California -- three
based in Riverside, the other three in Redding. Twice a day, they
provide fire departments across the state with information about
wind direction, fuel moisture, dew-point temperature and other
relevant data -- all tailored to specific geographical regions.
</P>
<P>
   And on severe fires, forecasters have been known to rush to the
scene, laptop computer and sleeping bag in tow, to help gather
site-specific weather data.
</P>
<P>
   Some fire departments worry about losing a vital source of
information. Humphrey calls the forecasters ``the keystone in the
prediction as well as deployment and response to major fire
incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be unfathomable how we could proceed in fire season
without adequate scientific detail,'' Humphrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Weather service officials insist the changes will not have a
major impact on the basic services. Fire departments will receive
the same daily reports, for instance. What's more, since each of
the agency's forecasters will be trained in fire-weather analysis,
more trained people will be available in emergency situations, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going more and more toward this team approach, rather
than you have one lone person with the weight of the whole forecast
on them,'' said Paul Stokols, a National Weather Service program
manager in Silver Springs, Md.
</P>
<P>
   No one is quite sure when the new changes will occur. Estimates
range from a year to three or four years before the transition is
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton also predicted that the new forecasters would be less
willing to rush to a fire scene because they'd have too many other
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Gorski, fire-weather program manager for the National
Weather Service's Western region, called such issues a concern, but
not a major one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can free up more resources as we have more professionals
covering the different shifts,'' he said. ``Those guys can hop
right in.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
