<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLA </SLUG>
 ST-NOTES-AZR  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida State defensive coordinator Mickey Andrews said walk-on
brothers Billy and Bobby Rhodes were players who wouldn't be
denied, despite their physical limitations. They are in the mold of
Cardinals defensive end Andre Wadsworth, who went from walk-on to
the No. 3 pick of the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Billy, a senior, is a second-team defensive lineman. Bobby, a
junior, is a backup at outside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do all that big recruiting, and sometimes you've got
players who want to be a part of it so bad they'll listen to you,
they'll do what you ask them to do, and their heart is big enough
that they become players,'' Andrews said. ``That's exactly what
happened with Billy and Bobby Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't be the team we are without guys like them, or
Andre Wadsworth, and a lot of guys in past years who have played
that role.'' &QL; 
Take that &QL; 
Bowden was recalling a tale when he and then-Tennessee assistant
coach Phillip Fulmer were on a podium together at a college
football function, and Bowden had the microphone moments before
Fulmer was to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to introduce Phil, and just before I gave him the
mike, I said, `Alabama, Alabama, Alabama,' '' said Bowden,
referring to a seven-game losing streak the Volunteers had against
the Crimson Tide from 1986 to 1992. ``He grabbed the microphone and
said, `Miami, Miami, Miami.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes routinely kept Florida State from winning a
national championship throughout the 1980s, beating the Seminoles
seven of nine times from 1980 to '88.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me all the time why I always had one loss in the
'80s,'' Bowden said. ``I tell 'em it's because I played Miami every
year. In the '90s, it's been Florida. We're the only school that
plays both Miami and Florida. I'd like to see what other schools
would do playing both of them every year.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Familiar situation &QL; 
Florida State will play today with a backup quarterback, Marcus
Outzen, in the No. 1 spot. It's not an unfamiliar situation for
Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played Arizona State twice here during the regular
season (1983 and '84), and in both games our first-team quarterback
got knocked out. We ended up with our second-team quarterbacks and
won.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
No name, no problem &QL; 
Florida State is the nation's top-rated defense, but none of its
defenders stands out over the rest. Linebacker Lamont Green is OK
with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather be here than at another bowl where they say `we
have five All-Americans,' but they're playing in the Citrus Bowl,''
Green said. ``I'd rather be here with a no-name defense.'' &QL;
</P>
