agency has been snooping on members of the National Assembly has
created a furor. By Nicholas D. Kristof.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-PRICEHIKES (Mexico City) _ In a move that has sparked
concern among millions of families, the Mexican government has
ended decades-old corn subsidies and price controls on tortillas, a
staple that is as central to the Mexican diet _ particularly among
the poor _ as bread to Americans and rice to the Chinese. The
measure, government officials said, is part of an effort by Mexican
President Ernesto Zedillo to reduce government spending. Last year,
officials said, tortilla subsidies cost the government some $1
billion.
</P>
