disabilities. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS _ Since nobody except perhaps Rep. Tom DeLay of
Texas, the House majority whip, appears to believe that the Senate
might really vote to convict President Clinton and remove him from
office, the argument goes, why not get it over with quickly? Some
quick resolution, including a censure, seems to be the goal Trent
Lott and Tom Daschle, the Senate leaders, are pursuing with many
other senators. But there is a case for a trial. It is heard most
often from the president's critics in Congress who insist that when
the Constitution says, ``The Senate shall have the sole power to
try all impeachments,'' it offers no discretion. By Adam Clymer.
