<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6576 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-TENN-NOTES     01-03 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-TENN-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE LUMIA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tonight, Tennessee offensive coordinator Randy Sanders will call
plays for the first time outside his hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who replaced David Cutcliffe when he left the
Volunteers to become Mississippi's head coach, has been practicing
his play calling most of the week while watching tape in his room.
</P>
<P>
   He has tried to simulate game conditions, taking into account
such factors as down and distance, Florida State's tendencies and
the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called a lot of good ones last night,'' Sanders said with a
smile Friday. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Who's the boss? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sanders knows that not all his calls will make it onto the field.
Some speculate that Tennessee Coach Phillip Fulmer will have a big
hand in the play calling anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's vetoed me a number of times in the past, not necessarily
on play calls, but on different decisions,'' Sanders said. ``He's
the head coach and can do whatever he wants to do. If I want to be
at the University of Tennessee, part of my job description is
accept what he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a problem with that at all. If I was the head
coach, it would be the exact same way.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Change of allegiance &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's obvious his allegiances have changed, but Tennessee
quarterback Tee Martin admits he was a Florida State fan growing
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just liked the style of play,'' he said. ``I liked the
coaches, Bobby Bowden being there my whole life. And growing up in
high school, Charlie Ward was the quarterback I kind of modeled
myself after him. He's a good guy off the field as well as on the
field and won a Heisman Trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said Florida State recruited him a little bit but ``not
very hard.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quick hit &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fulmer said a busy schedule has not allowed the Tennessee coaching
staff to make any home recruiting visits while in the Valley, but
they've been keeping track of several players in the area. The
Volunteers made a major recruiting score in the Valley earlier this
decade, landing South Mountain cornerback Terry Fair, a first-round
draft choice of the Detroit Lions last year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mystery solved &QL; 
 &QL; 
John Ward, the longtime broadcasting voice of the Tennessee
football team, has come a long way since he tried to pick up a few
bucks as a sportswriter for the now-defunct Knoxville Journal while
attending law school. He didn't become the next Grantland Rice, but
he did solve a mystery concerning the legendary Robert Neyland,
former Volunteers football coach and athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most everyone here still pronounces it Nay-land,'' he said.
``But it's actually Knee-land. I know that because he told me.''
</P>
<P>
   The day in question was cold and rainy. Ward was happy to be
stuck in the office. But he was on the bottom rung, and the sports
editor barked, ``Ward, go cover the Tennessee practice!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The general was the athletic director then, and I was
terrified of him,'' Ward said. ``He said to me, `Let's go in the
car.' Well, we went into his car, and I'm not gonna ask him if the
weather's nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``So my first question was, `How do you say your name?' I told
him that I had heard people say it both ways. He told me, and
that's where I got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as a confirmation, he was making a speech years later and
retold the story. Neyland's widow was sitting at the head table,
and Ward asked, ``Is that correct, Mrs. Knee-land?''
</P>
<P>
   She got up and slapped her knee. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
