<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-TENN-RESPECT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLS SEEM LIKE A SOLID FAVORITE  
 SO WHY IS VEGAS BETTING ON THE SEMINOLES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's see . . . They finished 12-0, beat Florida for the first
time in six years and have held the No. 1 ranking for two months.
</P>
<P>
   And the Tennessee Volunteers are 5{-point underdogs to 11-1
Florida State in Monday's Fiesta Bowl because . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Beats me,'' said John Avello, director of Bally's race and
sports book in Las Vegas. ``I think they should be favored by a
few.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Tennessee players arrived in the Valley with
confidence, they also came with a chip on their shoulders. Respect
has been slow to come, they say, and the point spread confirms it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it insulting, but I would say that we're used
to it,'' linebacker Eric Westmoreland said. ``We're used to being
underdogs, second to everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems to bother the players more than Coach Phillip Fulmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been No. 1 in the country (for eight weeks),'' he said.
``I think that's about as much respect as you can get. Everywhere I
go, kids are interested in coming to Tennessee, so we're obviously
pretty hot right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth appears to lie somewhere in the middle. The Volunteers
``are'' respected, but it seems to be a tentative regard. Here are
several possibilities for the skepticism:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Arkansas victory.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee appeared ready to fall to 8-1 on Nov. 14. The
Razorbacks led the entire game and had possession with less than
two minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But then good fortune, the type that seems to touch teams of
destiny, reached down and swatted the ball out of Arkansas
quarterback Clint Stoerner's hands.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:43 remaining and Arkansas leading, 24-22, Stoerner
stumbled and tried to catch his fall with the ball. It popped out,
Tennessee recovered at the Razorbacks 43-yard line, and five
carries later, Travis Henry scored the game-winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the important thing was to win the game,'' Fulmer
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The recent history.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles won a national title in 1993. The Volunteers had a
chance to win over some skeptics last season in the Orange Bowl,
but a 21-point third quarter by Nebraska led to a convincing 42-17
Cornhuskers victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have as much tradition as any school in the
country, but we haven't been able to win the big game,'' cornerback
Steve Johnson said. ``We went down to the Orange Bowl last year and
played a good first half, but the second half, we stunk it up. So a
lot of people were saying, `Why is Tennessee in this game playing
Nebraska?'
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, after we refocused, we impressed a lot of people as
a hard-working, blue-collar team, and people are starting to take
notice.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Seminoles have a blemish on their record, a 24-7
loss to North Carolina State, it came early in the season. FSU
teams tend to peak at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, despite playing the fourth-toughest schedule in
the country, the Seminoles won many of their games convincingly.
Plus, their defense is ranked No. 1 in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the main reason people are picking Florida
State, and I wouldn't disagree with that,'' Avello said. ``But I
would also say Florida State's offense is weaker than Tennessee's,
and that alone is enough of a reason for me to like (the
Volunteers).''
</P>
<P>
   Few seem to be bothered that Seminoles quarterback Marcus Outzen
is starting only his third game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Both are among the best in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bowden's Seminoles have finished in the Associated Press'
Top Four for 11 consecutive seasons. He has a 12-1 bowl record over
the last 13 years, including a record 11 straight victories.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer has the best winning percentage among active coaches and
is 44-5 since 1995, the most victories over a four-year span in
school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps my personality hasn't lent itself to being something
that brings attention to the program,'' Fulmer said. ``I'm not
Bobby Bowden. I also haven't been in it as long as he's been in it,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   In Johnson's mind, there's only one way to correct people's
perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``To actually get the national respect everybody around here
wants,'' he said, ``we're going to have to beat a nationally ranked
team and well-respected team like Florida State. It's that
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' said defensive tackle Darwin Walker, ``is our
chance.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
