<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6582 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLAST-KIDN     01-03 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING WITH A LIGHTER LOAD  
 PAIR SHARE MOTHERS' ILLNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
 ST-KIDNEYS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The worry is gone from his face, replaced by relief and joy.
Now, for the first time in his Florida State career, senior free
safety Dexter Jackson can focus only on a football game. Which, in
this case, happens to be for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, the second-ranked Seminoles meet top-ranked Tennessee
in the Tostitos Fiesta Bowl at Sun Devil Stadium. Getting to Tempe
was the goal from the beginning of the season for Florida State.
They wore ``Discipline to Desert'' shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Before today, however, Jackson's thoughts were with his ailing
mother at home in Quincy, Fla. He would put tape on his wrist
before games and write ``Mom'' on it. He'd pray she would receive a
kidney.
</P>
<P>
   After a six-year wait, Lula Lee was given the transplant on
Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the greatest time in my life,'' Jackson said. ``Right
after that, Kansas State and UCLA both lost. We got the trip to the
national championship game. All that's left is a title. That would
be the perfect way to end my senior year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if that is lost, Jackson has won, knowing his mother is on
her way to recovery. She still has her down days and remains on a
dialysis machine until her new kidney gets stronger. But there is
hope, and that's all Jackson can ask for as he prepares for the
biggest game of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big burden off my shoulders,'' he said. ``I was always
playing, thinking about my mom and how she's doing back home. I'd
think, `Is she OK? Is she OK?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the kidney transplant, she's doing well. The pressure is
off me now. I can just go out and perform.''
</P>
<P>
   So can senior linebacker Lamont Green, who is inspired by
Jackson's story. Green's mother, Emma, received a kidney transplant
five years ago, but it is failing and she has been put on a donor
waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm on the field, I just try to concentrate on
football,'' Green said. ``I know she doesn't want me worrying about
her on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The two players have formed a special friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mom has had a transplant, and everything worked out
successfully, so that gives me a lot of hope that when my mom goes
in to have hers, everything will be fine,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Green talk about their mothers, but they don't dwell
on their problems. They feel it is bizarre that they ended up on
the same top-rated defense with similar situations at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly, we try to cheer each other up,'' Green said. ``We've
grown a lot closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, an only child whose father died of a heart attack eight
years ago, moved only 30 miles from his home in Quincy, Fla., not
only for the chance to play on a national championship team, but to
make sure he was there for his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Every other day during the season, he would drive from
Tallahassee to Quincy to visit his mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was hard on him,'' Jackson's mother said. ``He'd
keep it to himself. I just told him to do the best that he could
do. The Lord will take care of him.''
</P>
<P>
   With concerns for his mother, Jackson said he never felt he
played to his potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always thinking about her,'' he said. ``She'd say not to
worry, but I'd say, `Mom, it's not that easy. I'll always worry
about you, no matter what.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he wanted to give one of his kidneys to his mother,
but his blood type didn't match. Even if it had, Lee said she
wouldn't let her son give up a kidney for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to play football, and if he gave it up, I knew he
couldn't do that anymore,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson did other things to help his mother: He excelled on the
field and in the classroom. He is an honor student who is on
schedule to graduate this year with a degree in child psychology.
Last year, he made the All-Atlantic Coast Conference academic team.
</P>
<P>
   This season, he is the Seminoles' second-leading tackler with
69, including 44 solo stops. He has four interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thank the Lord that she's a strong woman,'' Jackson
said. ``She didn't look at it as a sickness. She looked at is a
part of life. She always told me to keep the faith and don't
question God's call.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Jackson tells Green now. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
