<DOCNO> NYT19990103.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6587 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-1998-2ndTAKE-L     01-03 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-1998-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
  
LOS ANGELES: ``Mighty Joe Young'' ($85 million).
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There was supposed to be a return to fiscal prudence after
`Titanic,' but it was such a hit that people still can't stop
trying to hit home runs,'' Rockwell said. ``I think they're trying
to slow down but it's very tough to generalize.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who is working on half a dozen projects including a
``Dolittle'' sequel, says he notices a difference from a few years
ago. ``I think it's gotten tougher to make movies,'' he asserts.
``You see studios canceling projects with big stars because the
economics have not been terrific in the last few years. It makes
for a much more cautious process.''
</P>
<P>
   But making movies remains enormously attractive. Everyone agrees
there were several major winners this year, including:
</P>
<P>
   Animated films. The Walt Disney Co. and DreamWorks SKG each
released two such films with fairly strong results; Paramount spent
a mere $25 million for ``The Rugrats Movie'' and established the
brand as a powerful franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided the time was right because it had become part of
the pop culture,'' said Albie Hecht, president of the Nickelodeon
cable channel, which airs ``Rugrats.'' ``We felt we could compete
because we had the first animated film that was really contemporary
movie rather than the classic animation look. We're not committed
to a particular style so we don't have to build a huge studio.''
</P>
<P>
   Low-cost comedies such as ``There's Something About Mary,''
``Rush Hour,'' ``The Wedding Singer'' and ``The Waterboy.''
``Mary,'' which cost $25 million, is expected to take in $350
million worldwide for 20th Century Fox, making it the year's most
profitable movie.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-range comedies with star appeal, including ``The Truman
Show,'' ``Dr. Dolittle,'' ``Patch Adams'' and ``You've Got Mail.''
``Moviegoers really looked for lighthearted entertainment this
year,'' Leatherman said. ``They told Hollywood, give me fun that's
not overly contrived.''
</P>
<P>
   New Line Cinema and DreamWorks, which finished well ahead of
Universal despite offering limited slates. New Line continued to
capitalize on niche films; DreamWorks became a player with the
year's second highest grosser and leading Academy Awards contender
in ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Split financing on big-budget films. The strategy enabled
Paramount, among the most cost-conscious of studios, to hold stakes
in ``Titanic,'' ``Saving Private Ryan,'' ``Deep Impact,'' ``A Civil
Action'' and ``Snake Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Giant-screen films. ``Everest'' grossed more than $55 million
this year despite never being on more than 62 screens at once.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign market, which now takes in over 60 percent of
worldwide grosses and continues to grow. Eighteen movies topped
$100 million overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Episode One: the Phantom Menace.'' Buzz generated by the
trailer for the ``Star Wars'' prequel shows that not even the
record for ``Titanic'' is safe.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
