<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6589 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-1998-2TAKES-LA     01-03 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-1998-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES DO BOFFO BOX OFFICE IN U.S. DURING '98
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Hollywood finished 1998 with a flourish, capping
a risk-filled year with a 9 percent rise in its all-important
domestic box office to nearly $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the final batch of major films -- ``Stepmom,'' ``You've
Got Mail'' and ``Patch Adams'' -- matched lofty expectations during
the crucial holiday season. The year's last eight weeks saw enough
success from three Disney films (``The Waterboy,'' ``A Bug's
Life,'' ``Enemy of the State'') to cancel out Universal's double
disaster from ``Meet Joe Black'' and ``Babe: Pig in the City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The holiday season hasn't been great, but it's been very
good,'' said analyst Arthur B. Rockwell, a former studio executive.
``There were no runaway blockbusters but there was a lot of good
product drawing audiences on a continuing basis. It's become harder
than ever to have a blockbuster because the business is so
competitive and the marketplace is far more crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynics may argue that ``Titanic,'' which drew 75 percent of its
$600 million total domestic gross during 1998, was the key factor
in the year-to-year increase. But it accounted for only half the
gain. Even though only one film, Disney's ``Armageddon'' topped
$200 million, 11 others grossed over $100 million and eight more
topped $75 million, reflecting an unprecedented breadth of strong
product.
</P>
<P>
   Overall strength was most evident during the Christmas weekend
when the industry smashed the record for biggest three-day box
office with $148.3 million in gross receipts. Seven films topped
$10 million over the weekend and the year's last seven days were on
track to become the highest-grossing week of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Even Universal Studios, which had suffered through a brutal
hitless stretch of 20 films, found a winner as ``Patch Adams'' led
the box office with a $25.3 million opening, followed by more than
$20 million on the year's last four days. Robert Bucksbaum,
president of Reel Source Inc., projected a $160 million final
gross.
</P>
<P>
   What was most impressive about 1998 was that Hollywood managed
to significantly improve its performance for the third year in a
row. Attendance rose 5.4 percent to 1.46 billion tickets as theater
chains replaced outmoded facilities with massive ``megaplexes''
with as many as 30 screens, huge snack bars and stadium seating.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 5,000 more domestic screens -- nearly all of them in
flashy new movie palaces -- have been added in the past four years
to push the current count to 34,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very good about the new theaters, which are leading a
renaissance of moviegoing,'' said Jeff Blake, head of Sony's
distribution arm. ``It's invigorated the business and brought back
some of the adults who weren't that interested in the older
six-plexes. With the new theaters, you can service a lot of
different audiences so we feel better about releasing our more
adult-oriented films wider.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ Leatherman, president of the MovieFone service, agreed.
``Chains are forced into upgrading because competition is so
high,'' he said. ``As studios make more technically sophisticated
movies, there's a need for great places to display them. I'm much
more likely to go to a theater that has nice presentation than one
that has my feet sticking to the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Many movies now open at more than 2,500 locations, making it
much easier than a few years ago for moviegoers to find a specific
film. The explosion in screens at improved locations means
moviegoers attend more often; in turn, studios are becoming less
likely to save all their best films for the holidays or the early
summer, which had been a huge complaint among exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   Prime examples of spreading out the schedule were evident
throughout 1998 -- February's ``The Wedding Singer,'' late July's
``There's Something About Mary'' and ``Saving Private Ryan,''
September's ``Rush Hour'' and October's ``Antz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a good movie, they come,'' said industry veteran
John Davis, producer of ``Dr. Dolittle.'' ``There's really no bad
time to open a film any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake said Sony's timing was a key factor in achieving a
third-place finish behind Disney and Paramount in the domestic box
office. He noted the studio placed one major wide release in every
month along with a dozen specialized films.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a challenge because it's such a crowded market, so
you definitely need a 52-week game plan,'' he said. ``I'd like to
see exhibitors play some of the titles longer, but I'm not upset
when we get a lot of screens for the hot title.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake said part of Sony's success was simply avoiding failure.
``We swung for the fences with `Godzilla,' which grossed $375
million worldwide, and we had lots of singles and doubles, like
`Mask of Zorro' '' he said. ``The key thing is we really didn't
have a big loser.''
</P>
<P>
   That's often the operative philosophy as studios try to keep
costs from soaring further amid actor salaries of $20 million per
movie and the need for never-before-seen special effects. The
average movie cost $53.4 million to produce and $22.2 million to
market in 1997, according to the Motion Picture Association of
America; 1998 numbers will likely be significantly higher.
</P>
<P>
   In response, top studio executives have limited the number of
major releases opening on 2,000 screens to about 140 a year, down
about a dozen from 1997. And they insist they are green-lighting
fewer ``tentpole'' big-budget films with whiz-bang, expensive
special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Still, studios managed to strike out on a lot of big budget
films. In recent months, many movies came into theaters with
questionable potential and eye-grabbing production budgets: ``Meet
Joe Black'' ($90 million), the ``Babe'' sequel ($85 million),
PolyGram's ``What Dreams May Come'' ($85 million), Warner's ``The
Avengers'' ($70 million), MGM's ``Ronin'' ($60 million), Warner's
``Soldier'' ($58 million) and Disney's ``Holy Man'' ($60 million)
and ``Mighty Joe Young'' ($85 million).
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
