<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6601 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     01-03 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ As the ball was snapped and the clock began ticking
down those last eight seconds, Terrell Owens didn't think about
anything at all. He couldn't afford to.
</P>
<P>
   There was so much to weigh him down as he came off the line of
scrimmage and gave Packers strong safety LeRoy Butler a head fake
to the outside, then cut right back over the middle toward the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   There was his reception and fumble on the opening series of the
game that set up a Packers field goal and early lead. There were
four dropped passes of assorted degrees of difficulty, one that was
a sure third-period touchdown and another on third down just a few
minutes earlier in the fourth quarter that led to the Packers
getting the ball back for their go-ahead score.
</P>
<P>
   So here was another playoff game with their tormentors from
Green Bay and another 49ers season coming down to one play, and
there was the pass from Steve Young headed straight for Edward
Scissorhands.
</P>
<P>
   As the ball zipped through the air like a tracer bullet, the
66,506 partisans in the stands at 3Com Park had every reason to be
more jittery than a Chihuahua inside a paint shaker.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, the only time it really counted, Owens wrapped up
the ball in his arms, took a pair of hammer-on-anvil hits from
safeties Darren Sharper and Pat Terrell, and hung on for the
25-yard touchdown with just three seconds left that gave the Niners
a 30-27 victory that was as shocking for who won it as how.
</P>
<P>
   After all, you wouldn't normally ask Venus de Milo to do the
delicate detail work for the bomb squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just happy I caught that ball,'' Owens said. ``I had a
rough day up to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is only like saying downtown Baghdad had a rough month.
</P>
<P>
   For a proud _ sometimes boastful _ franchise whose Super Bowl
roots grow out of Dwight Clark's dramatic reception of Joe
Montana's pass to beat the Dallas Cowboys in the 1981 NFC
Championship Game, this was a bookend clutch payoff in the end zone
at the other end of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catch'' _ as Montana-to-Clark is known around here _ at
long last has a cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call it `The Throw,''' Young said with a devilish smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call it `Redemption,''' said Owens, breathing a huge sigh of
relief. ``I just knew that I had to make a big play for this team.
All year, I had been making plays, and I didn't want to get into a
big game and choke up. All day long, those balls were bouncing off
my hands and my teammates on the sidelines kept telling me to keep
my head up. I'm just so glad I got that chance to redeem myself.''
</P>
<P>
   It was overdue redemption for the 49ers franchise, which had
been knocked out of the playoffs in each of the three previous
seasons by Green Bay. It's an organization that had been coming
unraveled as owner Ed DeBartolo Jr. lost control of his team
because of legal problems, and president Carmen Policy and Clark,
the director of football operations, quit to work for the expansion
club in Cleveland. Then, they lost their stranglehold on the NFC
West, finishing behind Atlanta in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   It was also personal redemption for Young, who had listened ad
nauseam in the week before the game that he was 0-8 lifetime
against the Packers and was again hearing the whispers that, unlike
the legendary Montana, he could not win the big games.
</P>
<P>
   So finally, Young did. And he did it with Montana's flair and
flourish.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sloppy, ugly game with seven turnovers and many
mistakes. The 49ers never looked streamlined or efficient. But
winning is the best deodorant, and the conclusion left only the
aroma of accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   After Owens had dropped the critical third-down pass with just
over four minutes left in the game and the Packers drove 89 yards
to go in front 27-23 when Brett Favre lobbed a 15-yard TD to
Antonio Freeman with only 1:56 to go, the Niners quarterback summed
up the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plenty of time,'' he said. ``Plenty of time.'' Which is just
what Montana would have said.
</P>
<P>
   Young was as sharp as a sushi chef in completing six of eight
passes and moving the 49ers from their 24 to the Green Bay 25 with
eight seconds on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The play is called ``All Go'' with four receivers heading for
the end zone. Young took the snap from center Chris Dalman and
tripped on a chunk of sod.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of disappeared there for a minute from the defense, and
maybe that helped it all develop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers were settled in a deep zone and amazingly allowed
the middle of the field to open up. Owens made his fake and the
cut. Young made the right read and the throw. Owens held on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Redemption, for so many.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
