<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TEMPE, Ariz. _ Florida State's Bobby Bowden and Tennessee's Phil
Fulmer are living proof that there is no cut-and-dried way of
reaching the pinnacle of the college football coaching profession.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Bowden, seems to be the classic cutup, like the
favorite uncle or grandfather who laughs his way through the day
and goes around saying things like, ``I got your nose,'' and,
``Pull my finger.''
</P>
<P>
   The other is the serious, meticulous workaholic, the one who
seems to have the personality of dried fruit and misses by just a
tick whenever he tries a one-liner.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden walks into a ballroom like he has never seen one before _
wide-eyed, curious, dropping his jaw at the sight of the glittery
chandelier overhead and marveling at the flashing lights in his
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   His saunter is right out of Satchel Paige's rules for longevity
_ loose, jangly and never looking back.
</P>
<P>
   He spins stories as if he's whittling on the front porch, not
standing in front of the nation on the verge of carving out another
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer walks into a ballroom like he's in the middle of a
leveraged buyout _ purposeful and determined, planning his course
and words carefully. His style is right out of Roberts' Rules of
Order.
</P>
<P>
   When he is asked a question, only occasionally does Fulmer turn
his head to look at the person asking it, instead responding as if
talking to the blankness in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here is Bowden. Here is Fulmer. Separate but equal.
</P>
<P>
   Neither denies that the reputation that follows him is mostly
true.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer has been known to work 18-hour days and admits, ``I'm not
real flashy.'' However, his players always defend their coach and
say the image shown to the nation goes only as deep as the starched
shirts he wears for the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden admits he likes to take an occasional nap and arrived at
his eighth consecutive January bowl this week in typical style, as
if walking off the Grayline in Las Vegas, wearing a windsuit,
bifocals and comfortable shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when he was handed a sack of Tostitos and a gift bag,
Bowden thanked the fellow who handed him the gifts and asked, ``Are
you the master of ceremonies?''
</P>
<P>
   The reply: ``No, I'm the mayor of Tempe.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of awkwardly backtracking over his mistake, Bowden
laughed a giddy laugh and slapped Mayor Neil Giuliano on the back,
saying, ``Oops.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden is Bowden; Fulmer is Fulmer. They have proved just how
diverse the roads to greatness can be. Neither is right; neither is
wrong. Both are worthy of all the good things ever said about them.
</P>
<P>
   For all the characterizations that have followed these coaches
throughout their different career paths, there remains one huge
similarity. When it's time to play the game, they get it done.
</P>
<P>
   Among active coaches, only Penn State's Joe Paterno has won more
college football games than Bowden's 292. And among active coaches,
no one has a higher winning percentage than Fulmer's .857.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Bowden is not always as casual about things as he
appears. In the pivotal moments against Florida in the final
regular-season game of the year, he was heard barking into the
headset to offensive coordinator Mark Richt, ``What are we gonna
do, punt them to death? Run that Peter thing!''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Richt called a reverse pass by All-American Peter
Warrick, and the ensuing 46-yard touchdown to Ron Dugans sealed the
23-12 win and the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Bowden and Fulmer meet.
</P>
<P>
   The pick here is for Bowden's Seminoles to ultimately walk away
with the championship, only because of a defensive line that
refuses to budge, a big play from Warrick and an edge in experience
over Fulmer and his staff that cannot be overestimated.
</P>
<P>
   But the beauty of tonight's game is that it shows just how many
different ways there are to become a champion.
</P>
<P>
   Witness: On the eve of the game, both coaches were asked to
describe the exhilarating feeling they might have with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer spoke of the immense sense of satisfaction he would feel,
the culmination of months of work, the realization of goals
achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Bowden: ``What's `exhilarating' mean?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
